{"title_page": "Everyday Use", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=September 2014}}\n{{original research|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name             = Everyday Use\n| image            = Everyday Use (Alice Walker short story).jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption    = \n| author           = [[Alice Walker]]\n| cover_artist     = \n| subject          = \n| genre            = [[Short story]]\n| publisher        = \n| pub_date         = 1973 (as part of ''In Love and Trouble'')\n| media_type       = \n| pages            = \n| isbn =  978-0-8135-2075-9\n| oclc             = 29028043\n| dewey            = \n| congress         = \n| preceded_by      = \n| followed_by      = \n| italic title     = no\n}}<!--\n{{Infobox Film\n| name           =  Everyday Use\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Bruce Schwartz]]\n| writer         = Bruce Schwartz<br />'''Short story'''[[Alice Walker]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Karen ffolkes]]<br />[[Rachel Luttrell]]\n| music          = [[Rocky Davis]]\n| cinematography = [[Brian C. Glover]]\n| editing        = [[Stephen Goetsch]]<br />[[Kristofer Lindquist]]\n| studio         = Films for the Humanities and Sciences\n| distributor    =  \n| released       =  \n| runtime        =  \n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[English language|English]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}-->\n\n\"'''Everyday Use'''\" is a widely studied and frequently anthologized short story by [[Alice Walker]]. It was first published in 1973 as part of Walker's short story collection ''In Love and Trouble''.\n\nThe short story is told in  [[first-person narrative|first person]] by \"Mama\", an African-American woman living in the [[Deep South]] with one of her two daughters. The story follows the differences between Mrs. Johnson and her shy younger daughter Maggie, who both still adhere to traditional black culture in the rural South, and her educated, successful daughter Dee, or \"Wangero\" as she prefers to be called, who takes a different route to reclaiming her cultural identity.\n\nA film version was released in 2005.\n\n==<span lang=\"fa\" dir=\"rtl\">Plot</span>==\nThe story opens on Mama waiting in the yard for her oldest daughter, Dee\u2019s, visit.  She reflects on the differences between Dee and Maggie, her youngest daughter, and knows that Maggie will be anxious and self-conscious around Dee. Maggie was burned in a house fire that happened more than a decade ago. Mama carried her out in her arms, as Dee watched the house burn. Dee was seemingly happy and excited about the fire, due to her extreme dislike for the house. The narrator continues to paint a picture of Maggie as helpless and rather awkward, whereas Dee is beautiful and seems to have had an easier time in life.\n\nDee left home to pursue an education in Augusta, afforded to her by Mama and the community\u2019s fund raising efforts. Mama never attended school past second grade, and Maggie has a very limited reading ability, so Dee\u2019s education is a stark difference and Mama seems to feel that starkness, commenting, \u201clike dimwits, we seemed about to understand\u201d. <ref name=\":1\" />  Mama discusses the physical differences between the three: her own manly looks, Maggie\u2019s timid disposition, and Dee\u2019s own nice hair, full figure, and stylish way of dress.\n\nWhen Dee finally arrives, she is accompanied by a man, whom Mama refers to as Hakim-a-barber. Mama and Maggie are a little taken aback by Dee's wild-looking outfit and her African greeting to them. Dee takes photos of Mama and Maggie in front of the house, and the greetings are stiff and unfamiliar. Dee informs her mother that she has now changed her name to Wangero Leewanika Kemanjo in order to protest the oppression and cultural white washing Black Americans faced. Mama rejects this, telling Dee she was named after her Aunt Dicie, who in turn was named after Grandma Dee, and that the name went on through the generations. Dee gives Mama the option of not using her new name, and Mama concludes that Hakim-a-barber must be related to a family of Muslims down the road. Hakim-a-barber says he accepts some of the doctrines of his beef-raising family, but is not interested in farming or herding as a profession.\n\nMama does not know whether Hakim-a-barber and Dee are married, nor does she ask. Hakim-a-barber has a restricted diet to follow, but Dee digs into the food Mama made. She begins asking for things around the house, like the top of a butter churn, and eventually she asks for two quilts as well.  This quilt in particular is one that Mama had promised to Maggie, and Dee\u2019s persistence frustrates Mama which develops into an argument between Mama and Dee. Dee argues that by using the quilt as a normal item, in \u201ceveryday use\u201d, the quilt will be ruined, and the cultural importance will be lost. Mama would rather the item be used practically by her family and be ruined than have it sit on a shelf or be hung on a wall as a piece of art, and as Dee readies to leave, she tells Mama that Mama doesn\u2019t understand her own heritage.  She adds that Mama should try and improve, and that there is a new path for Black Americans to follow. Maggie and Mama sit in the yard after watching them drive off, until bedtime.\n\n==Characters==\n* '''Dee''' \u2013 She is an educated African-American woman and the eldest daughter of Mama. She seeks to embrace her cultural identity through changing her name from Dee to Wangero Leewanika Kemanjo (an African name), marrying a Muslim man, and acquiring artifacts from Mama's house to put on display, an approach that puts her at odds with Mama and Maggie.  She is physically beautiful and is described as having a great sense of style.\n* '''Mama''' \u2013 She is described as a \"large, big-boned woman with rough, man-working hands.\"<ref name=\":1\" />  She enjoys her lifestyle (especially milking cows) and did not receive an education past second grade.\n* '''Maggie''' \u2013 Described by Mama as dull and unattractive, the youngest daughter Maggie has burn scars and marks from the burning down of their prior home, and is very nervous and self-conscious because of it. She leads a simple and traditional life with her mother in the South while her elder sister, Dee, is away at school.  She has very limited reading ability, unlike her sister Dee.\n* '''Hakim-a-barber''' \u2013 Dee\u2019s partner, he is referred to as \"Asalamalakim\", which is a Muslim greeting, throughout the story because he is Muslim.  Eventually he tells Mama to call him \"Hakim-a-barber\" due to Mama being unable to pronounce his real name.\n\n\n== Themes ==\nOne of the primary themes that the story revolves around is the idea of a person's relationship with their heritage.<ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|last=Walker, Alice, 1944-|title=Everyday use|date=2004|publisher=Recording for the Blind & Dyslexic|oclc=55770645}}</ref> In the story, Dee's mother remained close to immediate family traditions, while Dee herself chose to search more deeply into her African roots. Because of her different mindset, she does not have the same ideals as Mama and Maggie, particularly in regard to cultural preservation and the best way to go about it. Dee (Wangero) only wants the family heirlooms to display in her home for their \"artistic value\" whereas Maggie and her mother cherish these items because they \"remind them of their loved ones.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> In Mama\u2019s mind, Maggie learning to make her own quilt and putting it to \"everyday use\" is preserving the culture. She believes it should be used and if they \"end up in rags,\" more quilts can simply be made. <ref name=\":1\" /> On the other hand, Dee believes the proper way to preserve her culture is to display the quilt in her home and preserve the quilt itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/topics/everyday-use/themes|title=Everyday Use Themes - eNotes.com|website=eNotes|access-date=2016-11-03}}</ref> \n\n== Point of view ==\nBecause this story is told in [[first-person narrative|first-person]] the readers \"watch\" the story unfold through the eyes and opinions of Mama.  As Maggie and Mama wait for Dee to arrive for a visit Mama's mind wanders with various thoughts and memories of Dee, giving the audience an impartial view of Dee as being self-centered and uncaring.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Farrell|first=Susan|title=Fight vs. Flight: a re-evaluation of Dee in Alice Walker's 'Everyday Use'|journal=Literature Resource Center|volume= 35|issue= 2|via=}}</ref> Due to the fact that readers are getting only one view point it is uncertain if Dee truly does exhibit these characteristics or if it is only Mama's opinion of the eldest daughter that is being forced upon us.  It is thought by some that Mama does not judge Dee, nor Maggie, accurately due to Mama's own insecurities.<ref name=\":0\" />   This is evidenced during Mama's daydream of Dee and herself on an imaginary popular talk show under the context of children who have \"made it\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://intensiveenglish1.weebly.com/uploads/1/3/0/4/13041485/everyday_use_full-text.pdf|title=Everyday Use|website=weebly.com}}</ref> Mama notes being over-weight and rough around the edges and eludes to the fact that Dee is ashamed of Mama's appearance.<ref name=\":1\" />  As Mama continues to narrate the story the audience continues to get a sense of Dee's snobbish personality, along with moments of doubt as readers see glimpses of Mamas own short comings.  As the story concludes the audience is left with the vision of Mama and Maggie remaining alone, once again, on the front lawn; happy to be rid of Dee and the exhausting perfection as they bask in the simplicity of each other and the straight forward life that has been built.\n\n===Interpretations===\nIn the essay \"'Everyday Use' and the Black Power Movement\" by [[Barbara Christian|Barbara T. Christian]], the story is discussed in reference to slavery and the black power movement. The characters in the story focus a lot on African culture and heritage. Traditional African clothing is described throughout the story, and this is a symbol of the family's heritage. The mentioning of changing names relates back to slavery as well; the characters were trying to forget about their slave names, and think of more traditional names to remember their culture and \"[affirm] their African roots.\" Christian brings to light the difference in attitudes and perspectives about a shared culture. Christian points out that to Maggie and her mother, honoring their culture meant honoring the personal past of their family, by carrying on their names or putting the quilt to use, while to Dee, that meant honoring aesthetic and ancient traditions, such as traditional African names or hanging the quilt to be seen but not utilized. It is this very realization that leads to their mother choosing to give Maggie the quilts. <ref>{{Cite book|title=\"everyday use\" and the black power movement|last=Christian|first=Barbara|publisher=Pearson|year=1994|isbn=0-13-458638-7|location=|pages=492\u2013494}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, in the essay \"'Everyday Use' as a Portrait of the Artist\" by Mary Helen Washington, the story is looked at from a more artistic and cultural perspective. The essay describes Dee as an artist who \"returns home...in order to collect the material,\" which indicates that Dee comes home for a deeper understanding of her African culture. Although she changes her name from Dee to a more Native African name and wears African clothing, she lacks real knowledge of her culture. Because of this, Mama chooses Maggie over Dee to take the quilts, because Maggie shows more appreciation and knowledge of their culture and as she said in the story was involved in the making of those quilts whereas Dee had no part in.\n\nIn the essay \u201cStylish vs. Sacred in \u201cEveryday Use\u201d written by Houston A. Baker and Charlotte Pierce-Baker Dee or Wangero is called a \u201cgoddess\u201d. After highlighting a few passages from the story, it is mentioned that Dee/ Wangero has joined the black nationalists of the 1960s and 1970s and she shows it by changing both her name and her style. The essay doesn\u2019t see Dee/ Wangero as an activist of that cause but as someone being \u201cmanipulated by the style-makers\u201d as illustrated by the scene in which she described the quilt, for which she passionately fought for later in the story, as \u201cold-fashioned and out of style\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Baker |first1=Houston A. |last2=Pierce-Baker |first2=Charlotte |title=Patches: Quilts and Community in Alice Walker's\" Everyday Use\" |journal=The Southern Review |date=1985 |volume=21 |issue=3}}</ref>\n\n===Symbolism===\n{{Original research|section|date=August 2015}}\nOne symbol found in this short story is the quilt. The quilt itself is a very meaningful item in the sense that it has history in it. It includes clothes that Dee's great grandma used to wear and pieces of uniforms that Dee's great grandpa wore during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\":1\" />  However, it also symbolizes value in [[African-Americans|Negro-American]] experience.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cash|first=Floris Barnett|date=2012-02-22|title=Kinship and Quilting: An Examination of an African-American Tradition|url=https://faculty.risd.edu/bcampbel/cash-quilting.pdf|journal=The Journal of Negro History|volume=80|pages=30\u201341|doi=10.2307/2717705|jstor=2717705|via=}}</ref> The quilt additionally adds to the idea of creative activities women came up with to pass down history from generation to generation as a part of their heritage.\n\nAnother symbol found in \u201cEveryday Use\u201d is the yard. The yard plays an important role in the story and is described as \u201can extended living room\u201d. Mama and Maggie have both tidied up the yard in preparation of Dee\u2019s visit, and sit out in the yard for hours, even after Dee\u2019s departure. The yard seems to be a place to think for Mama, where she can imagine herself being someone more conventionally attractive than she actually is, but also remember just how much she has done for her family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sparknotes.com/short-stories/everyday-use/themes.html|title=SparkNotes: Everyday Use: Themes, Motifs, and Symbols|website=www.sparknotes.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-05}}</ref>\n\n===Quilting===\nIn the African-American community, women have engaged in the tradition of quilting since they were brought to America as slaves. Quilting requires sewing pieces of cloth together to create a coverlet that functions as both a piece of art and a household item. African-American women, often regarded as voiceless \u2018mule(s) of the world\u2019, inherited such creative legacies from maternal ancestors and their quilts have come to represent black heritage.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=In Search of Our Mothers' Gardens|journal=Within the Circle: An Anthology of African American Literary Criticism from the Harlem Renaissance to the Present|first=Alice|last=Walker|publisher=(Durham and London: Duke University Press, 1994)|page=402}}</ref> The voices of African-American women have been stitched into their quilts, providing an account of their cultural past. As Sam Whitsitt observes, the quilt reflects the experiences of African-American women: the quilt is a symbol reflective of \u2018herstory, history, and tradition\u2019.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Sam|last=Whitsitt| title=In Spite of It All: A Reading of Alice Walker's \"Everyday Use\"|journal=African American Review|volume=34|date=2000|issue=3|pages=443\u2013459 (445)|doi=10.2307/2901383|jstor=2901383}}</ref> The self-expression involved in quilt-making allowed women to take control of their lives through the only medium society permitted them to use. The communal nature of quilting strengthened the bonds of sisterhood and helped to move marginalized women from enslavement to empowerment. Quilting allowed these women to assert control over the colonial practice of slavery as enforced by white hegemony. Historically, products such as cotton and indigo dye were acquired as a result of black oppression. By sewing cotton into their quilts, African-American slaves formed a bond with nature, which replaced the hegemonic relationship enforced by slavery.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Jennifer|last=Martin|title=The Quilt Threads Together Sisterhood, Empowerment and Nature in Alice Walker's ''The Colour Purple'' and \"Everyday Use\"|journal=Journal of Intercultural Disciplines|volume=14|date=2014|pages=27\u201343 (38)}}</ref>\n\nBlack slaves often attended communal Quilting Bees, which offered these oppressed women the opportunity to create social bonds unsupervised. Thus, quilting became a symbol of sisterly solidarity for African-American slaves. Additionally, quilting functioned as a response to cultural and political change, allowing opportunity for political debate. Black women used quilting as a source of activism: their quilts often depicted anti-slavery slogans. However, quilting also came to represent the hegemony of patriarchal society. Women were often forced to learn to quilt, which became a substitute for the more \u2018masculine\u2019 activity of reading and writing.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Elaine|last=Hedges|title=Quilts and Women's Culture|journal=The Radical Teacher|volume=4|date=1977|pages=7\u201310 (10)}}</ref>\n\nQuilting features in \u2018Everyday Use\u2019 as a symbol of black heritage. Mama Johnson\u2019s quilts symbolizes cross-generational female bonding: they were sewn together by Grandma Dee, passed down to and then quilted by Mama and her sister, Big Dee. One quilt even features a piece of the war uniform worn by their Great Grandpa Ezra during the Civil War. These quilts represent the creativity of the sisterhood that created them; however, Mama\u2019s daughters, Maggie and Dee, view them very differently. Dee visits her family, intending to collect the artifacts of her family\u2019s past; she wants to display them in her home with museum-like accuracy. As David Cowart notes, \u2018The visitor [Dee] rightly recognizes the quilts as part of a fragile heritage, but she fails to see the extent to which she herself has traduced that heritage.\u2019<ref>{{Cite journal|first=David|last=Cowart|title=Heritage and Deracination in Walker's \"Everyday Use\"|journal=Studies in Short Fiction|volume=33|date=1996|pages=171\u2013183 (172)}}</ref> The story\u2019s climax, which sees Mama give the quilts to Maggie, rather than Dee, is viewed as representative of the quilts\u2019 functionality. Dee views the quilts as worthy of museum display (\"Maggie can't appreciate these quilts!...She'd probably be backward enough to put them to everyday use.\"), whilst Maggie treats them as household items (\"I been saving 'em for long enough with nobody using 'em. I hope [ Maggie puts them to \u2018everyday use\u2019]!\u201d).<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Alice|last=Walker|title=Everyday Use|journal=In Love and Trouble|publisher=New York: Harvest Books, 1974)|pages= 314\u2013321 (p. 320)}}</ref> Both Mama and Maggie recognise that the quilt is meant for \u2018everyday use\u2019, as practiced by their ancestors.\n\n==Reception==\nIn critical readings of this article, the largest trend regarding this story has been to criticize Dee and the way she goes about her personal cultural reclamation.  However, Matthew Mullins argues in his essay, ''Antagonized by the Text, Or, It Takes Two to Read Alice Walker\u2019s \u201cEveryday Use\u201d'', that this perspective isn\u2019t necessarily fair.  He found in reading and teaching the text, Dee was universally a disliked character, saying that in an epiphany he found in his defense of Dee rather a pitying attitude and concluding that \u201cit was impossible to see how anyone could truly \u2018like\u2019 Dee\u201d.  This, however, he goes on to point out as not being a direct result of Dee\u2019s actions alone, but rather the framing of her actions in the story.  He argues that the text itself is what antagonizes the reader to grow this dislike of Dee: \u201cThe first-person narrative voice, the fact that Mrs. Johnson [Mama] is both narrator and character, has an immediate and forceful effect upon our perception of Dee.\u201d  Mullins backs this up by quoting another scholar, Wayne Booth, who said in his work The Rhetoric of Fiction, \u201cNo narrator [\u2026] is simply convincing: he is convincingly decent or mean, brilliant or stupid, informed, intelligent, or muddled. [\u2026] we usually find our emotional and intellectual reactions to him as a character affects our reactions to the events he relates.\u201d  Mullins points out that if Dee herself, or even Maggie, were the narrators of the story, we would come away with a completely different perspective on probably all of the characters.  \u201cThe text actively prevents us from identifying with Dee,\u201d and this perspective has shaped the scholarly resources on this text since it came out.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mullins|first1=Matthew|title=Antagonized by the Text, Or, It Takes Two to Read Alice Walker's 'Everyday Use'|journal=Journal of the Southern Comparative Literature Association|date=May 2013|volume=37|pages=37\u201353|url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=mzh&AN=2013392796&site=ehost-live|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJoe Sarnowski, in his article ''Destroying to Save: Idealism and Pragmatism in Alice Walker\u2019s \u2018Everyday Use\u2019'', also points out this discrepancy but taking it one step further, arguing that even though it would be naive to claim Dee doesn\u2019t have faults, she, \u201cmore than any other character in the story, identifies and pursues corrective measures against the oppression of African-American society and culture.\u201d  Her fault, Sarnowski says, is in not realizing how idealism and pragmatism are \u201cintertwined\u201d and how \u201cprivileging one undermines both\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sarnowski|first1=Joe|title=Destroying to Save: Idealism and Pragmatism in Alice Walker's 'Everyday Use'|journal=Papers on Language and Literature: A Journal for Scholars and Critics of Language and Literature|date=2012|volume=48|issue=3|pages=269\u2013286|url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=mzh&AN=2012582914&site=ehost-live|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Walker, Alice. \"Everyday Use.\" ''The Story and Its Writer''. Ed. Anna Charters. Compact 8th edn. Boston: Bedfor/St. Martin's, 2011. 852\u2013858. Print.\n* Whitsitt, Sam. \"In Spite of It All: A Reading of Alice Walker's 'Everyday Use.'\" ''African American Review'' 34.3 (2000): 443. Web. October 24, 2011.\n* \"Everyday Use.\" sparknotes.com. sparknotes, n.d. Web. October 24, 2011.\n\n{{Alice Walker}}\n\n[[Category:1973 short stories]]\n[[Category:American short stories]]\n[[Category:African-American short stories]]\n[[Category:Southern United States in fiction]]\n[[Category:Works by Alice Walker]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=September 2014}}\n{{original research|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name             = Everyday Use\n| image            = Everyday Use (Alice Walker short story).jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption    = \n| author           = [[Alice Walker]]\n| cover_artist     = \n| subject          = \n| genre            = [[Short story]]\n| publisher        = \n| pub_date         = 1973 (as part of ''In Love and Trouble'')\n| media_type       = \n| pages            = \n| isbn =  978-0-8135-2075-9\n| oclc             = 29028043\n| dewey            = \n| congress         = \n| preceded_by      = \n| followed_by      = \n| italic title     = no\n}}<!--\n{{Infobox Film\n| name           =  Everyday Use\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Bruce Schwartz]]\n| writer         = Bruce Schwartz<br />'''Short story'''[[Alice Walker]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Karen ffolkes]]<br />[[Rachel Luttrell]]\n| music          = [[Rocky Davis]]\n| cinematography = [[Brian C. Glover]]\n| editing        = [[Stephen Goetsch]]<br />[[Kristofer Lindquist]]\n| studio         = Films for the Humanities and Sciences\n| distributor    =  \n| released       =  \n| runtime        =  \n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[English language|English]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}-->\n\n\"'''Everyday Use'''\" is a widely studied and frequently anthologized short story by [[Alice Walker]]. It was first published in 1973 as part of Walker's short story collection ''In Love and Trouble''.\n\nThe short story is told in  [[first-person narrative|first person]] by \"Mama\", an African-American woman living in the [[Deep South]] with one of her two daughters. The story follows the differences between Mrs. Johnson and her shy younger daughter Maggie, who both still adhere to traditional black culture in the rural South, and her educated, successful daughter Dee, or \"Wangero\" as she prefers to be called, who takes a different route to reclaiming her cultural identity.\n\nA film version was released in 2005.\n\n==<span lang=\"fa\" dir=\"rtl\">Plot</span>==\nThe story opens on Mama waiting in the yard for her oldest daughter, Dee\u2019s, visit.  She reflects on the differences between Dee and Maggie, her youngest daughter, and knows that Maggie will be anxious and self-conscious around Dee. Maggie was burned in a house fire that happened more than a decade ago. Mama carried her out in her arms, as Dee watched the house burn. Dee was seemingly happy and excited about the fire, due to her extreme dislike for the house. The narrator continues to paint a picture of Maggie as helpless and rather awkward, whereas Dee is beautiful and seems to have had an easier time in life.\n\nDee left home to pursue an education in Augusta, afforded to her by Mama and the community\u2019s fund raising efforts. Mama never attended school past second grade, and Maggie has a very limited reading ability, so Dee\u2019s education is a stark difference and Mama seems to feel that starkness, commenting, \u201clike dimwits, we seemed about to understand\u201d. <ref name=\":1\" />  Mama discusses the physical differences between the three: her own manly looks, Maggie\u2019s timid disposition, and Dee\u2019s own nice hair, full figure, and stylish way of dress.\n\nWhen Dee finally arrives, she is accompanied by a man, whom Mama refers to as Hakim-a-barber. Mama and Maggie are a little taken aback by Dee's wild-looking outfit and her African greeting to them. Dee takes photos of Mama and Maggie in front of the house, and the greetings are stiff and unfamiliar. Dee informs her mother that she has now changed her name to Wangero Leewanika Kemanjo in order to protest the oppression and cultural white washing Black Americans faced. Mama rejects this, telling Dee she was named after her Aunt Dicie, who in turn was named after Grandma Dee, and that the name went on through the generations. Dee gives Mama the option of not using her new name, and Mama concludes that Hakim-a-barber must be related to a family of Muslims down the road. Hakim-a-barber says he accepts some of the doctrines of his beef-raising family, but is not interested in farming or herding as a profession.\n\nMama does not know whether Hakim-a-barber and Dee are married, nor does she ask. Hakim-a-barber has a restricted diet to follow, but Dee digs into the food Mama made. She begins asking for things around the house, like the top of a butter churn, and eventually she asks for two quilts as well.  This quilt in particular is one that Mama had promised to Maggie, and Dee\u2019s persistence frustrates Mama which develops into an argument between Mama and Dee. Dee argues that by using the quilt as a normal item, in \u201ceveryday use\u201d, the quilt will be ruined, and the cultural importance will be lost. Mama would rather the item be used practically by her family and be ruined than have it sit on a shelf or be hung on a wall as a piece of art, and as Dee readies to leave, she tells Mama that Mama doesn\u2019t understand her own heritage.  She adds that Mama should try and improve, and that there is a new path for Black Americans to follow. Maggie and Mama sit in the yard after watching them drive off, until bedtime.\n\n==Characters==\n* '''Dee''' \u2013 She is an educated African-American woman and the eldest daughter of Mama. She seeks to embrace her cultural identity through changing her name from Dee to Wangero Leewanika Kemanjo (an African name), marrying a Muslim man, and acquiring artifacts from Mama's house to put on display, an approach that puts her at odds with Mama and Maggie.  She is physically beautiful and is described as having a great sense of style.\n* '''Mama''' \u2013 She is described as a \"large, big-boned woman with rough, man-working hands.\"<ref name=\":1\" />  She enjoys her lifestyle (especially milking cows) and did not receive an education past second grade.\n* '''Maggie''' \u2013 Described by Mama as dull and unattractive, the youngest daughter Maggie has burn scars and marks from the burning down of their prior home, and is very nervous and self-conscious because of it. She leads a simple and traditional life with her mother in the South while her elder sister, Dee, is away at school.  She has very limited reading ability, unlike her sister Dee.\n* '''Hakim-a-barber''' \u2013 Dee\u2019s partner, he is referred to as \"Asalamalakim\", which is a Muslim greeting, throughout the story because he is Muslim.  Eventually he tells Mama to call him \"Hakim-a-barber\" due to Mama being unable to pronounce his real name.\n\n\n== Themes ==\nOne of the primary themes that the story revolves around is the idea of a person's relationship to their heritage.<ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|last=Walker, Alice, 1944-|title=Everyday use|date=2004|publisher=Recording for the Blind & Dyslexic|oclc=55770645}}</ref> In the story, Dee's mother remained close to immediate family traditions, while Dee herself chose to search more deeply into her African roots. Because of her different mindset, she does not have the same ideals as Mama and Maggie, particularly in regard to cultural preservation and the best way to go about it. Dee (Wangero) only wants the family heirlooms to display in her home for their \"artistic value\" whereas Maggie and her mother cherish these items because they \"remind them of their loved ones.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> In Mama\u2019s mind, Maggie learning to make her own quilt and putting it to \"everyday use\" is preserving the culture. She believes it should be used and if they \"end up in rags,\" more quilts can simply be made. <ref name=\":1\" /> On the other hand, Dee believes the proper way to preserve her culture is to display the quilt in her home and preserve the quilt itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/topics/everyday-use/themes|title=Everyday Use Themes - eNotes.com|website=eNotes|access-date=2016-11-03}}</ref> \n\n== Point of view ==\nBecause this story is told in [[first-person narrative|first-person]] the readers \"watch\" the story unfold through the eyes and opinions of Mama.  As Maggie and Mama wait for Dee to arrive for a visit Mama's mind wanders with various thoughts and memories of Dee, giving the audience an impartial view of Dee as being self-centered and uncaring.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Farrell|first=Susan|title=Fight vs. Flight: a re-evaluation of Dee in Alice Walker's 'Everyday Use'|journal=Literature Resource Center|volume= 35|issue= 2|via=}}</ref> Due to the fact that readers are getting only one view point it is uncertain if Dee truly does exhibit these characteristics or if it is only Mama's opinion of the eldest daughter that is being forced upon us.  It is thought by some that Mama does not judge Dee, nor Maggie, accurately due to Mama's own insecurities.<ref name=\":0\" />   This is evidenced during Mama's daydream of Dee and herself on an imaginary popular talk show under the context of children who have \"made it\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://intensiveenglish1.weebly.com/uploads/1/3/0/4/13041485/everyday_use_full-text.pdf|title=Everyday Use|website=weebly.com}}</ref> Mama notes being over-weight and rough around the edges and eludes to the fact that Dee is ashamed of Mama's appearance.<ref name=\":1\" />  As Mama continues to narrate the story the audience continues to get a sense of Dee's snobbish personality, along with moments of doubt as readers see glimpses of Mamas own short comings.  As the story concludes the audience is left with the vision of Mama and Maggie remaining alone, once again, on the front lawn; happy to be rid of Dee and the exhausting perfection as they bask in the simplicity of each other and the straight forward life that has been built.\n\n===Interpretations===\nIn the essay \"'Everyday Use' and the Black Power Movement\" by [[Barbara Christian|Barbara T. Christian]], the story is discussed in reference to slavery and the black power movement. The characters in the story focus a lot on African culture and heritage. Traditional African clothing is described throughout the story, and this is a symbol of the family's heritage. The mentioning of changing names relates back to slavery as well; the characters were trying to forget about their slave names, and think of more traditional names to remember their culture and \"[affirm] their African roots.\" Christian brings to light the difference in attitudes and perspectives about a shared culture. Christian points out that to Maggie and her mother, honoring their culture meant honoring the personal past of their family, by carrying on their names or putting the quilt to use, while to Dee, that meant honoring aesthetic and ancient traditions, such as traditional African names or hanging the quilt to be seen but not utilized. It is this very realization that leads to their mother choosing to give Maggie the quilts. <ref>{{Cite book|title=\"everyday use\" and the black power movement|last=Christian|first=Barbara|publisher=Pearson|year=1994|isbn=0-13-458638-7|location=|pages=492\u2013494}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, in the essay \"'Everyday Use' as a Portrait of the Artist\" by Mary Helen Washington, the story is looked at from a more artistic and cultural perspective. The essay describes Dee as an artist who \"returns home...in order to collect the material,\" which indicates that Dee comes home for a deeper understanding of her African culture. Although she changes her name from Dee to a more Native African name and wears African clothing, she lacks real knowledge of her culture. Because of this, Mama chooses Maggie over Dee to take the quilts, because Maggie shows more appreciation and knowledge of their culture and as she said in the story was involved in the making of those quilts whereas Dee had no part in.\n\nIn the essay \u201cStylish vs. Sacred in \u201cEveryday Use\u201d written by Houston A. Baker and Charlotte Pierce-Baker Dee or Wangero is called a \u201cgoddess\u201d. After highlighting a few passages from the story, it is mentioned that Dee/ Wangero has joined the black nationalists of the 1960s and 1970s and she shows it by changing both her name and her style. The essay doesn\u2019t see Dee/ Wangero as an activist of that cause but as someone being \u201cmanipulated by the style-makers\u201d as illustrated by the scene in which she described the quilt, for which she passionately fought for later in the story, as \u201cold-fashioned and out of style\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Baker |first1=Houston A. |last2=Pierce-Baker |first2=Charlotte |title=Patches: Quilts and Community in Alice Walker's\" Everyday Use\" |journal=The Southern Review |date=1985 |volume=21 |issue=3}}</ref>\n\n===Symbolism===\n{{Original research|section|date=August 2015}}\nOne symbol found in this short story is the quilt. The quilt itself is a very meaningful item in the sense that it has history in it. It includes clothes that Dee's great grandma used to wear and pieces of uniforms that Dee's great grandpa wore during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name=\":1\" />  However, it also symbolizes value in [[African-Americans|Negro-American]] experience.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cash|first=Floris Barnett|date=2012-02-22|title=Kinship and Quilting: An Examination of an African-American Tradition|url=https://faculty.risd.edu/bcampbel/cash-quilting.pdf|journal=The Journal of Negro History|volume=80|pages=30\u201341|doi=10.2307/2717705|jstor=2717705|via=}}</ref> The quilt additionally adds to the idea of creative activities women came up with to pass down history from generation to generation as a part of their heritage.\n\nAnother symbol found in \u201cEveryday Use\u201d is the yard. The yard plays an important role in the story and is described as \u201can extended living room\u201d. Mama and Maggie have both tidied up the yard in preparation of Dee\u2019s visit, and sit out in the yard for hours, even after Dee\u2019s departure. The yard seems to be a place to think for Mama, where she can imagine herself being someone more conventionally attractive than she actually is, but also remember just how much she has done for her family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sparknotes.com/short-stories/everyday-use/themes.html|title=SparkNotes: Everyday Use: Themes, Motifs, and Symbols|website=www.sparknotes.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-05}}</ref>\n\n===Quilting===\nIn the African-American community, women have engaged in the tradition of quilting since they were brought to America as slaves. Quilting requires sewing pieces of cloth together to create a coverlet that functions as both a piece of art and a household item. African-American women, often regarded as voiceless \u2018mule(s) of the world\u2019, inherited such creative legacies from maternal ancestors and their quilts have come to represent black heritage.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=In Search of Our Mothers' Gardens|journal=Within the Circle: An Anthology of African American Literary Criticism from the Harlem Renaissance to the Present|first=Alice|last=Walker|publisher=(Durham and London: Duke University Press, 1994)|page=402}}</ref> The voices of African-American women have been stitched into their quilts, providing an account of their cultural past. As Sam Whitsitt observes, the quilt reflects the experiences of African-American women: the quilt is a symbol reflective of \u2018herstory, history, and tradition\u2019.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Sam|last=Whitsitt| title=In Spite of It All: A Reading of Alice Walker's \"Everyday Use\"|journal=African American Review|volume=34|date=2000|issue=3|pages=443\u2013459 (445)|doi=10.2307/2901383|jstor=2901383}}</ref> The self-expression involved in quilt-making allowed women to take control of their lives through the only medium society permitted them to use. The communal nature of quilting strengthened the bonds of sisterhood and helped to move marginalized women from enslavement to empowerment. Quilting allowed these women to assert control over the colonial practice of slavery as enforced by white hegemony. Historically, products such as cotton and indigo dye were acquired as a result of black oppression. By sewing cotton into their quilts, African-American slaves formed a bond with nature, which replaced the hegemonic relationship enforced by slavery.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Jennifer|last=Martin|title=The Quilt Threads Together Sisterhood, Empowerment and Nature in Alice Walker's ''The Colour Purple'' and \"Everyday Use\"|journal=Journal of Intercultural Disciplines|volume=14|date=2014|pages=27\u201343 (38)}}</ref>\n\nBlack slaves often attended communal Quilting Bees, which offered these oppressed women the opportunity to create social bonds unsupervised. Thus, quilting became a symbol of sisterly solidarity for African-American slaves. Additionally, quilting functioned as a response to cultural and political change, allowing opportunity for political debate. Black women used quilting as a source of activism: their quilts often depicted anti-slavery slogans. However, quilting also came to represent the hegemony of patriarchal society. Women were often forced to learn to quilt, which became a substitute for the more \u2018masculine\u2019 activity of reading and writing.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Elaine|last=Hedges|title=Quilts and Women's Culture|journal=The Radical Teacher|volume=4|date=1977|pages=7\u201310 (10)}}</ref>\n\nQuilting features in \u2018Everyday Use\u2019 as a symbol of black heritage. Mama Johnson\u2019s quilts symbolizes cross-generational female bonding: they were sewn together by Grandma Dee, passed down to and then quilted by Mama and her sister, Big Dee. One quilt even features a piece of the war uniform worn by their Great Grandpa Ezra during the Civil War. These quilts represent the creativity of the sisterhood that created them; however, Mama\u2019s daughters, Maggie and Dee, view them very differently. Dee visits her family, intending to collect the artifacts of her family\u2019s past; she wants to display them in her home with museum-like accuracy. As David Cowart notes, \u2018The visitor [Dee] rightly recognizes the quilts as part of a fragile heritage, but she fails to see the extent to which she herself has traduced that heritage.\u2019<ref>{{Cite journal|first=David|last=Cowart|title=Heritage and Deracination in Walker's \"Everyday Use\"|journal=Studies in Short Fiction|volume=33|date=1996|pages=171\u2013183 (172)}}</ref> The story\u2019s climax, which sees Mama give the quilts to Maggie, rather than Dee, is viewed as representative of the quilts\u2019 functionality. Dee views the quilts as worthy of museum display (\"Maggie can't appreciate these quilts!...She'd probably be backward enough to put them to everyday use.\"), whilst Maggie treats them as household items (\"I been saving 'em for long enough with nobody using 'em. I hope [ Maggie puts them to \u2018everyday use\u2019]!\u201d).<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Alice|last=Walker|title=Everyday Use|journal=In Love and Trouble|publisher=New York: Harvest Books, 1974)|pages= 314\u2013321 (p. 320)}}</ref> Both Mama and Maggie recognise that the quilt is meant for \u2018everyday use\u2019, as practiced by their ancestors.\n\n==Reception==\nIn critical readings of this article, the largest trend regarding this story has been to criticize Dee and the way she goes about her personal cultural reclamation.  However, Matthew Mullins argues in his essay, ''Antagonized by the Text, Or, It Takes Two to Read Alice Walker\u2019s \u201cEveryday Use\u201d'', that this perspective isn\u2019t necessarily fair.  He found in reading and teaching the text, Dee was universally a disliked character, saying that in an epiphany he found in his defense of Dee rather a pitying attitude and concluding that \u201cit was impossible to see how anyone could truly \u2018like\u2019 Dee\u201d.  This, however, he goes on to point out as not being a direct result of Dee\u2019s actions alone, but rather the framing of her actions in the story.  He argues that the text itself is what antagonizes the reader to grow this dislike of Dee: \u201cThe first-person narrative voice, the fact that Mrs. Johnson [Mama] is both narrator and character, has an immediate and forceful effect upon our perception of Dee.\u201d  Mullins backs this up by quoting another scholar, Wayne Booth, who said in his work The Rhetoric of Fiction, \u201cNo narrator [\u2026] is simply convincing: he is convincingly decent or mean, brilliant or stupid, informed, intelligent, or muddled. [\u2026] we usually find our emotional and intellectual reactions to him as a character affects our reactions to the events he relates.\u201d  Mullins points out that if Dee herself, or even Maggie, were the narrators of the story, we would come away with a completely different perspective on probably all of the characters.  \u201cThe text actively prevents us from identifying with Dee,\u201d and this perspective has shaped the scholarly resources on this text since it came out.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mullins|first1=Matthew|title=Antagonized by the Text, Or, It Takes Two to Read Alice Walker's 'Everyday Use'|journal=Journal of the Southern Comparative Literature Association|date=May 2013|volume=37|pages=37\u201353|url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=mzh&AN=2013392796&site=ehost-live|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJoe Sarnowski, in his article ''Destroying to Save: Idealism and Pragmatism in Alice Walker\u2019s \u2018Everyday Use\u2019'', also points out this discrepancy but taking it one step further, arguing that even though it would be naive to claim Dee doesn\u2019t have faults, she, \u201cmore than any other character in the story, identifies and pursues corrective measures against the oppression of African-American society and culture.\u201d  Her fault, Sarnowski says, is in not realizing how idealism and pragmatism are \u201cintertwined\u201d and how \u201cprivileging one undermines both\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sarnowski|first1=Joe|title=Destroying to Save: Idealism and Pragmatism in Alice Walker's 'Everyday Use'|journal=Papers on Language and Literature: A Journal for Scholars and Critics of Language and Literature|date=2012|volume=48|issue=3|pages=269\u2013286|url=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=mzh&AN=2012582914&site=ehost-live|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Walker, Alice. \"Everyday Use.\" ''The Story and Its Writer''. Ed. Anna Charters. Compact 8th edn. Boston: Bedfor/St. Martin's, 2011. 852\u2013858. Print.\n* Whitsitt, Sam. \"In Spite of It All: A Reading of Alice Walker's 'Everyday Use.'\" ''African American Review'' 34.3 (2000): 443. Web. October 24, 2011.\n* \"Everyday Use.\" sparknotes.com. sparknotes, n.d. Web. October 24, 2011.\n\n{{Alice Walker}}\n\n[[Category:1973 short stories]]\n[[Category:American short stories]]\n[[Category:African-American short stories]]\n[[Category:Southern United States in fiction]]\n[[Category:Works by Alice Walker]]\n", "name_user": "Angiekullira", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThemes:It makes more sense to have a relationship with something.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Everyday_Use"}
{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on games and sports", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports|2=Talk:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on games and sports#Requested move 10 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{current related||2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Impact of coronavirus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has caused the most significant disruption to the [[2020 in sports|worldwide sporting calendar]] since [[World War II]]. [[Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Across the world]] and to varying degrees, sports events have been cancelled or postponed.<ref name=\"BBC overview\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: How the virus has impacted sporting events around the world |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/51605235 |website=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=How the coronavirus is affecting sports leagues and events |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-09/coronavirus-latest-news-sports-world |website=Los Angeles Times |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nSpectators have no games to watch and players no games to play. In response, players are being encouraged to \"play for lives\" rather than for points. Former footballer [[Craig Foster]], for example, is using his connections in the sporting world to set up a volunteer workforce for charities helping those in need.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fitzsimmons |first=Caitlin |url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/health-and-wellness/craig-foster-rallying-sport-to-play-for-lives-in-volunteer-response-20200404-p54h0t.html |title=Craig Foster rallying sport to 'play for lives' in volunteer response |date=5 April 2020 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Multiple event competitions==\nThe [[2020 Arctic Winter Games]] were cancelled,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/arctic-winter-games-cancelled-coronavirus-1.5490055 |title='Shocked and disappointed': Arctic Winter Games cancelled due to coronavirus concerns &#124; CBC News}}</ref> while the [[2020 ASEAN Para Games]] were postponed.<ref name=philippinencaa>{{cite news |last1=Villar |first1=Joey |title=NCAA succumbs to coronavirus scare, postpones all high school games |url=https://www.philstar.com/sports/2020/02/07/1991189/ncaa-succumbs-coronavirus-scare-postpones-all-high-school-games |accessdate=7 February 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=7 February 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Summer Olympics===\nThe [[2020 Summer Olympics]] were scheduled to take place in [[Tokyo]] starting at the end of July. Due to the upcoming Olympic games, the [[Government of Japan|country's government]] had taken extra precautions to help minimize the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Japan|outbreak's worst impact]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/abe-brushes-worries-virus-impact-tokyo-olympics-68719487 |title=Abe brushes aside worries of virus impact on Tokyo Olympics |first=A. B. C. |last=News |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/01/tokyo-2020-organisers-fight-false-rumours-olympics-cancelled-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Tokyo 2020 organisers fight false rumours Olympics cancelled over coronavirus crisis |first=Justin |last=McCurry |date=1 February 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> However, qualifying events were being canceled or postponed almost daily.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sltrib.com/sports/2020/03/10/coronavirus-already/ |title=Coronavirus already causing Olympic chaos at qualifying events |first=Ellingworth |last=Ellingworth |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Salt Lake Tribune}}</ref> There had been suggestions that the 2020 Olympics be moved to [[London]] in light of the situation, but Governor of Tokyo [[Yuriko Koike]] indicated at the end of February 2020 that such a move was not under consideration at the moment.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Keh |first=Andrew |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/sports/olympics/tokyo-coronavirus.html |title=Grappling With Coronavirus, Tokyo Olympic Leaders Have No Good Options |date=26 February 2020 |work=The New York Times|access-date=25 March 2020 |last2=Dooley |first2=Ben |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-02-21/tokyo-governor-2020-olympics-coronavirus |title=Tokyo governor: 'Inappropriate' to suggest moving 2020 Olympics because of coronavirus |date=21 February 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe traditional [[Olympic flame]] lighting ceremony in [[Olympia, Greece]], to mark the start of the [[2020 Summer Olympics torch relay]] was held on 12 March without spectators.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-2020-flame/tokyo-2020-torch-lit-behind-closed-doors-in-ancient-olympia-idUSKBN20Z1EO |title=Tokyo 2020 torch lit behind closed doors in ancient Olympia |website=Reuters |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, it was announced that the Summer Olympics would be postponed to 2021, still to be held in Tokyo. Six days later, the Olympics made a reschedule date to twelve months from the original scheduled dates of 24 July to 9 August 2020, to 23 July to 8 August 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/fc044c3fa987a60534a804046215f3de |title=On hold: Tokyo Olympics postponed to 2021 |date=24 March 2020 |website=AP NEWS|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=IOC_2021_Dates>{{cite web |url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-ipc-tokyo-2020-organising-committee-and-tokyo-metropolitan-government-announce-new-dates-for-the-olympic-and-paralympic-games-tokyo-2020 |title=IOC, IPC, Tokyo 2020 Organising Committee and Tokyo Metropolitan Government Announce New Dates for the Olympic and Paralympic Games Tokyo 2020 |date=30 March 2020 |website=olympic.org |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Gaelic games===\nThe [[Gaelic games]] of [[Gaelic football|football]], [[hurling]], [[camogie]] and [[ladies' Gaelic football|ladies' football]] \u2013 mostly played in [[Ireland]] \u2013 saw all competitions suspended from 12 March 2020. The [[2020 National Hurling League|National Hurling League]], [[2020 National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]], [[2020 National Camogie League|National Camogie League]] and [[2020 Ladies' National Football League|Ladies' National Football League]] were suspended, with competitions not intended to resume until 29 March at the earliest.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gaa.ie/news-archive/news/gaa-camogie-association-and-the-lgfa-suspend-all-activity/ |title=GAA, Camogie Association, and the LGFA suspend all activity |website=www.gaa.ie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.balls.ie/gaa/gaa-camogie-association-gaa-suspend-activities-march-29th-427885 |title=GAA, Camogie Association And LGFA Suspend All Activity Until March 29th |first=P. J. |last=Browne |website=Balls.ie}}</ref> On 17 March, the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) confirmed that [[2020 Connacht Senior Football Championship|the opening fixture]] of the [[2020 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] \u2013 due to have taken place at [[Gaelic Park]] in [[Riverdale, Bronx|The Bronx]] on 3 May \u2013 had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/gaa/galway-and-new-york-clash-first-major-casualty-of-pandemic-988773.html |title=Galway and New York clash first major casualty of pandemic |work=[[Irish Examiner]] |first=Eoghan |last=Cormican |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nOn 11 March 2020, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) \u2014 the main U.S. sanctioning body for [[College athletics in the United States|college athletics]] \u2014 initially announced that its winter-semester championships and tournaments, including its popular [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's basketball tournament]] (widely known as \"March Madness\"), would be conducted with \"only essential staff and limited family attendance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2020/03/11/ncaa-tournament-fans-banned-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/5024027002/ |title=NCAA men's and women's basketball tournaments will not include fans due to coronavirus concerns |first=Tom |last=Schad |newspaper=USA Today |date=11 March 2020|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> However, the following day, the NCAA announced that all remaining championship events for the 2019\u201320 academic year would be cancelled entirely. This marked the first cancellation in the 81-year history of the NCAA basketball tournament.<ref name=\"NCAA cancellations\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships |publisher=NCAA |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>  This ''de facto'' created a [[mythical national championship]] situation in college basketball and hockey, with such winners being crowned by polls.  Other American multi-sports organizations; [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.naia.org/general/2019-20/releases/spring-sports-cancelled|title=NAIA Cancels Spring 2020 Sports Season|date=16 March 2020|website=NAIA}}</ref> [[NJCAA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://njcaa.org/general/2019-20/releases/20200316k2au00|title=NJCAA COVID-19 update - spring sports season cancelled|date=16 March 2020|website=NJCAA}}</ref> [[CCCAA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cccaasports.org/coronavirus/spring_sports_cancellation|title=CCCAA cancels spring sports, restores seasons of competition for student-athletes and announces recruiting ban|date=19 March 2020|website=CCCAA}}</ref> have also cancelled their seasons.  Additionally the Community College level sports governing bodies restored the season of eligibility to athletes who had already participated in the 2020 spring season.\n\n===BUCS===\nOn 16 March 2020, [[British Universities and Colleges Sport]], the UK organisation for university sport, announced that all fixtures from 17 March to 1 April would not take place. Some individual events, like the [[orienteering]] and [[windsurfing]] championships were cancelled entirely, while others were postponed indefinitely.<ref name=\"BUCS Cancellations\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bucs.org.uk/update-covid-19-coronavirus.html |title=BUCS Statement regarding CoVid-19 |publisher=BUCS |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\nIn the Philippines, [[NCAA Season 95]] and [[UAAP Season 82]] were both indefinitely suspended.<ref name=\"philippinencaa\" /><ref name=\"pba\" /> NCAA Season 95 was terminated on 19 March after the [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|then community quarantine in Luzon]] was upgraded to an \"enhanced community quarantine\", in effect a lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/university/ncaa/255125-season-95-terminated-coronavirus-luzon-lockdown|title=NCAA Season 95 terminated|last=Go|first=Beatrice|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> UAAP Season 82 was canceled on 7 April, after the enhanced community quarantine was extended to 30 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/sports/2020/4/7/uaap-cancels-season-82-covid-pandemic.html|title=UAAP board cancels Season 82 due to COVID-19 pandemic|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Alpine skiing==\nThe [[2019\u201320 FIS Alpine Ski World Cup]] ended two weeks earlier after World Cup races in Sweden, Slovenia, and Italy scheduled for March were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/international-ski-federation/news-multimedia/news/fis-alpine-ski-world-cup-finals-cortina-ita-cancelled |title=FIS Alpine Ski World Cup Finals in Cortina Cancelled |date=6 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/alpine-skiing/alpine-news-multimedia/news-multimedia/news/test2/audi-fis-women-s-world-cup-races-in-are-swe-cancelled |title=Audi FIS Women's World Cup races in Are (SWE) Cancelled |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/alpine-skiing/alpine-news-multimedia/news-multimedia/news/test2/audi-fis-men-s-world-cup-races-in-kranjska-gora-slo-cancelled |title=Audi FIS Men's World Cup races in Kranjska Gora (SLO) Cancelled |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> An earlier February World Cup race was moved from China to Austria.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/skiing/story/_/id/28600579/world-cup-ski-races-canceled-china-move-austria |title=World Cup ski races canceled in China move to Austria |date=30 January 2020 |website=[[ESPN]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=29 March 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Archery==\nThe opening stage of the [[2020 Archery World Cup]], scheduled to be held in [[Guatemala City]], [[Guatemala]] from 20 to 26 April, was postponed. Other events postponed include the [[Pan American Archery Championships]], which were scheduled to be held in [[Monterrey]], [[Mexico]], from 23 to 29 March, and the [[European Para-Archery Championships]], which were scheduled to be held in [[Olbia]], [[Italy]], from 18 to 26 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Archery Suspended Until 30 April due to COVID-19 Outbreak |url=https://worldarchery.org/news/178285/international-archery-suspended-until-30-april-due-covid-19-outbreak-1 |website=World Archery |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Association football==\nOn 13 March 2020, FIFA announced that clubs did not have to release players to their national teams during the international windows of March and April 2020, while players also had the option to decline a call-up without any consequences. FIFA also recommended that all international matches during these windows be postponed, though the final decision was left to the competition organisers or member associations for [[Exhibition game#International football|friendly]] matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/fifa-statement-x8681 |title=FIFA statement |work=[[FIFA]] |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 10 April, [[2020 \u00ddokary Liga]],<ref>[https://turkmenportal.com/en/blog/26677/19-aprelya-vozobnovitsya-chempionat-turkmenistana-po-futbolu Turkmenistan Higher League to resume on April 19]</ref> [[2020 Tajikistan Higher League]], [[2020 Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian Premier League]] and [[2019\u201320 Liga Primera de Nicaragua|Liga Primera de Nicaragua]] were the only four top flight national football leagues not suspended.<ref>[http://www.la-razon.com/marcas/futbol-covid-19-nicaragua-bielorrusia_0_3338666136.html En el planeta f\u00fatbol, solo Nicaragua y Bielorrusia contin\u00faan con sus torneos] la-razon.com {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2020, FIFA announced that the [[2020 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup]], scheduled to be held in Panama and Costa Rica in August, and the [[2020 FIFA U-17 Women's World Cup]], scheduled to be held in India in November, would be postponed and rescheduled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/dedicated-covid-19-working-group-proposes-recommendations-after-first-meeting|title=Dedicated COVID-19 working group proposes recommendations after first meeting|publisher=FIFA.com|date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\nOn 17 March 2020, [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] announced that the [[2020 African Nations Championship]] had been postponed to a later date due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cafonline.com/news-center/news/statement-on-total-chan-cameroon-2020 |title=Statement on Total CHAN Cameroon 2020 |publisher=CAF |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nIn China, the [[2020 Chinese Super League]] was postponed as a result of the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecfa.cn/lstz/20200130/28537.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u8db3\u534f\u5173\u4e8e2020\u8d5b\u5b63\u56fd\u5185\u8db3\u7403\u8d5b\u4e8b\u5ef6\u671f\u5f00\u59cb\u7684\u516c\u544a |work=Chinese Football Association |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=zh}}</ref> In Hong Kong, the [[2020 Lunar New Year Cup]] was cancelled on 23 January.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chan |first1=Kin-wa |title=Wuhan coronavirus: Lunar New Year Cup cancelled by government just hours after HKFA promotes the event |url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/hong-kong/article/3047415/wuhan-virus-lunar-new-year-cup-go-ahead-hong-kong-despite |website=South China Morning Post |date=23 January 2020 |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref> Other leagues in Asia were affected, including South Korea's [[2020 K League 1|K League 1]] and Japan's [[2020 J1 League|J1 League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=K-League season postponed as COVID-19 spreads in South Korea |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/24/soccer/k-league-season-postponed-covid-19-spreads-south-korea/#.Xms5EqgzaUk |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Japan Times |agency=Associated Press |date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Orlowitz |first1=Dan |title=Amid COVID-19 outbreak, J. League postpones all matches until March 15 |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/25/soccer/j-league/jleague-cancels-levain-cup-coronavirus/#.Xms5FagzaUk |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Japan Times |date=25 February 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 AFC Champions League|AFC Champions League]] and [[2020 AFC Cup|AFC Cup]] was also impacted, a number of group stage and play-off matches being postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-champions-league/latest/news/afc-competitions-update |title=AFC Competitions update |publisher=Asian Football Confederation |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2020, FIFA and AFC announced that [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] matches due to take place in March and June 2020 were postponed to later dates due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=AFC |date=9 March 2020}}</ref> Play-off matches between South Korea and China in the [[2020 AFC Women's Olympic Qualifying Tournament]] were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=FIFA.com |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn India, the remaining [[2019\u201320 I-League|I-League]] matches were postponed and the [[2020 Indian Super League Final|Indian Super League final]] was played behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-aiff.com/article/aiff-statement-10 |title=AIFF Statement |publisher=All India Football Federation |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nIn Europe, various knockout matches in the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] were played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] in February and March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2639297.html |title=Update on UEFA competition matches being played this week |work=UEFA |date=26 February 2020 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2640496.html |title=Update on UEFA competition matches |work=UEFA |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> On 12 March 2020, [[UEFA]] announced that the elite qualification round of the men and women's under-17 and under-19 youth international tournaments had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2640886.html |title=Postponement of Youth tournaments |publisher=UEFA.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, UEFA postponed all fixtures for the following week in the Champions League, Europa League and [[2019\u201320 UEFA Youth League|Youth League]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2641054.html |title=All of next week's UEFA matches postponed |work=UEFA |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany of the domestic European leagues were impacted in February and March 2020. After various fixtures were rescheduled or played behind closed doors, [[2019\u201320 Serie A|Serie A]] was postponed on 9 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/51808683 |title=Coronavirus: All sport in Italy to be suspended because of outbreak |date=9 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> On 12 March, [[2019\u201320 La Liga|La Liga]] and the [[2019\u201320 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] were suspended for at least two weeks after a [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] basketball player tested positive for the virus, which resulted in Real Madrid's footballers being put in quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=Real Madrid players in quarantine and La Liga suspended due to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/12/real-madrid-players-in-quarantine-and-la-liga-suspended-due-to-coronavirus |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2019\u201320 Eredivisie|Eredivisie]] was also suspended,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/246406552/streep-door-eredivisie-en-interlands-van-oranje-in-maart |title=Streep door Eredivisie \u00e9n interlands van Oranje in maart |date=12 March 2020 |website=Telegraaf}}</ref> while [[2019\u201320 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]] and the [[2019\u201320 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] followed suit shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"BBC overview\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lfp.fr/Articles/COMMUNIQU\u00c9S/2020/03/13/communique-de-la-lfp |title=Communiqu\u00e9 de la LFP |publisher=lfp.fr |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/coronavirus-what-games-are-cancelled-postponed-behind-closed-doors-overview-10410 |title=Coronavirus: Bundesliga suspended until 2 April |publisher=Bundesliga |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the [[2019\u201320 Premier League|Premier League]] match between Manchester City and Arsenal, due to be played the next day, was postponed after a number of Arsenal players made close contact with Olympiacos owner [[Evangelos Marinakis]], who had tested positive for [[coronavirus]], when the two teams had met in the Europa League 13 days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester City vs. Arsenal postponed after players exposed to Olympiakos owner Evangelos Marinakis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/english-premier-league/story/4071980/arsenal-vs-manchester-city-postponed-after-players-exposed-to-olympiakos-owner-evangelos-marinakis |website=ESPN |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> Arsenal manager [[Mikel Arteta]] tested positive for the disease, prompting the team's Premier League match against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] for that weekend to also be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal boss Mikel Arteta tests positive for coronavirus, match against Brighton postponed |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/arsenal/story/4073648/arsenal-boss-mikel-arteta-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-squad-set-to-self-isolate |website=ESPN |accessdate=13 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> As of 13 March, there has been at least one recorded case of the disease affecting a player in the aforementioned leagues; Serie A footballers [[Daniele Rugani]] and [[Manolo Gabbiadini]], [[2. Bundesliga]] footballer [[Timo H\u00fcbers]], and Premier League footballer [[Callum Hudson-Odoi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/151101/official-gabbiadini-has-coronavirus |title=Official: Gabbiadini has Coronavirus |publisher=Football Italia |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/03/13/chelsea-fc-training-facility-will-undergo-partial-closure-after- |title=CHELSEA FC TRAINING FACILITY WILL UNDERGO PARTIAL CLOSURE AFTER MEN'S TEAM PLAYER TESTED POSITIVE FOR COVID-19 |publisher=Chelsea Football Club |accessdate=13 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Rugani tested positive while being [[Asymptomatic carrier|asymptomatic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51844945 |title=Coronavirus: Juventus centre-back Daniele Rugani tests positive for virus |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March, English elite football was suspended until early April, including the [[Premier League]], [[English Football League]], [[FA Women's Super League]] and [[FA Women's Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nBy 19 March, the [[2020 Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian Premier League]] was the only active top flight in all 55 UEFA member associations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/03/19/football/1584633269_267045.html |title=Amid global coronavirus pandemic, new Belarus season starts |work=AS |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nConcerns were raised regarding [[UEFA Euro 2020]], being held in twelve host cities across Europe, and the potential impact of the coronavirus on players, staff and tournament visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Homewood |first=Brian |location=Rome |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy-soccer/uefa-says-monitoring-coronavirus-not-yet-clear-if-any-impact-on-euro-2020-idUSKBN20J1XS |title=UEFA says monitoring coronavirus, not yet clear if any impact on Euro 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=25 February 2020 |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> UEFA president [[Aleksander \u010ceferin]] said the organisation was confident that the situation could be dealt with, while general secretary [[Theodore Theodoridis]] stated that UEFA was maintaining contact with the [[World Health Organization]] and national governments regarding the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |location=Amsterdam |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/03/uefa-congress-ceferin-coronavirus-dark-scenarios |title=Uefa's Ceferin warns against fixating on 'dark scenarios' over coronavirus threat |work=The Guardian |date=3 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> UEFA announced that a [[videoconference]] would be held on 17 March with representatives of its 55 member associations, along with a [[FIFPro]] representative and the boards of the [[European Club Association]] and [[European Leagues]], to discuss the response to the outbreak for domestic and European competitions, including Euro 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2640887.html |title=UEFA calls meeting of European Football Stakeholders |work=UEFA |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The tournament was moved by 12 months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/mediaservices/mediareleases/newsid=2641071.html |title=UEFA postpones EURO 2020 by 12 months |work=UEFA |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn 12 March 2020, the [[2020 CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions League]] was suspended with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.concacafchampionsleague.com/en/article/concacaf-suspends-scotiabank-concacaf-champions-league-with-immediate-effect |title=Concacaf suspends Scotiabank Concacaf Champions League with immediate effect |publisher=CONCACAF Champions League |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe same day, [[2020 Major League Soccer season|Major League Soccer]] was suspended for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/12/major-league-soccer-suspends-season-30-days-impact-coronavirus |title=MLS suspends 2020 season for 30 days due to coronavirus |publisher=mlssoccer.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlso on 12 March, the [[National Women's Soccer League]] (NWSL), whose [[2020 National Women's Soccer League season|season]] was not scheduled to start until 18 April, canceled its preseason matches,<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/statement-from-nwsl-commissioner-lisa-baird-regarding-the-2020-season |title=Statement from NWSL Commissioner Lisa Baird regarding the 2020 season |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> and also imposed a moratorium on team training that initially ran through 22 March.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/covid-19-resources-and-updates-for-nwsl-fans |title=COVID-19 resources and updates for NWSL fans |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 19 March, Major League Soccer's suspension was extended to a target return date of 10 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/19/mls-extends-season-suspension-accordance-cdc-guidance-covid-19 |title=MLS extends season suspension in accordance with CDC guidance on COVID-19 |publisher=mlssoccer.com |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 April, MLS announced that it was \"extremely unlikely based on the guidance of federal and local public health authorities\" that they would meet this target, and stated that \"our goal remains to play as many games as possible, and while we currently have enough dates to play the entire season, we recognize at this time that it may become difficult to do so.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/major-league-soccer/story/4085343/mls-mulling-tournament-formatneutral-site-games-if-season-returns|title=Garber: MLS mulling tourney, neutral-site games|date=2020-04-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe day after MLS was initially postponed, all [[CONCACAF]] competitions scheduled for the next month were suspended. Match week 10 of Mexican [[Liga MX]] was played but as of 15 March, league executives have now taken the decision to postpone Liga MX activity until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/article/concacaf-suspends-all-its-competitions-scheduled-to-take-place-over-the-next-30-days |title=CONCACAF Champions League |publisher=CONCACAF |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Major Arena Soccer League season]] was terminated early, effective 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.maslsoccer.com/news/major-arena-soccer-league-to-end-regular-season-ef |title=MAJOR ARENA SOCCER LEAGUE TO END REGULAR SEASON EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY |publisher=Major Arena Soccer League |website=maslsoccer.com |first=Jeff |last=Husted |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[USL Championship]] suspended the [[2020 USL Championship season|2020 season]] on 12 March, for at least 30 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uslchampionship.com/news_article/show/1094891 |title=USL Championship Temporarily Suspends Play |publisher=uslchampionship.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nOn 9 March 2020, the [[Oceania Football Confederation]] announced that all tournaments were postponed until May 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=OFC tournaments, workshops, training and courses postponed until 6 May |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc-tournaments-workshops-training-and-courses-postponed-until-6-may/ |publisher=OFC |accessdate=9 March 2020 |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===South America===\nOn 12 March 2020, FIFA announced that the first two rounds of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|South American qualification for the 2022 World Cup]] due to take place in March 2020 were postponed to later dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers-in-south-america |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers in South America |publisher=FIFA.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, CONMEBOL announced that the [[2020 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]] would be temporarily suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-conmebol-libertadores-queda-suspendida-temporalmente |title=La CONMEBOL Libertadores queda suspendida temporalmente |publisher=CONMEBOL.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March all top-tier football in Brazil was suspended until April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/eb6fe061d42f1c68f151697dfe25f1d8 |title=The Latest: T-Wolves' Towns donating $100K to Mayo Clinic |date=15 March 2020 |website=AP NEWS}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March CONMEBOL announced that the 2020 edition of [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] was postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Euro 2020 and Copa Am\u00e9rica Are Postponed for a Year |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/sports/euro-2020-postponed.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |last1=Panja |first1=Tariq}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nThe [[2021 World Athletics Indoor Championships|2020 World Athletics Indoor Championships]] were scheduled to be held from 13 to 15 March in [[Nanjing]], [[China]], but were postponed until March 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Athletics to postpone World Athletics Indoor Championships Nanjing 2020 |url=https://www.worldathletics.org/news/press-releases/indoor-championships-nanjing-2020-postponed |website=World Athletics |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 World Athletics Half Marathon Championships]] was scheduled to be held on 29 March in [[Gdynia]], [[Poland]], but was postponed until October 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Half Marathon Championships in Gdynia to be postponed |url=https://www.worldathletics.org/competitions/world-athletics-half-marathon-championships/news/world-half-marathon-championships-gdynia-post |website=World Athletics |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first three events of the [[2020 Diamond League]], scheduled to be held in [[Qatar]] in April, followed by two events in [[China]] in May, were postponed until later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wanda Diamond League suspends early-season events |url=https://www.diamondleague.com/news/single-news/news/detail/News/wanda-diamond-league-suspends-early-season-events/ |website=Diamond League |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Boston Marathon]], originally scheduled for 20 April, was postponed until 14 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-marathon/2020/03/15/2020-boston-marathon-monday-september |title=Marathon Monday in September? Here's what we know so far about the 2020 Boston Marathon's new date |work=Boston.com |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 London Marathon]], scheduled to take place on 26 April, was postponed until 4 October.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234 |title=Coronavirus: London Marathon postponed until October |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The 2020 [[Rome Marathon]] was cancelled.<ref name=\"cancellation.1\">{{cite web |author=user |url=https://www.runromethemarathon.com/en/2020/03/05/acea-run-rome-the-marathon-of-29-march-2020-cancelled/ |title=Acea Run Rome The Marathon of 29 March 2020 cancelled \u2013 ACEA RUN ROME THE MARATHON |publisher=Runromethemarathon.com |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Two Oceans Marathon]], scheduled for 8\u201311 April has been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.twooceansmarathon.org.za/2020-two-oceans-marathon-cancelled-amid-covid-19-pandemic/ |title=2020 Two Oceans Marathon cancelled amid COVID-19 Pandemic |website=Two Oceans Marathon |language=en-US|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Three Peaks Race]] originally scheduled for 25 April has been postponed to 26 September.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.grough.co.uk/magazine/2020/03/12/coronavirus-claims-second-dales-event-as-three-peaks-race-put-back-to-September |title=Coronavirus claims second Dales event as Three Peaks Race put back to September |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=Grough |first=Bob |last=Smith}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Grandma's Marathon]], scheduled for 20 June, was canceled by the organizers more than 50 days before it was to begin. They announced on 31 March that the marathon, the half-marathon and the 5K would all be canceled. <ref>{{cite web |author1=Grandma's Marathon staff |title=COVID-19 Update/Cancellation |url=https://grandmasmarathon.com/covid19/ |website=grandmasmarathon.com |accessdate=31 March 2020 |location=Duluth, Minnesota |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo of the [[Standard Chartered]] 2020 marathon series, [[Hong Kong Marathon]] and [[Kuala Lumpur Marathon]] was cancelled by the organizer over uncertainty of the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite news\n| author       = SCMP Sport\n| date         = 2020-01-25\n| title        = Hong Kong Marathon cancelled in wake of coronavirus outbreak \u2013 most social media users say it's a 'wise' and 'right' decision\n| url          = https://www.scmp.com/sport/hong-kong/article/3047648/hong-kong-marathon-cancelled-wake-coronavirus-outbreak-public\n| work         = [[South China Morning Post]]\n| location     = \n| access-date  = 2020-04-07\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.kl-marathon.com/news/74/\n |title=CANCELLATION OF THE KUALA LUMPUR STANDARD CHARTERED MARATHON (KLSCM) 2020\n |last=\n |first=\n |date=\n |website=[[Kuala Lumpur Marathon]]\n |publisher=[[Standard Chartered]]\n |access-date=2020-04-07\n |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Australian rules football==\nAt the conclusion of its first round of games, the [[2020 AFL season]] was suspended until 31 May at the earliest, while the Finals series of the [[2020 AFL Women's season]] was cancelled after its semi-finals were played with no premiership awarded.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/afl-round-one-live-updates-travel-warnings-threaten-2020-season/news-story/7d60daac2b783f10205d648b1f19fc33 |title=AFL 2020 premiership officially postponed |date=22 March 2020 |website=NewsComAu |language=en|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Badminton==\nAll scheduled [[Badminton World Federation]] tournaments were suspended until 12 April due to coronavirus concerns.<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Suspends International Badminton |url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/03/14/bwf-suspends-international-badminton/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> The affected tournaments are [[2020 Swiss Open (badminton)|Swiss Open]], [[2020 India Open|India Open]], [[2020 Orl\u00e9ans Masters|Orl\u00e9ans Masters]], [[2020 Malaysia Open|Malaysia Open]], and [[2020 Singapore Open|Singapore Open]]. Previously the body had suspended the [[2020 German Open (badminton)|German Open]]<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Media Statement on Yonex German Open 2020 |url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/02/26/bwf-media-statement-on-yonex-german-open-2020-2/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=2 March 2020 |date=26 February 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> and pushed the [[2020 Lingshui China Masters|Lingshui China Masters]] from February to May 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Statement on Postponement of Lingshui China Masters |url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/02/01/bwf-statement-on-postponement-of-lingshui-china-masters/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=2 February 2020 |date=1 February 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> The [[2020 Thomas & Uber Cup]] had also been postponed to 15\u201323 August.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Baseball==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2021 World Baseball Classic \u2013 Qualification|qualifying round]] of the [[World Baseball Softball Confederation]]-sanctioned [[2021 World Baseball Classic]], scheduled in [[Tucson, Arizona]], United States in March 2020 was postponed on 12 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harrigan |first1=Thomas |title=World Baseball Classic qualifier games postponed |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/world-baseball-classic-qualifier-games-postponed |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=MLB.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n\n====Japan====\nOn 26 February 2020, [[Nippon Professional Baseball]] announced that spring training would continue without fans in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japanese baseball to play remainder of preseason without spectators due to virus fears |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/26/baseball/japanese-baseball/japanese-baseball-play-remainder-preseason-without-spectators-due-virus-fears/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Japan Times |agency=Kyodo News |date=26 February 2020}}</ref> On 9 March, the league announced that the start of its [[2020 Nippon Professional Baseball season|2020 season]] would be postponed until April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's pro baseball league delays season start over coronavirus |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/6cba442bcfa8-breaking-news-japan-pro-baseball-to-delay-start-of-season-over-virus-source.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Coskrey |first1=Jason |title=BayStars, Tigers managers react to NPB's decision to push back start of season |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/?post_type=sports&p=2526679 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Japan Times |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, the [[Japan High School Baseball Federation]] announced that the [[National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament]], scheduled to begin on 19 March, would take place without fans in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's Senbatsu spring HS baseball tourney to be held with no spectators due to virus |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200304/p2a/00m/0na/025000c |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Mainichi |date=4 March 2020}}</ref> However, on 11 March, the governing body of [[high school baseball in Japan]] declared that the tournament had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Organizers cancel Spring Koshien due to COVID-19 crisis |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/03/11/baseball/cancel-spring-koshien-coronavirus/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Japan Times |agency=Kyodo News |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's Senbatsu spring HS baseball tournament canceled over coronavirus fears |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200311/p2a/00m/0sp/017000c |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Manichi |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The cancellation of the 2020 tournament marked the first time the contest had been cancelled since its establishment in 1924. The tournaments were not formally scheduled between 1942 and 1946, due to [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Koshien cancelation stuns players |url=https://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0006415873 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Japan News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Spring high school baseball tourney cancelled over coronavirus |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/c9ea2971def3-breaking-news-national-invitational-hs-baseball-tournament-cancelled-due-to-virus.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nOpening Day of the [[2020 KBO League season]] was originally scheduled for 28 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baseball league announces 2020 regular season schedule |archiveurl=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20191216000870 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Korea Herald |agency=Yonhap News Agency |archivedate=16 December 2019 |date=16 December 2019 |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191216007100315}}</ref> The [[Korea Baseball Organization]] announced in March that all ten exhibition games would be cancelled, and the start of the regular season would be delayed until April.<ref>{{cite news |title=(LEAD) Pro baseball league postpones start of regular season over coronavirus |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200310005251315?input=tw |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Yonhap News Agency |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: South Korean baseball season postponed |url=https://wtmj.com/national/2020/03/12/the-latest-south-korean-baseball-season-postponed/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=WTMJ-TV |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn 12 March 2020, [[Major League Baseball]] suspended all spring training activities. [[Opening Day]] of the [[2020 Major League Baseball season]], scheduled for 26 March, was postponed, as was the start of the regular season for [[Minor League Baseball]], which was to begin on 9 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=MLB suspends spring training, delays Opening Day at least two weeks |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/28892315/sources-mlb-expected-suspend-spring-training |accessdate=12 March 2020 |website=[[ESPN.com]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/mlb-2020-season-delayed |title=Opening Day delayed at least 2 weeks; Spring Training games cancelled |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> In addition, the [[MLB Mexico Series|Mexico Series]] and [[MLB Puerto Rico Series|Puerto Rico Series]] games were canceled; the former would have featured the [[San Diego Padres]] playing the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] at Mexico City's [[Estadio Alfredo Harp Hel\u00fa]], and the latter featuring the [[New York Mets]] playing the [[Miami Marlins]] at  [[Hiram Bithorn Stadium]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/cubs/ct-chicago-cubs-london-coronavirus-20200319-mrawzroybfeddblje4ltkxvf7q-story.html|title=MLB just canceled 2 international series in April. What does it mean for the Cubs-Cardinals series in London in June?|last=Gonzales|first=Mark|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> MLB also canceled the 2020 [[MLB London Series|London Series]] games, which would have featured the [[Chicago Cubs]] playing the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] at [[London Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/28981187/mlb-cancels-cubs-cards-london-series-june|title=MLB cancels Cubs-Cards London series in June|date=April 1, 2020|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlso on 12 March, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] announced the suspension of its baseball season and cancellation of the [[2020 College World Series]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.omaha.com/sports/cws/college-baseball-stunned-after-ncaa-decision-to-cancel-college-world/article_ba4b22b5-7cbd-52a7-b0a0-edb0eba8f079.html |title=College baseball stunned after NCAA decision to cancel College World Series, end season in March |newspaper=Omaha World-Herald |last=Bland |first=Evan |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Basketball==\n\n===Africa===\nThe launch of the [[2020 BAL season|inaugural season]] of the [[Basketball Africa League]] set for March 2020 was delayed due to the coronavirus pandemic. No new date has been announced.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Solomon |first1=Salem |title=Basketball Africa League Delays Inaugural Season Because of Coronavirus |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/basketball-africa-league-delays-inaugural-season-because |accessdate=13 March 2020 |agency=Voice of America |date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nThe [[2019\u201320 Chinese Basketball Association season]] was suspended on 1 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Prewitt |first=Alex |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2020/03/13/cba-coronavirus-nba-allerik-freeman |title=While the NBA Pauses, China Is Ready to Play Again. For Better or Worse |date=13 March 2020 |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, [[FIBA]] ordered two [[2021 FIBA Asia Cup qualification|qualifying games for the 2021 FIBA Asia Cup]], [[Philippines men's national basketball team|Philippines]] vs [[Thailand national basketball team|Thailand]] in [[Quezon City]], and [[Japan national basketball team|Japan]] vs. [[China men's national basketball team|China]] in [[Chiba (city)|Chiba]] to be postponed to a later date. This brought the postponed games to three, after FIBA earlier ordered the China vs. [[Malaysia national basketball team|Malaysia]] game in [[Foshan]] to be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/asiacup/2021/qualifiers/news/three-fiba-asia-cup-2021-qualifier-games-postponed |title=Three FIBA Asia Cup 2021 Qualifier games postponed |website=FIBA.basketball |language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Later that week, the [[Guam national basketball team|Guam]] vs. [[Hong Kong basketball team|Hong Kong]] game in [[Hag\u00e5t\u00f1a, Guam|Hag\u00e5t\u00f1a]] was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/asiacup/2021/qualifiers/news/fiba-asia-cup-2021-qualifier-between-guam-and-hong-kong-postponed |title=FIBA Asia Cup 2021 Qualifier game between Guam and Hong Kong postponed |website=FIBA.basketball |language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Korean Basketball League]] canceled its [[2019\u201320 KBL season|2019\u201320 season]] on 24 March, after playing its last game on 29 February. This comes as the [[Women's Korean Basketball League]] canceled its season a week before.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200324000415 |title=Men's basketball league cancels season due to coronavirus |last=Herald |first=The Korea |date=24 March 2020 |website=www.koreaherald.com |language=en|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, FIBA announced the cancellation of the [[2019 FIBA Under-16 Asian Championship]] in [[Beirut]] and the 2019 FIBA Under-16 Asian Championship for Women in [[Canberra]]. It also postponed the [[Basketball at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3x3 qualification|3x3 Olympic qualification tournament]] in [[Bangalore]], and rescheduled the 2020 [[FIBA Asia 3x3 Cup]]s in [[Changsha]] and the 2020 FIBA 3x3 Under-17 Asian Cup in [[Cyberjaya]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/news/changes-made-to-several-fiba-events-due-to-covid-19-virus |title=Changes made to several FIBA events due to COVID-19 virus |website=FIBA.basketball |language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====ASEAN Basketball League====\nSeveral fixtures of the [[ASEAN Basketball League]] [[2019\u201320 ABL season|2019\u201320 season]] scheduled on February onwards were rescheduled due to the coronavirus pandemic. In early March 2020, four participating teams, [[Alab Pilipinas]], [[Hong Kong Eastern Basketball Team|Hong Kong Eastern]], [[Macau Black Bears]] and [[Formosa Dreamers]] has released statements urging the suspension of the whole season due to logistical issues posed by COVID-19-related travel measures in Southeast Asia, mainland China and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alab Pilipinas, three other teams want ABL to suspend season due to COVID-19 |url=https://sports.mb.com.ph/2020/03/12/alab-pilipinas-three-other-teams-want-abl-to-suspend-season-due-to-covid-19/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2020, the league's 2019\u201320 season was postponed indefinitely.<ref name=\"pbateams\">{{cite news |last1=Dalupang |first1=Denison Rey |title=PBA: Teams can't hold practices, scrimmages |url=https://sports.inquirer.net/389302/pba-teams-cant-hold-practices-scrimmages |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Philippines====\nThe [[2020 PBA season|2020 season]] of the [[Philippine Basketball Association]] (PBA) and the [[PBA D-League]] was suspended indefinitely on 10 March 2020. The inaugural of the PBA's 3x3 tournament was also likewise delayed.<ref name=pba>{{cite news |title=PBA suspends games indefinitely due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/sports/basketball/729223/pba-suspends-games-indefinitely-due-to-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=GMA News |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> The PBA management also imposed a two-week prohibition on team \"practices, scrimmages and other related activities\" which took effect on 14 March 2020.<ref name=\"pbateams\"/>\n\nSeveral leagues have suspended their tournaments on March 12: [[Community Basketball Association]], [[National Basketball League (Philippines)|National Basketball League]], [[Maharlika Pilipinas Basketball League]].<ref>[https://www.spin.ph/life/guide/list-of-sports-events-suspended-coronavirus-a1374-20200312 Here's a list of sports events suspended due to coronavirus], [[Sports Interactive Network|spin.ph]], March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, the PBA Board of Governors have decided to shorten this season into a two-conference format following the postponement of the Philippine Cup due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] and the enforcement of the Enhanced Community Quarantine in Luzon until April 30.<ref name = \"PBA-COVID\">[https://www.pba.ph/news/pba-board-decides-to-shorten-season-45  PBA board decides to shorten Season 45], PBA.ph, April 7, 2020</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n[[Jordi Bertomeu]], CEO of the [[Euroleague]], suspended the games from 14 March to 11 April. The Euroleague previously suspended the [[EuroCup Basketball|Eurocup]]. FIBA also suspended the [[Basketball Champions League]] and the [[FIBA Europe Cup]] starting on 14 March. [[Lietuvos krep\u0161inio lyga|Lithuania]], [[Swedish Basketball League|Sweden]], [[Swiss Basketball League|Switzerland]], [[Slovak Basketball League|Slovakia]] and [[Ukrainian Basketball SuperLeague|Ukraine]] canceled outright their respective first division leagues, naming the teams in the top of the standings as champions. Top flight divisions in [[Liga ACB|Spain]], [[LNB Pro A|France]], [[Basketball Bundesliga|Germany]], [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italy]], [[Israeli Basketball Premier League|Israel]], [[Pro Basketball League|Belgium]], [[Korisliiga|Finland]], [[HT Premijer liga|Croatia]], [[Greek Basket League|Greece]], [[Polish Basketball League|Poland]], [[Cyprus Basketball Division A|Cyprus]] and [[National Basketball League (Czech Republic)|Czech Republic]] suspended its games as of 14 March. The [[ABA League|Adriatic League]] and the [[VTB United League]] suspended its competitions until April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28898393/international-basketball-virtually-shut-coronavirus-concerns |title=International basketball virtually shut down |date=13 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The government of Turkey suspended the [[Basketball Super League]] on 19 March, the last major European league to do so.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2020/03/19/turkey-basketball-soccer-suspended-coronavirus |title=Turkey Suspends Soccer, Basketball Seasons |last=West |first=Jenna |website=Sports Illustrated |language=en-us|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\n[[File:Signs during pandemic in Brooklyn (20555).jpg|thumb|In many New York City parks, hoops were removed from basketball courts to discourage people being in groups.]]\nOn 11 March 2020, the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) [[Suspension of the 2019\u201320 NBA season|suspended its season]] after [[Utah Jazz]] player [[Rudy Gobert]] tested positive for coronavirus prior to tip-off for a scheduled game against the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref name=\"nba-suspension-of-season\">{{cite web |title=NBA to suspend season following Wednesday's games |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/03/11/nba-suspend-season-following-wednesdays-games |website=NBA.com |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Commissioner [[Adam Silver]] stated the next day that this suspension \"will be most likely at least 30 days, and we don't know enough to be more specific than that\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=12 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On April 6 in an interview with [[NBA on TNT|TNT]]'s [[Ernie Johnson Jr.]], he stated there would be no decision on a restart of the season made before May 1 at the minimum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/29003667/commissioner-adam-silver-does-not-expect-make-decisions-nba-season-least-may|title=Commissioner Adam Silver does not expect to make any decisions on NBA season until at least May|last=Bontemps|first=Tim|date=6 April 2020|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, all [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] conferences in [[NCAA]] [[college basketball]] cancelled their respective tournaments in-progress. The [[Ivy League]] had already called off its tournament prior to the decision, while some conferences, as well as the NCAA for its [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's]] and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women's]] tournaments, had previously announced that they would conduct their games behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/12/coronavirus-ncaa-conference-tournaments-cancellations.html |title=Big Ten, SEC, ACC scrap conference tournaments, adding to wave of coronavirus-related sports cancellations |last=Eudaily |first=Chris |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=CNBC|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/pac-12-mens-basketball-tournament-canceled-over-coronavirus-pandemic |title=Pac-12 cancels all sports competitions 'until further notice' because of coronavirus |date=12 March 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28891602/big-ten-sec-american-cancel-conference-tournaments |title=Conference tournaments shut down over virus |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The NCAA subsequently cancelled its tournaments outright.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/march-madness-ncaa-tournament-canceled-coronavirus |title=No shining moments: NCAA basketball tournaments are canceled for the first time |date=13 March 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/coronavirus-updates-ncaa-cancels-championship-competition-for-all-winter-and-spring-sports/ |title=Coronavirus updates: NCAA cancels championship competition for all winter and spring sports |website=CBSSports.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Baloncesto Superior Nacional]] of Puerto Rico suspended its season on 14 March.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe [[National Basketball League of Canada]] suspended the remainder of the [[2019\u201320 NBL Canada season|2019\u201320 season]] on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nblcanada.ca/sports/mbkb/2019-20/releases/20200312nqi4na |title=NBLC Suspends Remainder of 2019\u201320 Season Until Further Notice |website=National Basketball League of Canada |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2020, the [[Women's National Basketball Association]] (WNBA) announced that they will postponed the start of training camp and regular season which was originally scheduled for 15 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-statement-regarding-the-start-of-the-2020-regular-season/ |title=WNBA Statement Regarding the Start of the 2020 Regular Season |publisher=WNBA |website=wnba.com |date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 WNBA draft]] will be held virtually on 17 April 2020 without players, guests, and media on-site and will be televised as planned.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-draft-2020-to-be-held-april-17/ |title=WNBA Draft 2020 Presented By State Farm To Be Held As Scheduled On April 17 |publisher=WNBA |website=wnba.com |date=26 March 2020 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nIn Australia's [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League]], the [[Sydney Kings]] announced 17 March that they would pull out of the [[2020 NBL Finals]] after three games, due to \"a critical mass of relevant and actual concerns related to player welfare and the club's social responsibility\". The NBL had been considering playing Game 4 of the series on 18 March instead of 20 March as originally scheduled to accelerate its completion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/perth-wildcats-disappointed-with-sydney-kings-nbl-grand-final-decision/news-story/2426c7f70f33f5a06e963a4c971365c4 |title=NBL Grand Final 2020: Perth Wildcats 'disappointed' with Sydney Kings' NBL Grand Final decision |date=17 March 2020 |website=Fox Sports |language=en-AU|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/breaking-nbl-season-called-off-midfinals-due-to-coronavirus-crisis/news-story/7f707f71310056816e01d8d99e7748cf |title=NBL Grand Final 2020: NBL season called off mid-finals due to coronavirus crisis, Sydney Kings vs Perth Wildcats |date=17 March 2020 |website=Fox Sports |language=en-AU|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> The decision effectively [[Forfeit (sport)|forfeited]] the series to the [[Perth Wildcats]]\u2014who were leading the best-of-five series 2\u20131 after Game 3, and were officially announced as NBL champions on 18 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thewest.com.au/sport/perth-wildcats/nbl-grand-final-title-win-the-last-piece-of-the-puzzle-for-stoked-perth-wildcats-ng-b881494184z |title=Title win the last piece of the puzzle for stoked Cats |date=19 March 2020 |website=The West Australian |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The series was played behind closed doors beginning with Game 2, and the NBL stated that it would be suspended immediately if any player was diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/nbl-grand-final-series-to-be-completed-behind-closed-doors-20200313-p549xx.html |title=NBL grand final series to be completed behind closed doors |last=Ward |first=Roy |date=13 March 2020 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Biathlon==\nThe [[2019\u201320 Biathlon World Cup]] ended a week and a day earlier than previously scheduled. The World Cup final in Norway was cancelled as was the last day of the penultimate World Cup in Finland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biathlonworld.com/news/detail/ibu-statement-on-world-cup-in-oslo |title=Update: IBU Statement on World Cup in Oslo, Kontiolahti and Junior OECH |date=13 March 2020 |website=Biathlon World |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bodybuilding==\nSeveral competitive events in international [[Bodybuilding|competitive bodybuilding]] on the amateur and [[Professional bodybuilding|professional]] levels have seen limitations, postponements, or even cancellations due to concerns about the spread of COVID-19.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nDue to these concerns Ohio governor [[Mike DeWine]] reduced the 2020 [[Arnold Sports Festival]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]] on 3 March, before any [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ohio|cases or deaths had been reported in the state]]. The cancellation was widely regarded as 'radical' at the time.<ref>{{cite web |title=The US governor who saw it coming early |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52113186 |website=[[BBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401045917/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52113186 |archivedate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=barrett>{{Cite news |last=Barrett |first=Joe |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ohio-governor-on-why-he-ordered-early-tough-coronavirus-lockdowns-11585501200 |title=Ohio Governor on Why He Ordered Early, Tough Coronavirus Lockdowns |date=29 March 2020 |work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=30 March 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref> The Fitness Expo (under orders from the state government) held the bodybuilding and physique competitions, including the Arnold Classic, without spectators with exceptions for parents and guardians of minors participating in the competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldsportsfestival.com/visitor-info/media/update-March-3/ |title=UPDATED EVENTS SCHEDULE |work=Arnold Sports Festival |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Similar Arnold Sports Festivals planned to be held in Africa, Australia, and South America were postponed for later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldsportsfestival.com/ |title=ARNOLD SPORTS FESTIVALS IN AUSTRALIA, SOUTH AMERICA & AFRICA HAVE BEEN POSTPONED. NEW DATES TBD |work=Arnolds Sports Festival |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, Jim Manion, president of the [[IFBB Professional League]] and the [[National Physique Committee]] announced that competitions planned through to 10 May 2020 in the United States would be postponed for later in the year or cancelled until the 2021 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ifbbpro.com/npc-news/npc-ifbb-professional-league-president-jim-manion-addresses-coronavirus-concerns-for-contests-in-the-united-states/ |title=NPC & IFBB Professional League President Jim Manion Addresses Coronavirus Concerns For Contests In The United States |work=IFBB Professional League \u2013 NPC News Online |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bowls==\nThe [[2020 World Outdoor Bowls Championship]] scheduled to be held on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] from 23 May to 7 June 2020,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bowls.com.au/events-page/international-events/world-bowls-championships/ |title=2020 World Bowls Championship |publisher=Bowls Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bowlsmalaysia.com/world-events-calendar/ |title=WORLD EVENTS CALENDAR |publisher=Bowls Malaysia}}</ref> has been postponed until 25 May to 6 June 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bowls.com.au/2020-world-bowls-championships-to-be-postponed-indefinitely/ |title=2020 World Bowls Championships to be postponed indefinitely |date=17 March 2020 |website=Bowls Australia |language=en-AU|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Castells==\nIn response to the shutdown of extracurricular activities for children in [[Catalonia]], the Coordinadora de Colles Castelleres de Catalunya (CCCC), the governing body for [[castell]]s (Catalan human towers), issued a statement on 10 March 2020, recommending the suspension of all castells practices and performances.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mu\u00f1oz |first1=Silvia |title=Primers assajos i diades castelleres suspeses en prevenci\u00f3 pel coronavirus |url=https://www.elmoncasteller.cat/primers-assajos-i-diades-castelleres-suspeses-en-prevencio-pel-coronavirus/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=M\u00f3n Casteller |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|lockdown imposed throughout Spain]] shut down all castells activities throughout Catalonia as of 15 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Segon cap de setmana de confinament casteller |url=http://revistacastells.cat/2020/03/segon-cap-de-setmana-de-confinament-casteller/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> As of 25 March 2020, there was no word about the potential impact of the pandemic on the biennial [[:ca:XXVIII Concurs de castells de Tarragona|Tarragona Castells Contest]], scheduled for 3 and 4 October 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Madrid, una ciutat en hores baixes |url=http://revistacastells.cat/2020/03/madrid-una-ciutat-en-hores-baixes/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the CCCC, the last April without any castells was in 1966. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Cam\u00ed d'un abril a zero |url=https://revistacastells.cat/2020/04/cami-dun-abril-a-zero/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Chess==\nThe [[44th Chess Olympiad]] scheduled to take place in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]] from 5\u201317 August 2020 was postponed and rescheduled for the summer of 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fide.com/news/460 |title=Statement by the FIDE Council regarding the Chess Olympiad |date=24 March 2020 |website=fide.com |publisher=FIDE |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"postponed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chess.com/news/view/fide-postpones-chess-olympiad-to-2021 |title=FIDE Postpones Chess Olympiad To 2021 |author=Peter Doggers |date=24 March 2020 |publisher=[[Chess.com]] |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe FIDE [[Candidates Tournament 2020]], held in [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Russia]], was suspended at the mid-point of the tournament on 26 March. FIDE decided to postpone the second half of the tournament after Russia announced it would be interrupting air traffic with other countries starting on 27 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.chessbase.com/post/breaking-news-fide-stops-the-candidates-tournament |title=Breaking News: FIDE stops the Candidates Tournament! |date=26 March 2020 |website=Chess News |language=en |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Combat sports==\n===Mixed martial arts===\n[[ONE Championship]] moved its 28 February \"King of the Jungle\" event behind closed doors, and announced that its ONE Infinity 1 event on 10 April would move from [[Chongqing]], China to [[Jakarta]], Indonesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/28725093/one-championship-card-go-minus-fans-due-coronavirus-fears|title=MMA event to go on sans fans due to coronavirus|date=2020-02-17|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> On 13 March, ONE announced that all cards would be held behind closed doors in Singapore until ONE Infinity 1 on 29 May, re-located to [[Manila]], Philippines (which was originally to host ONE Infinity 2). The ONE Championship \"Heart of Heroes\" event in [[Vietnam]] (originally scheduled for 20 March) was postponed to June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/24/one-championship-goes-ahead-with-events-despite-pandemic.html|title=ONE Championship goes ahead with events despite pandemic|website=The Jakarta Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/mma-one-championship-suspends-live-events-until-may-due-to-coronavirus|title=MMA: One Championship suspends live events until May due to coronavirus|last=hermesauto|date=2020-03-13|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/martial-arts/mixed-martial-arts/article/3075055/coronavirus-one-championship-moves-all-events|title=Coronavirus: One Championship moves all events behind closed doors|date=2020-03-13|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> On 6 April, due to lockdown orders issued by the Singapore government that restrict non-essential business, ONE announced that the two April cards would be postponed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/6/21209252/one-championship-postpones-upcoming-events-in-april-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic|title=ONE Championship postpones upcoming events in April due to coronavirus pandemic|last=Martin|first=Damon|date=2020-04-06|website=MMA Fighting|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, [[Combate Americas]] announced that its March events would be cancelled and replaced by closed-door tapings beginning April 3.<ref name=\":8\" /> On 10 March, Polish MMA promotion [[Konfrontacja Sztuk Walki]] (KSW) cancelled its 21 March 2020 event KSW 53 in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightsports.tv/ksw-cancels-upcoming-event-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=KSW Cancels Upcoming Event Due To Coronavirus Outbreak|date=11 March 2020|website=FIGHT SPORTS|language=en-US|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March, [[Bellator MMA|Bellator]] cancelled [[Bellator MMA in 2020|Bellator 241]] in [[Uncasville, Connecticut]] (which was scheduled to occur later that day), and has since cancelled all events through May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Bellator-MMA-Changes-Course-Cancels-Bellator-241-171477|title=Bellator MMA Changes Course, Cancels Bellator 241|website=[[Sherdog]]|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/mma/2020/03/31/bellator-canceled-may-coronavirus-crisis|title=Bellator Cancels Events Through May Amid COVID-19 Outbreak|last=Shapiro|first=Michael|website=Sports Illustrated|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==== Ultimate Fighting Championship ====\nThe main North American promotion [[UFC]] went on with its 13 March event [[UFC Fight Night: Lee vs. Oliveira]] in [[Bras\u00edlia]], [[Brazil]], behind closed doors.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/28873544/ufc-bellator-moving-ahead-events-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|title=UFC, Bellator events still on amid virus outbreak|date=2020-03-09|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/3/12/21176396/ufc-brasilia-behind-closed-doors-coronavirus-decree|title=UFC Brasilia to go on behind closed doors after coronavirus decree|last=Cruz|first=Guilherme|date=2020-03-12|website=MMA Fighting|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>  On 16 March, UFC announced that the next three UFC Fight Night events, [[UFC Fight Night: Overeem vs. Harris|Overeem vs. Harris]], [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik|Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]], and [[UFC Fight Night: Woodley vs. Edwards|Woodley vs. Edwards]], would be postponed to future dates.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/ufc-postpones-three-events-coronavirus-pandemic |title=UFC postpones three events amid growing coronavirus outbreak |date=16 March 2020 |website=MMA Junkie |language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn regards to its next [[pay-per-view]], [[UFC 249]] on 18 April, UFC president [[Dana White]] stated that the event would likely go on, but at a new venue behind closed doors. It was originally to be held at [[Barclays Center]], but a [[stay-at-home order]] was issued by the New York state government.<ref name=\":4\" /> On 18 March, the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] also withdrew its sanctioning for the event.<ref name=\":6\" /> Due to international travel restrictions and other withdrawals, a revised card for UFC 249 was unveiled 6 April with a location still being determined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29002048/dana-white-says-tony-ferguson-justin-gaethje-headline-ufc-249|title=Dana White says Tony Ferguson-Justin Gaethje to headline UFC 249|work=ESPN|author=Marc Raimondi|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/6/21209211/ufc-announces-updated-lineup-for-ufc-249-andrade-vs-namajunas-2-still-co-headlines|title=UFC 249 fight card announced, Andrade vs. Namajunas 2 still co-headlines|work=MMAFighting.com|author=Alexander K. Lee|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On 7 April, White disclosed that he had booked an unspecified venue for two months, in order to host both UFC 249 and other future events involving U.S. fighters. He also disclosed plans to secure a [[private island]] to host events with international fighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/7/21211634/dana-white-covid-19-plans-weekly-fights-at-ufc-249-location-a-private-island-and-joe-rogan|title=Dana White's COVID-19 plan: Two months of weekly fights at UFC 249 location, a private island, and Joe Rogan|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Steven Marrocco|date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29006529/dana-white-secured-us-location-private-island-ufc-fights|title=UFC's White: Secured private island for fights|date=2020-04-07|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nThe new UFC 249 venue was subsequently revealed to be [[Tachi Palace]]\u2014a [[Native American gaming|tribal casino]] in [[Lemoore, California]]; as it is on tribal land, it also fell outside of the jurisdiction of the [[California State Athletic Commission]], meaning that events held there could be self-sanctioned.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=Draper|first=Kevin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/sports/ufc-249-coronavirus-location.html|title=U.F.C. 249, Skirting Coronavirus Limits, Is Set for Tribal Land in California|date=2020-04-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On 9 April, UFC announced that UFC 249 had been cancelled, and all other UFC events would be suspended until further notice. White cited interventions from high-ranking staff of the UFC's U.S. media rightsholders, [[ESPN Inc.]] and parent [[The Walt Disney Company]].<ref name=\":5\" /> ''[[The New York Post]]'' reported that Governor of California [[Gavin Newsom]] had contacted Disney CEO [[Bob Iger]], urging ESPN and the UFC to not hold the event.<ref name=\":7\" /> Despite the cancellation, White stated that he was still going on with his \"Fight Island\" project.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Draper|first=Kevin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/sports/ufc-249-canceled.html|title=U.F.C. 249 Is Off After Requests From California, Disney and ESPN|date=2020-04-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|last2=Garcia|first2=Oskar|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/09/ufc-249-espn-wasnt-only-one-to-tell-dana-white-to-stand-down/|title=ESPN wasn't only one to tell UFC, Dana White to 'stand down'|last=Willis|first=George|date=2020-04-10|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n===Kickboxing===\n[[Kunlun Fight]] cancelled multiple events due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ecosports.cn/Home/Consultation/show/id/14744.html |title=\u9996\u9875 \u6c2a\u4f53 |publisher=Ecosports.cn |date=2020-01-26 |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kunlunjue.com/articleDetail?id=6060 |title=\u6606\u4ed1\u51b3\u4e16\u754c\u683c\u6597\u51a0\u519b\u8d5b |publisher=Kunlunjue.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Glory (kickboxing)|Glory]] cancelled events in [[Lint, Belgium|Lint]], [[Belgium]] and [[Miami]], [[United States|USA]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sports |first=Fight |url=https://www.fightsports.tv/glory-kickboxing-postpones-antwerp-miami-events/ |title=GLORY Kickboxing Postpones Antwerp, Miami Events &#124; FIGHT SPORTS |publisher=Fightsports.tv |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n===Professional wrestling===\nNumerous [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotions]] have cancelled major events, such as [[Impact Wrestling]]'s [[TNA: There's No Place Like Home]], [[Ring of Honor]]'s [[ROH 18th Anniversary Show|18th Anniversary Show]] and the [[National Wrestling Alliance]]'s [[Crockett Cup (2020)|Crockett Cup]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rohwrestling.com/news/roh-18th-anniversary-and-past-vs-present-shows-cancellation|title=ROH 18TH ANNIVERSARY AND PAST VS PRESENT SHOWS CANCELLATION|date=12 March 2020|website=Ring of Honor|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Impact, ROH and NWA also cancelled future tapings for their respective weekly television shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://impactwrestling.com/our-response-to-covid-19/|title=An Update on Events|date=24 March 2020|website=Impact Wrestling|language=en|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rohwrestling.com/news/roh-cancels-all-live-events-through-may-31st-2020|title=ROH 18TH ROH CANCELS ALL LIVE EVENTS THROUGH MAY 31ST, 2020|date=17 March 2020|website=Ring of Honor|language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwrestlingalliance.com/news/nwa-suspends-crockett-cup-amp-nwa-powerrr-live-events|title=NWA SUSPENDS CROCKETT CUP & NWA POWERRR LIVE EVENTS|website=NWA|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> In Mexico, [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] cancelled tapings for their weekly shows for the foreseeable future and [[Lucha Libre AAA Worldwide]] postponed the [[Rey de Reyes (2020)|2020 Rey de Reyes]] event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://superluchas.com/funciones-canceladas-por-coronavirus-en-mexico/|title=Primeras funciones canceladas por Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico|last=Acosta|first=Carlos|date=13 March 2020|work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://superluchas.com/aaa-se-cancela-rey-de-reyes-2020-por-coronavirus/|title=AAA: Se cancela \"Rey de Reyes 2020\" por Coronavirus|last=Acosta|first=Carlos|date=13 March 2020|work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]]|language=Spanish|trans-title=AAA: Cancelling \"Rey de Reyes 2020\" because of the Coronoavirus|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====New Japan Pro-Wrestling====\nIn accordance with recommendations from the Japanese Ministry of Health, [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) decided to cancel all scheduled shows from 1 March through 15 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-shows-march-1-15-due-coronavirus-outbreak-305026 |title=NJPW CANCELS SHOWS FROM MARCH 1\u201315 DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |first=Joseph |last=Currier |date=26 February 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On 10 March, NJPW announced that they were cancelling all shows through 22 March, which meant that they either cancelled the [[New Japan Cup#2020|2020 New Japan Cup]] as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-remainder-new-japan-cup-tour-due-coronavirus-306136 |title=NJPW CANCELS REMAINDER OF NEW JAPAN CUP TOUR DUE TO CORONAVIRUS |first=Brian |last=Rose |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> The [[World Wonder Ring Stardom|Stardom]] promotion, sister company of NJPW also owned by [[Bushiroad]], also made adjustments to their scheduled, cancelling shows from 19 February to 14 March. Their 8 March show in [[Korakuen Hall]] was held without any spectators in attendance, instead streaming live on their [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/stardom-makes-major-schedule-changes-due-coronavirus-outbreak-304441 |title=STARDOM MAKES MAJOR SCHEDULE CHANGES DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |first=Josh |last=Nason |date=18 February 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On March 23, 2020 NJPW would later cancelled 2020 [[Sakura Genesis]] event was originally scheduled to take place in 2020 on March 31, but would also be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/68654 |title=2020.03.31 SAKURA GENESIS 2020 |accessdate=December 28, 2019 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/73631 |title=Sakura Genesis, April 11 Kanagawa events cancelled |accessdate=March 23, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref> On April 8, 2020 NJPW would cancel more events from April 11 through May 4, which mean both nights of 2020 [[Wrestling Dontaku]] being cancelled as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-events-through-may-4-wrestling-dontaku-included-308401 |title=NJPW cancels events through May 4, Wrestling Dontaku included |publisher=F4wonline.com |date=2020-04-07 |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n====WWE====\nAmerican promotion [[WWE]] began to move the broadcasts of its weekly programs ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'' and ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' (which usually broadcast from arenas) to a training facility, the [[WWE Performance Center]] in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], beginning with ''SmackDown'' on 13 March, with no audience and only essential staff in attendance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-raw-results-recap-grades-steve-austin-celebrates-new-wrestlemania-36-matches-made/live/ |title=WWE Raw results, recap, grades: Steve Austin celebrates, new WrestleMania 36 matches made |website=CBSSports.com |language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/coronavirus-wwe-smackdown-live-1203532469/ |title=WWE Moves 'SmackDown Live' to Orlando Performance Center With No Live Audience Due to Coronavirus |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=12 March 2020 |website=Variety|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-smackdown-results-recap-grades-john-cena-caps-surreal-empty-arena-showy-you-have-to-see/live/ |title=WWE SmackDown results, recap, grades: John Cena caps surreal empty arena show you have to see |website=CBSSports.com|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The promotion also postponed some of its upcoming [[house show]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2020/03/13/22805585.html |title=WWE house shows cancelled, AEW alters plans |website=canoe.com|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[WrestleMania 36]]\u2014WWE's flagship [[pay-per-view]] event\u2014was originally scheduled to be held at [[Raymond James Stadium]] in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]]. On 16 March, WWE announced that it would also be produced from the Performance Center and air across two nights (4 and 5 April).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/wrestlemania-canceled-coronavirus-wwe-tampa-1202881422/ |title=WrestleMania To Stream Live Without Audience Due To Coronavirus Outbreak |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |date=16 March 2020 |website=Deadline |language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/wwe-splits-audience-less-wrestlemania-36-into-two-nights/ |title=WWE Splits Audience-Less WrestleMania 36 Into Two Nights |last=Maglio |first=Tony |date=18 March 2020 |website=TheWrap |language=en-US|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/article/wrestlemania-36-two-night-wwe-network-rob-gronkowski-host |title=Unprecedented two-night WrestleMania to be hosted by Rob Gronkowski on WWE Network |date=17 March 2020 |work=WWE |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> WrestleMania's associated festivities, such as the [[NXT TakeOver: Tampa Bay|NXT TakeOver]] event and [[WWE Hall of Fame (2020)|2020 Hall of Fame ceremony]] were also postponed to unannounced dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/134766/wwe-hall-of-fame-nxt-takeover-off.html?p=1 |title=WWE HALL OF FAME, NXT TAKEOVER OFF |work=PW Insider |first=Mike |last=Johnson |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> Matches for WrestleMania, as well as the final two episodes of ''SmackDown'' and final episode of ''Raw'' before WrestleMania, were recorded in advance at the Performance Center between 21 and 26 March.<ref name=\"taped\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/134908/wwe-scheduled-to-tape-everything-through-wrestlemania-this-week.html?p=1 |title=WWE SCHEDULED TO TAPE EVERYTHING THROUGH WRESTLEMANIA THIS WEEK |last=Johnson |first=Mike |date=21 March 2020 |publisher=PWInsider |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> While the majority of matches were filmed in Performance Center arena and presented plausibly live, two matches were filmed off-site in different, cinematic styles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/wwe-triple-h-wrestlemania-coronavirus-impact/ |title=WWE's Triple H Explains What It's Like to Film WrestleMania Without the Fans |date=2 April 2020 |website=TVGuide.com|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-wrestlemania-36-results-recap-grades-huge-title-changes-epic-special-matches-on-unique-2020-show/live/|title=WWE WrestleMania 36 results, recap, grades: Huge title changes, epic special matches on unique 2020 show|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/john-cena-bray-wyatt-firefly-fun-house-win-wrestlemania/|title=Bray Wyatt Defeats John Cena in Firefly Fun House Match at WrestleMania|last=Satin|first=Ryan|date=2020-04-06|website=Pro Wrestling Sheet {{!}} Insider Wrestling News and Reports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nAfter continuing with pre-taped episodes for the [[Go-home show|go-home shows]] after WrestleMania, WWE announced that its weekly series would resume live broadcasts on 13 April, with ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' from the Performance Center as before, and ''[[WWE NXT]]'' from its existing studio at [[Full Sail University]] in [[Winter Park, Florida|Winter Park]].<ref name=\"cbs-wwelive\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-to-resume-live-matches-on-tv-starting-with-the-next-monday-night-raw/|title=WWE to resume live matches on TV starting with the next 'Monday Night Raw'|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/29024319/wwe-resume-live-tv-matches-starting-monday|title=WWE to resume live TV matches starting Monday|date=2020-04-11|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> WWE told ESPN that \"it is now more important than ever to provide people with a diversion from these hard times\", and that its programming \"bring[s] families together and deliver a sense of hope, determination and perseverance\".<ref name=\":9\" /> WWE also confirmed that one of its employees had contracted COVID-19 after a meeting with two health care workers on 26 March. The company stated that the exposure occurred after production had wrapped, the employee had not made any contact with WWE staff since the exposure, and that they had had made a complete recovery.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/wwe-confirms-coronavirus-case-1202906432/|title=WWE Confirms First Known Coronavirus Case|last=Bennett|first=Anita|date=2020-04-12|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/wwe-positive-covid-19-test-confirmed/|title=Positive COVID-19 Test Confirmed by WWE|last=Satin|first=Ryan|date=2020-04-11|website=Pro Wrestling Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Wrestling writer [[Dave Meltzer]] noted that WWE's television contracts with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and [[USA Network]] likely restricted the number of non-live episodes it could broadcast per-year (accommodating breaks usually held around the [[Christmas]] and [[New Year]] holidays).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-resume-live-raw-smackdown-nxt-tv-shows-308611|title=WWE to resume live Raw, SmackDown & NXT TV shows|date=2020-04-10|website=WON/F4W|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nWWE's next PPV, [[Money in the Bank (2020)|Money in the Bank]], was expected to be held at [[Baltimore]]'s [[Royal Farms Arena]] in May, but was cancelled by the arena on 9 April.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Mike|title=WWE MONEY IN THE BANK WILL NOT TAKE PLACE IN BALTIMORE, ROYAL FARMS ARENA ANNOUNCES CANCELLATION|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/135465/wwe-money-in-the-bank-will-not-take-place-in-baltimore-royal-farms-arena-announces-cancellation.html?p=1|work=PWInsider|date=April 9, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilen|first=Jerome|title=WWE Money in the Bank pay-per view canceled due to COVID-19 outbreak|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/153495-wwe-money-in-the-bank-pay-per-view-canceled-covid-19/|work=WrestleView|date=April 9, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> WWE had already promoted Money in the Bank during WrestleMania, with no reference to a host venue,<ref name=\"WM36Part2\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=WrestleMania 36 results: Powell's live review of Night Two featuring Brock Lesnar vs. Drew McIntyre for the WWE Championship, John Cena vs. \"The Fiend\" Bray Wyatt in a Firefly Funhouse match, Edge vs. Randy Orton in a Last Man Standing match, Rhea Ripley vs. Charlotte Flair for the NXT Women's Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/05/wrestlemania-36-results-powells-live-review-of-night-two-featuring-brock-lesnar-vs-drew-mcintyre-for-the-wwe-championship-john-cena-vs-the-fiend-bray-wyatt-in-a-firefly-funhouse-match/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> and began promoting qualification matches for the PPV's [[Money in the Bank ladder match|titular match]] on 10 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/article/naomi-dana-brooke-money-in-the-bank-qualifying-match|title=Naomi meets Dana Brooke in Women's Money in the Bank Qualifying Match|website=WWE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/article/daniel-bryan-cesaro-money-in-the-bank-qualifying|title=Daniel Bryan to face Cesaro in Men's Money in the Bank Qualifying Match|website=WWE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n====All Elite Wrestling====\nOn 12 March, [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW) announced the relocation of its two remaining live broadcasts of ''[[AEW Dynamite|Dynamite]]'' on [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] for the month of March, scheduled for [[Rochester, New York]] and [[Newark, New Jersey]] respectively (with the latter originally scheduled to feature AEW's \"[[AEW Blood and Guts|Blood and Guts]]\" event, also indefinitely postponed),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allelitewrestling.com/post/message-from-aew-president-ceo-tony-khan |title=Message From AEW President & CEO Tony Khan |date=21 March 2020 |website=All Elite Wrestling |language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> to an alternative location with no audience. AEW stated that it had re-booked the two cities for future episodes in July.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbr.com/aew-dynamite-coronavirus-venue-changes/ |title=AEW Announces Venue Changes, Including Blood & Guts Show, Due to COVID-19 |date=13 March 2020 |website=CBR |language=en-US|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>  AEW subsequently cancelled on-location ''Dynamite'' broadcasts through at least 13 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/23/aew-postpones-additional-events-still-planning-to-air-dynamite/ |title=AEW postpones additional events, still planning to air Dynamite |date=23 March 2020 |website=Pro Wrestling Dot Net |language=en-US|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/13/aew-announces-additional-postponements-of-dynamite-events/ |title=AEW announces additional postponements of Dynamite events |date=13 March 2020 |website=Pro Wrestling Dot Net |language=en-US|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBeginning on 15 March, AEW began to originate ''Dynamite'' from a closed stage at [[TIAA Bank Field]]'s [[Daily's Place]] amphitheater in [[Jacksonville, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.news4jax.com/news/local/2020/03/13/aew-moves-show-from-rochester-to-jacksonville-due-to-coronavirus/ |title=AEW moves show from Rochester to Jacksonville due to coronavirus |last=Mealey |first=Jason |date=13 March 2020 |website=WJXT |language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Beginning with 1 April episode, ''Dynamite'' moved to an undisclosed location,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-news/aew-filming-dynamite-dark-undisclosed-location-307786 |title=AEW filming Dynamite & Dark in undisclosed location |date=31 March 2020 |website=WON/F4W |language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> later reported to be in [[Norcross, Georgia]]. On 3 April, after a state-wide stay-at-home order was issued, it was reported that AEW had also pre-recorded content for ''Dynamite'' on 1 and 2 April, and that they had amassed enough content \"for weeks if not months if necessary.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/03/aew-taped-weeks-of-television-georgia-state-official-attended-this-weeks-taping/ |title=AEW taped weeks of television, Georgia state official attended this week's taping |last=Papaleo |first=Dennis |date=3 April 2020 |website=Pro Wrestling Dot Net |language=en-US|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sumo wrestling===\nIn spite the March {{ill|2020 in sumo#Haru basho|ja|\u5927\u76f8\u64b2\u4ee4\u548c2\u5e743\u6708\u5834\u6240|lt=Haru basho 2020}} taking behind closed doors without a hitch, bar one rishiki ([[Chiyomaru]]) having temporarily withdrawn from the tournament with a fever whilst undergoing tests; both Natsu basho in May and Nagoya basho in May and July have been postponed by two weeks. The July tournament had been previously moved forward a week to avoid conflict with the 2020 Olympics in Tokyo, which have since been postponed a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200317/p2g/00m/0sp/107000c|title=Sumo: Hakuho suffers upset, falls into 2-way tie for lead on Day 10|date=17 March 2020|work=The Mainichi|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=kyodopostpone>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/04/e6a03e47c65f-breaking-news-grand-sumo-tournament-in-may-to-be-postponed-2-weeks-due-to-virus.html |title=May Sumo tournament to be postponed 2 weeks due to virus |publisher=English.kyodonews.net |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nA week later, the [[Japan Sumo Association]] confirmed the sport's first case when an undisclosed rishiki in the lower ranks, was tested positive after developing a fever some six days earlier. This led to all rishikis and officials being ordered to stay indoor until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/04/d25d0f1d5acb-breaking-news-1st-sumo-wrestler-tests-positive-for-coronavirus.html|title=1st sumo wrestler tests positive for coronavirus\n|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 April 2020|website=english.kyodonews.net|publisher=Kyodo|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cricket==\nThe coronavirus pandemic impacted on several international cricket fixtures and tournaments. The [[2020 ACA Africa T20 Cup Finals]] was scheduled to take place in Kenya in March 2020, before it was postponed in line with the Kenyan government's 30-day ban on international gatherings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africacricket.com/read_more_news.php?id=145 |title=ACA T20 Africa Cup Kenya 2020 postponed |work=Africa Cricket Association |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.busybuddiesng.com/ncf-closes-lagos-camp-as-coronavirus-forces-postponement-of-africa-cricket-championship/ |title=NCF closes Lagos camp as coronavirus forces postponement of Africa Cricket Championship |work=Busy Buddies |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> A women's [[2020 Thailand Women's Quadrangular Series|quadrangular series]] was scheduled to take place in Thailand in April 2020,<ref name=\"CV1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cricketireland.ie/news/article/quadrangular-tournament-ahead-for-ireland-women |title=Quadrangular tournament ahead for Ireland Women |work=Cricket Ireland |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> but was cancelled a month before it was due to start.<ref name=\"CV2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kncb.nl/en/news/womens-quadrangular-series-in-thailand-called-off/ |title=Women's Quadrangular Series in Thailand called off |work=Royal Dutch Cricket Association |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Malaysia Cricket World Cup Challenge League A]], scheduled to take place in March 2020, was postponed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1636508 |title=Men's Cricket World Cup Challenge League A postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> along with two T20I matches [[Mujib 100 T20 Cup Bangladesh 2020|between a World XI and Asia XI side]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28882792/world-xi-v-asia-xi-matches-postponed-amid-coronavirus-fears |title=World XI v Asia XI matches postponed amid coronavirus fears |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2020, English teams [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] and [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] both cancelled their pre-season warm-up tours to the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/51835256 |title=Worcestershire & Surrey cancel pre-season trips to United Arab Emirates over coronavirus fear |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, Australia Women's [[Australia women's cricket team in South Africa in 2019\u201320|tour to South Africa]] in March 2020 became the first major international series not to go ahead as planned due to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1219220.html |title=Australia Women won't tour South Africa as scheduled because of coronavirus |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2020, the [[2020 United States Tri-Nation Series]] was postponed due to the pandemic and travel restrictions to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1645150 |title=Series six of Men's CWC League 2 in USA postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usacricket.org/media-release/mens-cricket-world-cup-league-2-in-usa-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=Men's Cricket World Cup League 2 in USA Postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=USA Cricket |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 12 March, the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] announced that all remaining matches of the [[Pakistan Super League]]'s ongoing [[2020 Pakistan Super League|fifth season]] being played in [[Karachi]] (where the majority of cases in Pakistan had been concentrated) would be closed to spectators.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2174849/1-coronavirus-fears-psl-matches-karachi-played-empty-stadium/ |title=Covid-19: PSL matches in Karachi to be played in empty stadium |work=The Express Tribune |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/psl-matches-in-karachi-to-be-held-closed-door-without-crowd-coronavirus-outbreak-pandemic-1654922-2020-03-12 |title=Coronavirus pandemic: Pakistan Super League matches in Karachi to be played in front of empty stands |work=India Today |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Everest Premier League]] was also postponed on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everest Premier League 2020 postponed due to coronavirus threat |url=https://www.emergingcricket.com/events/everest-premier-league/everest-premier-league-2020-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-threat/ |website=Emerging Cricket |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) announced that the start of [[2020 Indian Premier League]] will be postponed from 29 March to 15 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's official: IPL 2020 postponed to April 15 due to coronavirus |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/top-stories/its-official-ipl-2020-postponed-to-mid-april-due-to-coronavirus/articleshow/74609776.cms |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Times of India}}</ref> Later that day, it cancelled the [[South African cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|ODI matches between India and South Africa on 15 and 18 March]], which were originally announced to be played without spectators.<ref>{{cite news |title=India-South Africa series called off due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/cricket/coronavirus-india-south-africa-series-called-off-due-to-covid-19-threat/article31061061.ece |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Hindu}}</ref> On the same day, the two-match Test series between [[English cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2019\u201320|Sri Lanka and England]], scheduled to be played in March 2020, was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28896266/england-tour-sri-lanka-cancelled-amid-covid-19-spread |title=England tour of Sri Lanka cancelled amid COVID-19 spread |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The remaining seven matches of the [[2020 Road Safety World Series]] were rescheduled to a later date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldseriest20.com/news/in-the-interest-of-public-safety-security-and-support-to-the-government-road-safety-world-series-rescheduled |title=In the interest of public safety & security and support to the Government, Road Safety World Series rescheduled, new dates to be announced later |date=13 March 2020 |website=Road Safety World Series |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> It was earlier decided that the remaining seven matches of the tournament would be played behind the closed doors in [[DY Patil Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldseriest20.com/news/unacademy-road-safety-world-series-to-be-played-behind-closed-doors-in-dy-patil-stadium |title=Unacademy Road Safety World Series to be played behind closed doors in DY Patil Stadium |date=12 March 2020 |website=Road Safety World Series |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2020, the [[New Zealand cricket team in Australia in 2019\u201320|remaining two One Day International (ODI) matches]] of the [[Chappell-Hadlee Trophy]] along with the three-match [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) series [[Australian cricket team in New Zealand in 2019\u201320|between Australia and New Zealand]] were cancelled due to new border restrictions imposed by the New Zealand government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://es.pn/2U7Ngt5 |title=Australia v NZ cancelled amid travel restrictions |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> The first ODI match of the series had been played on 13 March behind closed doors in Sydney.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1645137 |title=COVID-19 outbreak: Chappell-Hadlee series to be held behind closed doors |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, [[Cricket Australia]] confirmed that the final round of matches in the [[2019\u201320 Sheffield Shield season]] had been cancelled, with [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]] being named as the winners of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28913589/new-south-wales-named-sheffield-shield-winners-final-cancelled |title=New South Wales named Sheffield Shield winners as final cancelled |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[New Zealand Cricket]] cancelled the final two rounds of matches in the [[2019\u201320 Plunket Shield season]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28909068/plunket-shield-cancelled-due-coronavirus-measures,-wellington-named-champions |title=Plunket Shield cancelled due to coronavirus measures, Wellington named champions |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> with [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]] being named the winners of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120318144/coronavirus-plunket-shield-cancelled-wellington-firebirds-declared-champions |title=Coronavirus: Plunket Shield cancelled, Wellington Firebirds declared champions |work=Stuff |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, the remaining play-offs in the [[2020 Pakistan Super League]] were postponed due to a huge spike in the number of coronavirus cases around the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geosuper.tv/latest/4433-pcb-decides-to-call-off-psl-2020-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-report |title=PCB 'postpones' PSL 2020 amid coronavirus outbreak |website=www.geosuper.tv}}</ref> The [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]] tour of Pakistan for a single [[One Day International|ODI]] and a [[Test cricket|Test]] match was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1645763 |title=Bangladesh's Karachi leg of Pakistan tour postponed |work=[[International Cricket Council]] |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 West Indies Championship]] was suspended due to the pandemic and [[Barbados national cricket team|Barbados]] was declared the champion on 24 March.<ref>[https://apnews.com/435405d82ed4d043a7998c2a32fc8e87 Barbados declared winners of West Indies championship] AP, 24 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Curling==\nThe [[2019\u201320 curling season|curling season]] typically ends in May but was cut short by the pandemic, effectively ending in early March. The [[World Curling Federation]] cancelled the last five championships scheduled for the 2019\u201320 curling season, most importantly the [[2020 World Women's Curling Championship]], [[2020 World Men's Curling Championship]], and [[2020 World Mixed Doubles Curling Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2019\u20132020 season ends with event cancellations |url=https://worldcurling.org/2020/03/2019-2020-season-ends/ |website=World Curling Federation |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cycling==\n\n===Road cycling===\nThe [[2020 UAE Tour]] was scheduled to run until 29 February, but was abandoned following stage five after two support staff tested positive for coronavirus. Of the following nineteen [[2020 UCI World Tour]] races scheduled to take place up to 31 May, only [[2020 Omloop Het Nieuwsblad|Omloop Het Nieuwsblad]] and [[2020 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]], which also had the final day of racing removed, took place at the intended time, some with the stated hope of taking place at a later date.  The postponed races in this block include the [[2020 Giro d'Italia]] and four of the five annual [[Cycling monument|monuments]], and many lower category races were also cancelled or postponed. Also races of the [[2020 UCI Women's World Tour]] were cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/news/2020/novel-coronavirus-important-information |title=Novel coronavirus: important information |website=UCI |language=en|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Farrand |first=Stephen |title=RCS Sport cancels Strade Bianche in light of coronavirus measures |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/rcs-sport-cancels-strade-bianche-in-light-of-coronavirus-measures/ |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=5 March 2020 |date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Frattini |first=Kirsten |title=Coronavirus: Women's WorldTour Trofeo Alfredo Binda postponed until June 2 |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/coronavirus-womens-worldtour-trofeo-alfredo-binda-postponed-until-june-2/ |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=5 March 2020 |date=5 March 2020 |quote=They are still awaiting the authorisation of the new date from the UCI.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/coronavirus-womens-worldtour-ronde-van-drenthe-cancelled/ |title=Coronavirus: Women's WorldTour Ronde van Drenthe cancelled |first=Lukas |last=Kn\u00f6fler |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |quote=Sadly, this means that our races will not go ahead [...] We hope to be back next year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Geen koers tot en met drie april, Ronde van Vlaanderen maakt nog een waterkansje maar houdt rekening met annulering |language=Dutch|trans-title=No race until 3 April, Tour of Flanders still has a remote chance but takes cancellation into account |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200312_04887671 |work=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |publisher=[[Mediahuis]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |quote=We besluiten bij deze om onze wedstrijd Driedaagse Brugge De Panne ook uit te stellen naar een later tijdstip. We hopen dat we een plaatsje krijgen op de kalender in het najaar. [We hereby decide to postpone our match Three Days Bruges De Panne to a later date. We hope that we will have a place on the calendar in the autumn].}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://sporza.be/nl/2020/03/12/alle-sportactiviteiten-in-belgie-tot-en-met-3-april-worden-gean~1584050395120/ |title=Alle sportactiviteiten in Belgi\u00eb tot en met 3 april worden geannuleerd |language=Dutch|trans-title=All sports activities in Belgium until 3 April will be canceled |work=[[Sporza]] |publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie]] |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |quote=In het wielrennen worden Nokere Koerse (18 maart), de Bredene Koksijde Classic (20 maart), de Driedaagse Brugge-De Panne (25 maart), de E3 Harelbeke (27 maart), Gent-Wevelgem (29 maart) en Dwars door Vlaanderen (1 april) geschrapt. [In cycling Nokere Koerse (March 18), the Bredene Koksijde Classic (March 20), the Driedaagse Brugge-De Panne (March 25), the E3 Harelbeke (March 27), Ghent-Wevelgem (March 29) and Dwars door Vlaanderen (April 1) are scrapped.]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://womenstour.co.uk/womens-tour-2020-postponed |title=Women's Tour 2020 postponed |first=Nick |last=Bull |work=[[The Women's Tour]] |publisher=SweetSpot Group |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/paris-roubaix-fleche-wallonne-and-liege-bastogne-liege-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/ |title=Paris-Roubaix, Fl\u00e8che Wallonne and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge postponed due to coronavirus pandemic |first=Barry |last=Ryan |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |quote=As part of the fight against the spread of Coronavirus (COVID19), Amaury Sport Organisation, with the agreement of the Union Cycliste Internationale (UCI), has decided to not organise Paris-Roubaix (12th April), the Fl\u00e8che Wallonne and the Fl\u00e8che Wallonne Women (22nd April) and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge Women (26th April) races on their scheduled dates.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/tour-of-flanders-cancelled-over-coronavirus-concerns/ |title=Tour of Flanders cancelled over coronavirus concerns |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |quote=Organisers of the Tour of Flanders made the long-anticipated decision to cancel their April 5 race, saying they will work with the UCI and representatives of the teams and riders to look at the potential for scheduling a new date later this year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.velonews.com/2020/03/news/rolling-report-impact-of-coronavirus-on-pro-racing_505843 |title=Rolling report: Impact of coronavirus on pro racing |work=[[VeloNews]] |publisher=Pocket Outdoor Media, LLC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |quote=March 18, 5:15 a.m. (MT): Amstel Gold race postponed}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] requested to suspend all UCI-sanctioned events in affected territories until 3 April, and the qualification for the Tokyo 2020 Olympic Games and Paralympic Games to stop retroactively as of 3 March.<ref name=\"uci20200315\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-takes-strong-measures-faced-with-the-development-of-the-coronavirus |title=The UCI takes strong measures faced with the development of the coronavirus |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March, the suspension of events were extended at least until the end of April.<ref name=\"uci20200318\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-and-its-partners-unite-to-face-the-consequences-of-the-coronavirus-for-road-cycling |title=The UCI and its partners unite to face the consequences of the coronavirus for road cycling |date=18 March 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>  On 1 April, the suspension was extended until 1 June.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-prolongs-the-suspension-of-cycling-events-until-1-june-2020-and-continues-consultations-for-the-reorganisation-of-the-uci-international-road-calendar |title=The UCI prolongs the suspension of cycling events until 1 June 2020 and continues consultations for the reorganisation of the UCI International Road Calendar |date=1 April 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, the annual [[2020 Tour de France|Tour de France]] was originally scheduled for 27 June \u2013 19 July, but it was postponed to an unknown date due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|country's strict measures with the coronavirus]] as [[Government of France|the government]] extended a ban on mass gatherings until July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/cycling/story/_/id/29033546/tour-de-france-postponed-no-new-dates-set|title=Tour de France postponed no new dates set |work=ESPN |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===BMX===\nRace days of the 2020 [[UCI BMX Supercross World Cup]] were cancelled including 2 to 3 May in Papendal, the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://myprivacy.dpgmedia.net/?siteKey=Oom2kBLTny5zJUeO&callbackUrl=https%3a%2f%2fwww.gelderlander.nl%2fprivacy-gate%2faccept%3fredirectUri%3d%252fsport-arnhem%252fwereldbeker-bmx-papendal-ook-van-de-agenda-geld-terug-voor-deelnemers-en-fans%257ea71539c9%252f%253freferrer%253dhttps%253a%252f%252fwww.google.nl%252f |title=Privacy settings |website=myprivacy.dpgmedia.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[UCI BMX World Championships]], scheduled to take place in [[Houston]], United States on 26\u201331 May, are postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/l/2328063 |title=Ook wereldkampioenschappen BMX uitgesteld wegens coronavirus |website=nos.nl |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nThe annual [[Cape Epic]] endurance race scheduled from 15 to 22 March was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cape-epic.com/riders/the-2020-race/official-statement-2020-absa-cape-epic-cancellation |title=The Official Statement regarding the cancellation of the 2020 Absa Cape Epic {{!}} Absa Cape Epic|website=cape-epic.com|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Darts==\nThe [[Professional Darts Corporation]]'s [[PDC European Tour|European Tour]] was impacted by the coronavirus; with the [[2020 European Darts Grand Prix]], the [[2020 European Darts Open]] and the [[2020 German Darts Grand Prix]] all being postponed following restrictions on gatherings implemented by federal governments in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] and [[Bavaria]], respectively. The two [[2020 Premier League Darts]] rounds to be held in [[Rotterdam]] at the end of March were postponed to September following restrictions on gatherings in the Netherlands; and the round to be held in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] a week earlier was subsequently postponed to October.  The next five rounds, in [[Belfast]], [[Sheffield]], [[Manchester]], [[Berlin]] and [[Birmingham]] were also postponed to later dates, with the Sheffield dates now serving as the Play-Off Round.  All ProTour events from 16 March to the end of April were postponed.\n\nThe planned first event on the [[2020 World Series of Darts]], the US Darts Masters, was cancelled for 2020, and the [[2020 Nordic Darts Masters]] was postponed from June to October. The PDC's North American affiliate, the Championship Darts Corporation, cancelled the first weekend of its season in [[Ontario]], and the New Zealand affiliate DartPlayers tour was ended for 2019/20 following the cancellation of events in [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus \u2013 Latest re PDC events |url=https://www.pdc.tv/Coronavirus |publisher=[[Professional Darts Corporation]] |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Esports==\nImpact of the pandemic on [[esports]] have primarily affected events and leagues that host competitions in-person at venues with spectators, which have led to cancellations, postponements, and competitions being held behind closed doors\u2014either in the traditional sense, or with competition being conducted entirely [[Multiplayer video game|over the internet]] (although [[Latency (engineering)|latency]] between players can be a factor), with streaming broadcasts (as is typical for esports).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21167652/coronavirus-esports-impact-league-of-legends-pubg-csgo-iem-katowice |title=The coronavirus' human impact on esports |last=Garst |first=Aron |date=6 March 2020 |website=The Verge |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/esports/2020/03/17/esports-streamers-coronavirus-sports-canceled/ |title=While the sports world falls silent, esports and streamers fill the void |last=Smith |first=Noah |date=17 March 2020 |website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\" />\n\n===Leagues===\n==== Global StarCraft II League ====\nThe [[Global StarCraft II League]] Super Tournament Season I were delayed, but remain offline event, but without spectators. The event won by Terran player Maru.\n\n====Overwatch League====\nThe [[Overwatch League]] cancelled homestand events (matches held on-location at home venues akin to traditional sports leagues, as opposed to a centralized studio) in Asia at the onset of the pandemic, and subsequently cancelled all homestands through to April following its spread in North America in mid-March. The league planned a shift to online play, and competition of the [[2020 Overwatch League season|2020 season]] to resume 21 March. The mid-season tournament was also removed from the schedule, and its all-star festivities were moved to the off-season due to not all players having played an equal number of games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28885048/coronavirus-leads-overwatch-league-suspend-play-march-april |title=Coronavirus leads OWL to cancel events for March, April |date=11 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\"/> Due to [[stay-at-home orders]] imposed by the state of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]] (where [[Blizzard Entertainment|Blizzard]]'s headquarters and several other teams are located), the resumption of play was postponed (although exhibition matches showcasing the game's newly-unveiled character Echo were still held). Play resumed on 28 March, with teams realigned into three regional conferences. Due to various factors, including several teams suspending their operations (including the [[New York Excelsior]], in compliance with a [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|local]] stay-at-home order, and the [[London Spitfire]] and [[Vancouver Titans]] re-locating their staff to South Korea), six of the 16 matches scheduled for the weekend were dropped from the schedule.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28928919/overwatch-league-postpones-first-weekend-online-matches |title=Overwatch League postpones first weekend of online matches |date=20 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/esports/2020/03/27/overwatch-league-schedule-coronavirus-online/ |title=Overwatch League teams face a reset after pandemic spoils its grand plans |last= |first= |date=27 March 2020 |website=Launcher (Washington Post)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/multiple-overwatch-league-matches-canceled-on-march-28-and-29 |title=Multiple Overwatch League matches canceled on March 28 and 29 |last= |first= |date=27 March 2020 |website=Dot eSports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====''League of Legends''====\n[[Riot Games]] announced that the [[League of Legends Championship Series]] would temporarily suspend its season and switch to online play. In addition, the Spring Finals event in Frisco, Texas was called off and moved back to Riot's Los Angeles studio.<ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\">{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28852881/how-coronavirus-affecting-esports-gaming-events |title=How coronavirus is affecting esports and gaming events |last= |first= |date=13 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/14/21179779/league-of-legends-lcs-spring-finals-canceled-moved-ea-sports-fifa-global-series-apex-legends |title=League of Legends, EA suspend all esports due to coronavirus |last=Good |first=Owen S. |date=14 March 2020 |website=Polygon |language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====''Counter-Strike: Global Offensive''====\nThe 2020 IEM Katowice World Championship was played without a live audience due to preemptive closures of large events in Poland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan |title=IEM Katowice playoffs to be played without audience due to coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/29153/iem-katowice-playoffs-to-be-played-without-audience-due-to-coronavirus-concerns |website=HLTV.org |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> As the pandemic became more severe and closures became more common, virtually all [[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]] events were either postponed, cancelled, or moved online. Most notably, the [[ESL One Rio Major 2020]] was postponed from March to November. Remaining qualifiers for the major were cancelled, to be rerun online later.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan |title=Event status update: How the coronavirus is affecting LAN tournaments* |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/29302/event-status-update-how-the-coronavirus-is-affecting-lan-tournaments |website=HLTV.org |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Crossover with traditional sports===\nSportcal suggested that the esports industry had an opportunity to attract mainstream sports fans as a \"viable alternative\" to traditional sporting events.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://advanced-television.com/2020/03/18/analyst-coronavirus-a-significant-opportunity-for-esports/ |title=Analyst: \"Coronavirus a significant opportunity for eSports\" |last= |first= |date= |website=advanced-television.com |language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>  Roundhill Investments CEO Will Hershey predicted that games that are straightforward for casual viewers to understand (such as [[sports game]]s) could see particular interest among this new audience.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWith the suspension of nearly all sporting events, some professional athletes began to increase their involvement in video game streaming as a means to engage with fans.<ref name=\":2\" /> Some teams have taken advantage of sports games in a similar manner, such as the [[Phoenix Suns]] holding ''[[NBA 2K20]]'' streams with guest players, between the teams the Suns were scheduled to play that night if the season had continued.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28900417/luka-doncic-50-leads-mavs-suns-twitch |title=Luka's 50 lead Mavericks past Suns \u2013 on Twitch |date=14 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28964373/bridges-leads-suns-victory-first-nba-2k-game-broadcast-radio |title=Bridges leads Suns to victory in first NBA 2K game broadcast on radio |date=28 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> This culminated with a game actually being commentated by the team's radio broadcasters on team flagship [[KMVP-FM]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nEsports organisations have also invited professional athletes to compete in specific competitions (often alongside, or in competition with professional players); [[FaZe Clan]] organized a charity ''[[Call of Duty: Warzone]]'' pro-am entitled \"Fight 2 Fund\" in support of coronavirus-related charities, where professional players were partnered with celebrity participants (such as [[Ben Simmons]], [[Chad Johnson]], and [[JuJu Smith-Schuster]]),<ref name=\":2\" /> and several [[sim racing]] competitions similarly invited professional race drivers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2020/03/esports-fills-the-gap-as-coronavirus-cancels-in-person-sporting-events/ |title=F1 drivers and other pros switch to esports in the age of the coronavirus |last=Gitlin |first=Jonathan M. |date=16 March 2020 |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/22/21184192/sim-racing-coronavirus-f1-nascar-iracing-veloce-esports-max-verstappen-lando-norris |title=Pro drivers are competing with gamers after F1 and NASCAR canceled races |last=O'Kane |first=Sean |date=22 March 2020 |website=The Verge |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn turn, both the [[IndyCar Series]] and [[NASCAR]] announced partnerships with sim racing platform ''[[iRacing]]'' to hold online invitational events featuring series regulars, with the latter employing television broadcasts by NASCAR television partner [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Sports]] (styled after and still featuring personalities associated with their traditional broadcasts, including the commentary pair of [[Mike Joy]] and [[Jeff Gordon]], based at [[Fox Sports 1]]'s studio in Charlotte).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2020/03/22/nascar-iracing-pro-invitational-series-fox-sports-1-high-marks/2894874001/ |title=FS1 broadcast of NASCAR iRacing comes extremely close to the real thing |last=Gardner |first=Steve |website=USA Today |language=en-US|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/story/_/id/28919500/with-nascar-season-postponed-drivers-compete-esports-series |title=NASCAR greats set to compete in esports series |date=18 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn.com\" />  The first event (using [[Homestead-Miami Speedway]], where the [[NASCAR Cup Series]] was to have raced that weekend) drew a television audience of 903,000 on [[Fox Sports 1]], making it the most-watched esports broadcast on U.S. linear television since a 2016 ''[[Mortal Kombat X]]'' event aired by [[The CW]]. This record was surpassed the following week with a Texas Motor Speedway race \u2014 also aired by the main [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox network]] \u2014 which attracted 1.339 million viewers.<ref name=\"AW\">{{cite web |last1=Weaver |first1=Matt |title=Texas eNASCAR iRacing Event Breaks TV Record for Esports Broadcast |url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a31996587/texas-enascar-iracing-event-breaks-tv-record-for-esports-broadcast/ |website=Autoweek.com |publisher=Autoweek |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=AW}}</ref>\n\n==Fencing==\nOn 3 March 2020 the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale d'Escrime]] (FIE) issued its first bulletin on COVID-19 precautions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fie.org/articles/942 |title=INTERNATIONAL FENCING FEDERATION - The International Fencing Federation official website |publisher=Fie.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 10 March FIE strongly recommended that all participants in its competitions (athletes and other members of national delegations) fill and carry with them a questionnaire about their health status.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fie.org/articles/947 |title=INTERNATIONAL FENCING FEDERATION - The International Fencing Federation official website |publisher=Fie.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 12 March a FIE circular reported the postponement of six World Cup or Grand Prix competitions and the World Junior/Cadet Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fie.org/articles/948 |title=INTERNATIONAL FENCING FEDERATION - The International Fencing Federation official website |publisher=Fie.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Since the World Cup and Grand Prix events were part of the [[Fencing at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|qualifications for the 2020 Tokyo Olympics]], the circular warned on the need to postpone the zonal qualifications tournament for the Olympics. No news was given on other events, and their possible postponement or cancellation.\n\nFIE reported on its web site<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fie.org/articles/949 |title=INTERNATIONAL FENCING FEDERATION - The International Fencing Federation official website |publisher=Fie.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> the postponement of the Olympic Games, but hasn't yet given any information on the [[World Fencing Championships]], which is supposed to happen in non-Olympic years, so there is a 2021 Championship planned (assigned to Cairo), but not a 2020 Championship.\n\nIndividual countries had different decisions. For example, on 4 April the [[Federazione Italiana Scherma]] announced it was suspending all competitions until 31 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.federscherma.it/homepage/media/news/14-news/top-news/30976-il-consiglio-federale-sospende-l-attivita-agonistica-fino-al-31-agosto-in-pedana-solo-per-allenarsi,-quando-sara-consentito.html |title=Federazione Italiana Scherma - IL CONSIGLIO FEDERALE SOSPENDE L'ATTIVITA' AGONISTICA FINO AL 31 AGOSTO. IN PEDANA SOLO PER ALLENARSI, QUANDO SARA' CONSENTITO |publisher=Federscherma.it |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Field hockey==\nMany field hockey leagues in Europe have been suspended, including in Spain,<ref>{{cite web |title=Comunicado Oficial RFEH |url=https://www.rfeh.es/comunicado-oficial-rfeh-7/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=es}}</ref> England,<ref>{{cite web |title=England Hockey suspends national hockey activity |url=https://www.englandhockey.co.uk/news.asp?itemid=49019&itemTitle=England+Hockey+suspends+national+hockey+activity&section=22 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> Germany,<ref>{{cite web |title=Feldhockey-Bundesligen: Spielverkehr bis Ende April ausgesetzt |url=https://web.hockey.de/news/lgtz22.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=de}}</ref> and the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geen competitie en hockeyactiviteiten tot 1 april |url=https://www.knhb.nl/nieuws/geen-competitie-en-hockeyactiviteiten-tot-1-april |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Euro Hockey League]] Final 8 and [[2020 Euro Hockey League Women]] seasons were suspended on 12 March.<ref name=\"EHL\">{{cite web |title=EHL Final8 Put on Hold |url=https://ehlhockey.tv/2020/03/12/ehl-final8-put-on-hold/ |website=ehlhockey.tv |publisher=[[Euro Hockey League]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Men's EuroHockey Club Trophy I]], [[2020 Men's EuroHockey Club Trophy II]], [[2020 Boys' EuroHockey Youth Championships]] and [[2020 Girls' EuroHockey Youth Championships]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=EHF cancels all EuroHockey Club Trophy and Challenge events, 2020 |url=https://eurohockey.org/2020/03/24/ehf-cancels-all-eurohockey-club-trophy-and-challenge-events-2020/ |website=eurohockey.org |publisher=[[European Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=EuroHockey U18 Championships boys and girls 2020 are cancelled |url=https://eurohockey.org/2020/03/31/eurohockey-u18-championships-boys-and-girls-2020-are-cancelled/ |website=eurohockey.org |publisher=[[European Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Asia, the [[2020 Men's Hockey Junior Asia Cup]], [[2020 Women's Asian Champions Trophy]], and [[2020 Women's Hockey Junior Asia Cup]] were postponed.<ref name=\"AHF2020\">{{cite web |title=Announcement: Postponement of the Bangabandhu Al-Arafah Islami Bank Junior Asia Cup Dhaka 2020 & the Women's Asian Champions Trophy Donghae 2020 |url=http://www.asiahockey.org/news/announcement-postponement-of-the-bangabandhu-al-arafah-islami-bank-junior-asia-cup-dhaka-2020-the-womens-asian-champions-trophy-donghae-2020/ |website=asiahockey.org |publisher=[[Asian Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Junior Asia Cup Gifu Kakamigahara 2020 \u2013 Formal Announcement of Postponement |url=http://www.asiahockey.org/news/womens-junior-asia-cup-gifu-kakamigahara-2020-formal-announcement-of-postponement/ |website=asiahockey.org}}</ref> The [[2020 Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] has been postponed to 24 September.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Azlan Shah Cup Hockey Tournament Postponed |url=https://sports.ndtv.com/hockey/coronavirus-azlan-shah-cup-hockey-tournament-postponed-2188516 |website=ndtv.com |publisher=[[NDTV]]}}</ref>\n\n==Futsal==\nThe [[2020 AFC Futsal Championship]] in [[Ashgabat]] had been postponed following consultation with all relevant stakeholders. On 9 March 2020, FIFA and AFC announced that the tournament were postponed to 5\u201316 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers|title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers|publisher=FIFA.com|date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers|title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers|publisher=AFC|date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://futsalfeed.com/original-content/robert-grdovic-talks-about-postponed-afc-futsal-championship-and-predicts-the-outcome|title=Robert Grdovic talks about postponed AFC Futsal Championship and predicts the outcome|publisher=futsallfeed.com| accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Golf==\nMany elite golf tournaments, both professional and amateur, have either been postponed or cancelled in response to the pandemic, including the [[Men's major golf championships|major championships]].<ref name=golftourneys/> On 13 March, it was announced that the [[2020 Masters Tournament|Masters Tournament]] (scheduled for 9\u201312 April) had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Masters Tournament Postponed |url=https://www.masters.com/en_US/news/articles/2020-03-13/2020_masters_tournament_postponed.html |publisher=Masters.com |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=Augusta National announces Masters will be postponed |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28897249/augusta-national-announces-masters-postponed-played |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 PGA Championship]] (scheduled for 11\u201317 May) was postponed the following week.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/sports/golf/pga-championship-postponed.html |title=P.G.A. Championship Is Postponed |newspaper=The New York Times |last=Pennington |first=Bill |date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 6 April, [[The Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St Andrews|The R&A]] announced the cancellation of the [[2020 Open Championship]], the first cancellation since World War II.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/golf/news/12176/11969376/the-149th-open-cancelled-for-this-year-and-will-return-to-sandwich-in-2021 |title=The 149th Open cancelled for this year and will return to Sandwich in 2021 |website=Sky Sports |first=Keith |last=Jackson |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> This was soon followed by the [[United States Golf Association|USGA]] announcing the rescheduling of the [[2020 U.S. Open (golf)|2020 U.S. Open]] from 18\u201321 June to 17\u201320 September, and new dates in November for the Masters and in August for the PGA Championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/52135613 |title=The Open cancelled; Masters, US Open & US PGA Championship rescheduled |website=BBC Sport |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The ladies majors have been similarly affected, with the [[LPGA Tour]] postponing the [[ANA Inspiration]] until September.<ref name=lpga1/>\n\nOn 12 March 2020, midway through the first round of the [[2020 Players Championship]], the [[PGA Tour]] announced that the remainder of the tournament and the next three events, the [[Valspar Championship]], [[WGC Match Play]], and the [[Valero Texas Open]], would continue without fan attendance. Subsequently, after completion of the days play, the tour decided to cancel the remainder of tournament and the three following events.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=Players Championship, other events won't have fans in attendance |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28890609/players-starts-autograph-ban-place |accessdate=13 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=PGA Tour cancels Players Championship after first round |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28894497/pga-tour-cancels-players-championship-first-round |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March, the tour announced the cancellation of all scheduled tournaments through 10 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pgatour.com/company/2020/03/17/pga-tour-news-tournament-cancellations-rbc-heritage-zurich-classic-new-orleans-wells-fargo-championship-att-byron-nelson-pga-championship.html |title=PGA Tour statement regarding additional tournament cancellations |publisher=PGA Tour |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> The [[European Tour]] have also cancelled or postponed many tournaments, mostly those scheduled from mid-March through to the end of May,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/news/articles/detail/update-on-european-tour-events/ |title=Update on European Tour events |website=European Tour |date=27 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> including the [[Irish Open (golf)|Irish Open]], a [[Rolex Series]] event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/52092416 |title=Irish Open: Mount Juliet European Tour event postponed because of coronavirus |website=BBC Sport |date=30 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Ladies European Tour]] postponed the 2020 [[Evian Championship]], originally scheduled for 23\u201326 July, to 6\u20139 August.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Evian Championship Moves to Early August |url=https://ladieseuropeantour.com/the-evian-championship-moves-to-early-august/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |publisher=Ladies European Tour |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther leading professional tours have announced similar measures, as have the bodies responsible for organising leading amateur events.<ref name=golftourneys/> On 1 April, the R&A and the USGA jointly announced that the [[2020 Curtis Cup|Curtis Cup]] was being postponed until 2021, and the British [[The Amateur Championship|mens]] and [[The Womens Amateur Championship|womens]] amateur championships were being rescheduled from June to August.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.golfchannel.com/news/curtis-cup-postponed-2021-british-amateur-championships-rescheduled |title=Curtis Cup postponed to 2021; British Ams rescheduled |website=Golf Channel |date=1 April 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The LPGA Tour have cancelled three tournaments and postponed five others including the ANA Inspiration,<ref name=lpga1>{{cite news |title=LPGA to reschedule 3 events, including first major, the ANA Inspiration |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28893923/lpga-reschedule-3-events-including-first-major-ana-inspiration |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=golftourneys>{{cite web |url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/here-are-all-the-golf-tournaments-that-have-been-canceled-or-postponed-due-to-the-coronavirus |title=Here are all the golf tournaments that have been canceled or postponed due to the coronavirus |website=Golf Digest |publisher=Golf World |first=Ryan |last=Herrington |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Japan LPGA Tour]] cancelled five tournaments scheduled from March into April.<ref name=sched>{{cite web |url=https://www.lpga.or.jp/tournament/jlpgatour/2020 |title=2020\u5e74\u5ea6 JLPGA\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc\u30b9\u30b1\u30b8\u30e5\u30fc\u30eb |trans-title=2020 JLPGA Tour Schedule |publisher=JLPGA |language=ja}}</ref>\n\nRecreational golf has also been affected, with many countries and regions ordering the closure of golf [[country club|clubs]] and [[golf course|courses]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/coronavirus-more-than-1-3-of-europes-golf-courses-now-closed |title=Coronavirus: Almost half of Europe's golf courses are now closed! |website=Bunkered |date=18 March 2020 |first=Michael |last=McEwan |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/golf-canada-ceo-applebaum-asks-golfers-to-stay-home-during-covid-19-pandemic-1.4863339 |title=Golf Canada CEO Applebaum asks golfers to stay home during COVID-19 pandemic |first=John |last=Chidley-Hill |agency=The Canadian Press |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/golf-courses-to-close-as-uk-steps-up-coronavirus-fight |title=Golf courses to CLOSE as UK steps up coronavirus fight |website=Bunkered |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://7news.com.au/sport/golf/australian-golf-courses-told-to-close-immediately-as-coronavirus-restrictions-take-hold-c-772433 |title=Australian golf courses told to close immediately as coronavirus restrictions take hold |first=Glenn |last=Valencich |website=Seven News |date=30 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/heres-a-state-by-state-breakdown-of-where-golfs-allowed-and-where-it-isnt |title=Here's a state-by-state breakdown of where golf's allowed and where it isn't |website=Golf World (Golf Digest) |first=Mike |last=Stachura |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Greyhound racing==\nThe [[2020 English Greyhound Derby]] was postponed on 16 March with no replacement dates set at present.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/derby-postponed-statement/ |title=DERBY POSTPONED \u2013 ARC STATEMENT |website=Greyhound Star}}</ref> The [[Arena Racing Company]] tracks announced a behind closed doors policy from 24 March <ref>{{cite web |url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/arc-meetings-staged-behind-closed-doors/ |title=ALL ARC MEETINGS TO BE STAGED BEHIND CLOSED DOORS |website=Greyhound Star}}</ref> and [[Greyhound racing in Ireland|racing in Ireland]] continued with a behind closed doors policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.igb.ie/talking-dogs/covid-19-update-racing-behind-closed-doors/ |title=COVID 19 UPDATE: RACING BEHIND CLOSED DOORS |publisher=Irish Greyhound Board}}</ref> Subsequently all racing in the United Kingdom and Ireland was postponed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/greyhound-racing-suspended-press-release/|title=Greyhound racing suspended \u2013 Press release|publisher=Greyhound Star}}</ref>\n\n==Gridiron football==\n\n===Canadian Football League===\nOn 12 March, the [[Canadian Football League]] announced the cancellation or modification of several pre-season events in response to the pandemic. Several scouting combines across Canada and the United States were cancelled, while other events such as rules committee meetings will now be held remotely. The League initially planned to hold both its International and National Drafts in April, but it was announced on 24 March that the Global Draft would be postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/2020/03/12/statement-cfl-coronavirus-situation/ |title=A statement from the CFL on the Coronavirus situation |website=cfl.ca|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/2020/03/24/cfl-global-draft-rescheduled-lead-event-prior-training-camp/ |title=CFL GLOBAL DRAFT RESCHEDULED AS LEAD-IN EVENT PRIOR TO TRAINING CAMP |website=cfl.ca|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe start of the [[2020 CFL season|2020 regular season]] was officially postponed until at least the start of July by Commissioner [[Randy Ambrosie]] on 7 April. In a press statement, he announced that the CFL was exploring multiple options to ensure that the league will be able to play as close to a full season as possible.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/2020/04/07/ambrosie-issues-statement-behalf-cfl/ |title=AMBROSIE ISSUES STATEMENT ON BEHALF OF CFL |website=cfl.ca|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> The regular season had originally been scheduled to begin on 11 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cfl.ca/schedule/?season=2020|title=2020 CFL Schedule|publisher=cfl.ca|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===National Football League===\nThe [[National Football League]] has been in its off-season since [[Super Bowl LIV|2 February 2020]], but the [[2020 NFL Draft]] is scheduled to be held in [[Las Vegas]] from 23\u201325 April 2020. On 12 March, various NFL teams began to suspend travel by their coaches and [[Scout (sport)|player scout]]s, while the league itself had advised its non-critical staff to work from home. On 13 March 2020, the NFL announced that it had temporarily prohibited draft-eligible players from travelling to meet team personnel, and vice versa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/nfl-coronavirus-updates-league-prohibits-pre-draft-visits-mulls-draft-changes-xfl-player-tests-positive/ |title=NFL coronavirus updates: League prohibits pre-draft visits, mulls draft changes, XFL player tests positive |website=CBSSports.com |language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the NFL announced that it had cancelled public festivities associated with the draft; the draft itself will still be held, but the league stated that it was exploring \"innovative options for how the process will be conducted\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Belson |first=Ken |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/sports/football/nfl-draft-coronavirus.html |title=How the N.F.L. Draft Process Works From Home |date=27 March 2020 |work=The New York Times|access-date=29 March 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106351/article/nfl-draft-to-proceed-april-2325-sans-public-events-in-las-vegas |title=NFL draft to proceed April 23\u201325 sans public events in Las Vegas |website=NFL.com |language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLabor negotiations with the [[National Football League Players Association]] continued through the pandemic, resulting in ratification of a new, ten-year [[collective bargaining agreement]] in March 2020.\n\n===XFL===\nOn 12 March, the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] (a revival of the one-season [[XFL (2001)|2001 league]]) announced the suspension of the 2020 season, with all players to be paid their base pay and benefits for the full 2020 regular season; the season was officially cancelled on 20 March, with half of its ten-week regular season schedule played.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/xfl-officially-cancels-inaugural-season-reveals-when-players-can-sign-with-nfl-or-cfl-teams/ |title=XFL officially cancels inaugural season, reveals when players can sign with NFL or CFL teams |last=Dajani |first=Jordan |date=20 March 2020 |publisher=[[CBSSports.com]] |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, the league announced that it would suspend all operations and lay off all but a few critical executives, and said it was unlikely a 2021 season would be organized and played, with those executives remaining to wind down the league's business and operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/xfl/story/_/id/29021347/xfl-suspends-operations-lays-employees-no-plans-return-2021|title=XFL suspends operations, lays off employees and has no plans for 2021 season|last=Siefert|first=Kevin|date=10 April 2020|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gymnastics==\nMultiple international artistic gymnastics competitions, many of which were [[Gymnastics at the 2020 Summer Olympics|Olympic]] qualifying events, were either canceled or postponed.  On 13 March, after already having completed qualifications, the [[2020 FIG Artistic Gymnastics World Cup series|Baku World Cup]] canceled its event finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/news/displaynews.php?idNews=2836 |title=Finals of Baku World Cup cancelled |work=[[International Gymnastics Federation]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>  The Stuttgart, Birmingham, and Tokyo World Cups (scheduled to take place between 21 March \u2013 5 April) were all canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/news/displaynews.php?idNews=2827 |title=Impact of the COVID-19 outbreak on the upcoming FIG events |work=[[International Gymnastics Federation]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.british-gymnastics.org/news-and-events/news/latest-news/9015-british-gymnastics-national-events-announcement-including-fig-world-cup |title=British Gymnastics national events announcement, including FIG World Cup |work=[[British Gymnastics]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=tokyowc>{{cite tweet |number=1239945252183703553 |user=FIG_media |date=17 March 2020 |title=Japan Gymnastics Association has decided to cancel the #Tokyo All-Around World Cup that was scheduled on 4\u20135 April 2020}}</ref>  The [[European Women's Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] (scheduled to take place 30 April \u2013 3 May) and the [[European Men's Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] (scheduled to take place 27\u201331 May) were both canceled.<ref name=euros2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.ueg.org/news/covid-19-update-event-cancellations |title=COVID-19 update \u2013 event cancellations |work=[[European Union of Gymnastics]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>  The [[Pacific Rim Championships]] (scheduled to take place 17\u201319 April) was postponed until 2021.<ref name=pacrim>{{cite web |url=https://www.gymnasticsnz.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/2020-Pacific-Rim-postponement-announcement-final-17Mar20.pdf |title=2020 Pacific Rim Championships Postponed |date=17 March 2020 |work=Gymnastics New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n==Handball==\nThe 25\u201329 March, [[2020 European Women's Handball Championship qualification]] matches in Rotterdam, the Netherlands were cancelled.<ref name=\"nu.nl\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nu.nl/sport-overig/6033687/deze-sportevenementen-zijn-afgelast-vanwege-het-coronavirus.html |title=Deze sportevenementen zijn afgelast vanwege het coronavirus |date=27 February 2020 |website=NU |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Horse racing==\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, most horse racing events remained scheduled as normal, but with restricted attendance at racecourses. This included Hong Kong, France,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/sports/hippisme/coronavirus-les-courses-hippiques-et-les-turfistes-s-adaptent-10-03-2020-8276982.php |title=Coronavirus : Les courses hippiques et les turfistes s'adaptent |first1=Par St\u00e9phan FlourentLe 10 mars 2020 |last1=\u00e0 19h56 |first2=Modifi\u00e9 Le 10 Mars 2020 |last2=\u00c0 19h57 |date=10 March 2020 |website=leparisien.fr}}</ref> Japan,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/238823/coronavirus-forces-bettors-online-in-japan |title=Coronavirus Forces Bettors Online in Japan |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |first=Naohiro |last=Goda |date=2 March 2020}}</ref> United Arab Emirates,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/horse-racing/the-35-million-dubai-world-cup-show-must-go-on-1.70362919 |title=The $35 million Dubai World Cup show must go on |website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> United States, Australia,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.racenet.com.au/news/all-star-mile-slated-to-go-ahead-yet-fans-banned-from-australian-grand-prix-20200313 |title=LATEST BREAKING NEWS \u2013 All-Star Mile to go ahead but crowd lockout |website=www.racenet.com.au}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/latest/dundalk-to-race-behind-closed-doors-as-ireland-launches-coronavirus-restrictions/427842 |title=Racing in Ireland to go ahead behind closed doors until March 29 &#124; Horse Racing News &#124; Racing Post |website=www.racingpost.com}}</ref> United Kingdom, Germany, New Zealand, and Singapore.\n\nThe [[Macau Jockey Club]] suspended racing events from 31 January to 15 February and resumed racing from 22 February. The [[Korea Racing Authority]] suspended horse racing from 8 March. [[Sunland Park Racetrack & Casino|Sunland Park Racetrack]] in the United States canceled its race meeting from 16 March, which included the [[Sunland Derby]], part of the [[2020 Road to the Kentucky Derby]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239094/maryland-new-mexico-close-tracks-simulcast-facilities |title=Maryland, New Mexico Close Tracks, Simulcast Facilities |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Many tracks in North America followed suit over the following weeks, although some remained open depending on state-by-state decisions. In Britain, although the [[Cheltenham Festival]] proceeded as normal in mid-March,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oliphant |first1=Vickiie |title=Cheltenham coronavirus advice: How to avoid COVID-19 \u2013 Festival guidelines in FULL |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/horseracing/1252795/Cheltenham-coronavirus-advice-guidelines-in-full-cheltenham-festival-races |website=Express.co.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> the [[Grand National]] meeting at Aintree in April was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/grand-national-meeting-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/428688 |title=Grand National cancelled as Aintree card lost to spiralling coronavirus crisis &#124; Horse Racing News &#124; Racing Post |website=www.racingpost.com}}</ref> By mid-March [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] had become the only major horse racing country in Europe where the sport continued, albeit strictly regulated and behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/18/talking-horses-racing-industry-left-to-contemplate-cost-of-suspension |title=Ireland goes it alone as racing continues behind closed doors |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Greg |last=Wood |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Ireland finally closed down racing on 25 March until at least 19 April.<ref name=IrelandCancelled />\n\n[[Churchill Downs]] announced that the [[2020 Kentucky Derby]], normally the first leg of the [[Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing|American Triple Crown]], would be delayed to 5 September;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239121/the-146th-kentucky-derby-moved-to-sept-5 |title=The 146th Kentucky Derby Moved to Sept. 5 |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Eric |last1=Mitchell |first2=Byron |last2=King |title=Owners, Trainers React to Kentucky Derby Postponement |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239123/owners-trainers-react-to-kentucky-derby-postponement |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |date=17 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> this also cascaded to the [[Preakness Stakes]], with the [[Maryland Jockey Club]] delaying their second leg race to a date to be determined, likely in September as well.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-latest-will-the-preakness-be-postponed-jockey-club-discussing/ |title=Coronavirus Latest: Preakness To Be Postponed, Likely To September |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=[[WJZ-TV]] |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The [[New York Racing Association]] has not announced plans to reschedule the [[Belmont Stakes]], normally the third leg.\n\nOn 22 March, it was announced that the [[Dubai World Cup]], due to celebrate its 25th anniversary running on 28 March, had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Dubai World Cup night is called off at Meydan |url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/2020-dubai-world-cup-night-is-called-off-at-meydan-1.1584882198359 |website=Gulf News |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, [[Jockey Club|Jockey Club Racecourses]] announced that the first four [[British Classic Races|Classics]] of the British flat racing season \u2013 the [[2000 Guineas Stakes|2000]] and [[1000 Guineas Stakes|1000 Guineas]], scheduled to be held on 2\u20133 May, and the [[Epsom Oaks]] and [[Epsom Derby|Derby]], scheduled to be held on 5\u20136 June \u2013 would be postponed until later in the season. Ascot Racecourse also announced that [[Royal Ascot]], scheduled to be held from 16\u201320 June, would take place [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] if it gets the go-ahead.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guineas and Derby meetings to be held later in the season, Jockey Club announces |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/guineas-and-derby-meetings-to-be-held-later-in-the-season-jockey-club-announces/431135 |website=Racing Post |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Royal Ascot to take place behind closed doors if given green light |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/royal-ascot-to-take-place-behind-closed-doors-due-to-the-coronavirus/431128 |website=Racing Post |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome horsemen are limited from travelling to other racecouses or horse racing facilities. Hong Kong-based jockey [[Keith Yeung]] felt unwell on 22 March night, but his test for COVID-19 PCR was negative.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/racing/article/3076478/hong-kong-jockey-keith-yeungs-covid-19-test-comes-back-negative |title=Hong Kong jockey Keith Yeung's Covid-19 test comes back negative |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, it was announced that American-based jockey [[Javier Castellano]] had tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=King |first1=Byron |title=Jockey Castellano Tests Positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239301/jockey-castellano-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |website=BloodHorse.com |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n;Cancelled race meetings<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Updates/Announcements |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/section/covid-19-updates-announcements |website=www.bloodhorse.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Macau Jockey Club]] \u2013 31 to 15 January February 28 March to 11 April<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mjc.mo/race_en/info/news_detail.php?newsid=32256 |title=Macau Jockey Club \u2013 Company News |website=Macau Jockey Club |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Korea Racing Authority]] \u2013 from 8 March\n*Selangor Turf Club, Malaysia \u2013 from 14 March\n*[[Sunland Park Racetrack & Casino|Sunland Park Racetrack]], New Mexico \u2013 March meeting\n*[[Keeneland]], Kentucky \u2013 April meeting. [[Kentucky Downs]] and [[Ellis Parks]] closed down in mid-March, while [[Turfway Park]] cancelled the last 4 days of its meeting at the end of March. Churchill Downs deferred the Kentucky Derby and Kentucky Oaks, normally scheduled for early May, to September\n* [[Woodbine Racetrack]], Toronto \u2013 harness racing from 14 March. Thoroughbred meeting scheduled to open on April 18 postponed to at least June 30\n* [[Aqueduct Racetrack]], New York \u2013 indefinitely from 19 March after a backstretch worker tested positive\n* [[Laurel Park (race track)|Laurel Park]], Maryland \u2013 indefinitely from 20 March\n* [[Fair Grounds Race Course|Fair Grounds]], Louisiana \u2013 cancelled last week of its winter meeting, 22 to 29 March\n* [[Santa Anita Park]], California \u2013 indefinitely from 27 March. Racing at Golden Gate Fields was suspended on April 2\n*All United Kingdom racecourses \u2013 18 March to 30 April (excluding [[Downpatrick Racecourse|Downpatrick]] and [[Down Royal Racecourse|Down Royal]] in Northern Ireland, which come under Irish racing rules)\n*All Ireland racecourses \u2013 25 March to 19 April<ref name=IrelandCancelled>{{cite web |title=Racing off in Ireland from Wednesday after all sporting events are cancelled |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/racing-off-after-all-sporting-events-are-cancelled-in-ireland/429939 |website=Racing Post |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*All German racecourses \u2013 17 March to 18 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.turf-times.de/tt-artikel/wegen-des-coronavirus-renn-stopp-bis-zum-18-april-deutschland |title=Wegen des Coronavirus: Renn-Stopp bis zum 18. April in Deutschland! &#124; Turf-Times Deutschland |website=www.turf-times.de |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*All French racecourses [[France Galop]] and [[LeTrot]] \u2013 17 March to 15 April\n*All United Arab Emirates race meetings \u2013 Including [[Dubai World Cup Night]] and four April meetings.\n*All New Zealand racecourses \u2013 From 24 March\n*All South African racecourses \u2013 27 March to 16 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportingpost.co.za/2020/03/sa-horseracing/ |title=Newsflash: It's Official \u2013 No SA Racing |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Singapore Turf Club]] \u2013 Form 4 April\n\n;Remaining racing meetings<ref>[https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/where-is-racing-still-happening-globally-and-when-could-countries-start-up-again/431022  Where is racing still happening and when could countries start up again?]</ref>\n*[[Hong Kong Jockey Club]] \u2013 no meeting canceled or rescheduled under coronavirus.\n*[[Macau Jockey Club]] \u2013 resumed racing from 22 February to 21 March\n*[[Japan Racing Association]] and [[National Association of Racing]] \u2013 no meeting canceled ot rescheduled under coronavirus.\n*Sweden, including flat racing and harness racing.\n*Most Australian racecourses \u2013 Some County and Picnic meetings are canceled, also Tasmanian racing canceled form 2 April.\n*Some American racecourses, including [[Gulfstream Park]] and [[Tampa Bay Downs]] in Florida, and [[Oaklawn Park]] in Arkansas\n\n==Ice hockey==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship|IIHF Women's World Championship]], [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division IV|IIHF World Championship Division IV]] and [[2020 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships|Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]] were all cancelled by the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] due to the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://iihf.com/en/events/2020/ww/news/18296/women%E2%80%99s-worlds-cancelled |title=Women's Worlds cancelled |date=7 March 2020 |work=iihf.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/news/18277/iihf-cancels-march-tournaments |title=IIHF cancels March tournaments |date=2 March 2020 |work=iihf.com}}</ref> The federation also cancelled the [[2020 IIHF World U18 Championships|2020 event]] of one of its two official junior world championship tournaments, the [[IIHF World U18 Championship]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=IIHF cancels U18 Worlds |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/events/2020/wm18/news/18313/iihf-cancels-u18-world-chhmpionship |location=[[Plymouth Charter Township, Michigan]] & [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], [[United States]] |publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]] |first=Adam |last=Steiss |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, IIHF publicly announced that the senior men's world championships had also been cancelled.<ref>{{cite press release |title=2020 IIHF Ice Hockey World Championship cancelled |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/events/2020/wm/news/18344/2020-iihf-ice-hockey-world-championship-cancelled |location=[[Switzerland]] |publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]] |website=iihf.com |first=Adam |last=Steiss |date=21 March 2020 | access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Cancelled tournaments:'''\n\n* [[2020 IIHF World U18 Championships]]\n*[[2020 IIHF World Championship]]s\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division I]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division II]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division III]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division IV]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship Division I]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship Division II]] Group A\n\n===Europe===\nAs a result of the German government's ban on large events, the [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] announced on 10 March that it would cancel the remainder of its season, marking the first time in the league's history a champion would not be crowned. The top four teams at the time of the cancellation \u2014 [[EHC Red Bull M\u00fcnchen]], [[Adler Mannheim]], [[Straubing Tigers]], and [[Eisbaren Berlin]] \u2014 would advance to the [[Champions Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=German League cancels season, won't crown champion as a result of coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/german-league-cancels-season-wont-crown-champion-as-a-result-of-coronavirus-outbreak |first=Jared |last=Clinton |publisher=[[The Hockey News]] |website=thehockeynews.com |date=10 March 2020 | access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Swedish Ice Hockey Association]] suspended all remaining hockey, the playoffs and qualification rounds, in the Swedish elite leagues on 15 March; no awarding of the [[Le Mat Trophy]] for the 2019/20 season nor transference of teams from the leagues' qualification plays for the 2020/21 season will happen as a result.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hockeys\u00e4songen 2019/20 st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.hockeyallsvenskan.se/artikel/2ittak7t7-1el1/hockeysasongen-2019-20-stalls-in |publisher=[[HockeyAllsvenskan]] |language=Swedish |website=hockeyallsvenskan.se |date=10 March 2020 | access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Cancelled or ended leagues:'''\n\n* [[2019\u201320 Czech Extraliga season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 Slovak Extraliga season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 Austrian Hockey League season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 DEL season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 SHL season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 EIHL season]]\n\n===North America===\nIn early March 2020, the [[National Hockey League]] suspended media access to the locker rooms, saying that only official personnel would be allowed in after the games to limit person-to-person contact. On 12 March, the NHL, [[American Hockey League]], the leagues of the [[Canadian Hockey League]] ([[Ontario Hockey League]], [[Quebec Major Junior Hockey League]], and [[Western Hockey League]]), the [[United States Hockey League|USHL]], and [[ECHL]] announced that their [[2019\u201320 NHL season|2019\u201320 seasons]] would be indefinitely suspended.<ref>{{cite web |title=NHL pauses regular season because of coronavirus |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gaydos |first1=Ryan |title=NHL suspends 2019\u201320 season over coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/nhl-suspends-season-over-coronavirus-outbreak |website=Fox News |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaplan |first1=Emily |title=NHL suspending play immediately due to virus |url=https://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/28891430/sources-nhl-suspending-play-immediately-due-virus |accessdate=12 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wearegreenbay.com/community/health/coronavirus/green-bay-gamblers-season-suspended-due-to-covid-19/ |title=Green Bay Gamblers season suspended due to COVID-19 |last=Rose |first=Joshua |date=12 March 202 |work=[[WFRV-TV|WeAreGreenBay.com]] |publisher=[[Nexstar Media Group]] |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, the [[National Women's Hockey League]] postponed its [[Isobel Cup]] Final game indefinitely. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/olympics/women-hockey/nwhl-postpones-2020-isobel-cup-final-due-covid-19-concerns/ |title=NWHL postpones 2020 Isobel Cup Final due to COVID-19 concerns |date=12 March 2020 |website=www.sportsnet.ca |language=en|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe ECHL announced on 14 March that the remainder of the season would be scrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/28904194/prudent-decision |title=ECHL cancels season amid concerns over virus |date=15 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The leagues of the CHL announced on 18 March that they would scrap the remainder of their regular seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/qmjhl-becomes-first-chl-league-to-cancel-remainder-of-regular-season |title=CHL leagues cancel remainder of regular season campaigns; playoff status still undetermined |last=EllisMarch 18 |first=Steven |last2=2020 |date=18 March 2020 |website=The Hockey News |language=en-CA|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March, the CHL confirmed that all playoffs and the [[2020 Memorial Cup]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/hockey/junior-hockey/covid-19-forces-cancellation-of-chl-playoffs-and-2020-memorial-cup |title=COVID-19 forces cancellation of CHL playoffs and 2020 Memorial Cup |date=23 March 2020 |website=The Province |language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hockey Canada]], the governing body for amateur hockey in the country, cancelled the remainder of its season on 13 March. This included national championships such as the [[Telus Cup]] and [[Esso Cup]], as well as all regional and provincial playoffs.  It also included the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]] playoffs and the [[2020 Centennial Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/news/2020-news-hockey-canada-ends-season |title=Hockey Canada statement in response to coronavirus (COVID-19) |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=Hockey Canada}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/hockey-canada-ends-season-cancels-championships-1.4851343 |title=Hockey Canada ends season, cancels championships |last=Hunt |first=Stephen |date=12 March 2020 |website=Calgary |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lacrosse==\nThe [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL) temporarily suspended the [[2020 NLL season|2020 season]] on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nll.com/news/nll-statement-on-game-play-march-12-2020/ |title=NLL STATEMENT ON GAME PLAY (MARCH 12, 2020) |publisher=National Lacrosse League |website=nll.com |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsport==\n\n===Australian Supercars===\nThe [[Supercars Championship]] had planned to hold an event, the [[Melbourne 400]] supporting the Australian Grand Prix. The event was cancelled the same time the Grand Prix was also cancelled. The Championship is currently seeking to hold a replacement event later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/13/supercars-confirms-albert-park-cancellation-seeking-replacement-event/ |title=Supercars confirms Albert Park cancellation, seeking replacement event |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The Supercars' [[Tasmania Super400]] at [[Symmons Plains Raceway]] (originally scheduled for 4\u20135 April), the [[Auckland Super400]] at Hampton Downs ( 25\u201326 April), and the [[Perth SuperNight]] at [[Wanneroo Raceway]] (16\u201317 May) rounds were also postponed beyond June.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chapman |first=Simon |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/18/breaking-supercars-postpones-tasmania-auckland-and-perth/ |title=Supercars postpones Tasmania, Auckland and Perth |publisher=[[Speedcafe]] |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> The Supercars' support series like the [[Boost Mobile Super Trucks]] were also affected, though the trucks intend to commit to their support schedule once new dates are finalised.<ref>{{cite web |last=Nguyen |first=Justin |url=https://www.thecheckeredflag.co.uk/2020/03/tasmania-auckland-perth-races-postponed-sst-to-follow-reschedules/ |title=Tasmania, Auckland, Perth races postponed, SST to follow reschedules |publisher=The Checkered Flag |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSupercars formed the [[Supercars eSeries|All Stars Eseries]] to allow its drivers to compete against each other.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bartolomaeus |first=Stefan |url=https://www.supercars.com/news/championship/what-you-need-to-know-supercars-goes-virtual/ |title=What you need to know: Supercars goes virtual |publisher=[[Supercars Championship]] |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters===\nThe [[2020 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters]] series postponed the start of its championship until July 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/dtm/news/148790/dtm-issues-revised-2020-calendar-set-for-july-start |title=The DTM has issued a revised 2020 calendar set to start in July |first=Rachit |last=Thukral |website=Autosport.com |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Formula One===\nThe early [[2020 Formula One World Championship|Formula One season]] was disrupted by the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"CHN postponed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.chinese-grand-prix-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.3g2y5Ngyrk1MbNxQB9hj4s.html |title=2020 F1 Chinese Grand Prix postponed due to novel coronavirus outbreak |date=12 February 2020 |website=Formula1.com |publisher=Formula One World Championship Limited|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212184109/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.chinese-grand-prix-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.3g2y5Ngyrk1MbNxQB9hj4s.html|archive-date=12 February 2020|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Prior to the start of the season, [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] and [[Scuderia AlphaTauri|AlphaTauri]] expressed concern about the spread of the virus and its effect on the championship. Both teams are based in Italy, which has suffered [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|one of the worst outbreaks of the virus]] outside China,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148478/ferrari-wants-assurances-over-coronavirus-from-f1 |title=Ferrari wants assurances over coronavirus from F1 before travel |last=Noble |first=Jonathan |date=28 February 2020 |website=[[Autosport|Autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229014941/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148478/ferrari-wants-assurances-over-coronavirus-from-f1|archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148508/tost-unfair-if-australia-goes-ahead-without-all-teams |title=Tost: Unfair if Australia goes ahead without all F1 teams |last=Noble |first=Jonathan |date=2 March 2020 |website=[[Autosport|Autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303042841/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148508/tost-unfair-if-australia-goes-ahead-without-all-teams|archive-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> and so both Ferrari and AlphaTauri were therefore concerned over the ability of their staff to leave a quarantine zone that was established in northern Italy. [[Ross Brawn]], the managing director of the sport, announced that Grands Prix would not go ahead if a team were blocked from entering a host nation, but that events could go ahead if a team voluntarily chose not to enter a host nation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51727401 |title=Coronavirus: F1 will not hold race in country preventing teams entering |last=Benson |first=Andrew |date=4 March 2020 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134810/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51727401|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Australian Grand Prix|Australian]] and [[Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grands Prix]] were cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51849163 |title=Coronavirus: Australian Grand Prix called off |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"NEDMONESP\"/> The cancellation of the Monaco Grand Prix meant that 2020 would mark the first time since {{F1|1954}} that the race has not been held. The [[Azerbaijan Grand Prix|Azerbaijan]], [[Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain]], [[Chinese Grand Prix|Chinese]], [[Canadian Grand Prix|Canadian]], [[Dutch Grand Prix|Dutch]], [[Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish]] and [[Vietnam Grand Prix|Vietnam Grands Prix]] were postponed.<ref name=\"NEDMONESP\">{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.dutch-spanish-and-monaco-grands-prix-postponed.5CggooJeHoDchKkFehkrkY.html |title=Dutch, Spanish and Monaco Grands Prix postponed |website=formula1.com |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"spectators\">{{cite web |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/08/no-spectators-for-bahrain-grand-prix/ |title=No spectators for Bahrain Grand Prix |last=Chapman |first=Simon |date=8 March 2020 |website=Speedcafe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-13/f1-grand-prix-in-china-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-fears/11960614 |title=Coronavirus fears force the postponement of the F1 Grand Prix in China in April |work=abc.net.au |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=13 February 2020 |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CAN postponed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.canadian-grand-prix-organisers-announce-postponement-of-2020-race.7rkpGKnxnRQVe6uPcZSRbP.html|title=Canadian Grand Prix organisers announce postponement of 2020 race|website=formula1.com|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The summer break shut down period\u2014which includes mandatory factory closures as a cost-cutting measure\u2014was also brought forward from August to March and April and was extended to three weeks, allowing for postponed races to be held in August.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.f1-summer-shutdown-brought-forward-in-response-to-coronavirus-outbreak.5a4PM49x3Rs3WKMmxfUIO8.html |title=F1 summer shutdown brought forward in response to coronavirus outbreak |last= |first= |date=18 March 2020 |website=Formula1.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe sport had planned to overhaul its technical regulations for the {{F1|2021}} championship in one of the largest changes in its seventy-year history. The pandemic prompted these changes to be postponed until {{F1|2022}}, with teams required to enter their {{F1|2020}} cars in the 2021 championship to minimise the financial stress placed on the teams.<ref name=\"19 chassis\">{{cite news |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/20/formula-1s-new-regulations-delayed-until-2022/ |title=Formula 1's new regulations delayed until 2022 |first=Daniel |last=Herrero |work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]] |publisher=[[Speedcafe]] |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRecently,{{when|date=March 2020}} some Formula One drivers have entered a virtual version of the [[Australian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DG1cFm3dsaU |title=Veloce Esports's NotAusGP |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Bahrain Grand Prix]] <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vVLTdi4BtPE |title=Veloce Esports's NotTheBahGP |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QwcRDOjgfkE |title=F1 Bahrain Virtual Grand Prix |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The races are hosted by [[Jean-\u00c9ric Vergne]]'s Veloce Esports and F!. The online races are contested by current and former F1 drivers, like [[Lando Norris]], [[Nicholas Latifi]], [[Stoffel Vandoorne]], [[Esteban Guti\u00e9rrez]], [[Nico H\u00fclkenberg]], [[Johnny Herbert]] and [[Martin Brundle]], as well as celebrities and other sportsmen.\n\n====Formula 2 and Formula 3====\nThe [[Bahrain International Circuit|Bahrain]], [[Circuit Zandvoort|Zandvoort]] and [[Circuit de Barcelona|Barcelona]] rounds of the [[2020 FIA Formula 2 Championship|FIA Formula 2]] and [[2020 FIA Formula 3 Championship|Formula 3 Championships]]\u2014a series of races for junior drivers that run in support of Formula 1 events\u2014were postponed when the Bahrain, Dutch and Spanish Grands Prix were postponed.<ref name=\"BHR postponed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2020/03_March/FIA-Formula-2-and-FIA-Formula-3-Championships-Round-1-in-Bahrain-postponed/ |title=FIA Formula 2 and FIA Formula 3 Championships Round 1 in Bahrain postponed \u2013 Formula 2 |website=fiaformula2.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ZANBARMON\">{{cite news |url=https://www.fiaformula2.com/Latest/53FNxDGggZW5n65yl8aFpB/fia-formula-2-and-fia-formula-3-championships-may-races-and-tests-postponed |title=FIA Formula 2 and FIA Formula 3 Championships May races and tests postponed |work=fiaformula2.com |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Circuit de Monaco|Monaco]] Formula 2 round was cancelled when the Monaco Grand Prix was cancelled and the [[Baku City Circuit|Baku]] round postponed when the Azerbaijan Grand Prix was postponed;<ref name=\"ZANBARMON\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fiaformula2.com/Latest/3jBJqgLEiIY3w7fOsUwScE/fia-f2-round-in-baku-postponed-as-coronavirus-outbreak-continues |title=FIA Formula 2 round in Baku postponed as Coronavirus outbreak continues |work=fiaformula2.com |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Formula 3 had not been scheduled to race in Monaco or Azerbaijan.\n\n===Formula E===\nThe [[Formula E]] championship for electric cars initially responded to the pandemic by postponing the [[Rome ePrix|Rome]] and [[Sanya ePrix]]. Planned races in [[Paris ePrix|Paris]], [[Jakarta ePrix|Jakarta]] and [[Seoul ePrix|Seoul]] were also postponed, prompting organisers to postpone the entire season by two months.<ref name=Sanya>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/fe-china-sanya-eprix-coronavirus/4679553/amp/ |title=Formula E postpones China race amid virus outbreak |first=Alex |last=Kalinauckas |date=2 February 2020|access-date=2 February 2020 |website=motorsport.com}}</ref><ref name=Rome>{{cite news |url=https://www.fiaformulae.com/NEWS/2020/March/rome-eprix-update-march-2020?utm_source=FormulaETwitter&utm_mediumSocialPost&utm_campaign=rome&utm_source=FormulaETwitter&utm_mediumSocialPost&utm_campaign=rome |date=6 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020 |website=fiaformulae.com |title=Statement on the 2020 Rome E-Prix}}</ref><ref name=ParisAndSeoul>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/coronavirus-suspend-season-two-months/4740500/ |first1=Charles |last1=Bradley |title=Formula E set to suspend 2019\u201320 season for two months |website=motorsport.com |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===GT World Challenge Europe===\nThe 3 Hours of Monza round of the [[2020 GT World Challenge Europe Endurance Cup]], scheduled for 19 April, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/gt/news/148594/gtwce-opener-in-italy-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus |title=GT World Challenge Europe Monza opener cancelled due to coronavirus |first=Gary |last=Watkins |website=Autosport.com |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===IndyCar===\nThe [[IndyCar Series]] initially announced on 12 March that it would hold the [[Firestone Grand Prix of St. Petersburg|Grand Prix of St. Petersburg]] \u2014 the opening race of the [[2020 IndyCar Series|2020 season]] \u2014 behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/12/indycar-st-pete-to-run-behind-closed-doors-condensed-schedule/ |title=IndyCar St Pete to run behind closed doors; condensed schedule |date=12 March 2020 |website=RACER |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March, the series announced that it would cancel all races through at least the end of April, including St. Petersburg, [[Honda Indy Grand Prix of Alabama|Alabama]], [[Grand Prix of Long Beach|Long Beach]], and [[AutoNation IndyCar Challenge|Austin]]. IndyCar intended to begin the season with the traditional \"Month of May\" races at [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]], including the [[GMR Grand Prix]] (held on IMS's road course configuration), and the 104th running of the [[Indianapolis 500]] on its traditional [[Memorial Day]] weekend scheduling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/13/indycar-cancels-st-pete-first-four-races/ |title=IndyCar cancels St Pete, first four races |date=13 March 2020 |website=RACER |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, IndyCar announced that it would tentatively delay the beginning of the season to the end of May (beginning with the [[Detroit Grand Prix (IndyCar)|Detroit Grand Prix]] on 30 and 31 May) by postponing the two Indianapolis races to later in the season. The GMR Grand Prix will join the [[NASCAR Cup Series]]' [[Brickyard 400]] weekend, as part of a double-header with the [[NASCAR Xfinity Series|Xfinity Series]]' [[Pennzoil 150]] on the [[Independence Day (United States)|Fourth of July]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/26/indianapolis-motor-speedway-nascar-indycar-july-4-doubleheader/ |title=Indy road course set for July 4 NASCAR-IndyCar doubleheader |date=26 March 2020 |website=NASCAR.com |language=en-US|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/motor/2020/03/27/tony-stewart-attempt-four-races-during-brickyard-weekend/2924343001/ |title=Could Tony Stewart attempt four races during the Brickyard weekend? 'Get me the good rides' |website=Indianapolis Star |language=en|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> The Indianapolis 500 was postponed to 23 August\u2014marking the first time in history that it has not been held in May. The Grand Prix of St. Petersburg was reinstated as the planned season finale, with a date to be determined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/motor/2020/03/26/indycar-calendar-undergoes-massive-overhaul/2918583001/ |title=IndyCar calendar undergoes massive overhaul in response to coronavirus |website=Indianapolis Star |language=en|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 6 April, IndyCar once again postponed the start of the season, scrapping the Detroit Grand Prix, but converting the [[Iowa 300|Iowa]] and [[IndyCar Monterey Grand Prix|Laguna Seca]] weekends to double-headers with two races each, and adding a second Indianapolis Motor Speedway road course race on 3 October\u2014the [[Harvest Auto Racing Classic|Harvest Grand Prix]]\u2014which will be a support race for the [[2020 Intercontinental GT Challenge|Intercontinental GT Challenge]]'s Indianapolis 8 Hour, and may serve as the season finale if the St. Petersburg race does not come to fruition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/motor/2020/04/06/indycar-cancels-detroit-but-adds-races-ims-iowa-and-laguna-seca/2953930001/|title=IndyCar's latest schedule change: three races added, including one at IMS; Detroit canceled|last=Brown|first=Nathan|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIndyCar formed the IndyCar iRacing Challenge, with its drivers racing against one another on the ''[[iRacing]]'' [[racing simulation]] game.<ref>{{cite web |last=Eubanks |first=Michael |url=https://motorsports.nbcsports.com/2020/03/28/indycar-iracing-challenge-drivers-first-virtual-race-at-watkins-glen/ |title=What drivers said after IndyCar's iRacing opener at Watkins Glen |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===MotoGP===\nThe [[MotoGP|MotoGP World Championship]] cancelled the opening round of the 2020 championship in [[2020 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar]]. The [[Moto2]] and [[Moto3]] support categories raced in the country, as the teams were already in Qatar before the quarantine measures were put in place. Planned events in Thailand, the United States, and Argentina were also postponed, but were later rescheduled to 4 October, 15 November and 22 November respectively. The races at Jerez, Le Mans, Mugello, and Catalunya were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fim-live.com/en/article/motogp-class-cancelled-at-the-grand-prix-of-qatar/ |title=MOTOGP CLASS CANCELLED AT THE GRAND PRIX OF QATAR |last= |first= |date=1 March 2020 |website=FIM-live.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NASCAR===\nPrior to the [[2020 Folds of Honor QuikTrip 500]], part of the [[2020 NASCAR Cup Series]], [[NASCAR]] announced that no fans would be permitted to attend the race; this event, along with the [[Dixie Vodka 400]] at [[Homestead-Miami Speedway]], were later postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/12/nascar-statement-atlanta-homestead-race-schedules/ |title=NASCAR statement on Atlanta and Homestead {{!}} NASCAR|date=12 March 2020|website=Official Site Of NASCAR|language=en-US|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, NASCAR announced that all race events through 3 May were postponed, however they still intend to run all 36 races for the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/16/nascar-schedule-update-statement-race-coronavirus/ |title=NASCAR statement: All race events through May 3 postponed {{!}} NASCAR|date=16 March 2020|website=NASCAR.com|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nNASCAR subsequently began to organize invitational [[eSports]] events on ''iRacing'', featuring current and past NASCAR drivers, officially known as the [[eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series]]. [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Sports]] also picked up broadcasts of these events to provide filler content for [[Fox Sports 1]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a31789600/fox-sports-to-air-iracing-event-featuring-full-field-of-nascar-drivers/ |title=Fox Sports to air iRacing event featuring full field of NASCAR drivers |last=Weaver |first=Matt |date=19 March 2020 |website=Autoweek |language=en-US|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Endurance Championship===\nThe [[1000 Miles of Sebring]] race was cancelled.<ref name=\"Sebring\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailysportscar.com/2020/03/12/wec-set-to-cancel-sebring-trip.html |title=WEC Cancels Sebring Race (Updated) |date=12 March 2020 |work=Marshall Pruett |publisher=Dailysportscar.com |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[6 Hours of Spa-Francorchamps]] and the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] were both postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/16/wec-postpones-spa/ |title=WEC postpones Spa |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/motorsport/51946353 |title=Coronavirus: Le Mans 24 Hours postponed until September |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Rally Championship===\nThe 2020 running of [[Rally Argentina]], [[Rally Italia Sardegna]] and [[Rally Portugal]] were postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/148648/coronavirus-forces-rally-argentina-to-be-postponed |title=Coronavirus forces WRC Rally Argentina to be postponed |first=Nick |last=Garton |work=[[Autosport|autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]] |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/148778/wrc-season-hit-by-more-postponements |title=WRC 2020 season hit by more rally postponements due to coronavirus |first=Pablo |last=Elizalde |work=[[Autosport|autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]] |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Rally Mexico]] was shortened to allow competitors time to pack their equipment up and return to their headquarters in Europe before a series of travel bans were implemented.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/15/rally-mexico-shortened-by-a-day-due-to-travel-restrictions/ |title=Rally Mexico shortened by a day due to travel restrictions |first=Daniel |last=Herrero |work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]] |publisher=[[Speedcafe]] |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 World Rally Championship-2|World Rally Championship-2]], [[2020 World Rally Championship-3|World Rally Championship-3]] and [[2020 Junior World Rally Championship|Junior World Rally Championship]] support categories were also affected by the postponements.\n\n===World Rallycross Championship===\nThe opening rounds of the [[2020 FIA World Rallycross Championship]] in [[World RX of Barcelona|Barcelona]] and [[World RX of Portugal|Portugal]] were postponed.<ref name=\"BarcelonaPostponed\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/world-rx/news/world-rallycross-opener-barcelona-coronavirus/4746950/ |title=World RX postpones Barcelona opener over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |last=Ridge |first=Hal |publisher=motorsport.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PortugalPostponed\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/world-rx/news/portugal-second-round-postponed-coronavirus/4771259/ |title=World RX's second round also postponed due to coronavirus |date=20 March 2020 |last=Ridge |first=Hal |publisher=motorsport.com |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Touring Car Cup===\nThe opening rounds of the [[2020 World Touring Car Cup]] in [[FIA WTCC Race of Hungary|Hungary]] and [[FIA WTCC Race of Germany|Germany]] were cancelled.<ref name=\"hun2020cancellation\">{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/wtcr/wtcr-race-of-hungary-statement_sto7702776/story.shtml |title=WTCR Race of Hungary statement |date=13 March 2020 |work=Eurosport |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/nurburgring-24-hours-race-weekend-postponed-september/ |title=N\u00fcrburgring 24 Hours race weekend postponed to September |date=17 March 2020 |work=TouringCarTimes |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fiawtcr.com/update-wtcr-race-of-germany/ |title=Update: WTCR Race of Germany |date=17 March 2020 |work=FIA WTCR {{!}} World Touring Car Cup|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> The four races that would have been held across the two rounds were rescheduled for other rounds.\n\n===Motorcycle road racing===\nThe 2020 [[Isle of Man TT]] and [[Scottish Six Days Trial]] were cancelled.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20200316235253/https://www.iomtt.com/news/2020/03/16/tt-2020-cancelled Isle of Mann Government announces cancellation of 2020 TT Races] Isle of Mann TT 16 March 2020</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.obantimes.co.uk/2020/03/16/scottish-six-days-trial-and-pre-65-trial-cancelled-due-to-covid-19-outbreak-2/ |title=Scottish Six Days Trial and Pre '65 Trial cancelled due to Covid-19 outbreak |date=16 March 2020 |website=The Oban Times |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/highlands/2077336/coronavirus-lochabers-scottish-six-days-trial-event-cancelled/ |title=Coronavirus: Lochaber's Scottish Six Days Trial event cancelled |first=Stuart |last=Findlay |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The 2020 [[North West 200]] event was postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Re the Postponement of the 2020 fonaCAB and Nicholl Oils North West 200 |url=https://www.northwest200.org/statement-re-the-postponement-of-the-2020-fonacab-and-nicholl-oils-north-west-200/ |website=northwest200.org |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===British national-level championships===\nAll British motorsport, including the [[2020 British Touring Car Championship|British Touring Car Championship]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/btcc-postpones-opening-three-rounds-coronavirus-policy-change/ |title=BTCC postpones opening three rounds after coronavirus policy change |date=17 March 2020 |website=Touring Car Times|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> the [[2020 British GT Championship|British GT Championship]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.britishgt.com/news/590/british-gt-season-opener-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak |title=British GT season opener postponed due to coronavirus outbreak |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=britishgt.com |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Britcar]] [[2020 Britcar Endurance Championship|Endurance]] and [[2020 Britcar Trophy Championship|Trophy Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.britcar-endurance.com/newsRead.php?link=317&page=0 |title=Opening Rounds Postponed |website=Britcar Endurance |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> were postoned until July 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/national/news/148772/uk-motorsport-on-hold-until-july-due-to-covid19 |title=UK motorsport on hold until July to contain spread of coronavirus |first=Stefan Mackley, Paul |last=Lawrence |website=Autosport.com |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Monster trucks===\n[[Monster Jam]] events in multiple localities were affected. Shows in [[Austin, Texas]], [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], [[Columbia, South Carolina]], [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], [[Columbus, Ohio]], [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], and [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] were postponed; and a show in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.monsterjam.com/en-US/event-basic-page |title=Event basic page &#124; Monster Jam |website=www.monsterjam.com |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hot Wheels|Hot Wheels Monster Trucks Live]] postponed a show in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whas11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/hot-wheels-monster-trucks-postponed/417-fe68c6a7-fba6-46f3-b913-d4ab3ad5cc99 |title=Hot Wheels Monster Trucks Live postpones shows this weekend |website=WHAS11 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMonster X Tour postponed its World Finals event in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://alohastadium.hawaii.gov/main/monster-x-tour/ |title=MONSTER X TOUR WORLD FINALS 2020 \u2013 RESCHEDULED JULY 25\u201326 |website=alohastadium.hawaii.gov |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2020, [[Monster Jam World Finals XXI|World Finals XXI]], scheduled to take place 2\u20133 May 2020, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Monster Jam World Finals 2020 Cancelled |date=27 March 2020 |url=https://www.monsterjam.com/en-US/2020-worldfinals-cancelled |publisher=[[Monster Jam]]|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Radio-controlled racing===\nDespite taking place in the second half of the year, all 4 blocks (representing Asia ([[Far East Model Car Association|FEMCA]]), North America ([[Remotely Operated Auto Racers|ROAR]]), Europe ([[European Federation of Radio Operated Model Automobiles|EFRA]]) and the rest of the world ([[Fourth Association of Model Auto Racing|FAMAR]])) and the [[International Federation of Model Auto Racing|IFMAR committee]] have agreed to postpone all remaining [[IFMAR World Championships]] ([[2020 IFMAR ISTC World Championship|1:10 Electric Touring Car]] in Heemstede, Netherlands); [[2020 IFMAR 1:8 IC Off-Road World Championship|1:8 IC Off-Road]] in Cianorte, Brasil and [[2020 IFMAR 1:10 IC Touring Car World Championship|1:10 IC Touring Car]] in Brisbane, Australia) to an alternative date, possibly early 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverc.com/news/announcements/22360-All_2020_IFMAR_World_Championships_Postponed/ |title=All 2020 IFMAR World Championships Postponed |publisher=LiveRC.com |date= |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.redrc.net/2020/03/ifmar-call-off-2020-season/ |title=IFMAR call off 2020 season |publisher=Red RC |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> This was the first postponement since 2001 when the events of the [[September 11 attacks]] caused the [[IFMAR 1:10 Electric Off-Road World Championship|1:10 Electric Off-Road Worlds]] to be moved to May the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverc.com/news/special_features/8137-FLASHBACK_FRIDAY:_Brian_Kinwald_leads_Team_Losi's_Golden_Age/|title=FLASHBACK FRIDAY: Brian Kinwald leads Team Losi's Golden Age|first=Aaron|last=Waldron|website=www.liverc.com}}</ref>\n\n===TCR Touring Car Racing===\nAlmost all [[TCR Touring Car|TCR]] championships have been affected by the outbreak, resulting in complete calendar changes, race postponements and cancellations. These include: [[2020 TCR Australia Touring Car Series|TCR Australia]], [[2020 TCR Asia Pacific Cup|TCR Asia Pacific Cup]], [[ADAC TCR Germany Touring Car Championship|TCR Germany]], [[2020 Touring Car Trophy|TCR UK]], [[2020 TCR Japan Touring Car Series|TCR Japan]], [[TCR Italian Series|TCR Italy]], [[2020 STCC TCR Scandinavia Touring Car Championship|TCR Scandinavia]], [[2020 TCR Denmark Touring Car Series|TCR Denmark]], [[2020 TCR Asia Series|TCR Asia]], [[TCR China Touring Car Championship|TCR China]], [[2020 TCR Europe Touring Car Series|TCR Europe]] and [[2020 TC America Series|TC America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/13/australian-grand-prix-support-categories-called-off/|title=Australian Grand Prix and support categories called off|date=13 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/18/motorsport-australia-suspends-championships-notice/|title=Motorsport Australia suspend championships until further notice|date=18 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/10/tcr-germany-announce-revised-calendar/|title=TCR Germany announce revised calendar|date=10 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/16/oschersleben-pre-season-test-season-opener-cancelled/|title=Oschersleben pre-season test cancelled and season opener postponed|date=16 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/tcr-uk-confirm-postponed-season-start/|title=TCR UK confirm postponed season start|date=17 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/06/tcr-uk-announce-scaled-back-calendar/|title=TCR UK announce scaled back calendar|date=6 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/18/tcr-japan-season-opener-postponed-pre-season-test-goes-ahead/|title=TCR Japan season opener postponed while pre-season test goes ahead|date=18 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/31/autopolis-race-weekend-postponed-due-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=Autopolis race weekend postponed due to coronavirus pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/08/monza-season-opener-postponed-moved-misano/|title=Monza season opener postponed and moved to Misano|date=8 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/03/stcc-tcr-scandinavia-confirm-postponed-season-start/|title=STCC TCR Scandinavia confirm postponed season start|date=3 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/19/tcr-denmark-season-opener-moved-two-weeks/|title=TCR Denmark season opener moved two weeks|date=19 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/24/aarhus-street-race-postponed-2021-pre-season-test-day-moved/|title=Aarhus street race postponed until 2021, pre-season test day moved|date=24 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/09/tcr-denmark-consider-options-revised-2020-calendar/|title=TCR Denmark consider options for revised 2020 calendar|date=9 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/21/tcr-asia-announce-postponed-season-premiere/|title=TCR Asia announce postponed season premiere|date=21 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/11/tcr-china-issue-revised-2020-calendar-following-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=TCR China issue revised 2020 calendar following coronavirus outbreak|date=11 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/01/tcr-europe-issue-revised-calendar-red-bull-ring-removed/|title=TCR Europe issue revised calendar with Red Bull Ring removed|date=1 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/13/st-petersburg-race-weekend-called-off-coronavirus/|title=St Petersburg race weekend called off over coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Poker==\nAs of 18 March most casinos and other gaming venues worldwide have been closed indefinitely, and many upcoming live [[poker tournament]]s have been either postponed, cancelled, or (in jurisdictions where currently permitted) moved to an [[online poker|online platform]]. Tournaments originally scheduled to be played live are now being played online, including the 2020 [[Irish Poker Open]].\n\nThe pandemic has resulted in a massive increase in online poker traffic. It is believed to have directed both professional and recreational players who normally prefer live poker to online platforms due to the indefinite closure of most casinos and other live gaming venues worldwide, with even many [[Underground poker|unlicensed venues]] shutting down. In addition, the sudden dearth of live entertainment options due to the widespread disruption of the sports and entertainment schedules around the world is believed to have resulted in more than the usual number of casual players turning to online poker as an alternative. Many operators reported traffic of double or more the previous volume, depending on the time of day.\n\n==Rodeo==\nThe 2020 [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] was cancelled after a festival attendee was diagnosed positive with the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.click2houston.com/rodeo/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-amid-growing-concerns-over-coronavirus/ |title=Houston Rodeo canceled; coronavirus patient attended Rodeo cookoff in February |last=Barker |first=Daniela Sternitzky-Di Napoli, Aaron |date=12 March 2020 |website=KPRC |language=en|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rowing==\nFour [[Rowing at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|Olympic qualification regattas]] were cancelled, including the final qualification event scheduled to be held in [[Lucerne]], [[Switzerland]], from 17 to 19 May. All three events of the 2020 [[World Rowing Cup]] were also cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Joint Decisions related to the impact of the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) on remaining Olympic and Paralympic qualification events |url=http://www.worldrowing.com/news/joint-decisions-related-the-impact-the-novel-coronavirus-covid-remaining-olympic-and-paralympic-qualification-events |website=World Rowing |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[The Boat Race 2020]], due to take place on the [[River Thames]] in [[London]] on 29 March, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-03-16/the-boat-race-has-been-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus/ |publisher=ITV |title=The Boat Race has been cancelled due to Coronavirus |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby league==\nThe Australian/New Zealand [[National Rugby League]] was scheduled to continue with no spectators permitted in the stadiums however this was abandoned after round two.\n\nFor the first time in the competition's history, the entire season was suspended indefinitely on 23 March 2020,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/03/23/nrl-suspends-competition-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/ |title=NRL suspends competition due to coronavirus pandemic |date=23 March 2020 |work=National Rugby League |author=Dan Walsh}}</ref> and if the season cannot be restarted by 1 September, it will be abandoned with no premiership awarded.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/03/24/nrl-tells-clubs-season-needs-to-start-by-september-to-be-salvaged/ |title=NRL tells clubs season must restart by September to be salvaged |publisher=NRL.com |first=Dan |last=Walsh |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSuper League and the Rugby Football League suspended the season until 3 April as a result of the spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/51911290 |title=Coronavirus: Rugby Football League suspends season until 3 April |date=16 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=16 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby union==\nAt the end of February and start of March, the [[2020 Six Nations Championship]] saw all games against [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]] postponed due to the worsening situation in that country,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51749254 |title=Coronavirus: England's Six Nations games against Italy postponed |date=5 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> with games against the [[Scotland women's national rugby union team|Scotland women's team]] also cancelled as one of the players tested positive and the team went into isolation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51777621 |title=Women's Six Nations: Scotland v France postponed after home player tests positive for coronavirus |date=6 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> By 13 March, the competition had been suspended.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907 |title=Six Nations: Wales v Scotland off because of coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> On 12 March, the [[Pro14]] European rugby competition was suspended,.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51858815 |title=Coronavirus: Pro14 suspended indefinitely due to coronavirus |date=12 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Super Rugby]], two fixtures of Japanese team [[Sunwolves]] had been moved to Australia from Japan, while Australia announced on 12 March that beginning in the next round of fixtures, all matches held in Australia would be played with no spectators, but otherwise continue as normal. However, on 14 March, New Zealand (who fields five teams in the competition) announced that it will require 14 days self-isolation for any person that arrives in the country from outside of the Pacific Islands, regardless of origin and including New Zealand citizens. League organizer [[SANZAAR]] stated that it was evaluating the impact of this restriction,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/rugby/super-rugby/super-rugby-coronavirus-news-2020-new-zealand-government/news-story/794c8a43de0a3806ea699a7503063461 |title=Super Rugby season on verge of shutdown after NZ restrictions |date=14 March 2020 |website=Fox Sports |language=en-AU|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au:443/news/2020/03/13/corona-virus-international-updates |title=Coronavirus: How rugby has been affected around the world |website=www.rugby.com.au |language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au:443/news/2020/03/12/super-rugby-waratahs-coronavirus |title=LOCKOUT: Coronavirus forces rugby behind closed doors next week but fans welcome at weekend |website=www.rugby.com.au |language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> and ultimately announced later in the day that the season would be suspended following the completion of the weekend's fixtures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/rugby-union/all-super-rugby-matches-to-be-cancelled-after-sunday-s-fixtures-20200314-p54a4u.html |title=All Super Rugby matches to be cancelled after Sunday's fixtures |last=Decent |first=Tom |date=14 March 2020 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, [[Major League Rugby]] in the United States suspended its third season for 30 days,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.majorleague.rugby/news/major-league-rugby-suspends-2020-season-for-30-days/ |title=MAJOR LEAGUE RUGBY SUSPENDS 2020 SEASON FOR 30 DAYS |website=Major League Rugby |language=en-US|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> but on 18 March, organizers announced that it will suspend until 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americasrugbynews.com/2020/03/18/major-league-rugby-to-suspend-until-2021/ |title=Major League Rugby to suspend until 2021 |date=19 March 2020 |website=Americas Rugby News |language=en-US|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Shooting==\nThe 2020 [[ISSF World Cup]], which was to commence on 15 March in New Delhi, was postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/virus-hits-indian-sports/articleshow/74519560.cms |title=Virus hits Indian sports |work=Economic Times |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> The Olympic Test Event in Tokyo, originally scheduled for April 2020, was also cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.issf-sports.org/news.ashx?newsid |title=Test Event \"READY STEADY TOKYO\" |publisher=International Shooting Sport Federation |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Short track speed skating==\nThe 2020 [[World Short Track Speed Skating Championships]] in Seoul, South Korea scheduled 13\u201315 March were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://speedskating.ca/news-and-info/news/isu-officially-cancels-world-short-track-championships-in-south-korea-due-to-coronavirus |title=ISU Officially Cancels World Short Track Championships in South Korea due to Coronavirus &#124; Speed Skating Canada |website=speedskating.ca |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The [[International Skating Union]] announced they were trying to reschedule the tournament to late 2020 at the beginning of the 2020\u201321 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2325012|title=ISU wil afgelast WK shorttrack later dit jaar alsnog op kalender zetten|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Snooker==\nThe [[2020 Gibraltar Open]] and its qualifying rounds took place from 11 to 15 March.  For the first day, there was a limit of 100 spectators per session.  On the remaining days, there were no spectators.  A significant number of players withdrew, and there was a shortage of referees, with some early matches played without referees.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bizarre times at Gibraltar Open as games played without referees and player brings wrong cue |publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |first=Phil |last=Haigh |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/gibraltar-open-chaos-12400612/}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Tour Championship]], originally scheduled for 17 to 22 March, was postponed until 21 July.\n\nThe 2020 [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]], originally scheduled for 30 March to 5 April, was indefinitely postponed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: China Open in Beijing postponed |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/51325726 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=31 January 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020|}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 World Snooker Championship]], originally scheduled 18 April to 4 May, has been postponed,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/51964887 |title=Coronavirus: World Snooker Championship at Crucible postponed |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> tentatively until July or August.\n\nThe [[2020 World Women's Snooker Championship]], originally scheduled 22 to 27 June, has been postponed. \n<ref>{{cite web |title=World Women's Championship Postponed |url=https://wst.tv/world-womens-championship-postponed/ |date=31 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |publisher=[[World Snooker Tour]]}}</ref>\n\n==Squash==\nThe 2020 [[European Squash Individual Championships]], scheduled to take place in [[Eindhoven]], the Netherlands from 29 April to 2 May are cancelled.<ref name=\"nu.nl\"/>\n\n==Surfing==\nThe 2020 [[World Surf League]], which was due to start in Australia on 26 March, is on hold until at least June. The first event of the season, the [[Quiksilver Pro Gold Coast|Corona Open Gold Coast]], was cancelled, while the second and third events, the [[Rip Curl Pro|Rip Curl Pro Bells Beach]] and [[Margaret River Pro]], were postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=WSL Cancels All Events In March |url=https://www.worldsurfleague.com/posts/449880/wsl-cancels-all-events-in-march |website=World Surf League |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=WSL Cancels Or Postpones Events Through May |url=https://www.worldsurfleague.com/posts/450379/wsl-cancels-or-postpones-events-through-may |website=World Surf League |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 ISA World Surfing Games]], scheduled to be held from 9 to 17 May in [[El Salvador]], was postponed. It is hoped that it will take place during the second half of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=ISA Postpones Surf City El Salvador ISA World Surfing Games Until Further Notice |url=https://www.isasurf.org/isa-postpones-surf-city-el-salvador-isa-world-surfing-games-until-further-notice/ |website=International Surfing Association |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Swimming==\nThe [[YMCA]] [[Short course|Short Course]] Nationals swim meet is canceled in the United States for the first time since 1947.<ref>{{cite web |title=YMCA Short Course Nationals Canceled For First Time Since 1947 |url=https://swimswam.com/ymca-short-course-nationals-canceled-for-first-time-since-1947/ |website=Swim Swam |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=Swim Swam |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Table tennis==\nThe [[2020 World Team Table Tennis Championships]], which was scheduled to be held from 22\u201329 March in [[Busan]], [[South Korea]], was postponed to 27 September\u20134 October.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 World Table Tennis Championships postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/02/25/2020-world-table-tennis-championships-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=25 February 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New dates for 2020 World Table Tennis Championships|url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/04/07/new-dates-2020-world-table-tennis-championships/|website=ITTF |date=7 April 2020 |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 ITTF-ATTU Asian Cup]] was scheduled to be held from 28 February to 1 March in [[Hainan]], [[China]], but was postponed until later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Postponement of 2020 Asian Cup |url=http://www.attu.org/en/news/1057 |website=ATTU |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFive events on the [[2020 ITTF World Tour]] have also been postponed, including the [[China Open (table tennis)|China Open]] and the [[Japan Open (table tennis)|Japan Open]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 ITTF World Tour Japan Open postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/03/10/2020-ittf-world-tour-japan-open-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hong Kong and China Opens postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/03/20/hong-kong-china-opens-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Four [[Table tennis at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|Olympic qualifying events]], scheduled to be held in April, were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=ITTF consider Tokyo 2020 Olympic qualification measures after events postponed |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1092033/ittf-tokyo-2020-qualification-plans |website=Inside The Games |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis==\nIn one of the first major U.S. sport cancellations of the pandemic, the [[2020 BNP Paribas Open]] [[tennis]] tournament in [[Indian Wells, California]] was postponed on 8 March 2020 as a precautionary measure, with organizers stating they planned to seek a new date.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rothenberg|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/sports/coronavirus-indian-wells-canceled.html|title=Indian Wells Tennis Tournament Canceled Because of Coronavirus Outbreak|date=2020-03-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|last2=Clarey|first2=Christopher|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/columnist/dan-wolken/2020/03/08/coronavirus-indian-wells-cancellation-potential-sports-turning-point/4997987002/|title=Opinion: Indian Wells cancellation could be turning point for sports and coronavirus|last=Wolken|first=Dan|website=USA Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On 12 March, [[List of mayors of Miami|Mayor of Miami]] [[Carlos A. Gim\u00e9nez]] ordered the cancellation of the [[Miami Open (tennis)|Miami Open]] pursuant to the state of emergency in [[Miami-Dade County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/tennis/story/_/id/28891183/miami-open-canceled-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Miami Open becomes latest top tourney canceled|date=2020-03-12|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, the [[Association of Tennis Professionals|ATP]] announced that in response to the aforementioned cancellations among others, they would suspend events for at least six weeks. The [[International Tennis Federation]] also suspended play through at least 20 April, and the [[Women's Tennis Association|WTA]] cancelled [[WTA Tour]] events through 12 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/tennis/story/_/id/28891268/atp-suspends-men-tennis-tournaments-six-weeks|title=ATP, ITF announce six-week shutdown over virus|date=2020-03-12|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> On 16 March, the WTA suspended play through May 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/tennis/story/_/id/28910506/wta-suspends-tour-2-due-coronavirus|title=WTA suspends tour until May 2 due to virus|date=2020-03-16|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the start of the [[2020 French Open]] was postponed from 24 May to 20 September, and the ATP and WTA jointly announced that their suspension of play had been extended through through 7 June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/tennis/story/_/id/28922126/tennis-tours-suspend-play-june-7-eliminating-clay-court-circuit|title=ATP, WTA suspend tour play until June 7|date=2020-03-18|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/sports/tennis/french-open-postponed.html |title=The French Open Is Postponed, to the Surprise of the Tours |last=Clarey |first=Christopher |newspaper=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On 1 April, [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] was cancelled for the first time since [[World War II]], while the ATP and WTA announced that their suspension will be extended through 13 July.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atptour.com/en/news/atp-wta-tours-announce-further-suspension-wimbledon|title=ATP & WTA Announce Further Suspension Of Tours|website=ATP Tour|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/tennis/52104196 |title=Wimbledon cancelled due to coronavirus \u2013 where does that leave tennis in 2020? |date=1 April 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=4 April 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Ultimate==\nOn March 24th, the World Flying Disc Federation announced to cancel or postpone all world championships over the next sixth months. This included the World Ultimate and Guts Championships (WUGC), World Junior Ultimate Championships (WJUC) and the World Masters Ultimate Championships (WMUC) due to the rapid spread of coronavirus.\n\nNorth America's national body for ultimate, USA Ultimate, also cancelled all scheduled club and college tournaments as well as the suspension of the semi-professional league, the AUDL, from commencing the 2020 season.\n\n==Volleyball==\nOn 13 March, the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball|International Volleyball Federation]] (FIVB) decided to postpone the Nations League for [[2020 FIVB Volleyball Men's Nations League|men]] (finals scheduled for [[Turin]], Italy) and [[2020 FIVB Volleyball Women's Nations League|women]] until after the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] caused by the outbreak of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fivb.com/en/about/news/fivb-announces-changes-to-events-calendar?id=90648 |title=FIVB announces changes to events calendar |date=13 March 2020 |website=FIVB|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Water polo==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2020 Women's Water Polo Olympic Qualification Tournament]] was scheduled to take place in [[Trieste]], [[Italy]], 8\u201315 March 2020. On 28 February 2020, [[FINA|International Swimming Federation]] (FINA) announced that the tournament would be postponed to 17\u201324 May due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fina.org/news/fina-announcement-fina-womens-water-polo-olympic-games-qualification-tournament |date=28 February 2020 |title=FINA ANNOUNCEMENT: FINA Women's Water Polo Olympic Games Qualification Tournament |publisher=[[FINA]] |website=fina.org |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, FINA announced that several international water polo tournaments would be postponed due to the coronavirus pandemic. The [[2020 Men's Water Polo Olympic Qualification Tournament]] due to take place in [[Rotterdam]], [[Netherlands]], 22\u201329 March, would be postponed to 31 May \u2013 7 June. The [[2020 FINA Men's Water Polo World League]] and [[2020 FINA Women's Water Polo World League]] would be postponed to September\u2013October 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fina.org/news/pr-16-first-meeting-fina-covid-19-taskforce |date=12 March 2020 |title=PR 16 \u2013 First meeting of FINA COVID-19 taskforce |publisher=[[FINA]] |website=fina.org |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n[[2020 Asian Water Polo Championship]], the Asian continental qualification for the [[Water polo at the 2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Olympic water polo tournament]], was scheduled to take place in [[Nur-Sultan]], [[Kazakhstan]], 12\u201316 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://astanatimes.com/2020/01/kazakh-capital-to-host-olympics-water-polo-asian-pre-qualification-tournament/ |first=Nurdana |last=Adylkhanova |date=31 January 2020 |title=Kazakh capital to host Olympics water polo Asian pre-qualification tournament |publisher=Astana Times |website=astanatimes.com |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In late January the event was cancelled as the Kazakh Government suspended all flights and visas from [[China]] due to concerns about the coronavirus outbreak in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/coronavirus-claims-first-tokyo-olympic-victim-2020-asian-water-polo-championships/ |first=Michael |last=Randazzo |date=13 February 2020 |title=Coronavirus Claims First Tokyo Olympic Victim: 2020 Asian Water Polo Championships |publisher=[[Swimming World]] |website=swimmingworldmagazine.com |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In mid-February [[Asia Swimming Federation]] decided to use the final ranking of the [[Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games|2018 Asian Games]] to allocate its continental quotas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://total-waterpolo.com/asian-federation-decides-kazakhstan-and-china-goes-to-tokyo/ |first=Ivan |last=Curcic |date=14 February 2020 |title=Asian Federation decides: Kazakhstan and China go to Tokyo |publisher=Total Waterpolo |website=total-waterpolo.com |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nOn 28 February 2020, [[LEN|European Swimming League]] (LEN) announced that the match of [[2019\u201320 LEN Champions League]] Day 10 between [[Ferencv\u00e1rosi TC (men's water polo)|Ferencv\u00e1ros]] (Hungary) and [[Pro Recco]] (Italy), and the match of [[2019\u201320 LEN Euro Cup]] semifinal between [[Egri VK]] (Hungary) and [[AN Brescia]] (Italy) would be postponed due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.len.eu/?p=16594 |date=28 February 2020 |title=Two matches postponed \u2013 Euro Cup & Champions League |publisher=[[LEN]] |website=len.eu |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2020, LEN announced that all eight matches of 2019\u201320 LEN Champions League Day 11, the second leg of the [[2019\u201320 LEN Euro League Women]] quarter-finals, and the 2020 men's U19 European Championships qualification tournaments would be postponed to later dates due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.len.eu/?p=16631 |date=11 March 2020 |title=LEN postpones upcoming water polo competitions |publisher=[[LEN]] |website=len.eu |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn 11 March 2020, the [[USA Water Polo]] (USAWP) announced that the 2020 ODP Girls National Water Polo Championship would be postponed, and the exhibition matches scheduled to be played on 19\u201321 March 2020 in [[California]] between [[United States men's national water polo team|United States]] and [[Spain men's national water polo team|Spain]] men's national water polo teams would be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usawaterpolo.org/news/2020/3/11/general-2020-odp-girls-national-championship-postponed-usa-mens-national-team-series-with-spain-canceled.aspx |date=11 March 2020 |title=2020 ODP Girls National Championship Postponed; USA Men's National Team Series With Spain Canceled |publisher=[[USA Water Polo]] |website=usawaterpolo.org |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, USAWP announced that the inaugural USA Water Polo Division III Women's National Championship scheduled for 8\u201310 May 2020 in [[Southern California]] would be rescheduled for May 2021; and week three of the 2020 National Water Polo League and the 2020 National League Championship/Fisher Cup would be canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usawaterpolo.org/news/2020/3/16/general-usa-water-polo-announces-the-cancellation-of-multiple-upcoming-events.aspx |date=16 March 2020 |title=USA Water Polo Announces The Cancellation Of Multiple Upcoming Events |publisher=[[USA Water Polo]] |website=usawaterpolo.org |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nOn 16 March 2020, the [[Australian Water Polo]] (WPA) announced that the 2020 [[Australian National Water Polo League]] would be terminated, the 2020 WPA National Championships scheduled to take place in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]] in May would be cancelled, and the 2020 Open Championships (Country and Masters) scheduled to take place in the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]] in May would be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.waterpoloaustralia.com.au/news/covid-19-virus-i-changes-to-national-calendar-/ |date=16 March 2020 |title=COVID-19 virus I Changes to National Calendar |publisher=[[Australian Water Polo]] |website=waterpoloaustralia.com.au |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in sports]]\n[[Category:Sports events cancelled due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:Sports events postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|sports]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports|2=Talk:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on games and sports#Requested move 10 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{current related||2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Impact of coronavirus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has caused the most significant disruption to the [[2020 in sports|worldwide sporting calendar]] since [[World War II]]. [[Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Across the world]] and to varying degrees, sports events have been cancelled or postponed.<ref name=\"BBC overview\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: How the virus has impacted sporting events around the world |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/51605235 |website=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=How the coronavirus is affecting sports leagues and events |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-09/coronavirus-latest-news-sports-world |website=Los Angeles Times |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nSpectators have no games to watch and players no games to play. In response, players are being encouraged to \"play for lives\" rather than for points. Former footballer [[Craig Foster]], for example, is using his connections in the sporting world to set up a volunteer workforce for charities helping those in need.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fitzsimmons |first=Caitlin |url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/health-and-wellness/craig-foster-rallying-sport-to-play-for-lives-in-volunteer-response-20200404-p54h0t.html |title=Craig Foster rallying sport to 'play for lives' in volunteer response |date=5 April 2020 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Multiple event competitions==\nThe [[2020 Arctic Winter Games]] were cancelled,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/arctic-winter-games-cancelled-coronavirus-1.5490055 |title='Shocked and disappointed': Arctic Winter Games cancelled due to coronavirus concerns &#124; CBC News}}</ref> while the [[2020 ASEAN Para Games]] were postponed.<ref name=philippinencaa>{{cite news |last1=Villar |first1=Joey |title=NCAA succumbs to coronavirus scare, postpones all high school games |url=https://www.philstar.com/sports/2020/02/07/1991189/ncaa-succumbs-coronavirus-scare-postpones-all-high-school-games |accessdate=7 February 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=7 February 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Summer Olympics===\nThe [[2020 Summer Olympics]] were scheduled to take place in [[Tokyo]] starting at the end of July. Due to the upcoming Olympic games, the [[Government of Japan|country's government]] had taken extra precautions to help minimize the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Japan|outbreak's worst impact]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/abe-brushes-worries-virus-impact-tokyo-olympics-68719487 |title=Abe brushes aside worries of virus impact on Tokyo Olympics |first=A. B. C. |last=News |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/01/tokyo-2020-organisers-fight-false-rumours-olympics-cancelled-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Tokyo 2020 organisers fight false rumours Olympics cancelled over coronavirus crisis |first=Justin |last=McCurry |date=1 February 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> However, qualifying events were being canceled or postponed almost daily.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sltrib.com/sports/2020/03/10/coronavirus-already/ |title=Coronavirus already causing Olympic chaos at qualifying events |first=Ellingworth |last=Ellingworth |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Salt Lake Tribune}}</ref> There had been suggestions that the 2020 Olympics be moved to [[London]] in light of the situation, but Governor of Tokyo [[Yuriko Koike]] indicated at the end of February 2020 that such a move was not under consideration at the moment.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Keh |first=Andrew |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/sports/olympics/tokyo-coronavirus.html |title=Grappling With Coronavirus, Tokyo Olympic Leaders Have No Good Options |date=26 February 2020 |work=The New York Times|access-date=25 March 2020 |last2=Dooley |first2=Ben |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-02-21/tokyo-governor-2020-olympics-coronavirus |title=Tokyo governor: 'Inappropriate' to suggest moving 2020 Olympics because of coronavirus |date=21 February 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe traditional [[Olympic flame]] lighting ceremony in [[Olympia, Greece]], to mark the start of the [[2020 Summer Olympics torch relay]] was held on 12 March without spectators.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-2020-flame/tokyo-2020-torch-lit-behind-closed-doors-in-ancient-olympia-idUSKBN20Z1EO |title=Tokyo 2020 torch lit behind closed doors in ancient Olympia |website=Reuters |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, it was announced that the Summer Olympics would be postponed to 2021, still to be held in Tokyo. Six days later, the Olympics made a reschedule date to twelve months from the original scheduled dates of 24 July to 9 August 2020, to 23 July to 8 August 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/fc044c3fa987a60534a804046215f3de |title=On hold: Tokyo Olympics postponed to 2021 |date=24 March 2020 |website=AP NEWS|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=IOC_2021_Dates>{{cite web |url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-ipc-tokyo-2020-organising-committee-and-tokyo-metropolitan-government-announce-new-dates-for-the-olympic-and-paralympic-games-tokyo-2020 |title=IOC, IPC, Tokyo 2020 Organising Committee and Tokyo Metropolitan Government Announce New Dates for the Olympic and Paralympic Games Tokyo 2020 |date=30 March 2020 |website=olympic.org |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Gaelic games===\nThe [[Gaelic games]] of [[Gaelic football|football]], [[hurling]], [[camogie]] and [[ladies' Gaelic football|ladies' football]] \u2013 mostly played in [[Ireland]] \u2013 saw all competitions suspended from 12 March 2020. The [[2020 National Hurling League|National Hurling League]], [[2020 National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]], [[2020 National Camogie League|National Camogie League]] and [[2020 Ladies' National Football League|Ladies' National Football League]] were suspended, with competitions not intended to resume until 29 March at the earliest.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gaa.ie/news-archive/news/gaa-camogie-association-and-the-lgfa-suspend-all-activity/ |title=GAA, Camogie Association, and the LGFA suspend all activity |website=www.gaa.ie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.balls.ie/gaa/gaa-camogie-association-gaa-suspend-activities-march-29th-427885 |title=GAA, Camogie Association And LGFA Suspend All Activity Until March 29th |first=P. J. |last=Browne |website=Balls.ie}}</ref> On 17 March, the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) confirmed that [[2020 Connacht Senior Football Championship|the opening fixture]] of the [[2020 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] \u2013 due to have taken place at [[Gaelic Park]] in [[Riverdale, Bronx|The Bronx]] on 3 May \u2013 had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/gaa/galway-and-new-york-clash-first-major-casualty-of-pandemic-988773.html |title=Galway and New York clash first major casualty of pandemic |work=[[Irish Examiner]] |first=Eoghan |last=Cormican |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nOn 11 March 2020, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) \u2014 the main U.S. sanctioning body for [[College athletics in the United States|college athletics]] \u2014 initially announced that its winter-semester championships and tournaments, including its popular [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's basketball tournament]] (widely known as \"March Madness\"), would be conducted with \"only essential staff and limited family attendance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2020/03/11/ncaa-tournament-fans-banned-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/5024027002/ |title=NCAA men's and women's basketball tournaments will not include fans due to coronavirus concerns |first=Tom |last=Schad |newspaper=USA Today |date=11 March 2020|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> However, the following day, the NCAA announced that all remaining championship events for the 2019\u201320 academic year would be cancelled entirely. This marked the first cancellation in the 81-year history of the NCAA basketball tournament.<ref name=\"NCAA cancellations\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships |publisher=NCAA |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>  This ''de facto'' created a [[mythical national championship]] situation in college basketball and hockey, with such winners being crowned by polls.  Other American multi-sports organizations; [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.naia.org/general/2019-20/releases/spring-sports-cancelled|title=NAIA Cancels Spring 2020 Sports Season|date=16 March 2020|website=NAIA}}</ref> [[NJCAA]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://njcaa.org/general/2019-20/releases/20200316k2au00|title=NJCAA COVID-19 update - spring sports season cancelled|date=16 March 2020|website=NJCAA}}</ref> [[CCCAA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cccaasports.org/coronavirus/spring_sports_cancellation|title=CCCAA cancels spring sports, restores seasons of competition for student-athletes and announces recruiting ban|date=19 March 2020|website=CCCAA}}</ref> have also cancelled their seasons.  Additionally the Community College level sports governing bodies restored the season of eligibility to athletes who had already participated in the 2020 spring season.\n\n===BUCS===\nOn 16 March 2020, [[British Universities and Colleges Sport]], the UK organisation for university sport, announced that all fixtures from 17 March to 1 April would not take place. Some individual events, like the [[orienteering]] and [[windsurfing]] championships were cancelled entirely, while others were postponed indefinitely.<ref name=\"BUCS Cancellations\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bucs.org.uk/update-covid-19-coronavirus.html |title=BUCS Statement regarding CoVid-19 |publisher=BUCS |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\nIn the Philippines, [[NCAA Season 95]] and [[UAAP Season 82]] were both indefinitely suspended.<ref name=\"philippinencaa\" /><ref name=\"pba\" /> NCAA Season 95 was terminated on 19 March after the [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|then community quarantine in Luzon]] was upgraded to an \"enhanced community quarantine\", in effect a lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/university/ncaa/255125-season-95-terminated-coronavirus-luzon-lockdown|title=NCAA Season 95 terminated|last=Go|first=Beatrice|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> UAAP Season 82 was canceled on 7 April, after the enhanced community quarantine was extended to 30 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/sports/2020/4/7/uaap-cancels-season-82-covid-pandemic.html|title=UAAP board cancels Season 82 due to COVID-19 pandemic|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Alpine skiing==\nThe [[2019\u201320 FIS Alpine Ski World Cup]] ended two weeks earlier after World Cup races in Sweden, Slovenia, and Italy scheduled for March were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/international-ski-federation/news-multimedia/news/fis-alpine-ski-world-cup-finals-cortina-ita-cancelled |title=FIS Alpine Ski World Cup Finals in Cortina Cancelled |date=6 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/alpine-skiing/alpine-news-multimedia/news-multimedia/news/test2/audi-fis-women-s-world-cup-races-in-are-swe-cancelled |title=Audi FIS Women's World Cup races in Are (SWE) Cancelled |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/alpine-skiing/alpine-news-multimedia/news-multimedia/news/test2/audi-fis-men-s-world-cup-races-in-kranjska-gora-slo-cancelled |title=Audi FIS Men's World Cup races in Kranjska Gora (SLO) Cancelled |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> An earlier February World Cup race was moved from China to Austria.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/skiing/story/_/id/28600579/world-cup-ski-races-canceled-china-move-austria |title=World Cup ski races canceled in China move to Austria |date=30 January 2020 |website=[[ESPN]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=29 March 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Archery==\nThe opening stage of the [[2020 Archery World Cup]], scheduled to be held in [[Guatemala City]], [[Guatemala]] from 20 to 26 April, was postponed. Other events postponed include the [[Pan American Archery Championships]], which were scheduled to be held in [[Monterrey]], [[Mexico]], from 23 to 29 March, and the [[European Para-Archery Championships]], which were scheduled to be held in [[Olbia]], [[Italy]], from 18 to 26 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Archery Suspended Until 30 April due to COVID-19 Outbreak |url=https://worldarchery.org/news/178285/international-archery-suspended-until-30-april-due-covid-19-outbreak-1 |website=World Archery |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Association football==\nOn 13 March 2020, FIFA announced that clubs did not have to release players to their national teams during the international windows of March and April 2020, while players also had the option to decline a call-up without any consequences. FIFA also recommended that all international matches during these windows be postponed, though the final decision was left to the competition organisers or member associations for [[Exhibition game#International football|friendly]] matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/fifa-statement-x8681 |title=FIFA statement |work=[[FIFA]] |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 10 April, [[2020 \u00ddokary Liga]],<ref>[https://turkmenportal.com/en/blog/26677/19-aprelya-vozobnovitsya-chempionat-turkmenistana-po-futbolu Turkmenistan Higher League to resume on April 19]</ref> [[2020 Tajikistan Higher League]], [[2020 Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian Premier League]] and [[2019\u201320 Liga Primera de Nicaragua|Liga Primera de Nicaragua]] were the only four top flight national football leagues not suspended.<ref>[http://www.la-razon.com/marcas/futbol-covid-19-nicaragua-bielorrusia_0_3338666136.html En el planeta f\u00fatbol, solo Nicaragua y Bielorrusia contin\u00faan con sus torneos] la-razon.com {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2020, FIFA announced that the [[2020 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup]], scheduled to be held in Panama and Costa Rica in August, and the [[2020 FIFA U-17 Women's World Cup]], scheduled to be held in India in November, would be postponed and rescheduled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/dedicated-covid-19-working-group-proposes-recommendations-after-first-meeting|title=Dedicated COVID-19 working group proposes recommendations after first meeting|publisher=FIFA.com|date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\nOn 17 March 2020, [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] announced that the [[2020 African Nations Championship]] had been postponed to a later date due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cafonline.com/news-center/news/statement-on-total-chan-cameroon-2020 |title=Statement on Total CHAN Cameroon 2020 |publisher=CAF |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nIn China, the [[2020 Chinese Super League]] was postponed as a result of the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecfa.cn/lstz/20200130/28537.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u8db3\u534f\u5173\u4e8e2020\u8d5b\u5b63\u56fd\u5185\u8db3\u7403\u8d5b\u4e8b\u5ef6\u671f\u5f00\u59cb\u7684\u516c\u544a |work=Chinese Football Association |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=zh}}</ref> In Hong Kong, the [[2020 Lunar New Year Cup]] was cancelled on 23 January.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chan |first1=Kin-wa |title=Wuhan coronavirus: Lunar New Year Cup cancelled by government just hours after HKFA promotes the event |url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/hong-kong/article/3047415/wuhan-virus-lunar-new-year-cup-go-ahead-hong-kong-despite |website=South China Morning Post |date=23 January 2020 |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref> Other leagues in Asia were affected, including South Korea's [[2020 K League 1|K League 1]] and Japan's [[2020 J1 League|J1 League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=K-League season postponed as COVID-19 spreads in South Korea |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/24/soccer/k-league-season-postponed-covid-19-spreads-south-korea/#.Xms5EqgzaUk |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Japan Times |agency=Associated Press |date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Orlowitz |first1=Dan |title=Amid COVID-19 outbreak, J. League postpones all matches until March 15 |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/25/soccer/j-league/jleague-cancels-levain-cup-coronavirus/#.Xms5FagzaUk |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Japan Times |date=25 February 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 AFC Champions League|AFC Champions League]] and [[2020 AFC Cup|AFC Cup]] was also impacted, a number of group stage and play-off matches being postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-champions-league/latest/news/afc-competitions-update |title=AFC Competitions update |publisher=Asian Football Confederation |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2020, FIFA and AFC announced that [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] matches due to take place in March and June 2020 were postponed to later dates due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=AFC |date=9 March 2020}}</ref> Play-off matches between South Korea and China in the [[2020 AFC Women's Olympic Qualifying Tournament]] were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=FIFA.com |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn India, the remaining [[2019\u201320 I-League|I-League]] matches were postponed and the [[2020 Indian Super League Final|Indian Super League final]] was played behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-aiff.com/article/aiff-statement-10 |title=AIFF Statement |publisher=All India Football Federation |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nIn Europe, various knockout matches in the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] were played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] in February and March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2639297.html |title=Update on UEFA competition matches being played this week |work=UEFA |date=26 February 2020 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2640496.html |title=Update on UEFA competition matches |work=UEFA |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> On 12 March 2020, [[UEFA]] announced that the elite qualification round of the men and women's under-17 and under-19 youth international tournaments had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2640886.html |title=Postponement of Youth tournaments |publisher=UEFA.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, UEFA postponed all fixtures for the following week in the Champions League, Europa League and [[2019\u201320 UEFA Youth League|Youth League]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2641054.html |title=All of next week's UEFA matches postponed |work=UEFA |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany of the domestic European leagues were impacted in February and March 2020. After various fixtures were rescheduled or played behind closed doors, [[2019\u201320 Serie A|Serie A]] was postponed on 9 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/51808683 |title=Coronavirus: All sport in Italy to be suspended because of outbreak |date=9 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> On 12 March, [[2019\u201320 La Liga|La Liga]] and the [[2019\u201320 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] were suspended for at least two weeks after a [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] basketball player tested positive for the virus, which resulted in Real Madrid's footballers being put in quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=Real Madrid players in quarantine and La Liga suspended due to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/12/real-madrid-players-in-quarantine-and-la-liga-suspended-due-to-coronavirus |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2019\u201320 Eredivisie|Eredivisie]] was also suspended,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/246406552/streep-door-eredivisie-en-interlands-van-oranje-in-maart |title=Streep door Eredivisie \u00e9n interlands van Oranje in maart |date=12 March 2020 |website=Telegraaf}}</ref> while [[2019\u201320 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]] and the [[2019\u201320 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] followed suit shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"BBC overview\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lfp.fr/Articles/COMMUNIQU\u00c9S/2020/03/13/communique-de-la-lfp |title=Communiqu\u00e9 de la LFP |publisher=lfp.fr |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/coronavirus-what-games-are-cancelled-postponed-behind-closed-doors-overview-10410 |title=Coronavirus: Bundesliga suspended until 2 April |publisher=Bundesliga |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the [[2019\u201320 Premier League|Premier League]] match between Manchester City and Arsenal, due to be played the next day, was postponed after a number of Arsenal players made close contact with Olympiacos owner [[Evangelos Marinakis]], who had tested positive for [[coronavirus]], when the two teams had met in the Europa League 13 days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester City vs. Arsenal postponed after players exposed to Olympiakos owner Evangelos Marinakis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/english-premier-league/story/4071980/arsenal-vs-manchester-city-postponed-after-players-exposed-to-olympiakos-owner-evangelos-marinakis |website=ESPN |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> Arsenal manager [[Mikel Arteta]] tested positive for the disease, prompting the team's Premier League match against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] for that weekend to also be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal boss Mikel Arteta tests positive for coronavirus, match against Brighton postponed |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/arsenal/story/4073648/arsenal-boss-mikel-arteta-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-squad-set-to-self-isolate |website=ESPN |accessdate=13 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> As of 13 March, there has been at least one recorded case of the disease affecting a player in the aforementioned leagues; Serie A footballers [[Daniele Rugani]] and [[Manolo Gabbiadini]], [[2. Bundesliga]] footballer [[Timo H\u00fcbers]], and Premier League footballer [[Callum Hudson-Odoi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/151101/official-gabbiadini-has-coronavirus |title=Official: Gabbiadini has Coronavirus |publisher=Football Italia |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/03/13/chelsea-fc-training-facility-will-undergo-partial-closure-after- |title=CHELSEA FC TRAINING FACILITY WILL UNDERGO PARTIAL CLOSURE AFTER MEN'S TEAM PLAYER TESTED POSITIVE FOR COVID-19 |publisher=Chelsea Football Club |accessdate=13 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Rugani tested positive while being [[Asymptomatic carrier|asymptomatic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51844945 |title=Coronavirus: Juventus centre-back Daniele Rugani tests positive for virus |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March, English elite football was suspended until early April, including the [[Premier League]], [[English Football League]], [[FA Women's Super League]] and [[FA Women's Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nBy 19 March, the [[2020 Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian Premier League]] was the only active top flight in all 55 UEFA member associations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/03/19/football/1584633269_267045.html |title=Amid global coronavirus pandemic, new Belarus season starts |work=AS |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nConcerns were raised regarding [[UEFA Euro 2020]], being held in twelve host cities across Europe, and the potential impact of the coronavirus on players, staff and tournament visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Homewood |first=Brian |location=Rome |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy-soccer/uefa-says-monitoring-coronavirus-not-yet-clear-if-any-impact-on-euro-2020-idUSKBN20J1XS |title=UEFA says monitoring coronavirus, not yet clear if any impact on Euro 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=25 February 2020 |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> UEFA president [[Aleksander \u010ceferin]] said the organisation was confident that the situation could be dealt with, while general secretary [[Theodore Theodoridis]] stated that UEFA was maintaining contact with the [[World Health Organization]] and national governments regarding the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |location=Amsterdam |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/03/uefa-congress-ceferin-coronavirus-dark-scenarios |title=Uefa's Ceferin warns against fixating on 'dark scenarios' over coronavirus threat |work=The Guardian |date=3 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> UEFA announced that a [[videoconference]] would be held on 17 March with representatives of its 55 member associations, along with a [[FIFPro]] representative and the boards of the [[European Club Association]] and [[European Leagues]], to discuss the response to the outbreak for domestic and European competitions, including Euro 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2640887.html |title=UEFA calls meeting of European Football Stakeholders |work=UEFA |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The tournament was moved by 12 months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/mediaservices/mediareleases/newsid=2641071.html |title=UEFA postpones EURO 2020 by 12 months |work=UEFA |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn 12 March 2020, the [[2020 CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions League]] was suspended with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.concacafchampionsleague.com/en/article/concacaf-suspends-scotiabank-concacaf-champions-league-with-immediate-effect |title=Concacaf suspends Scotiabank Concacaf Champions League with immediate effect |publisher=CONCACAF Champions League |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe same day, [[2020 Major League Soccer season|Major League Soccer]] was suspended for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/12/major-league-soccer-suspends-season-30-days-impact-coronavirus |title=MLS suspends 2020 season for 30 days due to coronavirus |publisher=mlssoccer.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlso on 12 March, the [[National Women's Soccer League]] (NWSL), whose [[2020 National Women's Soccer League season|season]] was not scheduled to start until 18 April, canceled its preseason matches,<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/statement-from-nwsl-commissioner-lisa-baird-regarding-the-2020-season |title=Statement from NWSL Commissioner Lisa Baird regarding the 2020 season |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> and also imposed a moratorium on team training that initially ran through 22 March.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/covid-19-resources-and-updates-for-nwsl-fans |title=COVID-19 resources and updates for NWSL fans |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 19 March, Major League Soccer's suspension was extended to a target return date of 10 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/19/mls-extends-season-suspension-accordance-cdc-guidance-covid-19 |title=MLS extends season suspension in accordance with CDC guidance on COVID-19 |publisher=mlssoccer.com |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 April, MLS announced that it was \"extremely unlikely based on the guidance of federal and local public health authorities\" that they would meet this target, and stated that \"our goal remains to play as many games as possible, and while we currently have enough dates to play the entire season, we recognize at this time that it may become difficult to do so.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/major-league-soccer/story/4085343/mls-mulling-tournament-formatneutral-site-games-if-season-returns|title=Garber: MLS mulling tourney, neutral-site games|date=2020-04-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe day after MLS was initially postponed, all [[CONCACAF]] competitions scheduled for the next month were suspended. Match week 10 of Mexican [[Liga MX]] was played but as of 15 March, league executives have now taken the decision to postpone Liga MX activity until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/article/concacaf-suspends-all-its-competitions-scheduled-to-take-place-over-the-next-30-days |title=CONCACAF Champions League |publisher=CONCACAF |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Major Arena Soccer League season]] was terminated early, effective 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.maslsoccer.com/news/major-arena-soccer-league-to-end-regular-season-ef |title=MAJOR ARENA SOCCER LEAGUE TO END REGULAR SEASON EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY |publisher=Major Arena Soccer League |website=maslsoccer.com |first=Jeff |last=Husted |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[USL Championship]] suspended the [[2020 USL Championship season|2020 season]] on 12 March, for at least 30 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uslchampionship.com/news_article/show/1094891 |title=USL Championship Temporarily Suspends Play |publisher=uslchampionship.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nOn 9 March 2020, the [[Oceania Football Confederation]] announced that all tournaments were postponed until May 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=OFC tournaments, workshops, training and courses postponed until 6 May |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc-tournaments-workshops-training-and-courses-postponed-until-6-may/ |publisher=OFC |accessdate=9 March 2020 |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===South America===\nOn 12 March 2020, FIFA announced that the first two rounds of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|South American qualification for the 2022 World Cup]] due to take place in March 2020 were postponed to later dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers-in-south-america |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers in South America |publisher=FIFA.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, CONMEBOL announced that the [[2020 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]] would be temporarily suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-conmebol-libertadores-queda-suspendida-temporalmente |title=La CONMEBOL Libertadores queda suspendida temporalmente |publisher=CONMEBOL.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March all top-tier football in Brazil was suspended until April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/eb6fe061d42f1c68f151697dfe25f1d8 |title=The Latest: T-Wolves' Towns donating $100K to Mayo Clinic |date=15 March 2020 |website=AP NEWS}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March CONMEBOL announced that the 2020 edition of [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] was postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Euro 2020 and Copa Am\u00e9rica Are Postponed for a Year |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/sports/euro-2020-postponed.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |last1=Panja |first1=Tariq}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nThe [[2021 World Athletics Indoor Championships|2020 World Athletics Indoor Championships]] were scheduled to be held from 13 to 15 March in [[Nanjing]], [[China]], but were postponed until March 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Athletics to postpone World Athletics Indoor Championships Nanjing 2020 |url=https://www.worldathletics.org/news/press-releases/indoor-championships-nanjing-2020-postponed |website=World Athletics |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 World Athletics Half Marathon Championships]] was scheduled to be held on 29 March in [[Gdynia]], [[Poland]], but was postponed until October 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Half Marathon Championships in Gdynia to be postponed |url=https://www.worldathletics.org/competitions/world-athletics-half-marathon-championships/news/world-half-marathon-championships-gdynia-post |website=World Athletics |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first three events of the [[2020 Diamond League]], scheduled to be held in [[Qatar]] in April, followed by two events in [[China]] in May, were postponed until later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wanda Diamond League suspends early-season events |url=https://www.diamondleague.com/news/single-news/news/detail/News/wanda-diamond-league-suspends-early-season-events/ |website=Diamond League |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Boston Marathon]], originally scheduled for 20 April, was postponed until 14 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-marathon/2020/03/15/2020-boston-marathon-monday-september |title=Marathon Monday in September? Here's what we know so far about the 2020 Boston Marathon's new date |work=Boston.com |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 London Marathon]], scheduled to take place on 26 April, was postponed until 4 October.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234 |title=Coronavirus: London Marathon postponed until October |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The 2020 [[Rome Marathon]] was cancelled.<ref name=\"cancellation.1\">{{cite web |author=user |url=https://www.runromethemarathon.com/en/2020/03/05/acea-run-rome-the-marathon-of-29-march-2020-cancelled/ |title=Acea Run Rome The Marathon of 29 March 2020 cancelled \u2013 ACEA RUN ROME THE MARATHON |publisher=Runromethemarathon.com |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Two Oceans Marathon]], scheduled for 8\u201311 April has been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.twooceansmarathon.org.za/2020-two-oceans-marathon-cancelled-amid-covid-19-pandemic/ |title=2020 Two Oceans Marathon cancelled amid COVID-19 Pandemic |website=Two Oceans Marathon |language=en-US|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Three Peaks Race]] originally scheduled for 25 April has been postponed to 26 September.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.grough.co.uk/magazine/2020/03/12/coronavirus-claims-second-dales-event-as-three-peaks-race-put-back-to-September |title=Coronavirus claims second Dales event as Three Peaks Race put back to September |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=Grough |first=Bob |last=Smith}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Grandma's Marathon]], scheduled for 20 June, was canceled by the organizers more than 50 days before it was to begin. They announced on 31 March that the marathon, the half-marathon and the 5K would all be canceled. <ref>{{cite web |author1=Grandma's Marathon staff |title=COVID-19 Update/Cancellation |url=https://grandmasmarathon.com/covid19/ |website=grandmasmarathon.com |accessdate=31 March 2020 |location=Duluth, Minnesota |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo of the [[Standard Chartered]] 2020 marathon series, [[Hong Kong Marathon]] and [[Kuala Lumpur Marathon]] was cancelled by the organizer over uncertainty of the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite news\n| author       = SCMP Sport\n| date         = 2020-01-25\n| title        = Hong Kong Marathon cancelled in wake of coronavirus outbreak \u2013 most social media users say it's a 'wise' and 'right' decision\n| url          = https://www.scmp.com/sport/hong-kong/article/3047648/hong-kong-marathon-cancelled-wake-coronavirus-outbreak-public\n| work         = [[South China Morning Post]]\n| location     = \n| access-date  = 2020-04-07\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.kl-marathon.com/news/74/\n |title=CANCELLATION OF THE KUALA LUMPUR STANDARD CHARTERED MARATHON (KLSCM) 2020\n |last=\n |first=\n |date=\n |website=[[Kuala Lumpur Marathon]]\n |publisher=[[Standard Chartered]]\n |access-date=2020-04-07\n |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Australian rules football==\nAt the conclusion of its first round of games, the [[2020 AFL season]] was suspended until 31 May at the earliest, while the Finals series of the [[2020 AFL Women's season]] was cancelled after its semi-finals were played with no premiership awarded.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/afl-round-one-live-updates-travel-warnings-threaten-2020-season/news-story/7d60daac2b783f10205d648b1f19fc33 |title=AFL 2020 premiership officially postponed |date=22 March 2020 |website=NewsComAu |language=en|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Badminton==\nAll scheduled [[Badminton World Federation]] tournaments were suspended until 12 April due to coronavirus concerns.<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Suspends International Badminton |url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/03/14/bwf-suspends-international-badminton/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> The affected tournaments are [[2020 Swiss Open (badminton)|Swiss Open]], [[2020 India Open|India Open]], [[2020 Orl\u00e9ans Masters|Orl\u00e9ans Masters]], [[2020 Malaysia Open|Malaysia Open]], and [[2020 Singapore Open|Singapore Open]]. Previously the body had suspended the [[2020 German Open (badminton)|German Open]]<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Media Statement on Yonex German Open 2020 |url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/02/26/bwf-media-statement-on-yonex-german-open-2020-2/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=2 March 2020 |date=26 February 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> and pushed the [[2020 Lingshui China Masters|Lingshui China Masters]] from February to May 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Statement on Postponement of Lingshui China Masters |url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/02/01/bwf-statement-on-postponement-of-lingshui-china-masters/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=2 February 2020 |date=1 February 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> The [[2020 Thomas & Uber Cup]] had also been postponed to 15\u201323 August.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Baseball==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2021 World Baseball Classic \u2013 Qualification|qualifying round]] of the [[World Baseball Softball Confederation]]-sanctioned [[2021 World Baseball Classic]], scheduled in [[Tucson, Arizona]], United States in March 2020 was postponed on 12 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harrigan |first1=Thomas |title=World Baseball Classic qualifier games postponed |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/world-baseball-classic-qualifier-games-postponed |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=MLB.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n\n====Japan====\nOn 26 February 2020, [[Nippon Professional Baseball]] announced that spring training would continue without fans in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japanese baseball to play remainder of preseason without spectators due to virus fears |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/26/baseball/japanese-baseball/japanese-baseball-play-remainder-preseason-without-spectators-due-virus-fears/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Japan Times |agency=Kyodo News |date=26 February 2020}}</ref> On 9 March, the league announced that the start of its [[2020 Nippon Professional Baseball season|2020 season]] would be postponed until April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's pro baseball league delays season start over coronavirus |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/6cba442bcfa8-breaking-news-japan-pro-baseball-to-delay-start-of-season-over-virus-source.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Coskrey |first1=Jason |title=BayStars, Tigers managers react to NPB's decision to push back start of season |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/?post_type=sports&p=2526679 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Japan Times |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, the [[Japan High School Baseball Federation]] announced that the [[National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament]], scheduled to begin on 19 March, would take place without fans in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's Senbatsu spring HS baseball tourney to be held with no spectators due to virus |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200304/p2a/00m/0na/025000c |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Mainichi |date=4 March 2020}}</ref> However, on 11 March, the governing body of [[high school baseball in Japan]] declared that the tournament had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Organizers cancel Spring Koshien due to COVID-19 crisis |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/03/11/baseball/cancel-spring-koshien-coronavirus/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Japan Times |agency=Kyodo News |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's Senbatsu spring HS baseball tournament canceled over coronavirus fears |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200311/p2a/00m/0sp/017000c |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Manichi |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The cancellation of the 2020 tournament marked the first time the contest had been cancelled since its establishment in 1924. The tournaments were not formally scheduled between 1942 and 1946, due to [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Koshien cancelation stuns players |url=https://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0006415873 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Japan News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Spring high school baseball tourney cancelled over coronavirus |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/c9ea2971def3-breaking-news-national-invitational-hs-baseball-tournament-cancelled-due-to-virus.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nOpening Day of the [[2020 KBO League season]] was originally scheduled for 28 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baseball league announces 2020 regular season schedule |archiveurl=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20191216000870 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Korea Herald |agency=Yonhap News Agency |archivedate=16 December 2019 |date=16 December 2019 |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191216007100315}}</ref> The [[Korea Baseball Organization]] announced in March that all ten exhibition games would be cancelled, and the start of the regular season would be delayed until April.<ref>{{cite news |title=(LEAD) Pro baseball league postpones start of regular season over coronavirus |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200310005251315?input=tw |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Yonhap News Agency |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: South Korean baseball season postponed |url=https://wtmj.com/national/2020/03/12/the-latest-south-korean-baseball-season-postponed/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=WTMJ-TV |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn 12 March 2020, [[Major League Baseball]] suspended all spring training activities. [[Opening Day]] of the [[2020 Major League Baseball season]], scheduled for 26 March, was postponed, as was the start of the regular season for [[Minor League Baseball]], which was to begin on 9 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=MLB suspends spring training, delays Opening Day at least two weeks |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/28892315/sources-mlb-expected-suspend-spring-training |accessdate=12 March 2020 |website=[[ESPN.com]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/mlb-2020-season-delayed |title=Opening Day delayed at least 2 weeks; Spring Training games cancelled |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> In addition, the [[MLB Mexico Series|Mexico Series]] and [[MLB Puerto Rico Series|Puerto Rico Series]] games were canceled; the former would have featured the [[San Diego Padres]] playing the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] at Mexico City's [[Estadio Alfredo Harp Hel\u00fa]], and the latter featuring the [[New York Mets]] playing the [[Miami Marlins]] at  [[Hiram Bithorn Stadium]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/cubs/ct-chicago-cubs-london-coronavirus-20200319-mrawzroybfeddblje4ltkxvf7q-story.html|title=MLB just canceled 2 international series in April. What does it mean for the Cubs-Cardinals series in London in June?|last=Gonzales|first=Mark|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> MLB also canceled the 2020 [[MLB London Series|London Series]] games, which would have featured the [[Chicago Cubs]] playing the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] at [[London Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/28981187/mlb-cancels-cubs-cards-london-series-june|title=MLB cancels Cubs-Cards London series in June|date=April 1, 2020|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlso on 12 March, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] announced the suspension of its baseball season and cancellation of the [[2020 College World Series]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.omaha.com/sports/cws/college-baseball-stunned-after-ncaa-decision-to-cancel-college-world/article_ba4b22b5-7cbd-52a7-b0a0-edb0eba8f079.html |title=College baseball stunned after NCAA decision to cancel College World Series, end season in March |newspaper=Omaha World-Herald |last=Bland |first=Evan |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Basketball==\n\n===Africa===\nThe launch of the [[2020 BAL season|inaugural season]] of the [[Basketball Africa League]] set for March 2020 was delayed due to the coronavirus pandemic. No new date has been announced.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Solomon |first1=Salem |title=Basketball Africa League Delays Inaugural Season Because of Coronavirus |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/basketball-africa-league-delays-inaugural-season-because |accessdate=13 March 2020 |agency=Voice of America |date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nThe [[2019\u201320 Chinese Basketball Association season]] was suspended on 1 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Prewitt |first=Alex |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2020/03/13/cba-coronavirus-nba-allerik-freeman |title=While the NBA Pauses, China Is Ready to Play Again. For Better or Worse |date=13 March 2020 |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, [[FIBA]] ordered two [[2021 FIBA Asia Cup qualification|qualifying games for the 2021 FIBA Asia Cup]], [[Philippines men's national basketball team|Philippines]] vs [[Thailand national basketball team|Thailand]] in [[Quezon City]], and [[Japan national basketball team|Japan]] vs. [[China men's national basketball team|China]] in [[Chiba (city)|Chiba]] to be postponed to a later date. This brought the postponed games to three, after FIBA earlier ordered the China vs. [[Malaysia national basketball team|Malaysia]] game in [[Foshan]] to be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/asiacup/2021/qualifiers/news/three-fiba-asia-cup-2021-qualifier-games-postponed |title=Three FIBA Asia Cup 2021 Qualifier games postponed |website=FIBA.basketball |language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Later that week, the [[Guam national basketball team|Guam]] vs. [[Hong Kong basketball team|Hong Kong]] game in [[Hag\u00e5t\u00f1a, Guam|Hag\u00e5t\u00f1a]] was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/asiacup/2021/qualifiers/news/fiba-asia-cup-2021-qualifier-between-guam-and-hong-kong-postponed |title=FIBA Asia Cup 2021 Qualifier game between Guam and Hong Kong postponed |website=FIBA.basketball |language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Korean Basketball League]] canceled its [[2019\u201320 KBL season|2019\u201320 season]] on 24 March, after playing its last game on 29 February. This comes as the [[Women's Korean Basketball League]] canceled its season a week before.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200324000415 |title=Men's basketball league cancels season due to coronavirus |last=Herald |first=The Korea |date=24 March 2020 |website=www.koreaherald.com |language=en|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, FIBA announced the cancellation of the [[2019 FIBA Under-16 Asian Championship]] in [[Beirut]] and the 2019 FIBA Under-16 Asian Championship for Women in [[Canberra]]. It also postponed the [[Basketball at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3x3 qualification|3x3 Olympic qualification tournament]] in [[Bangalore]], and rescheduled the 2020 [[FIBA Asia 3x3 Cup]]s in [[Changsha]] and the 2020 FIBA 3x3 Under-17 Asian Cup in [[Cyberjaya]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/news/changes-made-to-several-fiba-events-due-to-covid-19-virus |title=Changes made to several FIBA events due to COVID-19 virus |website=FIBA.basketball |language=en|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====ASEAN Basketball League====\nSeveral fixtures of the [[ASEAN Basketball League]] [[2019\u201320 ABL season|2019\u201320 season]] scheduled on February onwards were rescheduled due to the coronavirus pandemic. In early March 2020, four participating teams, [[Alab Pilipinas]], [[Hong Kong Eastern Basketball Team|Hong Kong Eastern]], [[Macau Black Bears]] and [[Formosa Dreamers]] has released statements urging the suspension of the whole season due to logistical issues posed by COVID-19-related travel measures in Southeast Asia, mainland China and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alab Pilipinas, three other teams want ABL to suspend season due to COVID-19 |url=https://sports.mb.com.ph/2020/03/12/alab-pilipinas-three-other-teams-want-abl-to-suspend-season-due-to-covid-19/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2020, the league's 2019\u201320 season was postponed indefinitely.<ref name=\"pbateams\">{{cite news |last1=Dalupang |first1=Denison Rey |title=PBA: Teams can't hold practices, scrimmages |url=https://sports.inquirer.net/389302/pba-teams-cant-hold-practices-scrimmages |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Philippines====\nThe [[2020 PBA season|2020 season]] of the [[Philippine Basketball Association]] (PBA) and the [[PBA D-League]] was suspended indefinitely on 10 March 2020. The inaugural of the PBA's 3x3 tournament was also likewise delayed.<ref name=pba>{{cite news |title=PBA suspends games indefinitely due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/sports/basketball/729223/pba-suspends-games-indefinitely-due-to-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=GMA News |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> The PBA management also imposed a two-week prohibition on team \"practices, scrimmages and other related activities\" which took effect on 14 March 2020.<ref name=\"pbateams\"/>\n\nSeveral leagues have suspended their tournaments on March 12: [[Community Basketball Association]], [[National Basketball League (Philippines)|National Basketball League]], [[Maharlika Pilipinas Basketball League]].<ref>[https://www.spin.ph/life/guide/list-of-sports-events-suspended-coronavirus-a1374-20200312 Here's a list of sports events suspended due to coronavirus], [[Sports Interactive Network|spin.ph]], March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, the PBA Board of Governors have decided to shorten this season into a two-conference format following the postponement of the Philippine Cup due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] and the enforcement of the Enhanced Community Quarantine in Luzon until April 30.<ref name = \"PBA-COVID\">[https://www.pba.ph/news/pba-board-decides-to-shorten-season-45  PBA board decides to shorten Season 45], PBA.ph, April 7, 2020</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n[[Jordi Bertomeu]], CEO of the [[Euroleague]], suspended the games from 14 March to 11 April. The Euroleague previously suspended the [[EuroCup Basketball|Eurocup]]. FIBA also suspended the [[Basketball Champions League]] and the [[FIBA Europe Cup]] starting on 14 March. [[Lietuvos krep\u0161inio lyga|Lithuania]], [[Swedish Basketball League|Sweden]], [[Swiss Basketball League|Switzerland]], [[Slovak Basketball League|Slovakia]] and [[Ukrainian Basketball SuperLeague|Ukraine]] canceled outright their respective first division leagues, naming the teams in the top of the standings as champions. Top flight divisions in [[Liga ACB|Spain]], [[LNB Pro A|France]], [[Basketball Bundesliga|Germany]], [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italy]], [[Israeli Basketball Premier League|Israel]], [[Pro Basketball League|Belgium]], [[Korisliiga|Finland]], [[HT Premijer liga|Croatia]], [[Greek Basket League|Greece]], [[Polish Basketball League|Poland]], [[Cyprus Basketball Division A|Cyprus]] and [[National Basketball League (Czech Republic)|Czech Republic]] suspended its games as of 14 March. The [[ABA League|Adriatic League]] and the [[VTB United League]] suspended its competitions until April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28898393/international-basketball-virtually-shut-coronavirus-concerns |title=International basketball virtually shut down |date=13 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The government of Turkey suspended the [[Basketball Super League]] on 19 March, the last major European league to do so.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2020/03/19/turkey-basketball-soccer-suspended-coronavirus |title=Turkey Suspends Soccer, Basketball Seasons |last=West |first=Jenna |website=Sports Illustrated |language=en-us|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\n[[File:Signs during pandemic in Brooklyn (20555).jpg|thumb|In many New York City parks, hoops were removed from basketball courts to discourage people being in groups.]]\nOn 11 March 2020, the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) [[Suspension of the 2019\u201320 NBA season|suspended its season]] after [[Utah Jazz]] player [[Rudy Gobert]] tested positive for coronavirus prior to tip-off for a scheduled game against the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref name=\"nba-suspension-of-season\">{{cite web |title=NBA to suspend season following Wednesday's games |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/03/11/nba-suspend-season-following-wednesdays-games |website=NBA.com |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Commissioner [[Adam Silver]] stated the next day that this suspension \"will be most likely at least 30 days, and we don't know enough to be more specific than that\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=12 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On April 6 in an interview with [[NBA on TNT|TNT]]'s [[Ernie Johnson Jr.]], he stated there would be no decision on a restart of the season made before May 1 at the minimum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/29003667/commissioner-adam-silver-does-not-expect-make-decisions-nba-season-least-may|title=Commissioner Adam Silver does not expect to make any decisions on NBA season until at least May|last=Bontemps|first=Tim|date=6 April 2020|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, all [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] conferences in [[NCAA]] [[college basketball]] cancelled their respective tournaments in-progress. The [[Ivy League]] had already called off its tournament prior to the decision, while some conferences, as well as the NCAA for its [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's]] and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women's]] tournaments, had previously announced that they would conduct their games behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/12/coronavirus-ncaa-conference-tournaments-cancellations.html |title=Big Ten, SEC, ACC scrap conference tournaments, adding to wave of coronavirus-related sports cancellations |last=Eudaily |first=Chris |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=CNBC|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/pac-12-mens-basketball-tournament-canceled-over-coronavirus-pandemic |title=Pac-12 cancels all sports competitions 'until further notice' because of coronavirus |date=12 March 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28891602/big-ten-sec-american-cancel-conference-tournaments |title=Conference tournaments shut down over virus |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The NCAA subsequently cancelled its tournaments outright.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/march-madness-ncaa-tournament-canceled-coronavirus |title=No shining moments: NCAA basketball tournaments are canceled for the first time |date=13 March 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/coronavirus-updates-ncaa-cancels-championship-competition-for-all-winter-and-spring-sports/ |title=Coronavirus updates: NCAA cancels championship competition for all winter and spring sports |website=CBSSports.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Baloncesto Superior Nacional]] of Puerto Rico suspended its season on 14 March.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe [[National Basketball League of Canada]] suspended the remainder of the [[2019\u201320 NBL Canada season|2019\u201320 season]] on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nblcanada.ca/sports/mbkb/2019-20/releases/20200312nqi4na |title=NBLC Suspends Remainder of 2019\u201320 Season Until Further Notice |website=National Basketball League of Canada |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2020, the [[Women's National Basketball Association]] (WNBA) announced that they will postponed the start of training camp and regular season which was originally scheduled for 15 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-statement-regarding-the-start-of-the-2020-regular-season/ |title=WNBA Statement Regarding the Start of the 2020 Regular Season |publisher=WNBA |website=wnba.com |date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 WNBA draft]] will be held virtually on 17 April 2020 without players, guests, and media on-site and will be televised as planned.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-draft-2020-to-be-held-april-17/ |title=WNBA Draft 2020 Presented By State Farm To Be Held As Scheduled On April 17 |publisher=WNBA |website=wnba.com |date=26 March 2020 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nIn Australia's [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League]], the [[Sydney Kings]] announced 17 March that they would pull out of the [[2020 NBL Finals]] after three games, due to \"a critical mass of relevant and actual concerns related to player welfare and the club's social responsibility\". The NBL had been considering playing Game 4 of the series on 18 March instead of 20 March as originally scheduled to accelerate its completion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/perth-wildcats-disappointed-with-sydney-kings-nbl-grand-final-decision/news-story/2426c7f70f33f5a06e963a4c971365c4 |title=NBL Grand Final 2020: Perth Wildcats 'disappointed' with Sydney Kings' NBL Grand Final decision |date=17 March 2020 |website=Fox Sports |language=en-AU|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/breaking-nbl-season-called-off-midfinals-due-to-coronavirus-crisis/news-story/7f707f71310056816e01d8d99e7748cf |title=NBL Grand Final 2020: NBL season called off mid-finals due to coronavirus crisis, Sydney Kings vs Perth Wildcats |date=17 March 2020 |website=Fox Sports |language=en-AU|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> The decision effectively [[Forfeit (sport)|forfeited]] the series to the [[Perth Wildcats]]\u2014who were leading the best-of-five series 2\u20131 after Game 3, and were officially announced as NBL champions on 18 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thewest.com.au/sport/perth-wildcats/nbl-grand-final-title-win-the-last-piece-of-the-puzzle-for-stoked-perth-wildcats-ng-b881494184z |title=Title win the last piece of the puzzle for stoked Cats |date=19 March 2020 |website=The West Australian |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The series was played behind closed doors beginning with Game 2, and the NBL stated that it would be suspended immediately if any player was diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/nbl-grand-final-series-to-be-completed-behind-closed-doors-20200313-p549xx.html |title=NBL grand final series to be completed behind closed doors |last=Ward |first=Roy |date=13 March 2020 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Biathlon==\nThe [[2019\u201320 Biathlon World Cup]] ended a week and a day earlier than previously scheduled. The World Cup final in Norway was cancelled as was the last day of the penultimate World Cup in Finland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biathlonworld.com/news/detail/ibu-statement-on-world-cup-in-oslo |title=Update: IBU Statement on World Cup in Oslo, Kontiolahti and Junior OECH |date=13 March 2020 |website=Biathlon World |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bodybuilding==\nSeveral competitive events in international [[Bodybuilding|competitive bodybuilding]] on the amateur and [[Professional bodybuilding|professional]] levels have seen limitations, postponements, or even cancellations due to concerns about the spread of COVID-19.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nDue to these concerns Ohio governor [[Mike DeWine]] reduced the 2020 [[Arnold Sports Festival]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]] on 3 March, before any [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ohio|cases or deaths had been reported in the state]]. The cancellation was widely regarded as 'radical' at the time.<ref>{{cite web |title=The US governor who saw it coming early |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52113186 |website=[[BBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401045917/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52113186 |archivedate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=barrett>{{Cite news |last=Barrett |first=Joe |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ohio-governor-on-why-he-ordered-early-tough-coronavirus-lockdowns-11585501200 |title=Ohio Governor on Why He Ordered Early, Tough Coronavirus Lockdowns |date=29 March 2020 |work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=30 March 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref> The Fitness Expo (under orders from the state government) held the bodybuilding and physique competitions, including the Arnold Classic, without spectators with exceptions for parents and guardians of minors participating in the competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldsportsfestival.com/visitor-info/media/update-March-3/ |title=UPDATED EVENTS SCHEDULE |work=Arnold Sports Festival |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Similar Arnold Sports Festivals planned to be held in Africa, Australia, and South America were postponed for later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldsportsfestival.com/ |title=ARNOLD SPORTS FESTIVALS IN AUSTRALIA, SOUTH AMERICA & AFRICA HAVE BEEN POSTPONED. NEW DATES TBD |work=Arnolds Sports Festival |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, Jim Manion, president of the [[IFBB Professional League]] and the [[National Physique Committee]] announced that competitions planned through to 10 May 2020 in the United States would be postponed for later in the year or cancelled until the 2021 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ifbbpro.com/npc-news/npc-ifbb-professional-league-president-jim-manion-addresses-coronavirus-concerns-for-contests-in-the-united-states/ |title=NPC & IFBB Professional League President Jim Manion Addresses Coronavirus Concerns For Contests In The United States |work=IFBB Professional League \u2013 NPC News Online |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bowls==\nThe [[2020 World Outdoor Bowls Championship]] scheduled to be held on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] from 23 May to 7 June 2020,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bowls.com.au/events-page/international-events/world-bowls-championships/ |title=2020 World Bowls Championship |publisher=Bowls Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bowlsmalaysia.com/world-events-calendar/ |title=WORLD EVENTS CALENDAR |publisher=Bowls Malaysia}}</ref> has been postponed until 25 May to 6 June 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bowls.com.au/2020-world-bowls-championships-to-be-postponed-indefinitely/ |title=2020 World Bowls Championships to be postponed indefinitely |date=17 March 2020 |website=Bowls Australia |language=en-AU|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Castells==\nIn response to the shutdown of extracurricular activities for children in [[Catalonia]], the Coordinadora de Colles Castelleres de Catalunya (CCCC), the governing body for [[castell]]s (Catalan human towers), issued a statement on 10 March 2020, recommending the suspension of all castells practices and performances.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mu\u00f1oz |first1=Silvia |title=Primers assajos i diades castelleres suspeses en prevenci\u00f3 pel coronavirus |url=https://www.elmoncasteller.cat/primers-assajos-i-diades-castelleres-suspeses-en-prevencio-pel-coronavirus/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=M\u00f3n Casteller |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|lockdown imposed throughout Spain]] shut down all castells activities throughout Catalonia as of 15 March.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Segon cap de setmana de confinament casteller |url=http://revistacastells.cat/2020/03/segon-cap-de-setmana-de-confinament-casteller/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> As of 25 March 2020, there was no word about the potential impact of the pandemic on the biennial [[:ca:XXVIII Concurs de castells de Tarragona|Tarragona Castells Contest]], scheduled for 3 and 4 October 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Madrid, una ciutat en hores baixes |url=http://revistacastells.cat/2020/03/madrid-una-ciutat-en-hores-baixes/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the CCCC, the last April without any castells was in 1966. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Cam\u00ed d'un abril a zero |url=https://revistacastells.cat/2020/04/cami-dun-abril-a-zero/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Chess==\nThe [[44th Chess Olympiad]] scheduled to take place in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]] from 5\u201317 August 2020 was postponed and rescheduled for the summer of 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fide.com/news/460 |title=Statement by the FIDE Council regarding the Chess Olympiad |date=24 March 2020 |website=fide.com |publisher=FIDE |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"postponed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chess.com/news/view/fide-postpones-chess-olympiad-to-2021 |title=FIDE Postpones Chess Olympiad To 2021 |author=Peter Doggers |date=24 March 2020 |publisher=[[Chess.com]] |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe FIDE [[Candidates Tournament 2020]], held in [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Russia]], was suspended at the mid-point of the tournament on 26 March. FIDE decided to postpone the second half of the tournament after Russia announced it would be interrupting air traffic with other countries starting on 27 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.chessbase.com/post/breaking-news-fide-stops-the-candidates-tournament |title=Breaking News: FIDE stops the Candidates Tournament! |date=26 March 2020 |website=Chess News |language=en |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Combat sports==\n===Mixed martial arts===\n[[ONE Championship]] moved its 28 February \"King of the Jungle\" event behind closed doors, and announced that its ONE Infinity 1 event on 10 April would move from [[Chongqing]], China to [[Jakarta]], Indonesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/28725093/one-championship-card-go-minus-fans-due-coronavirus-fears|title=MMA event to go on sans fans due to coronavirus|date=2020-02-17|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> On 13 March, ONE announced that all cards would be held behind closed doors in Singapore until ONE Infinity 1 on 29 May, re-located to [[Manila]], Philippines (which was originally to host ONE Infinity 2). The ONE Championship \"Heart of Heroes\" event in [[Vietnam]] (originally scheduled for 20 March) was postponed to June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/24/one-championship-goes-ahead-with-events-despite-pandemic.html|title=ONE Championship goes ahead with events despite pandemic|website=The Jakarta Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/mma-one-championship-suspends-live-events-until-may-due-to-coronavirus|title=MMA: One Championship suspends live events until May due to coronavirus|last=hermesauto|date=2020-03-13|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/martial-arts/mixed-martial-arts/article/3075055/coronavirus-one-championship-moves-all-events|title=Coronavirus: One Championship moves all events behind closed doors|date=2020-03-13|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> On 6 April, due to lockdown orders issued by the Singapore government that restrict non-essential business, ONE announced that the two April cards would be postponed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/6/21209252/one-championship-postpones-upcoming-events-in-april-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic|title=ONE Championship postpones upcoming events in April due to coronavirus pandemic|last=Martin|first=Damon|date=2020-04-06|website=MMA Fighting|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, [[Combate Americas]] announced that its March events would be cancelled and replaced by closed-door tapings beginning April 3.<ref name=\":8\" /> On 10 March, Polish MMA promotion [[Konfrontacja Sztuk Walki]] (KSW) cancelled its 21 March 2020 event KSW 53 in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fightsports.tv/ksw-cancels-upcoming-event-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=KSW Cancels Upcoming Event Due To Coronavirus Outbreak|date=11 March 2020|website=FIGHT SPORTS|language=en-US|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March, [[Bellator MMA|Bellator]] cancelled [[Bellator MMA in 2020|Bellator 241]] in [[Uncasville, Connecticut]] (which was scheduled to occur later that day), and has since cancelled all events through May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Bellator-MMA-Changes-Course-Cancels-Bellator-241-171477|title=Bellator MMA Changes Course, Cancels Bellator 241|website=[[Sherdog]]|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/mma/2020/03/31/bellator-canceled-may-coronavirus-crisis|title=Bellator Cancels Events Through May Amid COVID-19 Outbreak|last=Shapiro|first=Michael|website=Sports Illustrated|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==== Ultimate Fighting Championship ====\nThe main North American promotion [[UFC]] went on with its 13 March event [[UFC Fight Night: Lee vs. Oliveira]] in [[Bras\u00edlia]], [[Brazil]], behind closed doors.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/28873544/ufc-bellator-moving-ahead-events-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|title=UFC, Bellator events still on amid virus outbreak|date=2020-03-09|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/3/12/21176396/ufc-brasilia-behind-closed-doors-coronavirus-decree|title=UFC Brasilia to go on behind closed doors after coronavirus decree|last=Cruz|first=Guilherme|date=2020-03-12|website=MMA Fighting|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>  On 16 March, UFC announced that the next three UFC Fight Night events, [[UFC Fight Night: Overeem vs. Harris|Overeem vs. Harris]], [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik|Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]], and [[UFC Fight Night: Woodley vs. Edwards|Woodley vs. Edwards]], would be postponed to future dates.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/ufc-postpones-three-events-coronavirus-pandemic |title=UFC postpones three events amid growing coronavirus outbreak |date=16 March 2020 |website=MMA Junkie |language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn regards to its next [[pay-per-view]], [[UFC 249]] on 18 April, UFC president [[Dana White]] stated that the event would likely go on, but at a new venue behind closed doors. It was originally to be held at [[Barclays Center]], but a [[stay-at-home order]] was issued by the New York state government.<ref name=\":4\" /> On 18 March, the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] also withdrew its sanctioning for the event.<ref name=\":6\" /> Due to international travel restrictions and other withdrawals, a revised card for UFC 249 was unveiled 6 April. with a location still being determined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29002048/dana-white-says-tony-ferguson-justin-gaethje-headline-ufc-249|title=Dana White says Tony Ferguson-Justin Gaethje to headline UFC 249|work=ESPN|author=Marc Raimondi|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/6/21209211/ufc-announces-updated-lineup-for-ufc-249-andrade-vs-namajunas-2-still-co-headlines|title=UFC 249 fight card announced, Andrade vs. Namajunas 2 still co-headlines|work=MMAFighting.com|author=Alexander K. Lee|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On 7 April, White disclosed that he had booked an unspecified venue for two months, in order to host both UFC 249 and other future events involving U.S. fighters. He also disclosed plans to secure a [[private island]] to host events with international fighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2020/4/7/21211634/dana-white-covid-19-plans-weekly-fights-at-ufc-249-location-a-private-island-and-joe-rogan|title=Dana White's COVID-19 plan: Two months of weekly fights at UFC 249 location, a private island, and Joe Rogan|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Steven Marrocco|date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29006529/dana-white-secured-us-location-private-island-ufc-fights|title=UFC's White: Secured private island for fights|date=2020-04-07|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nThe new UFC 249 venue was subsequently revealed to be [[Tachi Palace]]\u2014a [[Native American gaming|tribal casino]] in [[Lemoore, California]]; as it is on tribal land, it also fell outside of the jurisdiction of the [[California State Athletic Commission]], meaning that events held there could be self-sanctioned.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=Draper|first=Kevin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/sports/ufc-249-coronavirus-location.html|title=U.F.C. 249, Skirting Coronavirus Limits, Is Set for Tribal Land in California|date=2020-04-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On 9 April, UFC announced that UFC 249 had been cancelled, and all other UFC events would be suspended until further notice. White cited interventions from high-ranking staff of the UFC's U.S. media rightsholders, [[ESPN Inc.]] and parent [[The Walt Disney Company]].<ref name=\":5\" /> ''[[The New York Post]]'' reported that Governor of California [[Gavin Newsom]] had contacted Disney CEO [[Bob Iger]], urging ESPN and the UFC to not hold the event.<ref name=\":7\" /> Despite the cancellation, White stated that he was still going on with his \"Fight Island\" project.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Draper|first=Kevin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/sports/ufc-249-canceled.html|title=U.F.C. 249 Is Off After Requests From California, Disney and ESPN|date=2020-04-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|last2=Garcia|first2=Oskar|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/09/ufc-249-espn-wasnt-only-one-to-tell-dana-white-to-stand-down/|title=ESPN wasn't only one to tell UFC, Dana White to 'stand down'|last=Willis|first=George|date=2020-04-10|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n===Kickboxing===\n[[Kunlun Fight]] cancelled multiple events due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ecosports.cn/Home/Consultation/show/id/14744.html |title=\u9996\u9875 \u6c2a\u4f53 |publisher=Ecosports.cn |date=2020-01-26 |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kunlunjue.com/articleDetail?id=6060 |title=\u6606\u4ed1\u51b3\u4e16\u754c\u683c\u6597\u51a0\u519b\u8d5b |publisher=Kunlunjue.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Glory (kickboxing)|Glory]] cancelled events in [[Lint, Belgium|Lint]], [[Belgium]] and [[Miami]], [[United States|USA]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sports |first=Fight |url=https://www.fightsports.tv/glory-kickboxing-postpones-antwerp-miami-events/ |title=GLORY Kickboxing Postpones Antwerp, Miami Events &#124; FIGHT SPORTS |publisher=Fightsports.tv |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n===Professional wrestling===\nNumerous [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotions]] have cancelled major events, such as [[Impact Wrestling]]'s [[TNA: There's No Place Like Home]], [[Ring of Honor]]'s [[ROH 18th Anniversary Show|18th Anniversary Show]] and the [[National Wrestling Alliance]]'s [[Crockett Cup (2020)|Crockett Cup]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rohwrestling.com/news/roh-18th-anniversary-and-past-vs-present-shows-cancellation|title=ROH 18TH ANNIVERSARY AND PAST VS PRESENT SHOWS CANCELLATION|date=12 March 2020|website=Ring of Honor|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Impact, ROH and NWA also cancelled future tapings for their respective weekly television shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://impactwrestling.com/our-response-to-covid-19/|title=An Update on Events|date=24 March 2020|website=Impact Wrestling|language=en|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rohwrestling.com/news/roh-cancels-all-live-events-through-may-31st-2020|title=ROH 18TH ROH CANCELS ALL LIVE EVENTS THROUGH MAY 31ST, 2020|date=17 March 2020|website=Ring of Honor|language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwrestlingalliance.com/news/nwa-suspends-crockett-cup-amp-nwa-powerrr-live-events|title=NWA SUSPENDS CROCKETT CUP & NWA POWERRR LIVE EVENTS|website=NWA|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> In Mexico, [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] cancelled tapings for their weekly shows for the foreseeable future and [[Lucha Libre AAA Worldwide]] postponed the [[Rey de Reyes (2020)|2020 Rey de Reyes]] event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://superluchas.com/funciones-canceladas-por-coronavirus-en-mexico/|title=Primeras funciones canceladas por Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico|last=Acosta|first=Carlos|date=13 March 2020|work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://superluchas.com/aaa-se-cancela-rey-de-reyes-2020-por-coronavirus/|title=AAA: Se cancela \"Rey de Reyes 2020\" por Coronavirus|last=Acosta|first=Carlos|date=13 March 2020|work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]]|language=Spanish|trans-title=AAA: Cancelling \"Rey de Reyes 2020\" because of the Coronoavirus|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====New Japan Pro-Wrestling====\nIn accordance with recommendations from the Japanese Ministry of Health, [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) decided to cancel all scheduled shows from 1 March through 15 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-shows-march-1-15-due-coronavirus-outbreak-305026 |title=NJPW CANCELS SHOWS FROM MARCH 1\u201315 DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |first=Joseph |last=Currier |date=26 February 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On 10 March, NJPW announced that they were cancelling all shows through 22 March, which meant that they either cancelled the [[New Japan Cup#2020|2020 New Japan Cup]] as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-remainder-new-japan-cup-tour-due-coronavirus-306136 |title=NJPW CANCELS REMAINDER OF NEW JAPAN CUP TOUR DUE TO CORONAVIRUS |first=Brian |last=Rose |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> The [[World Wonder Ring Stardom|Stardom]] promotion, sister company of NJPW also owned by [[Bushiroad]], also made adjustments to their scheduled, cancelling shows from 19 February to 14 March. Their 8 March show in [[Korakuen Hall]] was held without any spectators in attendance, instead streaming live on their [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/stardom-makes-major-schedule-changes-due-coronavirus-outbreak-304441 |title=STARDOM MAKES MAJOR SCHEDULE CHANGES DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |first=Josh |last=Nason |date=18 February 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On March 23, 2020 NJPW would later cancelled 2020 [[Sakura Genesis]] event was originally scheduled to take place in 2020 on March 31, but would also be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/tornament/68654 |title=2020.03.31 SAKURA GENESIS 2020 |accessdate=December 28, 2019 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.njpw1972.com/73631 |title=Sakura Genesis, April 11 Kanagawa events cancelled |accessdate=March 23, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref> On April 8, 2020 NJPW would cancel more events from April 11 through May 4, which mean both nights of 2020 [[Wrestling Dontaku]] being cancelled as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-events-through-may-4-wrestling-dontaku-included-308401 |title=NJPW cancels events through May 4, Wrestling Dontaku included |publisher=F4wonline.com |date=2020-04-07 |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n====WWE====\nAmerican promotion [[WWE]] began to move the broadcasts of its weekly programs ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'' and ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' (which usually broadcast from arenas) to a training facility, the [[WWE Performance Center]] in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], beginning with ''SmackDown'' on 13 March, with no audience and only essential staff in attendance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-raw-results-recap-grades-steve-austin-celebrates-new-wrestlemania-36-matches-made/live/ |title=WWE Raw results, recap, grades: Steve Austin celebrates, new WrestleMania 36 matches made |website=CBSSports.com |language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/coronavirus-wwe-smackdown-live-1203532469/ |title=WWE Moves 'SmackDown Live' to Orlando Performance Center With No Live Audience Due to Coronavirus |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=12 March 2020 |website=Variety|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-smackdown-results-recap-grades-john-cena-caps-surreal-empty-arena-showy-you-have-to-see/live/ |title=WWE SmackDown results, recap, grades: John Cena caps surreal empty arena show you have to see |website=CBSSports.com|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The promotion also postponed some of its upcoming [[house show]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2020/03/13/22805585.html |title=WWE house shows cancelled, AEW alters plans |website=canoe.com|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[WrestleMania 36]]\u2014WWE's flagship [[pay-per-view]] event\u2014was originally scheduled to be held at [[Raymond James Stadium]] in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]]. On 16 March, WWE announced that it would also be produced from the Performance Center and air across two nights (4 and 5 April).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/wrestlemania-canceled-coronavirus-wwe-tampa-1202881422/ |title=WrestleMania To Stream Live Without Audience Due To Coronavirus Outbreak |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |date=16 March 2020 |website=Deadline |language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/wwe-splits-audience-less-wrestlemania-36-into-two-nights/ |title=WWE Splits Audience-Less WrestleMania 36 Into Two Nights |last=Maglio |first=Tony |date=18 March 2020 |website=TheWrap |language=en-US|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/article/wrestlemania-36-two-night-wwe-network-rob-gronkowski-host |title=Unprecedented two-night WrestleMania to be hosted by Rob Gronkowski on WWE Network |date=17 March 2020 |work=WWE |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> WrestleMania's associated festivities, such as the [[NXT TakeOver: Tampa Bay|NXT TakeOver]] event and [[WWE Hall of Fame (2020)|2020 Hall of Fame ceremony]] were also postponed to unannounced dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/134766/wwe-hall-of-fame-nxt-takeover-off.html?p=1 |title=WWE HALL OF FAME, NXT TAKEOVER OFF |work=PW Insider |first=Mike |last=Johnson |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> Matches for WrestleMania, as well as the final two episodes of ''SmackDown'' and final episode of ''Raw'' before WrestleMania, were recorded in advance at the Performance Center between 21 and 26 March.<ref name=\"taped\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/134908/wwe-scheduled-to-tape-everything-through-wrestlemania-this-week.html?p=1 |title=WWE SCHEDULED TO TAPE EVERYTHING THROUGH WRESTLEMANIA THIS WEEK |last=Johnson |first=Mike |date=21 March 2020 |publisher=PWInsider |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> While the majority of matches were filmed in Performance Center arena and presented plausibly live, two matches were filmed off-site in different, cinematic styles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/wwe-triple-h-wrestlemania-coronavirus-impact/ |title=WWE's Triple H Explains What It's Like to Film WrestleMania Without the Fans |date=2 April 2020 |website=TVGuide.com|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-wrestlemania-36-results-recap-grades-huge-title-changes-epic-special-matches-on-unique-2020-show/live/|title=WWE WrestleMania 36 results, recap, grades: Huge title changes, epic special matches on unique 2020 show|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/john-cena-bray-wyatt-firefly-fun-house-win-wrestlemania/|title=Bray Wyatt Defeats John Cena in Firefly Fun House Match at WrestleMania|last=Satin|first=Ryan|date=2020-04-06|website=Pro Wrestling Sheet {{!}} Insider Wrestling News and Reports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nAfter continuing with pre-taped episodes for the [[Go-home show|go-home shows]] after WrestleMania, WWE announced that its weekly series would resume live broadcasts on 13 April, with ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' from the Performance Center as before, and ''[[WWE NXT]]'' from its existing studio at [[Full Sail University]] in [[Winter Park, Florida|Winter Park]].<ref name=\"cbs-wwelive\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-to-resume-live-matches-on-tv-starting-with-the-next-monday-night-raw/|title=WWE to resume live matches on TV starting with the next 'Monday Night Raw'|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/29024319/wwe-resume-live-tv-matches-starting-monday|title=WWE to resume live TV matches starting Monday|date=2020-04-11|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> WWE told ESPN that \"it is now more important than ever to provide people with a diversion from these hard times\", and that its programming \"bring[s] families together and deliver a sense of hope, determination and perseverance\".<ref name=\":9\" /> WWE also confirmed that one of its employees had contracted COVID-19 after a meeting with two health care workers on 26 March. The company stated that the exposure occurred after production had wrapped, the employee had not made any contact with WWE staff since the exposure, and that they had had made a complete recovery.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/wwe-confirms-coronavirus-case-1202906432/|title=WWE Confirms First Known Coronavirus Case|last=Bennett|first=Anita|date=2020-04-12|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/wwe-positive-covid-19-test-confirmed/|title=Positive COVID-19 Test Confirmed by WWE|last=Satin|first=Ryan|date=2020-04-11|website=Pro Wrestling Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Wrestling writer [[Dave Meltzer]] noted that WWE's television contracts with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and [[USA Network]] likely restricted the number of non-live episodes it could broadcast per-year (accommodating breaks usually held around the [[Christmas]] and [[New Year]] holidays).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-resume-live-raw-smackdown-nxt-tv-shows-308611|title=WWE to resume live Raw, SmackDown & NXT TV shows|date=2020-04-10|website=WON/F4W|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nWWE's next PPV, [[Money in the Bank (2020)|Money in the Bank]], was expected to be held at [[Baltimore]]'s [[Royal Farms Arena]] in May, but was cancelled by the arena on 9 April.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Mike|title=WWE MONEY IN THE BANK WILL NOT TAKE PLACE IN BALTIMORE, ROYAL FARMS ARENA ANNOUNCES CANCELLATION|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/135465/wwe-money-in-the-bank-will-not-take-place-in-baltimore-royal-farms-arena-announces-cancellation.html?p=1|work=PWInsider|date=April 9, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilen|first=Jerome|title=WWE Money in the Bank pay-per view canceled due to COVID-19 outbreak|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/153495-wwe-money-in-the-bank-pay-per-view-canceled-covid-19/|work=WrestleView|date=April 9, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> WWE had already promoted Money in the Bank during WrestleMania, with no reference to a host venue,<ref name=\"WM36Part2\">{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Jason|title=WrestleMania 36 results: Powell's live review of Night Two featuring Brock Lesnar vs. Drew McIntyre for the WWE Championship, John Cena vs. \"The Fiend\" Bray Wyatt in a Firefly Funhouse match, Edge vs. Randy Orton in a Last Man Standing match, Rhea Ripley vs. Charlotte Flair for the NXT Women's Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/05/wrestlemania-36-results-powells-live-review-of-night-two-featuring-brock-lesnar-vs-drew-mcintyre-for-the-wwe-championship-john-cena-vs-the-fiend-bray-wyatt-in-a-firefly-funhouse-match/|work=Pro Wreslting Dot Net|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> and began promoting qualification matches for the PPV's [[Money in the Bank ladder match|titular match]] on 10 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/article/naomi-dana-brooke-money-in-the-bank-qualifying-match|title=Naomi meets Dana Brooke in Women's Money in the Bank Qualifying Match|website=WWE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/article/daniel-bryan-cesaro-money-in-the-bank-qualifying|title=Daniel Bryan to face Cesaro in Men's Money in the Bank Qualifying Match|website=WWE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n====All Elite Wrestling====\nOn 12 March, [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW) announced the relocation of its two remaining live broadcasts of ''[[AEW Dynamite|Dynamite]]'' on [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] for the month of March, scheduled for [[Rochester, New York]] and [[Newark, New Jersey]] respectively (with the latter originally scheduled to feature AEW's \"[[AEW Blood and Guts|Blood and Guts]]\" event, also indefinitely postponed),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allelitewrestling.com/post/message-from-aew-president-ceo-tony-khan |title=Message From AEW President & CEO Tony Khan |date=21 March 2020 |website=All Elite Wrestling |language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> to an alternative location with no audience. AEW stated that it had re-booked the two cities for future episodes in July.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbr.com/aew-dynamite-coronavirus-venue-changes/ |title=AEW Announces Venue Changes, Including Blood & Guts Show, Due to COVID-19 |date=13 March 2020 |website=CBR |language=en-US|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>  AEW subsequently cancelled on-location ''Dynamite'' broadcasts through at least 13 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/23/aew-postpones-additional-events-still-planning-to-air-dynamite/ |title=AEW postpones additional events, still planning to air Dynamite |date=23 March 2020 |website=Pro Wrestling Dot Net |language=en-US|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/13/aew-announces-additional-postponements-of-dynamite-events/ |title=AEW announces additional postponements of Dynamite events |date=13 March 2020 |website=Pro Wrestling Dot Net |language=en-US|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBeginning on 15 March, AEW began to originate ''Dynamite'' from a closed stage at [[TIAA Bank Field]]'s [[Daily's Place]] amphitheater in [[Jacksonville, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.news4jax.com/news/local/2020/03/13/aew-moves-show-from-rochester-to-jacksonville-due-to-coronavirus/ |title=AEW moves show from Rochester to Jacksonville due to coronavirus |last=Mealey |first=Jason |date=13 March 2020 |website=WJXT |language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Beginning with 1 April episode, ''Dynamite'' moved to an undisclosed location,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-news/aew-filming-dynamite-dark-undisclosed-location-307786 |title=AEW filming Dynamite & Dark in undisclosed location |date=31 March 2020 |website=WON/F4W |language=en|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> later reported to be in [[Norcross, Georgia]]. On 3 April, after a state-wide stay-at-home order was issued, it was reported that AEW had also pre-recorded content for ''Dynamite'' on 1 and 2 April, and that they had amassed enough content \"for weeks if not months if necessary.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/04/03/aew-taped-weeks-of-television-georgia-state-official-attended-this-weeks-taping/ |title=AEW taped weeks of television, Georgia state official attended this week's taping |last=Papaleo |first=Dennis |date=3 April 2020 |website=Pro Wrestling Dot Net |language=en-US|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sumo wrestling===\nIn spite the March {{ill|2020 in sumo#Haru basho|ja|\u5927\u76f8\u64b2\u4ee4\u548c2\u5e743\u6708\u5834\u6240|lt=Haru basho 2020}} taking behind closed doors without a hitch, bar one rishiki ([[Chiyomaru]]) having temporarily withdrawn from the tournament with a fever whilst undergoing tests; both Natsu basho in May and Nagoya basho in May and July have been postponed by two weeks. The July tournament had been previously moved forward a week to avoid conflict with the 2020 Olympics in Tokyo, which have since been postponed a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200317/p2g/00m/0sp/107000c|title=Sumo: Hakuho suffers upset, falls into 2-way tie for lead on Day 10|date=17 March 2020|work=The Mainichi|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=kyodopostpone>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/04/e6a03e47c65f-breaking-news-grand-sumo-tournament-in-may-to-be-postponed-2-weeks-due-to-virus.html |title=May Sumo tournament to be postponed 2 weeks due to virus |publisher=English.kyodonews.net |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nA week later, the [[Japan Sumo Association]] confirmed the sport's first case when an undisclosed rishiki in the lower ranks, was tested positive after developing a fever some six days earlier. This led to all rishikis and officials being ordered to stay indoor until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/04/d25d0f1d5acb-breaking-news-1st-sumo-wrestler-tests-positive-for-coronavirus.html|title=1st sumo wrestler tests positive for coronavirus\n|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 April 2020|website=english.kyodonews.net|publisher=Kyodo|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cricket==\nThe coronavirus pandemic impacted on several international cricket fixtures and tournaments. The [[2020 ACA Africa T20 Cup Finals]] was scheduled to take place in Kenya in March 2020, before it was postponed in line with the Kenyan government's 30-day ban on international gatherings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africacricket.com/read_more_news.php?id=145 |title=ACA T20 Africa Cup Kenya 2020 postponed |work=Africa Cricket Association |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.busybuddiesng.com/ncf-closes-lagos-camp-as-coronavirus-forces-postponement-of-africa-cricket-championship/ |title=NCF closes Lagos camp as coronavirus forces postponement of Africa Cricket Championship |work=Busy Buddies |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> A women's [[2020 Thailand Women's Quadrangular Series|quadrangular series]] was scheduled to take place in Thailand in April 2020,<ref name=\"CV1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cricketireland.ie/news/article/quadrangular-tournament-ahead-for-ireland-women |title=Quadrangular tournament ahead for Ireland Women |work=Cricket Ireland |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> but was cancelled a month before it was due to start.<ref name=\"CV2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kncb.nl/en/news/womens-quadrangular-series-in-thailand-called-off/ |title=Women's Quadrangular Series in Thailand called off |work=Royal Dutch Cricket Association |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Malaysia Cricket World Cup Challenge League A]], scheduled to take place in March 2020, was postponed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1636508 |title=Men's Cricket World Cup Challenge League A postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> along with two T20I matches [[Mujib 100 T20 Cup Bangladesh 2020|between a World XI and Asia XI side]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28882792/world-xi-v-asia-xi-matches-postponed-amid-coronavirus-fears |title=World XI v Asia XI matches postponed amid coronavirus fears |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2020, English teams [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] and [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] both cancelled their pre-season warm-up tours to the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/51835256 |title=Worcestershire & Surrey cancel pre-season trips to United Arab Emirates over coronavirus fear |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, Australia Women's [[Australia women's cricket team in South Africa in 2019\u201320|tour to South Africa]] in March 2020 became the first major international series not to go ahead as planned due to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1219220.html |title=Australia Women won't tour South Africa as scheduled because of coronavirus |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March 2020, the [[2020 United States Tri-Nation Series]] was postponed due to the pandemic and travel restrictions to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1645150 |title=Series six of Men's CWC League 2 in USA postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usacricket.org/media-release/mens-cricket-world-cup-league-2-in-usa-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=Men's Cricket World Cup League 2 in USA Postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=USA Cricket |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 12 March, the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] announced that all remaining matches of the [[Pakistan Super League]]'s ongoing [[2020 Pakistan Super League|fifth season]] being played in [[Karachi]] (where the majority of cases in Pakistan had been concentrated) would be closed to spectators.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2174849/1-coronavirus-fears-psl-matches-karachi-played-empty-stadium/ |title=Covid-19: PSL matches in Karachi to be played in empty stadium |work=The Express Tribune |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/psl-matches-in-karachi-to-be-held-closed-door-without-crowd-coronavirus-outbreak-pandemic-1654922-2020-03-12 |title=Coronavirus pandemic: Pakistan Super League matches in Karachi to be played in front of empty stands |work=India Today |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Everest Premier League]] was also postponed on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everest Premier League 2020 postponed due to coronavirus threat |url=https://www.emergingcricket.com/events/everest-premier-league/everest-premier-league-2020-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-threat/ |website=Emerging Cricket |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) announced that the start of [[2020 Indian Premier League]] will be postponed from 29 March to 15 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's official: IPL 2020 postponed to April 15 due to coronavirus |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/top-stories/its-official-ipl-2020-postponed-to-mid-april-due-to-coronavirus/articleshow/74609776.cms |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Times of India}}</ref> Later that day, it cancelled the [[South African cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|ODI matches between India and South Africa on 15 and 18 March]], which were originally announced to be played without spectators.<ref>{{cite news |title=India-South Africa series called off due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/cricket/coronavirus-india-south-africa-series-called-off-due-to-covid-19-threat/article31061061.ece |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Hindu}}</ref> On the same day, the two-match Test series between [[English cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2019\u201320|Sri Lanka and England]], scheduled to be played in March 2020, was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28896266/england-tour-sri-lanka-cancelled-amid-covid-19-spread |title=England tour of Sri Lanka cancelled amid COVID-19 spread |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The remaining seven matches of the [[2020 Road Safety World Series]] were rescheduled to a later date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldseriest20.com/news/in-the-interest-of-public-safety-security-and-support-to-the-government-road-safety-world-series-rescheduled |title=In the interest of public safety & security and support to the Government, Road Safety World Series rescheduled, new dates to be announced later |date=13 March 2020 |website=Road Safety World Series |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> It was earlier decided that the remaining seven matches of the tournament would be played behind the closed doors in [[DY Patil Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldseriest20.com/news/unacademy-road-safety-world-series-to-be-played-behind-closed-doors-in-dy-patil-stadium |title=Unacademy Road Safety World Series to be played behind closed doors in DY Patil Stadium |date=12 March 2020 |website=Road Safety World Series |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2020, the [[New Zealand cricket team in Australia in 2019\u201320|remaining two One Day International (ODI) matches]] of the [[Chappell-Hadlee Trophy]] along with the three-match [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) series [[Australian cricket team in New Zealand in 2019\u201320|between Australia and New Zealand]] were cancelled due to new border restrictions imposed by the New Zealand government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://es.pn/2U7Ngt5 |title=Australia v NZ cancelled amid travel restrictions |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> The first ODI match of the series had been played on 13 March behind closed doors in Sydney.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1645137 |title=COVID-19 outbreak: Chappell-Hadlee series to be held behind closed doors |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, [[Cricket Australia]] confirmed that the final round of matches in the [[2019\u201320 Sheffield Shield season]] had been cancelled, with [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]] being named as the winners of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28913589/new-south-wales-named-sheffield-shield-winners-final-cancelled |title=New South Wales named Sheffield Shield winners as final cancelled |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[New Zealand Cricket]] cancelled the final two rounds of matches in the [[2019\u201320 Plunket Shield season]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28909068/plunket-shield-cancelled-due-coronavirus-measures,-wellington-named-champions |title=Plunket Shield cancelled due to coronavirus measures, Wellington named champions |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> with [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]] being named the winners of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120318144/coronavirus-plunket-shield-cancelled-wellington-firebirds-declared-champions |title=Coronavirus: Plunket Shield cancelled, Wellington Firebirds declared champions |work=Stuff |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, the remaining play-offs in the [[2020 Pakistan Super League]] were postponed due to a huge spike in the number of coronavirus cases around the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geosuper.tv/latest/4433-pcb-decides-to-call-off-psl-2020-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-report |title=PCB 'postpones' PSL 2020 amid coronavirus outbreak |website=www.geosuper.tv}}</ref> The [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]] tour of Pakistan for a single [[One Day International|ODI]] and a [[Test cricket|Test]] match was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1645763 |title=Bangladesh's Karachi leg of Pakistan tour postponed |work=[[International Cricket Council]] |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 West Indies Championship]] was suspended due to the pandemic and [[Barbados national cricket team|Barbados]] was declared the champion on 24 March.<ref>[https://apnews.com/435405d82ed4d043a7998c2a32fc8e87 Barbados declared winners of West Indies championship] AP, 24 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Curling==\nThe [[2019\u201320 curling season|curling season]] typically ends in May but was cut short by the pandemic, effectively ending in early March. The [[World Curling Federation]] cancelled the last five championships scheduled for the 2019\u201320 curling season, most importantly the [[2020 World Women's Curling Championship]], [[2020 World Men's Curling Championship]], and [[2020 World Mixed Doubles Curling Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2019\u20132020 season ends with event cancellations |url=https://worldcurling.org/2020/03/2019-2020-season-ends/ |website=World Curling Federation |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cycling==\n\n===Road cycling===\nThe [[2020 UAE Tour]] was scheduled to run until 29 February, but was abandoned following stage five after two support staff tested positive for coronavirus. Of the following nineteen [[2020 UCI World Tour]] races scheduled to take place up to 31 May, only [[2020 Omloop Het Nieuwsblad|Omloop Het Nieuwsblad]] and [[2020 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]], which also had the final day of racing removed, took place at the intended time, some with the stated hope of taking place at a later date.  The postponed races in this block include the [[2020 Giro d'Italia]] and four of the five annual [[Cycling monument|monuments]], and many lower category races were also cancelled or postponed. Also races of the [[2020 UCI Women's World Tour]] were cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/news/2020/novel-coronavirus-important-information |title=Novel coronavirus: important information |website=UCI |language=en|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Farrand |first=Stephen |title=RCS Sport cancels Strade Bianche in light of coronavirus measures |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/rcs-sport-cancels-strade-bianche-in-light-of-coronavirus-measures/ |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=5 March 2020 |date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Frattini |first=Kirsten |title=Coronavirus: Women's WorldTour Trofeo Alfredo Binda postponed until June 2 |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/coronavirus-womens-worldtour-trofeo-alfredo-binda-postponed-until-june-2/ |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=5 March 2020 |date=5 March 2020 |quote=They are still awaiting the authorisation of the new date from the UCI.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/coronavirus-womens-worldtour-ronde-van-drenthe-cancelled/ |title=Coronavirus: Women's WorldTour Ronde van Drenthe cancelled |first=Lukas |last=Kn\u00f6fler |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |quote=Sadly, this means that our races will not go ahead [...] We hope to be back next year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Geen koers tot en met drie april, Ronde van Vlaanderen maakt nog een waterkansje maar houdt rekening met annulering |language=Dutch|trans-title=No race until 3 April, Tour of Flanders still has a remote chance but takes cancellation into account |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200312_04887671 |work=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |publisher=[[Mediahuis]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |quote=We besluiten bij deze om onze wedstrijd Driedaagse Brugge De Panne ook uit te stellen naar een later tijdstip. We hopen dat we een plaatsje krijgen op de kalender in het najaar. [We hereby decide to postpone our match Three Days Bruges De Panne to a later date. We hope that we will have a place on the calendar in the autumn].}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://sporza.be/nl/2020/03/12/alle-sportactiviteiten-in-belgie-tot-en-met-3-april-worden-gean~1584050395120/ |title=Alle sportactiviteiten in Belgi\u00eb tot en met 3 april worden geannuleerd |language=Dutch|trans-title=All sports activities in Belgium until 3 April will be canceled |work=[[Sporza]] |publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie]] |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |quote=In het wielrennen worden Nokere Koerse (18 maart), de Bredene Koksijde Classic (20 maart), de Driedaagse Brugge-De Panne (25 maart), de E3 Harelbeke (27 maart), Gent-Wevelgem (29 maart) en Dwars door Vlaanderen (1 april) geschrapt. [In cycling Nokere Koerse (March 18), the Bredene Koksijde Classic (March 20), the Driedaagse Brugge-De Panne (March 25), the E3 Harelbeke (March 27), Ghent-Wevelgem (March 29) and Dwars door Vlaanderen (April 1) are scrapped.]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://womenstour.co.uk/womens-tour-2020-postponed |title=Women's Tour 2020 postponed |first=Nick |last=Bull |work=[[The Women's Tour]] |publisher=SweetSpot Group |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/paris-roubaix-fleche-wallonne-and-liege-bastogne-liege-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/ |title=Paris-Roubaix, Fl\u00e8che Wallonne and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge postponed due to coronavirus pandemic |first=Barry |last=Ryan |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |quote=As part of the fight against the spread of Coronavirus (COVID19), Amaury Sport Organisation, with the agreement of the Union Cycliste Internationale (UCI), has decided to not organise Paris-Roubaix (12th April), the Fl\u00e8che Wallonne and the Fl\u00e8che Wallonne Women (22nd April) and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge Women (26th April) races on their scheduled dates.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/tour-of-flanders-cancelled-over-coronavirus-concerns/ |title=Tour of Flanders cancelled over coronavirus concerns |work=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |quote=Organisers of the Tour of Flanders made the long-anticipated decision to cancel their April 5 race, saying they will work with the UCI and representatives of the teams and riders to look at the potential for scheduling a new date later this year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.velonews.com/2020/03/news/rolling-report-impact-of-coronavirus-on-pro-racing_505843 |title=Rolling report: Impact of coronavirus on pro racing |work=[[VeloNews]] |publisher=Pocket Outdoor Media, LLC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |quote=March 18, 5:15 a.m. (MT): Amstel Gold race postponed}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] requested to suspend all UCI-sanctioned events in affected territories until 3 April, and the qualification for the Tokyo 2020 Olympic Games and Paralympic Games to stop retroactively as of 3 March.<ref name=\"uci20200315\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-takes-strong-measures-faced-with-the-development-of-the-coronavirus |title=The UCI takes strong measures faced with the development of the coronavirus |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March, the suspension of events were extended at least until the end of April.<ref name=\"uci20200318\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-and-its-partners-unite-to-face-the-consequences-of-the-coronavirus-for-road-cycling |title=The UCI and its partners unite to face the consequences of the coronavirus for road cycling |date=18 March 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>  On 1 April, the suspension was extended until 1 June.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-prolongs-the-suspension-of-cycling-events-until-1-june-2020-and-continues-consultations-for-the-reorganisation-of-the-uci-international-road-calendar |title=The UCI prolongs the suspension of cycling events until 1 June 2020 and continues consultations for the reorganisation of the UCI International Road Calendar |date=1 April 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, the annual [[2020 Tour de France|Tour de France]] was originally scheduled for 27 June \u2013 19 July, but it was postponed to an unknown date due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|country's strict measures with the coronavirus]] as [[Government of France|the government]] extended a ban on mass gatherings until July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/cycling/story/_/id/29033546/tour-de-france-postponed-no-new-dates-set|title=Tour de France postponed no new dates set |work=ESPN |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===BMX===\nRace days of the 2020 [[UCI BMX Supercross World Cup]] were cancelled including 2 to 3 May in Papendal, the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://myprivacy.dpgmedia.net/?siteKey=Oom2kBLTny5zJUeO&callbackUrl=https%3a%2f%2fwww.gelderlander.nl%2fprivacy-gate%2faccept%3fredirectUri%3d%252fsport-arnhem%252fwereldbeker-bmx-papendal-ook-van-de-agenda-geld-terug-voor-deelnemers-en-fans%257ea71539c9%252f%253freferrer%253dhttps%253a%252f%252fwww.google.nl%252f |title=Privacy settings |website=myprivacy.dpgmedia.net |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[UCI BMX World Championships]], scheduled to take place in [[Houston]], United States on 26\u201331 May, are postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/l/2328063 |title=Ook wereldkampioenschappen BMX uitgesteld wegens coronavirus |website=nos.nl |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nThe annual [[Cape Epic]] endurance race scheduled from 15 to 22 March was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cape-epic.com/riders/the-2020-race/official-statement-2020-absa-cape-epic-cancellation |title=The Official Statement regarding the cancellation of the 2020 Absa Cape Epic {{!}} Absa Cape Epic|website=cape-epic.com|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Darts==\nThe [[Professional Darts Corporation]]'s [[PDC European Tour|European Tour]] was impacted by the coronavirus; with the [[2020 European Darts Grand Prix]], the [[2020 European Darts Open]] and the [[2020 German Darts Grand Prix]] all being postponed following restrictions on gatherings implemented by federal governments in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] and [[Bavaria]], respectively. The two [[2020 Premier League Darts]] rounds to be held in [[Rotterdam]] at the end of March were postponed to September following restrictions on gatherings in the Netherlands; and the round to be held in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] a week earlier was subsequently postponed to October.  The next five rounds, in [[Belfast]], [[Sheffield]], [[Manchester]], [[Berlin]] and [[Birmingham]] were also postponed to later dates, with the Sheffield dates now serving as the Play-Off Round.  All ProTour events from 16 March to the end of April were postponed.\n\nThe planned first event on the [[2020 World Series of Darts]], the US Darts Masters, was cancelled for 2020, and the [[2020 Nordic Darts Masters]] was postponed from June to October. The PDC's North American affiliate, the Championship Darts Corporation, cancelled the first weekend of its season in [[Ontario]], and the New Zealand affiliate DartPlayers tour was ended for 2019/20 following the cancellation of events in [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus \u2013 Latest re PDC events |url=https://www.pdc.tv/Coronavirus |publisher=[[Professional Darts Corporation]] |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Esports==\nImpact of the pandemic on [[esports]] have primarily affected events and leagues that host competitions in-person at venues with spectators, which have led to cancellations, postponements, and competitions being held behind closed doors\u2014either in the traditional sense, or with competition being conducted entirely [[Multiplayer video game|over the internet]] (although [[Latency (engineering)|latency]] between players can be a factor), with streaming broadcasts (as is typical for esports).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21167652/coronavirus-esports-impact-league-of-legends-pubg-csgo-iem-katowice |title=The coronavirus' human impact on esports |last=Garst |first=Aron |date=6 March 2020 |website=The Verge |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/esports/2020/03/17/esports-streamers-coronavirus-sports-canceled/ |title=While the sports world falls silent, esports and streamers fill the void |last=Smith |first=Noah |date=17 March 2020 |website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\" />\n\n===Leagues===\n==== Global StarCraft II League ====\nThe [[Global StarCraft II League]] Super Tournament Season I were delayed, but remain offline event, but without spectators. The event won by Terran player Maru.\n\n====Overwatch League====\nThe [[Overwatch League]] cancelled homestand events (matches held on-location at home venues akin to traditional sports leagues, as opposed to a centralized studio) in Asia at the onset of the pandemic, and subsequently cancelled all homestands through to April following its spread in North America in mid-March. The league planned a shift to online play, and competition of the [[2020 Overwatch League season|2020 season]] to resume 21 March. The mid-season tournament was also removed from the schedule, and its all-star festivities were moved to the off-season due to not all players having played an equal number of games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28885048/coronavirus-leads-overwatch-league-suspend-play-march-april |title=Coronavirus leads OWL to cancel events for March, April |date=11 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\"/> Due to [[stay-at-home orders]] imposed by the state of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]] (where [[Blizzard Entertainment|Blizzard]]'s headquarters and several other teams are located), the resumption of play was postponed (although exhibition matches showcasing the game's newly-unveiled character Echo were still held). Play resumed on 28 March, with teams realigned into three regional conferences. Due to various factors, including several teams suspending their operations (including the [[New York Excelsior]], in compliance with a [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|local]] stay-at-home order, and the [[London Spitfire]] and [[Vancouver Titans]] re-locating their staff to South Korea), six of the 16 matches scheduled for the weekend were dropped from the schedule.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28928919/overwatch-league-postpones-first-weekend-online-matches |title=Overwatch League postpones first weekend of online matches |date=20 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/esports/2020/03/27/overwatch-league-schedule-coronavirus-online/ |title=Overwatch League teams face a reset after pandemic spoils its grand plans |last= |first= |date=27 March 2020 |website=Launcher (Washington Post)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/multiple-overwatch-league-matches-canceled-on-march-28-and-29 |title=Multiple Overwatch League matches canceled on March 28 and 29 |last= |first= |date=27 March 2020 |website=Dot eSports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====''League of Legends''====\n[[Riot Games]] announced that the [[League of Legends Championship Series]] would temporarily suspend its season and switch to online play. In addition, the Spring Finals event in Frisco, Texas was called off and moved back to Riot's Los Angeles studio.<ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\">{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28852881/how-coronavirus-affecting-esports-gaming-events |title=How coronavirus is affecting esports and gaming events |last= |first= |date=13 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/14/21179779/league-of-legends-lcs-spring-finals-canceled-moved-ea-sports-fifa-global-series-apex-legends |title=League of Legends, EA suspend all esports due to coronavirus |last=Good |first=Owen S. |date=14 March 2020 |website=Polygon |language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====''Counter-Strike: Global Offensive''====\nThe 2020 IEM Katowice World Championship was played without a live audience due to preemptive closures of large events in Poland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan |title=IEM Katowice playoffs to be played without audience due to coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/29153/iem-katowice-playoffs-to-be-played-without-audience-due-to-coronavirus-concerns |website=HLTV.org |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> As the pandemic became more severe and closures became more common, virtually all [[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]] events were either postponed, cancelled, or moved online. Most notably, the [[ESL One Rio Major 2020]] was postponed from March to November. Remaining qualifiers for the major were cancelled, to be rerun online later.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan |title=Event status update: How the coronavirus is affecting LAN tournaments* |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/29302/event-status-update-how-the-coronavirus-is-affecting-lan-tournaments |website=HLTV.org |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Crossover with traditional sports===\nSportcal suggested that the esports industry had an opportunity to attract mainstream sports fans as a \"viable alternative\" to traditional sporting events.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://advanced-television.com/2020/03/18/analyst-coronavirus-a-significant-opportunity-for-esports/ |title=Analyst: \"Coronavirus a significant opportunity for eSports\" |last= |first= |date= |website=advanced-television.com |language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>  Roundhill Investments CEO Will Hershey predicted that games that are straightforward for casual viewers to understand (such as [[sports game]]s) could see particular interest among this new audience.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWith the suspension of nearly all sporting events, some professional athletes began to increase their involvement in video game streaming as a means to engage with fans.<ref name=\":2\" /> Some teams have taken advantage of sports games in a similar manner, such as the [[Phoenix Suns]] holding ''[[NBA 2K20]]'' streams with guest players, between the teams the Suns were scheduled to play that night if the season had continued.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28900417/luka-doncic-50-leads-mavs-suns-twitch |title=Luka's 50 lead Mavericks past Suns \u2013 on Twitch |date=14 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28964373/bridges-leads-suns-victory-first-nba-2k-game-broadcast-radio |title=Bridges leads Suns to victory in first NBA 2K game broadcast on radio |date=28 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> This culminated with a game actually being commentated by the team's radio broadcasters on team flagship [[KMVP-FM]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nEsports organisations have also invited professional athletes to compete in specific competitions (often alongside, or in competition with professional players); [[FaZe Clan]] organized a charity ''[[Call of Duty: Warzone]]'' pro-am entitled \"Fight 2 Fund\" in support of coronavirus-related charities, where professional players were partnered with celebrity participants (such as [[Ben Simmons]], [[Chad Johnson]], and [[JuJu Smith-Schuster]]),<ref name=\":2\" /> and several [[sim racing]] competitions similarly invited professional race drivers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2020/03/esports-fills-the-gap-as-coronavirus-cancels-in-person-sporting-events/ |title=F1 drivers and other pros switch to esports in the age of the coronavirus |last=Gitlin |first=Jonathan M. |date=16 March 2020 |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/22/21184192/sim-racing-coronavirus-f1-nascar-iracing-veloce-esports-max-verstappen-lando-norris |title=Pro drivers are competing with gamers after F1 and NASCAR canceled races |last=O'Kane |first=Sean |date=22 March 2020 |website=The Verge |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn turn, both the [[IndyCar Series]] and [[NASCAR]] announced partnerships with sim racing platform ''[[iRacing]]'' to hold online invitational events featuring series regulars, with the latter employing television broadcasts by NASCAR television partner [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Sports]] (styled after and still featuring personalities associated with their traditional broadcasts, including the commentary pair of [[Mike Joy]] and [[Jeff Gordon]], based at [[Fox Sports 1]]'s studio in Charlotte).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2020/03/22/nascar-iracing-pro-invitational-series-fox-sports-1-high-marks/2894874001/ |title=FS1 broadcast of NASCAR iRacing comes extremely close to the real thing |last=Gardner |first=Steve |website=USA Today |language=en-US|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/story/_/id/28919500/with-nascar-season-postponed-drivers-compete-esports-series |title=NASCAR greats set to compete in esports series |date=18 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"espn.com\" />  The first event (using [[Homestead-Miami Speedway]], where the [[NASCAR Cup Series]] was to have raced that weekend) drew a television audience of 903,000 on [[Fox Sports 1]], making it the most-watched esports broadcast on U.S. linear television since a 2016 ''[[Mortal Kombat X]]'' event aired by [[The CW]]. This record was surpassed the following week with a Texas Motor Speedway race \u2014 also aired by the main [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox network]] \u2014 which attracted 1.339 million viewers.<ref name=\"AW\">{{cite web |last1=Weaver |first1=Matt |title=Texas eNASCAR iRacing Event Breaks TV Record for Esports Broadcast |url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a31996587/texas-enascar-iracing-event-breaks-tv-record-for-esports-broadcast/ |website=Autoweek.com |publisher=Autoweek |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=AW}}</ref>\n\n==Fencing==\nOn 3 March 2020 the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale d'Escrime]] (FIE) issued its first bulletin on COVID-19 precautions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fie.org/articles/942 |title=INTERNATIONAL FENCING FEDERATION - The International Fencing Federation official website |publisher=Fie.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 10 March FIE strongly recommended that all participants in its competitions (athletes and other members of national delegations) fill and carry with them a questionnaire about their health status.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fie.org/articles/947 |title=INTERNATIONAL FENCING FEDERATION - The International Fencing Federation official website |publisher=Fie.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 12 March a FIE circular reported the postponement of six World Cup or Grand Prix competitions and the World Junior/Cadet Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fie.org/articles/948 |title=INTERNATIONAL FENCING FEDERATION - The International Fencing Federation official website |publisher=Fie.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Since the World Cup and Grand Prix events were part of the [[Fencing at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|qualifications for the 2020 Tokyo Olympics]], the circular warned on the need to postpone the zonal qualifications tournament for the Olympics. No news was given on other events, and their possible postponement or cancellation.\n\nFIE reported on its web site<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fie.org/articles/949 |title=INTERNATIONAL FENCING FEDERATION - The International Fencing Federation official website |publisher=Fie.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> the postponement of the Olympic Games, but hasn't yet given any information on the [[World Fencing Championships]], which is supposed to happen in non-Olympic years, so there is a 2021 Championship planned (assigned to Cairo), but not a 2020 Championship.\n\nIndividual countries had different decisions. For example, on 4 April the [[Federazione Italiana Scherma]] announced it was suspending all competitions until 31 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.federscherma.it/homepage/media/news/14-news/top-news/30976-il-consiglio-federale-sospende-l-attivita-agonistica-fino-al-31-agosto-in-pedana-solo-per-allenarsi,-quando-sara-consentito.html |title=Federazione Italiana Scherma - IL CONSIGLIO FEDERALE SOSPENDE L'ATTIVITA' AGONISTICA FINO AL 31 AGOSTO. IN PEDANA SOLO PER ALLENARSI, QUANDO SARA' CONSENTITO |publisher=Federscherma.it |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Field hockey==\nMany field hockey leagues in Europe have been suspended, including in Spain,<ref>{{cite web |title=Comunicado Oficial RFEH |url=https://www.rfeh.es/comunicado-oficial-rfeh-7/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=es}}</ref> England,<ref>{{cite web |title=England Hockey suspends national hockey activity |url=https://www.englandhockey.co.uk/news.asp?itemid=49019&itemTitle=England+Hockey+suspends+national+hockey+activity&section=22 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> Germany,<ref>{{cite web |title=Feldhockey-Bundesligen: Spielverkehr bis Ende April ausgesetzt |url=https://web.hockey.de/news/lgtz22.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=de}}</ref> and the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geen competitie en hockeyactiviteiten tot 1 april |url=https://www.knhb.nl/nieuws/geen-competitie-en-hockeyactiviteiten-tot-1-april |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Euro Hockey League]] Final 8 and [[2020 Euro Hockey League Women]] seasons were suspended on 12 March.<ref name=\"EHL\">{{cite web |title=EHL Final8 Put on Hold |url=https://ehlhockey.tv/2020/03/12/ehl-final8-put-on-hold/ |website=ehlhockey.tv |publisher=[[Euro Hockey League]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Men's EuroHockey Club Trophy I]], [[2020 Men's EuroHockey Club Trophy II]], [[2020 Boys' EuroHockey Youth Championships]] and [[2020 Girls' EuroHockey Youth Championships]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=EHF cancels all EuroHockey Club Trophy and Challenge events, 2020 |url=https://eurohockey.org/2020/03/24/ehf-cancels-all-eurohockey-club-trophy-and-challenge-events-2020/ |website=eurohockey.org |publisher=[[European Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=EuroHockey U18 Championships boys and girls 2020 are cancelled |url=https://eurohockey.org/2020/03/31/eurohockey-u18-championships-boys-and-girls-2020-are-cancelled/ |website=eurohockey.org |publisher=[[European Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Asia, the [[2020 Men's Hockey Junior Asia Cup]], [[2020 Women's Asian Champions Trophy]], and [[2020 Women's Hockey Junior Asia Cup]] were postponed.<ref name=\"AHF2020\">{{cite web |title=Announcement: Postponement of the Bangabandhu Al-Arafah Islami Bank Junior Asia Cup Dhaka 2020 & the Women's Asian Champions Trophy Donghae 2020 |url=http://www.asiahockey.org/news/announcement-postponement-of-the-bangabandhu-al-arafah-islami-bank-junior-asia-cup-dhaka-2020-the-womens-asian-champions-trophy-donghae-2020/ |website=asiahockey.org |publisher=[[Asian Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Junior Asia Cup Gifu Kakamigahara 2020 \u2013 Formal Announcement of Postponement |url=http://www.asiahockey.org/news/womens-junior-asia-cup-gifu-kakamigahara-2020-formal-announcement-of-postponement/ |website=asiahockey.org}}</ref> The [[2020 Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] has been postponed to 24 September.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Azlan Shah Cup Hockey Tournament Postponed |url=https://sports.ndtv.com/hockey/coronavirus-azlan-shah-cup-hockey-tournament-postponed-2188516 |website=ndtv.com |publisher=[[NDTV]]}}</ref>\n\n==Futsal==\nThe [[2020 AFC Futsal Championship]] in [[Ashgabat]] had been postponed following consultation with all relevant stakeholders. On 9 March 2020, FIFA and AFC announced that the tournament were postponed to 5\u201316 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers|title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers|publisher=FIFA.com|date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers|title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers|publisher=AFC|date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://futsalfeed.com/original-content/robert-grdovic-talks-about-postponed-afc-futsal-championship-and-predicts-the-outcome|title=Robert Grdovic talks about postponed AFC Futsal Championship and predicts the outcome|publisher=futsallfeed.com| accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Golf==\nMany elite golf tournaments, both professional and amateur, have either been postponed or cancelled in response to the pandemic, including the [[Men's major golf championships|major championships]].<ref name=golftourneys/> On 13 March, it was announced that the [[2020 Masters Tournament|Masters Tournament]] (scheduled for 9\u201312 April) had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Masters Tournament Postponed |url=https://www.masters.com/en_US/news/articles/2020-03-13/2020_masters_tournament_postponed.html |publisher=Masters.com |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=Augusta National announces Masters will be postponed |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28897249/augusta-national-announces-masters-postponed-played |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 PGA Championship]] (scheduled for 11\u201317 May) was postponed the following week.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/sports/golf/pga-championship-postponed.html |title=P.G.A. Championship Is Postponed |newspaper=The New York Times |last=Pennington |first=Bill |date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 6 April, [[The Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St Andrews|The R&A]] announced the cancellation of the [[2020 Open Championship]], the first cancellation since World War II.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/golf/news/12176/11969376/the-149th-open-cancelled-for-this-year-and-will-return-to-sandwich-in-2021 |title=The 149th Open cancelled for this year and will return to Sandwich in 2021 |website=Sky Sports |first=Keith |last=Jackson |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> This was soon followed by the [[United States Golf Association|USGA]] announcing the rescheduling of the [[2020 U.S. Open (golf)|2020 U.S. Open]] from 18\u201321 June to 17\u201320 September, and new dates in November for the Masters and in August for the PGA Championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/52135613 |title=The Open cancelled; Masters, US Open & US PGA Championship rescheduled |website=BBC Sport |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The ladies majors have been similarly affected, with the [[LPGA Tour]] postponing the [[ANA Inspiration]] until September.<ref name=lpga1/>\n\nOn 12 March 2020, midway through the first round of the [[2020 Players Championship]], the [[PGA Tour]] announced that the remainder of the tournament and the next three events, the [[Valspar Championship]], [[WGC Match Play]], and the [[Valero Texas Open]], would continue without fan attendance. Subsequently, after completion of the days play, the tour decided to cancel the remainder of tournament and the three following events.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=Players Championship, other events won't have fans in attendance |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28890609/players-starts-autograph-ban-place |accessdate=13 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=PGA Tour cancels Players Championship after first round |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28894497/pga-tour-cancels-players-championship-first-round |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March, the tour announced the cancellation of all scheduled tournaments through 10 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pgatour.com/company/2020/03/17/pga-tour-news-tournament-cancellations-rbc-heritage-zurich-classic-new-orleans-wells-fargo-championship-att-byron-nelson-pga-championship.html |title=PGA Tour statement regarding additional tournament cancellations |publisher=PGA Tour |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> The [[European Tour]] have also cancelled or postponed many tournaments, mostly those scheduled from mid-March through to the end of May,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/news/articles/detail/update-on-european-tour-events/ |title=Update on European Tour events |website=European Tour |date=27 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> including the [[Irish Open (golf)|Irish Open]], a [[Rolex Series]] event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/52092416 |title=Irish Open: Mount Juliet European Tour event postponed because of coronavirus |website=BBC Sport |date=30 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Ladies European Tour]] postponed the 2020 [[Evian Championship]], originally scheduled for 23\u201326 July, to 6\u20139 August.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Evian Championship Moves to Early August |url=https://ladieseuropeantour.com/the-evian-championship-moves-to-early-august/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |publisher=Ladies European Tour |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther leading professional tours have announced similar measures, as have the bodies responsible for organising leading amateur events.<ref name=golftourneys/> On 1 April, the R&A and the USGA jointly announced that the [[2020 Curtis Cup|Curtis Cup]] was being postponed until 2021, and the British [[The Amateur Championship|mens]] and [[The Womens Amateur Championship|womens]] amateur championships were being rescheduled from June to August.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.golfchannel.com/news/curtis-cup-postponed-2021-british-amateur-championships-rescheduled |title=Curtis Cup postponed to 2021; British Ams rescheduled |website=Golf Channel |date=1 April 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The LPGA Tour have cancelled three tournaments and postponed five others including the ANA Inspiration,<ref name=lpga1>{{cite news |title=LPGA to reschedule 3 events, including first major, the ANA Inspiration |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28893923/lpga-reschedule-3-events-including-first-major-ana-inspiration |accessdate=13 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=golftourneys>{{cite web |url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/here-are-all-the-golf-tournaments-that-have-been-canceled-or-postponed-due-to-the-coronavirus |title=Here are all the golf tournaments that have been canceled or postponed due to the coronavirus |website=Golf Digest |publisher=Golf World |first=Ryan |last=Herrington |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Japan LPGA Tour]] cancelled five tournaments scheduled from March into April.<ref name=sched>{{cite web |url=https://www.lpga.or.jp/tournament/jlpgatour/2020 |title=2020\u5e74\u5ea6 JLPGA\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc\u30b9\u30b1\u30b8\u30e5\u30fc\u30eb |trans-title=2020 JLPGA Tour Schedule |publisher=JLPGA |language=ja}}</ref>\n\nRecreational golf has also been affected, with many countries and regions ordering the closure of golf [[country club|clubs]] and [[golf course|courses]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/coronavirus-more-than-1-3-of-europes-golf-courses-now-closed |title=Coronavirus: Almost half of Europe's golf courses are now closed! |website=Bunkered |date=18 March 2020 |first=Michael |last=McEwan |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/golf-canada-ceo-applebaum-asks-golfers-to-stay-home-during-covid-19-pandemic-1.4863339 |title=Golf Canada CEO Applebaum asks golfers to stay home during COVID-19 pandemic |first=John |last=Chidley-Hill |agency=The Canadian Press |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/golf-courses-to-close-as-uk-steps-up-coronavirus-fight |title=Golf courses to CLOSE as UK steps up coronavirus fight |website=Bunkered |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://7news.com.au/sport/golf/australian-golf-courses-told-to-close-immediately-as-coronavirus-restrictions-take-hold-c-772433 |title=Australian golf courses told to close immediately as coronavirus restrictions take hold |first=Glenn |last=Valencich |website=Seven News |date=30 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/heres-a-state-by-state-breakdown-of-where-golfs-allowed-and-where-it-isnt |title=Here's a state-by-state breakdown of where golf's allowed and where it isn't |website=Golf World (Golf Digest) |first=Mike |last=Stachura |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Greyhound racing==\nThe [[2020 English Greyhound Derby]] was postponed on 16 March with no replacement dates set at present.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/derby-postponed-statement/ |title=DERBY POSTPONED \u2013 ARC STATEMENT |website=Greyhound Star}}</ref> The [[Arena Racing Company]] tracks announced a behind closed doors policy from 24 March <ref>{{cite web |url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/arc-meetings-staged-behind-closed-doors/ |title=ALL ARC MEETINGS TO BE STAGED BEHIND CLOSED DOORS |website=Greyhound Star}}</ref> and [[Greyhound racing in Ireland|racing in Ireland]] continued with a behind closed doors policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.igb.ie/talking-dogs/covid-19-update-racing-behind-closed-doors/ |title=COVID 19 UPDATE: RACING BEHIND CLOSED DOORS |publisher=Irish Greyhound Board}}</ref> Subsequently all racing in the United Kingdom and Ireland was postponed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/greyhound-racing-suspended-press-release/|title=Greyhound racing suspended \u2013 Press release|publisher=Greyhound Star}}</ref>\n\n==Gridiron football==\n\n===Canadian Football League===\nOn 12 March, the [[Canadian Football League]] announced the cancellation or modification of several pre-season events in response to the pandemic. Several scouting combines across Canada and the United States were cancelled, while other events such as rules committee meetings will now be held remotely. The League initially planned to hold both its International and National Drafts in April, but it was announced on 24 March that the Global Draft would be postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/2020/03/12/statement-cfl-coronavirus-situation/ |title=A statement from the CFL on the Coronavirus situation |website=cfl.ca|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/2020/03/24/cfl-global-draft-rescheduled-lead-event-prior-training-camp/ |title=CFL GLOBAL DRAFT RESCHEDULED AS LEAD-IN EVENT PRIOR TO TRAINING CAMP |website=cfl.ca|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe start of the [[2020 CFL season|2020 regular season]] was officially postponed until at least the start of July by Commissioner [[Randy Ambrosie]] on 7 April. In a press statement, he announced that the CFL was exploring multiple options to ensure that the league will be able to play as close to a full season as possible.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/2020/04/07/ambrosie-issues-statement-behalf-cfl/ |title=AMBROSIE ISSUES STATEMENT ON BEHALF OF CFL |website=cfl.ca|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> The regular season had originally been scheduled to begin on 11 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cfl.ca/schedule/?season=2020|title=2020 CFL Schedule|publisher=cfl.ca|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===National Football League===\nThe [[National Football League]] has been in its off-season since [[Super Bowl LIV|2 February 2020]], but the [[2020 NFL Draft]] is scheduled to be held in [[Las Vegas]] from 23\u201325 April 2020. On 12 March, various NFL teams began to suspend travel by their coaches and [[Scout (sport)|player scout]]s, while the league itself had advised its non-critical staff to work from home. On 13 March 2020, the NFL announced that it had temporarily prohibited draft-eligible players from travelling to meet team personnel, and vice versa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/nfl-coronavirus-updates-league-prohibits-pre-draft-visits-mulls-draft-changes-xfl-player-tests-positive/ |title=NFL coronavirus updates: League prohibits pre-draft visits, mulls draft changes, XFL player tests positive |website=CBSSports.com |language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the NFL announced that it had cancelled public festivities associated with the draft; the draft itself will still be held, but the league stated that it was exploring \"innovative options for how the process will be conducted\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Belson |first=Ken |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/sports/football/nfl-draft-coronavirus.html |title=How the N.F.L. Draft Process Works From Home |date=27 March 2020 |work=The New York Times|access-date=29 March 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106351/article/nfl-draft-to-proceed-april-2325-sans-public-events-in-las-vegas |title=NFL draft to proceed April 23\u201325 sans public events in Las Vegas |website=NFL.com |language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLabor negotiations with the [[National Football League Players Association]] continued through the pandemic, resulting in ratification of a new, ten-year [[collective bargaining agreement]] in March 2020.\n\n===XFL===\nOn 12 March, the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] (a revival of the one-season [[XFL (2001)|2001 league]]) announced the suspension of the 2020 season, with all players to be paid their base pay and benefits for the full 2020 regular season; the season was officially cancelled on 20 March, with half of its ten-week regular season schedule played.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/xfl-officially-cancels-inaugural-season-reveals-when-players-can-sign-with-nfl-or-cfl-teams/ |title=XFL officially cancels inaugural season, reveals when players can sign with NFL or CFL teams |last=Dajani |first=Jordan |date=20 March 2020 |publisher=[[CBSSports.com]] |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, the league announced that it would suspend all operations and lay off all but a few critical executives, and said it was unlikely a 2021 season would be organized and played, with those executives remaining to wind down the league's business and operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/xfl/story/_/id/29021347/xfl-suspends-operations-lays-employees-no-plans-return-2021|title=XFL suspends operations, lays off employees and has no plans for 2021 season|last=Siefert|first=Kevin|date=10 April 2020|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gymnastics==\nMultiple international artistic gymnastics competitions, many of which were [[Gymnastics at the 2020 Summer Olympics|Olympic]] qualifying events, were either canceled or postponed.  On 13 March, after already having completed qualifications, the [[2020 FIG Artistic Gymnastics World Cup series|Baku World Cup]] canceled its event finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/news/displaynews.php?idNews=2836 |title=Finals of Baku World Cup cancelled |work=[[International Gymnastics Federation]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>  The Stuttgart, Birmingham, and Tokyo World Cups (scheduled to take place between 21 March \u2013 5 April) were all canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/news/displaynews.php?idNews=2827 |title=Impact of the COVID-19 outbreak on the upcoming FIG events |work=[[International Gymnastics Federation]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.british-gymnastics.org/news-and-events/news/latest-news/9015-british-gymnastics-national-events-announcement-including-fig-world-cup |title=British Gymnastics national events announcement, including FIG World Cup |work=[[British Gymnastics]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=tokyowc>{{cite tweet |number=1239945252183703553 |user=FIG_media |date=17 March 2020 |title=Japan Gymnastics Association has decided to cancel the #Tokyo All-Around World Cup that was scheduled on 4\u20135 April 2020}}</ref>  The [[European Women's Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] (scheduled to take place 30 April \u2013 3 May) and the [[European Men's Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] (scheduled to take place 27\u201331 May) were both canceled.<ref name=euros2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.ueg.org/news/covid-19-update-event-cancellations |title=COVID-19 update \u2013 event cancellations |work=[[European Union of Gymnastics]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>  The [[Pacific Rim Championships]] (scheduled to take place 17\u201319 April) was postponed until 2021.<ref name=pacrim>{{cite web |url=https://www.gymnasticsnz.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/2020-Pacific-Rim-postponement-announcement-final-17Mar20.pdf |title=2020 Pacific Rim Championships Postponed |date=17 March 2020 |work=Gymnastics New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n==Handball==\nThe 25\u201329 March, [[2020 European Women's Handball Championship qualification]] matches in Rotterdam, the Netherlands were cancelled.<ref name=\"nu.nl\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nu.nl/sport-overig/6033687/deze-sportevenementen-zijn-afgelast-vanwege-het-coronavirus.html |title=Deze sportevenementen zijn afgelast vanwege het coronavirus |date=27 February 2020 |website=NU |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Horse racing==\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, most horse racing events remained scheduled as normal, but with restricted attendance at racecourses. This included Hong Kong, France,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/sports/hippisme/coronavirus-les-courses-hippiques-et-les-turfistes-s-adaptent-10-03-2020-8276982.php |title=Coronavirus : Les courses hippiques et les turfistes s'adaptent |first1=Par St\u00e9phan FlourentLe 10 mars 2020 |last1=\u00e0 19h56 |first2=Modifi\u00e9 Le 10 Mars 2020 |last2=\u00c0 19h57 |date=10 March 2020 |website=leparisien.fr}}</ref> Japan,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/238823/coronavirus-forces-bettors-online-in-japan |title=Coronavirus Forces Bettors Online in Japan |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |first=Naohiro |last=Goda |date=2 March 2020}}</ref> United Arab Emirates,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/horse-racing/the-35-million-dubai-world-cup-show-must-go-on-1.70362919 |title=The $35 million Dubai World Cup show must go on |website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> United States, Australia,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.racenet.com.au/news/all-star-mile-slated-to-go-ahead-yet-fans-banned-from-australian-grand-prix-20200313 |title=LATEST BREAKING NEWS \u2013 All-Star Mile to go ahead but crowd lockout |website=www.racenet.com.au}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/latest/dundalk-to-race-behind-closed-doors-as-ireland-launches-coronavirus-restrictions/427842 |title=Racing in Ireland to go ahead behind closed doors until March 29 &#124; Horse Racing News &#124; Racing Post |website=www.racingpost.com}}</ref> United Kingdom, Germany, New Zealand, and Singapore.\n\nThe [[Macau Jockey Club]] suspended racing events from 31 January to 15 February and resumed racing from 22 February. The [[Korea Racing Authority]] suspended horse racing from 8 March. [[Sunland Park Racetrack & Casino|Sunland Park Racetrack]] in the United States canceled its race meeting from 16 March, which included the [[Sunland Derby]], part of the [[2020 Road to the Kentucky Derby]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239094/maryland-new-mexico-close-tracks-simulcast-facilities |title=Maryland, New Mexico Close Tracks, Simulcast Facilities |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Many tracks in North America followed suit over the following weeks, although some remained open depending on state-by-state decisions. In Britain, although the [[Cheltenham Festival]] proceeded as normal in mid-March,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oliphant |first1=Vickiie |title=Cheltenham coronavirus advice: How to avoid COVID-19 \u2013 Festival guidelines in FULL |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/horseracing/1252795/Cheltenham-coronavirus-advice-guidelines-in-full-cheltenham-festival-races |website=Express.co.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> the [[Grand National]] meeting at Aintree in April was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/grand-national-meeting-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/428688 |title=Grand National cancelled as Aintree card lost to spiralling coronavirus crisis &#124; Horse Racing News &#124; Racing Post |website=www.racingpost.com}}</ref> By mid-March [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] had become the only major horse racing country in Europe where the sport continued, albeit strictly regulated and behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/18/talking-horses-racing-industry-left-to-contemplate-cost-of-suspension |title=Ireland goes it alone as racing continues behind closed doors |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Greg |last=Wood |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Ireland finally closed down racing on 25 March until at least 19 April.<ref name=IrelandCancelled />\n\n[[Churchill Downs]] announced that the [[2020 Kentucky Derby]], normally the first leg of the [[Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing|American Triple Crown]], would be delayed to 5 September;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239121/the-146th-kentucky-derby-moved-to-sept-5 |title=The 146th Kentucky Derby Moved to Sept. 5 |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Eric |last1=Mitchell |first2=Byron |last2=King |title=Owners, Trainers React to Kentucky Derby Postponement |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239123/owners-trainers-react-to-kentucky-derby-postponement |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |date=17 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> this also cascaded to the [[Preakness Stakes]], with the [[Maryland Jockey Club]] delaying their second leg race to a date to be determined, likely in September as well.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-latest-will-the-preakness-be-postponed-jockey-club-discussing/ |title=Coronavirus Latest: Preakness To Be Postponed, Likely To September |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=[[WJZ-TV]] |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The [[New York Racing Association]] has not announced plans to reschedule the [[Belmont Stakes]], normally the third leg.\n\nOn 22 March, it was announced that the [[Dubai World Cup]], due to celebrate its 25th anniversary running on 28 March, had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Dubai World Cup night is called off at Meydan |url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/2020-dubai-world-cup-night-is-called-off-at-meydan-1.1584882198359 |website=Gulf News |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, [[Jockey Club|Jockey Club Racecourses]] announced that the first four [[British Classic Races|Classics]] of the British flat racing season \u2013 the [[2000 Guineas Stakes|2000]] and [[1000 Guineas Stakes|1000 Guineas]], scheduled to be held on 2\u20133 May, and the [[Epsom Oaks]] and [[Epsom Derby|Derby]], scheduled to be held on 5\u20136 June \u2013 would be postponed until later in the season. Ascot Racecourse also announced that [[Royal Ascot]], scheduled to be held from 16\u201320 June, would take place [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] if it gets the go-ahead.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guineas and Derby meetings to be held later in the season, Jockey Club announces |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/guineas-and-derby-meetings-to-be-held-later-in-the-season-jockey-club-announces/431135 |website=Racing Post |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Royal Ascot to take place behind closed doors if given green light |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/royal-ascot-to-take-place-behind-closed-doors-due-to-the-coronavirus/431128 |website=Racing Post |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome horsemen are limited from travelling to other racecouses or horse racing facilities. Hong Kong-based jockey [[Keith Yeung]] felt unwell on 22 March night, but his test for COVID-19 PCR was negative.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/racing/article/3076478/hong-kong-jockey-keith-yeungs-covid-19-test-comes-back-negative |title=Hong Kong jockey Keith Yeung's Covid-19 test comes back negative |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, it was announced that American-based jockey [[Javier Castellano]] had tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=King |first1=Byron |title=Jockey Castellano Tests Positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239301/jockey-castellano-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |website=BloodHorse.com |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n;Cancelled race meetings<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Updates/Announcements |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/section/covid-19-updates-announcements |website=www.bloodhorse.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Macau Jockey Club]] \u2013 31 to 15 January February 28 March to 11 April<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mjc.mo/race_en/info/news_detail.php?newsid=32256 |title=Macau Jockey Club \u2013 Company News |website=Macau Jockey Club |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Korea Racing Authority]] \u2013 from 8 March\n*Selangor Turf Club, Malaysia \u2013 from 14 March\n*[[Sunland Park Racetrack & Casino|Sunland Park Racetrack]], New Mexico \u2013 March meeting\n*[[Keeneland]], Kentucky \u2013 April meeting. [[Kentucky Downs]] and [[Ellis Parks]] closed down in mid-March, while [[Turfway Park]] cancelled the last 4 days of its meeting at the end of March. Churchill Downs deferred the Kentucky Derby and Kentucky Oaks, normally scheduled for early May, to September\n* [[Woodbine Racetrack]], Toronto \u2013 harness racing from 14 March. Thoroughbred meeting scheduled to open on April 18 postponed to at least June 30\n* [[Aqueduct Racetrack]], New York \u2013 indefinitely from 19 March after a backstretch worker tested positive\n* [[Laurel Park (race track)|Laurel Park]], Maryland \u2013 indefinitely from 20 March\n* [[Fair Grounds Race Course|Fair Grounds]], Louisiana \u2013 cancelled last week of its winter meeting, 22 to 29 March\n* [[Santa Anita Park]], California \u2013 indefinitely from 27 March. Racing at Golden Gate Fields was suspended on April 2\n*All United Kingdom racecourses \u2013 18 March to 30 April (excluding [[Downpatrick Racecourse|Downpatrick]] and [[Down Royal Racecourse|Down Royal]] in Northern Ireland, which come under Irish racing rules)\n*All Ireland racecourses \u2013 25 March to 19 April<ref name=IrelandCancelled>{{cite web |title=Racing off in Ireland from Wednesday after all sporting events are cancelled |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/racing-off-after-all-sporting-events-are-cancelled-in-ireland/429939 |website=Racing Post |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*All German racecourses \u2013 17 March to 18 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.turf-times.de/tt-artikel/wegen-des-coronavirus-renn-stopp-bis-zum-18-april-deutschland |title=Wegen des Coronavirus: Renn-Stopp bis zum 18. April in Deutschland! &#124; Turf-Times Deutschland |website=www.turf-times.de |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*All French racecourses [[France Galop]] and [[LeTrot]] \u2013 17 March to 15 April\n*All United Arab Emirates race meetings \u2013 Including [[Dubai World Cup Night]] and four April meetings.\n*All New Zealand racecourses \u2013 From 24 March\n*All South African racecourses \u2013 27 March to 16 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportingpost.co.za/2020/03/sa-horseracing/ |title=Newsflash: It's Official \u2013 No SA Racing |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Singapore Turf Club]] \u2013 Form 4 April\n\n;Remaining racing meetings<ref>[https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/where-is-racing-still-happening-globally-and-when-could-countries-start-up-again/431022  Where is racing still happening and when could countries start up again?]</ref>\n*[[Hong Kong Jockey Club]] \u2013 no meeting canceled or rescheduled under coronavirus.\n*[[Macau Jockey Club]] \u2013 resumed racing from 22 February to 21 March\n*[[Japan Racing Association]] and [[National Association of Racing]] \u2013 no meeting canceled ot rescheduled under coronavirus.\n*Sweden, including flat racing and harness racing.\n*Most Australian racecourses \u2013 Some County and Picnic meetings are canceled, also Tasmanian racing canceled form 2 April.\n*Some American racecourses, including [[Gulfstream Park]] and [[Tampa Bay Downs]] in Florida, and [[Oaklawn Park]] in Arkansas\n\n==Ice hockey==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship|IIHF Women's World Championship]], [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division IV|IIHF World Championship Division IV]] and [[2020 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships|Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]] were all cancelled by the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] due to the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://iihf.com/en/events/2020/ww/news/18296/women%E2%80%99s-worlds-cancelled |title=Women's Worlds cancelled |date=7 March 2020 |work=iihf.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/news/18277/iihf-cancels-march-tournaments |title=IIHF cancels March tournaments |date=2 March 2020 |work=iihf.com}}</ref> The federation also cancelled the [[2020 IIHF World U18 Championships|2020 event]] of one of its two official junior world championship tournaments, the [[IIHF World U18 Championship]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=IIHF cancels U18 Worlds |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/events/2020/wm18/news/18313/iihf-cancels-u18-world-chhmpionship |location=[[Plymouth Charter Township, Michigan]] & [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], [[United States]] |publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]] |first=Adam |last=Steiss |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, IIHF publicly announced that the senior men's world championships had also been cancelled.<ref>{{cite press release |title=2020 IIHF Ice Hockey World Championship cancelled |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/events/2020/wm/news/18344/2020-iihf-ice-hockey-world-championship-cancelled |location=[[Switzerland]] |publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]] |website=iihf.com |first=Adam |last=Steiss |date=21 March 2020 | access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Cancelled tournaments:'''\n\n* [[2020 IIHF World U18 Championships]]\n*[[2020 IIHF World Championship]]s\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division I]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division II]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division III]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division IV]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship Division I]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship Division II]] Group A\n\n===Europe===\nAs a result of the German government's ban on large events, the [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] announced on 10 March that it would cancel the remainder of its season, marking the first time in the league's history a champion would not be crowned. The top four teams at the time of the cancellation \u2014 [[EHC Red Bull M\u00fcnchen]], [[Adler Mannheim]], [[Straubing Tigers]], and [[Eisbaren Berlin]] \u2014 would advance to the [[Champions Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=German League cancels season, won't crown champion as a result of coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/german-league-cancels-season-wont-crown-champion-as-a-result-of-coronavirus-outbreak |first=Jared |last=Clinton |publisher=[[The Hockey News]] |website=thehockeynews.com |date=10 March 2020 | access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Swedish Ice Hockey Association]] suspended all remaining hockey, the playoffs and qualification rounds, in the Swedish elite leagues on 15 March; no awarding of the [[Le Mat Trophy]] for the 2019/20 season nor transference of teams from the leagues' qualification plays for the 2020/21 season will happen as a result.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hockeys\u00e4songen 2019/20 st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.hockeyallsvenskan.se/artikel/2ittak7t7-1el1/hockeysasongen-2019-20-stalls-in |publisher=[[HockeyAllsvenskan]] |language=Swedish |website=hockeyallsvenskan.se |date=10 March 2020 | access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Cancelled or ended leagues:'''\n\n* [[2019\u201320 Czech Extraliga season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 Slovak Extraliga season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 Austrian Hockey League season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 DEL season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 SHL season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 EIHL season]]\n\n===North America===\nIn early March 2020, the [[National Hockey League]] suspended media access to the locker rooms, saying that only official personnel would be allowed in after the games to limit person-to-person contact. On 12 March, the NHL, [[American Hockey League]], the leagues of the [[Canadian Hockey League]] ([[Ontario Hockey League]], [[Quebec Major Junior Hockey League]], and [[Western Hockey League]]), the [[United States Hockey League|USHL]], and [[ECHL]] announced that their [[2019\u201320 NHL season|2019\u201320 seasons]] would be indefinitely suspended.<ref>{{cite web |title=NHL pauses regular season because of coronavirus |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gaydos |first1=Ryan |title=NHL suspends 2019\u201320 season over coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/nhl-suspends-season-over-coronavirus-outbreak |website=Fox News |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaplan |first1=Emily |title=NHL suspending play immediately due to virus |url=https://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/28891430/sources-nhl-suspending-play-immediately-due-virus |accessdate=12 March 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wearegreenbay.com/community/health/coronavirus/green-bay-gamblers-season-suspended-due-to-covid-19/ |title=Green Bay Gamblers season suspended due to COVID-19 |last=Rose |first=Joshua |date=12 March 202 |work=[[WFRV-TV|WeAreGreenBay.com]] |publisher=[[Nexstar Media Group]] |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, the [[National Women's Hockey League]] postponed its [[Isobel Cup]] Final game indefinitely. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/olympics/women-hockey/nwhl-postpones-2020-isobel-cup-final-due-covid-19-concerns/ |title=NWHL postpones 2020 Isobel Cup Final due to COVID-19 concerns |date=12 March 2020 |website=www.sportsnet.ca |language=en|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe ECHL announced on 14 March that the remainder of the season would be scrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/28904194/prudent-decision |title=ECHL cancels season amid concerns over virus |date=15 March 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The leagues of the CHL announced on 18 March that they would scrap the remainder of their regular seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/qmjhl-becomes-first-chl-league-to-cancel-remainder-of-regular-season |title=CHL leagues cancel remainder of regular season campaigns; playoff status still undetermined |last=EllisMarch 18 |first=Steven |last2=2020 |date=18 March 2020 |website=The Hockey News |language=en-CA|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March, the CHL confirmed that all playoffs and the [[2020 Memorial Cup]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/hockey/junior-hockey/covid-19-forces-cancellation-of-chl-playoffs-and-2020-memorial-cup |title=COVID-19 forces cancellation of CHL playoffs and 2020 Memorial Cup |date=23 March 2020 |website=The Province |language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hockey Canada]], the governing body for amateur hockey in the country, cancelled the remainder of its season on 13 March. This included national championships such as the [[Telus Cup]] and [[Esso Cup]], as well as all regional and provincial playoffs.  It also included the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]] playoffs and the [[2020 Centennial Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/news/2020-news-hockey-canada-ends-season |title=Hockey Canada statement in response to coronavirus (COVID-19) |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=Hockey Canada}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/hockey-canada-ends-season-cancels-championships-1.4851343 |title=Hockey Canada ends season, cancels championships |last=Hunt |first=Stephen |date=12 March 2020 |website=Calgary |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lacrosse==\nThe [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL) temporarily suspended the [[2020 NLL season|2020 season]] on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nll.com/news/nll-statement-on-game-play-march-12-2020/ |title=NLL STATEMENT ON GAME PLAY (MARCH 12, 2020) |publisher=National Lacrosse League |website=nll.com |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsport==\n\n===Australian Supercars===\nThe [[Supercars Championship]] had planned to hold an event, the [[Melbourne 400]] supporting the Australian Grand Prix. The event was cancelled the same time the Grand Prix was also cancelled. The Championship is currently seeking to hold a replacement event later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/13/supercars-confirms-albert-park-cancellation-seeking-replacement-event/ |title=Supercars confirms Albert Park cancellation, seeking replacement event |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The Supercars' [[Tasmania Super400]] at [[Symmons Plains Raceway]] (originally scheduled for 4\u20135 April), the [[Auckland Super400]] at Hampton Downs ( 25\u201326 April), and the [[Perth SuperNight]] at [[Wanneroo Raceway]] (16\u201317 May) rounds were also postponed beyond June.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chapman |first=Simon |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/18/breaking-supercars-postpones-tasmania-auckland-and-perth/ |title=Supercars postpones Tasmania, Auckland and Perth |publisher=[[Speedcafe]] |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> The Supercars' support series like the [[Boost Mobile Super Trucks]] were also affected, though the trucks intend to commit to their support schedule once new dates are finalised.<ref>{{cite web |last=Nguyen |first=Justin |url=https://www.thecheckeredflag.co.uk/2020/03/tasmania-auckland-perth-races-postponed-sst-to-follow-reschedules/ |title=Tasmania, Auckland, Perth races postponed, SST to follow reschedules |publisher=The Checkered Flag |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSupercars formed the [[Supercars eSeries|All Stars Eseries]] to allow its drivers to compete against each other.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bartolomaeus |first=Stefan |url=https://www.supercars.com/news/championship/what-you-need-to-know-supercars-goes-virtual/ |title=What you need to know: Supercars goes virtual |publisher=[[Supercars Championship]] |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters===\nThe [[2020 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters]] series postponed the start of its championship until July 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/dtm/news/148790/dtm-issues-revised-2020-calendar-set-for-july-start |title=The DTM has issued a revised 2020 calendar set to start in July |first=Rachit |last=Thukral |website=Autosport.com |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Formula One===\nThe early [[2020 Formula One World Championship|Formula One season]] was disrupted by the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"CHN postponed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.chinese-grand-prix-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.3g2y5Ngyrk1MbNxQB9hj4s.html |title=2020 F1 Chinese Grand Prix postponed due to novel coronavirus outbreak |date=12 February 2020 |website=Formula1.com |publisher=Formula One World Championship Limited|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212184109/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.chinese-grand-prix-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.3g2y5Ngyrk1MbNxQB9hj4s.html|archive-date=12 February 2020|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Prior to the start of the season, [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] and [[Scuderia AlphaTauri|AlphaTauri]] expressed concern about the spread of the virus and its effect on the championship. Both teams are based in Italy, which has suffered [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|one of the worst outbreaks of the virus]] outside China,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148478/ferrari-wants-assurances-over-coronavirus-from-f1 |title=Ferrari wants assurances over coronavirus from F1 before travel |last=Noble |first=Jonathan |date=28 February 2020 |website=[[Autosport|Autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229014941/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148478/ferrari-wants-assurances-over-coronavirus-from-f1|archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148508/tost-unfair-if-australia-goes-ahead-without-all-teams |title=Tost: Unfair if Australia goes ahead without all F1 teams |last=Noble |first=Jonathan |date=2 March 2020 |website=[[Autosport|Autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303042841/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148508/tost-unfair-if-australia-goes-ahead-without-all-teams|archive-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> and so both Ferrari and AlphaTauri were therefore concerned over the ability of their staff to leave a quarantine zone that was established in northern Italy. [[Ross Brawn]], the managing director of the sport, announced that Grands Prix would not go ahead if a team were blocked from entering a host nation, but that events could go ahead if a team voluntarily chose not to enter a host nation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51727401 |title=Coronavirus: F1 will not hold race in country preventing teams entering |last=Benson |first=Andrew |date=4 March 2020 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134810/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51727401|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Australian Grand Prix|Australian]] and [[Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grands Prix]] were cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51849163 |title=Coronavirus: Australian Grand Prix called off |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"NEDMONESP\"/> The cancellation of the Monaco Grand Prix meant that 2020 would mark the first time since {{F1|1954}} that the race has not been held. The [[Azerbaijan Grand Prix|Azerbaijan]], [[Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain]], [[Chinese Grand Prix|Chinese]], [[Canadian Grand Prix|Canadian]], [[Dutch Grand Prix|Dutch]], [[Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish]] and [[Vietnam Grand Prix|Vietnam Grands Prix]] were postponed.<ref name=\"NEDMONESP\">{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.dutch-spanish-and-monaco-grands-prix-postponed.5CggooJeHoDchKkFehkrkY.html |title=Dutch, Spanish and Monaco Grands Prix postponed |website=formula1.com |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"spectators\">{{cite web |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/08/no-spectators-for-bahrain-grand-prix/ |title=No spectators for Bahrain Grand Prix |last=Chapman |first=Simon |date=8 March 2020 |website=Speedcafe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-13/f1-grand-prix-in-china-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-fears/11960614 |title=Coronavirus fears force the postponement of the F1 Grand Prix in China in April |work=abc.net.au |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=13 February 2020 |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CAN postponed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.canadian-grand-prix-organisers-announce-postponement-of-2020-race.7rkpGKnxnRQVe6uPcZSRbP.html|title=Canadian Grand Prix organisers announce postponement of 2020 race|website=formula1.com|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The summer break shut down period\u2014which includes mandatory factory closures as a cost-cutting measure\u2014was also brought forward from August to March and April and was extended to three weeks, allowing for postponed races to be held in August.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.f1-summer-shutdown-brought-forward-in-response-to-coronavirus-outbreak.5a4PM49x3Rs3WKMmxfUIO8.html |title=F1 summer shutdown brought forward in response to coronavirus outbreak |last= |first= |date=18 March 2020 |website=Formula1.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe sport had planned to overhaul its technical regulations for the {{F1|2021}} championship in one of the largest changes in its seventy-year history. The pandemic prompted these changes to be postponed until {{F1|2022}}, with teams required to enter their {{F1|2020}} cars in the 2021 championship to minimise the financial stress placed on the teams.<ref name=\"19 chassis\">{{cite news |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/20/formula-1s-new-regulations-delayed-until-2022/ |title=Formula 1's new regulations delayed until 2022 |first=Daniel |last=Herrero |work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]] |publisher=[[Speedcafe]] |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRecently,{{when|date=March 2020}} some Formula One drivers have entered a virtual version of the [[Australian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DG1cFm3dsaU |title=Veloce Esports's NotAusGP |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Bahrain Grand Prix]] <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vVLTdi4BtPE |title=Veloce Esports's NotTheBahGP |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QwcRDOjgfkE |title=F1 Bahrain Virtual Grand Prix |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The races are hosted by [[Jean-\u00c9ric Vergne]]'s Veloce Esports and F!. The online races are contested by current and former F1 drivers, like [[Lando Norris]], [[Nicholas Latifi]], [[Stoffel Vandoorne]], [[Esteban Guti\u00e9rrez]], [[Nico H\u00fclkenberg]], [[Johnny Herbert]] and [[Martin Brundle]], as well as celebrities and other sportsmen.\n\n====Formula 2 and Formula 3====\nThe [[Bahrain International Circuit|Bahrain]], [[Circuit Zandvoort|Zandvoort]] and [[Circuit de Barcelona|Barcelona]] rounds of the [[2020 FIA Formula 2 Championship|FIA Formula 2]] and [[2020 FIA Formula 3 Championship|Formula 3 Championships]]\u2014a series of races for junior drivers that run in support of Formula 1 events\u2014were postponed when the Bahrain, Dutch and Spanish Grands Prix were postponed.<ref name=\"BHR postponed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2020/03_March/FIA-Formula-2-and-FIA-Formula-3-Championships-Round-1-in-Bahrain-postponed/ |title=FIA Formula 2 and FIA Formula 3 Championships Round 1 in Bahrain postponed \u2013 Formula 2 |website=fiaformula2.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ZANBARMON\">{{cite news |url=https://www.fiaformula2.com/Latest/53FNxDGggZW5n65yl8aFpB/fia-formula-2-and-fia-formula-3-championships-may-races-and-tests-postponed |title=FIA Formula 2 and FIA Formula 3 Championships May races and tests postponed |work=fiaformula2.com |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Circuit de Monaco|Monaco]] Formula 2 round was cancelled when the Monaco Grand Prix was cancelled and the [[Baku City Circuit|Baku]] round postponed when the Azerbaijan Grand Prix was postponed;<ref name=\"ZANBARMON\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fiaformula2.com/Latest/3jBJqgLEiIY3w7fOsUwScE/fia-f2-round-in-baku-postponed-as-coronavirus-outbreak-continues |title=FIA Formula 2 round in Baku postponed as Coronavirus outbreak continues |work=fiaformula2.com |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Formula 3 had not been scheduled to race in Monaco or Azerbaijan.\n\n===Formula E===\nThe [[Formula E]] championship for electric cars initially responded to the pandemic by postponing the [[Rome ePrix|Rome]] and [[Sanya ePrix]]. Planned races in [[Paris ePrix|Paris]], [[Jakarta ePrix|Jakarta]] and [[Seoul ePrix|Seoul]] were also postponed, prompting organisers to postpone the entire season by two months.<ref name=Sanya>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/fe-china-sanya-eprix-coronavirus/4679553/amp/ |title=Formula E postpones China race amid virus outbreak |first=Alex |last=Kalinauckas |date=2 February 2020|access-date=2 February 2020 |website=motorsport.com}}</ref><ref name=Rome>{{cite news |url=https://www.fiaformulae.com/NEWS/2020/March/rome-eprix-update-march-2020?utm_source=FormulaETwitter&utm_mediumSocialPost&utm_campaign=rome&utm_source=FormulaETwitter&utm_mediumSocialPost&utm_campaign=rome |date=6 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020 |website=fiaformulae.com |title=Statement on the 2020 Rome E-Prix}}</ref><ref name=ParisAndSeoul>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/coronavirus-suspend-season-two-months/4740500/ |first1=Charles |last1=Bradley |title=Formula E set to suspend 2019\u201320 season for two months |website=motorsport.com |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===GT World Challenge Europe===\nThe 3 Hours of Monza round of the [[2020 GT World Challenge Europe Endurance Cup]], scheduled for 19 April, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/gt/news/148594/gtwce-opener-in-italy-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus |title=GT World Challenge Europe Monza opener cancelled due to coronavirus |first=Gary |last=Watkins |website=Autosport.com |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===IndyCar===\nThe [[IndyCar Series]] initially announced on 12 March that it would hold the [[Firestone Grand Prix of St. Petersburg|Grand Prix of St. Petersburg]] \u2014 the opening race of the [[2020 IndyCar Series|2020 season]] \u2014 behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/12/indycar-st-pete-to-run-behind-closed-doors-condensed-schedule/ |title=IndyCar St Pete to run behind closed doors; condensed schedule |date=12 March 2020 |website=RACER |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March, the series announced that it would cancel all races through at least the end of April, including St. Petersburg, [[Honda Indy Grand Prix of Alabama|Alabama]], [[Grand Prix of Long Beach|Long Beach]], and [[AutoNation IndyCar Challenge|Austin]]. IndyCar intended to begin the season with the traditional \"Month of May\" races at [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]], including the [[GMR Grand Prix]] (held on IMS's road course configuration), and the 104th running of the [[Indianapolis 500]] on its traditional [[Memorial Day]] weekend scheduling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/13/indycar-cancels-st-pete-first-four-races/ |title=IndyCar cancels St Pete, first four races |date=13 March 2020 |website=RACER |language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, IndyCar announced that it would tentatively delay the beginning of the season to the end of May (beginning with the [[Detroit Grand Prix (IndyCar)|Detroit Grand Prix]] on 30 and 31 May) by postponing the two Indianapolis races to later in the season. The GMR Grand Prix will join the [[NASCAR Cup Series]]' [[Brickyard 400]] weekend, as part of a double-header with the [[NASCAR Xfinity Series|Xfinity Series]]' [[Pennzoil 150]] on the [[Independence Day (United States)|Fourth of July]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/26/indianapolis-motor-speedway-nascar-indycar-july-4-doubleheader/ |title=Indy road course set for July 4 NASCAR-IndyCar doubleheader |date=26 March 2020 |website=NASCAR.com |language=en-US|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/motor/2020/03/27/tony-stewart-attempt-four-races-during-brickyard-weekend/2924343001/ |title=Could Tony Stewart attempt four races during the Brickyard weekend? 'Get me the good rides' |website=Indianapolis Star |language=en|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> The Indianapolis 500 was postponed to 23 August\u2014marking the first time in history that it has not been held in May. The Grand Prix of St. Petersburg was reinstated as the planned season finale, with a date to be determined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/motor/2020/03/26/indycar-calendar-undergoes-massive-overhaul/2918583001/ |title=IndyCar calendar undergoes massive overhaul in response to coronavirus |website=Indianapolis Star |language=en|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 6 April, IndyCar once again postponed the start of the season, scrapping the Detroit Grand Prix, but converting the [[Iowa 300|Iowa]] and [[IndyCar Monterey Grand Prix|Laguna Seca]] weekends to double-headers with two races each, and adding a second Indianapolis Motor Speedway road course race on 3 October\u2014the [[Harvest Auto Racing Classic|Harvest Grand Prix]]\u2014which will be a support race for the [[2020 Intercontinental GT Challenge|Intercontinental GT Challenge]]'s Indianapolis 8 Hour, and may serve as the season finale if the St. Petersburg race does not come to fruition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/motor/2020/04/06/indycar-cancels-detroit-but-adds-races-ims-iowa-and-laguna-seca/2953930001/|title=IndyCar's latest schedule change: three races added, including one at IMS; Detroit canceled|last=Brown|first=Nathan|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIndyCar formed the IndyCar iRacing Challenge, with its drivers racing against one another on the ''[[iRacing]]'' [[racing simulation]] game.<ref>{{cite web |last=Eubanks |first=Michael |url=https://motorsports.nbcsports.com/2020/03/28/indycar-iracing-challenge-drivers-first-virtual-race-at-watkins-glen/ |title=What drivers said after IndyCar's iRacing opener at Watkins Glen |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===MotoGP===\nThe [[MotoGP|MotoGP World Championship]] cancelled the opening round of the 2020 championship in [[2020 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar]]. The [[Moto2]] and [[Moto3]] support categories raced in the country, as the teams were already in Qatar before the quarantine measures were put in place. Planned events in Thailand, the United States, and Argentina were also postponed, but were later rescheduled to 4 October, 15 November and 22 November respectively. The races at Jerez, Le Mans, Mugello, and Catalunya were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fim-live.com/en/article/motogp-class-cancelled-at-the-grand-prix-of-qatar/ |title=MOTOGP CLASS CANCELLED AT THE GRAND PRIX OF QATAR |last= |first= |date=1 March 2020 |website=FIM-live.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NASCAR===\nPrior to the [[2020 Folds of Honor QuikTrip 500]], part of the [[2020 NASCAR Cup Series]], [[NASCAR]] announced that no fans would be permitted to attend the race; this event, along with the [[Dixie Vodka 400]] at [[Homestead-Miami Speedway]], were later postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/12/nascar-statement-atlanta-homestead-race-schedules/ |title=NASCAR statement on Atlanta and Homestead {{!}} NASCAR|date=12 March 2020|website=Official Site Of NASCAR|language=en-US|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, NASCAR announced that all race events through 3 May were postponed, however they still intend to run all 36 races for the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/16/nascar-schedule-update-statement-race-coronavirus/ |title=NASCAR statement: All race events through May 3 postponed {{!}} NASCAR|date=16 March 2020|website=NASCAR.com|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nNASCAR subsequently began to organize invitational [[eSports]] events on ''iRacing'', featuring current and past NASCAR drivers, officially known as the [[eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series]]. [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Sports]] also picked up broadcasts of these events to provide filler content for [[Fox Sports 1]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a31789600/fox-sports-to-air-iracing-event-featuring-full-field-of-nascar-drivers/ |title=Fox Sports to air iRacing event featuring full field of NASCAR drivers |last=Weaver |first=Matt |date=19 March 2020 |website=Autoweek |language=en-US|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Endurance Championship===\nThe [[1000 Miles of Sebring]] race was cancelled.<ref name=\"Sebring\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailysportscar.com/2020/03/12/wec-set-to-cancel-sebring-trip.html |title=WEC Cancels Sebring Race (Updated) |date=12 March 2020 |work=Marshall Pruett |publisher=Dailysportscar.com |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[6 Hours of Spa-Francorchamps]] and the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] were both postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/16/wec-postpones-spa/ |title=WEC postpones Spa |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/motorsport/51946353 |title=Coronavirus: Le Mans 24 Hours postponed until September |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Rally Championship===\nThe 2020 running of [[Rally Argentina]], [[Rally Italia Sardegna]] and [[Rally Portugal]] were postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/148648/coronavirus-forces-rally-argentina-to-be-postponed |title=Coronavirus forces WRC Rally Argentina to be postponed |first=Nick |last=Garton |work=[[Autosport|autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]] |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/148778/wrc-season-hit-by-more-postponements |title=WRC 2020 season hit by more rally postponements due to coronavirus |first=Pablo |last=Elizalde |work=[[Autosport|autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]] |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Rally Mexico]] was shortened to allow competitors time to pack their equipment up and return to their headquarters in Europe before a series of travel bans were implemented.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/15/rally-mexico-shortened-by-a-day-due-to-travel-restrictions/ |title=Rally Mexico shortened by a day due to travel restrictions |first=Daniel |last=Herrero |work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]] |publisher=[[Speedcafe]] |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 World Rally Championship-2|World Rally Championship-2]], [[2020 World Rally Championship-3|World Rally Championship-3]] and [[2020 Junior World Rally Championship|Junior World Rally Championship]] support categories were also affected by the postponements.\n\n===World Rallycross Championship===\nThe opening rounds of the [[2020 FIA World Rallycross Championship]] in [[World RX of Barcelona|Barcelona]] and [[World RX of Portugal|Portugal]] were postponed.<ref name=\"BarcelonaPostponed\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/world-rx/news/world-rallycross-opener-barcelona-coronavirus/4746950/ |title=World RX postpones Barcelona opener over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |last=Ridge |first=Hal |publisher=motorsport.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PortugalPostponed\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/world-rx/news/portugal-second-round-postponed-coronavirus/4771259/ |title=World RX's second round also postponed due to coronavirus |date=20 March 2020 |last=Ridge |first=Hal |publisher=motorsport.com |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Touring Car Cup===\nThe opening rounds of the [[2020 World Touring Car Cup]] in [[FIA WTCC Race of Hungary|Hungary]] and [[FIA WTCC Race of Germany|Germany]] were cancelled.<ref name=\"hun2020cancellation\">{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/wtcr/wtcr-race-of-hungary-statement_sto7702776/story.shtml |title=WTCR Race of Hungary statement |date=13 March 2020 |work=Eurosport |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/nurburgring-24-hours-race-weekend-postponed-september/ |title=N\u00fcrburgring 24 Hours race weekend postponed to September |date=17 March 2020 |work=TouringCarTimes |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fiawtcr.com/update-wtcr-race-of-germany/ |title=Update: WTCR Race of Germany |date=17 March 2020 |work=FIA WTCR {{!}} World Touring Car Cup|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> The four races that would have been held across the two rounds were rescheduled for other rounds.\n\n===Motorcycle road racing===\nThe 2020 [[Isle of Man TT]] and [[Scottish Six Days Trial]] were cancelled.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20200316235253/https://www.iomtt.com/news/2020/03/16/tt-2020-cancelled Isle of Mann Government announces cancellation of 2020 TT Races] Isle of Mann TT 16 March 2020</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.obantimes.co.uk/2020/03/16/scottish-six-days-trial-and-pre-65-trial-cancelled-due-to-covid-19-outbreak-2/ |title=Scottish Six Days Trial and Pre '65 Trial cancelled due to Covid-19 outbreak |date=16 March 2020 |website=The Oban Times |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/highlands/2077336/coronavirus-lochabers-scottish-six-days-trial-event-cancelled/ |title=Coronavirus: Lochaber's Scottish Six Days Trial event cancelled |first=Stuart |last=Findlay |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The 2020 [[North West 200]] event was postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Re the Postponement of the 2020 fonaCAB and Nicholl Oils North West 200 |url=https://www.northwest200.org/statement-re-the-postponement-of-the-2020-fonacab-and-nicholl-oils-north-west-200/ |website=northwest200.org |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===British national-level championships===\nAll British motorsport, including the [[2020 British Touring Car Championship|British Touring Car Championship]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/btcc-postpones-opening-three-rounds-coronavirus-policy-change/ |title=BTCC postpones opening three rounds after coronavirus policy change |date=17 March 2020 |website=Touring Car Times|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> the [[2020 British GT Championship|British GT Championship]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.britishgt.com/news/590/british-gt-season-opener-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak |title=British GT season opener postponed due to coronavirus outbreak |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=britishgt.com |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Britcar]] [[2020 Britcar Endurance Championship|Endurance]] and [[2020 Britcar Trophy Championship|Trophy Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.britcar-endurance.com/newsRead.php?link=317&page=0 |title=Opening Rounds Postponed |website=Britcar Endurance |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> were postoned until July 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/national/news/148772/uk-motorsport-on-hold-until-july-due-to-covid19 |title=UK motorsport on hold until July to contain spread of coronavirus |first=Stefan Mackley, Paul |last=Lawrence |website=Autosport.com |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Monster trucks===\n[[Monster Jam]] events in multiple localities were affected. Shows in [[Austin, Texas]], [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], [[Columbia, South Carolina]], [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], [[Columbus, Ohio]], [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], and [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] were postponed; and a show in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.monsterjam.com/en-US/event-basic-page |title=Event basic page &#124; Monster Jam |website=www.monsterjam.com |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hot Wheels|Hot Wheels Monster Trucks Live]] postponed a show in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whas11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/hot-wheels-monster-trucks-postponed/417-fe68c6a7-fba6-46f3-b913-d4ab3ad5cc99 |title=Hot Wheels Monster Trucks Live postpones shows this weekend |website=WHAS11 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMonster X Tour postponed its World Finals event in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://alohastadium.hawaii.gov/main/monster-x-tour/ |title=MONSTER X TOUR WORLD FINALS 2020 \u2013 RESCHEDULED JULY 25\u201326 |website=alohastadium.hawaii.gov |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2020, [[Monster Jam World Finals XXI|World Finals XXI]], scheduled to take place 2\u20133 May 2020, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Monster Jam World Finals 2020 Cancelled |date=27 March 2020 |url=https://www.monsterjam.com/en-US/2020-worldfinals-cancelled |publisher=[[Monster Jam]]|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Radio-controlled racing===\nDespite taking place in the second half of the year, all 4 blocks (representing Asia ([[Far East Model Car Association|FEMCA]]), North America ([[Remotely Operated Auto Racers|ROAR]]), Europe ([[European Federation of Radio Operated Model Automobiles|EFRA]]) and the rest of the world ([[Fourth Association of Model Auto Racing|FAMAR]])) and the [[International Federation of Model Auto Racing|IFMAR committee]] have agreed to postpone all remaining [[IFMAR World Championships]] ([[2020 IFMAR ISTC World Championship|1:10 Electric Touring Car]] in Heemstede, Netherlands); [[2020 IFMAR 1:8 IC Off-Road World Championship|1:8 IC Off-Road]] in Cianorte, Brasil and [[2020 IFMAR 1:10 IC Touring Car World Championship|1:10 IC Touring Car]] in Brisbane, Australia) to an alternative date, possibly early 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverc.com/news/announcements/22360-All_2020_IFMAR_World_Championships_Postponed/ |title=All 2020 IFMAR World Championships Postponed |publisher=LiveRC.com |date= |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.redrc.net/2020/03/ifmar-call-off-2020-season/ |title=IFMAR call off 2020 season |publisher=Red RC |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> This was the first postponement since 2001 when the events of the [[September 11 attacks]] caused the [[IFMAR 1:10 Electric Off-Road World Championship|1:10 Electric Off-Road Worlds]] to be moved to May the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverc.com/news/special_features/8137-FLASHBACK_FRIDAY:_Brian_Kinwald_leads_Team_Losi's_Golden_Age/|title=FLASHBACK FRIDAY: Brian Kinwald leads Team Losi's Golden Age|first=Aaron|last=Waldron|website=www.liverc.com}}</ref>\n\n===TCR Touring Car Racing===\nAlmost all [[TCR Touring Car|TCR]] championships have been affected by the outbreak, resulting in complete calendar changes, race postponements and cancellations. These include: [[2020 TCR Australia Touring Car Series|TCR Australia]], [[2020 TCR Asia Pacific Cup|TCR Asia Pacific Cup]], [[ADAC TCR Germany Touring Car Championship|TCR Germany]], [[2020 Touring Car Trophy|TCR UK]], [[2020 TCR Japan Touring Car Series|TCR Japan]], [[TCR Italian Series|TCR Italy]], [[2020 STCC TCR Scandinavia Touring Car Championship|TCR Scandinavia]], [[2020 TCR Denmark Touring Car Series|TCR Denmark]], [[2020 TCR Asia Series|TCR Asia]], [[TCR China Touring Car Championship|TCR China]], [[2020 TCR Europe Touring Car Series|TCR Europe]] and [[2020 TC America Series|TC America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/13/australian-grand-prix-support-categories-called-off/|title=Australian Grand Prix and support categories called off|date=13 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/18/motorsport-australia-suspends-championships-notice/|title=Motorsport Australia suspend championships until further notice|date=18 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/10/tcr-germany-announce-revised-calendar/|title=TCR Germany announce revised calendar|date=10 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/16/oschersleben-pre-season-test-season-opener-cancelled/|title=Oschersleben pre-season test cancelled and season opener postponed|date=16 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/tcr-uk-confirm-postponed-season-start/|title=TCR UK confirm postponed season start|date=17 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/06/tcr-uk-announce-scaled-back-calendar/|title=TCR UK announce scaled back calendar|date=6 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/18/tcr-japan-season-opener-postponed-pre-season-test-goes-ahead/|title=TCR Japan season opener postponed while pre-season test goes ahead|date=18 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/31/autopolis-race-weekend-postponed-due-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=Autopolis race weekend postponed due to coronavirus pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/08/monza-season-opener-postponed-moved-misano/|title=Monza season opener postponed and moved to Misano|date=8 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/03/stcc-tcr-scandinavia-confirm-postponed-season-start/|title=STCC TCR Scandinavia confirm postponed season start|date=3 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/19/tcr-denmark-season-opener-moved-two-weeks/|title=TCR Denmark season opener moved two weeks|date=19 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/24/aarhus-street-race-postponed-2021-pre-season-test-day-moved/|title=Aarhus street race postponed until 2021, pre-season test day moved|date=24 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/09/tcr-denmark-consider-options-revised-2020-calendar/|title=TCR Denmark consider options for revised 2020 calendar|date=9 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/21/tcr-asia-announce-postponed-season-premiere/|title=TCR Asia announce postponed season premiere|date=21 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/11/tcr-china-issue-revised-2020-calendar-following-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=TCR China issue revised 2020 calendar following coronavirus outbreak|date=11 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/04/01/tcr-europe-issue-revised-calendar-red-bull-ring-removed/|title=TCR Europe issue revised calendar with Red Bull Ring removed|date=1 April 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/13/st-petersburg-race-weekend-called-off-coronavirus/|title=St Petersburg race weekend called off over coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Poker==\nAs of 18 March most casinos and other gaming venues worldwide have been closed indefinitely, and many upcoming live [[poker tournament]]s have been either postponed, cancelled, or (in jurisdictions where currently permitted) moved to an [[online poker|online platform]]. Tournaments originally scheduled to be played live are now being played online, including the 2020 [[Irish Poker Open]].\n\nThe pandemic has resulted in a massive increase in online poker traffic. It is believed to have directed both professional and recreational players who normally prefer live poker to online platforms due to the indefinite closure of most casinos and other live gaming venues worldwide, with even many [[Underground poker|unlicensed venues]] shutting down. In addition, the sudden dearth of live entertainment options due to the widespread disruption of the sports and entertainment schedules around the world is believed to have resulted in more than the usual number of casual players turning to online poker as an alternative. Many operators reported traffic of double or more the previous volume, depending on the time of day.\n\n==Rodeo==\nThe 2020 [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] was cancelled after a festival attendee was diagnosed positive with the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.click2houston.com/rodeo/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-amid-growing-concerns-over-coronavirus/ |title=Houston Rodeo canceled; coronavirus patient attended Rodeo cookoff in February |last=Barker |first=Daniela Sternitzky-Di Napoli, Aaron |date=12 March 2020 |website=KPRC |language=en|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rowing==\nFour [[Rowing at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|Olympic qualification regattas]] were cancelled, including the final qualification event scheduled to be held in [[Lucerne]], [[Switzerland]], from 17 to 19 May. All three events of the 2020 [[World Rowing Cup]] were also cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Joint Decisions related to the impact of the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) on remaining Olympic and Paralympic qualification events |url=http://www.worldrowing.com/news/joint-decisions-related-the-impact-the-novel-coronavirus-covid-remaining-olympic-and-paralympic-qualification-events |website=World Rowing |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[The Boat Race 2020]], due to take place on the [[River Thames]] in [[London]] on 29 March, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-03-16/the-boat-race-has-been-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus/ |publisher=ITV |title=The Boat Race has been cancelled due to Coronavirus |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby league==\nThe Australian/New Zealand [[National Rugby League]] was scheduled to continue with no spectators permitted in the stadiums however this was abandoned after round two.\n\nFor the first time in the competition's history, the entire season was suspended indefinitely on 23 March 2020,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/03/23/nrl-suspends-competition-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/ |title=NRL suspends competition due to coronavirus pandemic |date=23 March 2020 |work=National Rugby League |author=Dan Walsh}}</ref> and if the season cannot be restarted by 1 September, it will be abandoned with no premiership awarded.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/03/24/nrl-tells-clubs-season-needs-to-start-by-september-to-be-salvaged/ |title=NRL tells clubs season must restart by September to be salvaged |publisher=NRL.com |first=Dan |last=Walsh |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSuper League and the Rugby Football League suspended the season until 3 April as a result of the spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/51911290 |title=Coronavirus: Rugby Football League suspends season until 3 April |date=16 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=16 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby union==\nAt the end of February and start of March, the [[2020 Six Nations Championship]] saw all games against [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]] postponed due to the worsening situation in that country,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51749254 |title=Coronavirus: England's Six Nations games against Italy postponed |date=5 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> with games against the [[Scotland women's national rugby union team|Scotland women's team]] also cancelled as one of the players tested positive and the team went into isolation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51777621 |title=Women's Six Nations: Scotland v France postponed after home player tests positive for coronavirus |date=6 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> By 13 March, the competition had been suspended.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907 |title=Six Nations: Wales v Scotland off because of coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> On 12 March, the [[Pro14]] European rugby competition was suspended,.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51858815 |title=Coronavirus: Pro14 suspended indefinitely due to coronavirus |date=12 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Super Rugby]], two fixtures of Japanese team [[Sunwolves]] had been moved to Australia from Japan, while Australia announced on 12 March that beginning in the next round of fixtures, all matches held in Australia would be played with no spectators, but otherwise continue as normal. However, on 14 March, New Zealand (who fields five teams in the competition) announced that it will require 14 days self-isolation for any person that arrives in the country from outside of the Pacific Islands, regardless of origin and including New Zealand citizens. League organizer [[SANZAAR]] stated that it was evaluating the impact of this restriction,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/rugby/super-rugby/super-rugby-coronavirus-news-2020-new-zealand-government/news-story/794c8a43de0a3806ea699a7503063461 |title=Super Rugby season on verge of shutdown after NZ restrictions |date=14 March 2020 |website=Fox Sports |language=en-AU|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au:443/news/2020/03/13/corona-virus-international-updates |title=Coronavirus: How rugby has been affected around the world |website=www.rugby.com.au |language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au:443/news/2020/03/12/super-rugby-waratahs-coronavirus |title=LOCKOUT: Coronavirus forces rugby behind closed doors next week but fans welcome at weekend |website=www.rugby.com.au |language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> and ultimately announced later in the day that the season would be suspended following the completion of the weekend's fixtures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/rugby-union/all-super-rugby-matches-to-be-cancelled-after-sunday-s-fixtures-20200314-p54a4u.html |title=All Super Rugby matches to be cancelled after Sunday's fixtures |last=Decent |first=Tom |date=14 March 2020 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, [[Major League Rugby]] in the United States suspended its third season for 30 days,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.majorleague.rugby/news/major-league-rugby-suspends-2020-season-for-30-days/ |title=MAJOR LEAGUE RUGBY SUSPENDS 2020 SEASON FOR 30 DAYS |website=Major League Rugby |language=en-US|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> but on 18 March, organizers announced that it will suspend until 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americasrugbynews.com/2020/03/18/major-league-rugby-to-suspend-until-2021/ |title=Major League Rugby to suspend until 2021 |date=19 March 2020 |website=Americas Rugby News |language=en-US|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Shooting==\nThe 2020 [[ISSF World Cup]], which was to commence on 15 March in New Delhi, was postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/virus-hits-indian-sports/articleshow/74519560.cms |title=Virus hits Indian sports |work=Economic Times |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref> The Olympic Test Event in Tokyo, originally scheduled for April 2020, was also cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.issf-sports.org/news.ashx?newsid |title=Test Event \"READY STEADY TOKYO\" |publisher=International Shooting Sport Federation |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Short track speed skating==\nThe 2020 [[World Short Track Speed Skating Championships]] in Seoul, South Korea scheduled 13\u201315 March were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://speedskating.ca/news-and-info/news/isu-officially-cancels-world-short-track-championships-in-south-korea-due-to-coronavirus |title=ISU Officially Cancels World Short Track Championships in South Korea due to Coronavirus &#124; Speed Skating Canada |website=speedskating.ca |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> The [[International Skating Union]] announced they were trying to reschedule the tournament to late 2020 at the beginning of the 2020\u201321 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2325012|title=ISU wil afgelast WK shorttrack later dit jaar alsnog op kalender zetten|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Snooker==\nThe [[2020 Gibraltar Open]] and its qualifying rounds took place from 11 to 15 March.  For the first day, there was a limit of 100 spectators per session.  On the remaining days, there were no spectators.  A significant number of players withdrew, and there was a shortage of referees, with some early matches played without referees.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bizarre times at Gibraltar Open as games played without referees and player brings wrong cue |publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |first=Phil |last=Haigh |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/gibraltar-open-chaos-12400612/}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Tour Championship]], originally scheduled for 17 to 22 March, was postponed until 21 July.\n\nThe 2020 [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]], originally scheduled for 30 March to 5 April, was indefinitely postponed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: China Open in Beijing postponed |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/51325726 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=31 January 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020|}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 World Snooker Championship]], originally scheduled 18 April to 4 May, has been postponed,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/51964887 |title=Coronavirus: World Snooker Championship at Crucible postponed |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> tentatively until July or August.\n\nThe [[2020 World Women's Snooker Championship]], originally scheduled 22 to 27 June, has been postponed. \n<ref>{{cite web |title=World Women's Championship Postponed |url=https://wst.tv/world-womens-championship-postponed/ |date=31 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |publisher=[[World Snooker Tour]]}}</ref>\n\n==Squash==\nThe 2020 [[European Squash Individual Championships]], scheduled to take place in [[Eindhoven]], the Netherlands from 29 April to 2 May are cancelled.<ref name=\"nu.nl\"/>\n\n==Surfing==\nThe 2020 [[World Surf League]], which was due to start in Australia on 26 March, is on hold until at least June. The first event of the season, the [[Quiksilver Pro Gold Coast|Corona Open Gold Coast]], was cancelled, while the second and third events, the [[Rip Curl Pro|Rip Curl Pro Bells Beach]] and [[Margaret River Pro]], were postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=WSL Cancels All Events In March |url=https://www.worldsurfleague.com/posts/449880/wsl-cancels-all-events-in-march |website=World Surf League |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=WSL Cancels Or Postpones Events Through May |url=https://www.worldsurfleague.com/posts/450379/wsl-cancels-or-postpones-events-through-may |website=World Surf League |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 ISA World Surfing Games]], scheduled to be held from 9 to 17 May in [[El Salvador]], was postponed. It is hoped that it will take place during the second half of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=ISA Postpones Surf City El Salvador ISA World Surfing Games Until Further Notice |url=https://www.isasurf.org/isa-postpones-surf-city-el-salvador-isa-world-surfing-games-until-further-notice/ |website=International Surfing Association |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Swimming==\nThe [[YMCA]] [[Short course|Short Course]] Nationals swim meet is canceled in the United States for the first time since 1947.<ref>{{cite web |title=YMCA Short Course Nationals Canceled For First Time Since 1947 |url=https://swimswam.com/ymca-short-course-nationals-canceled-for-first-time-since-1947/ |website=Swim Swam |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=Swim Swam |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Table tennis==\nThe [[2020 World Team Table Tennis Championships]], which was scheduled to be held from 22\u201329 March in [[Busan]], [[South Korea]], was postponed to 27 September\u20134 October.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 World Table Tennis Championships postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/02/25/2020-world-table-tennis-championships-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=25 February 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New dates for 2020 World Table Tennis Championships|url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/04/07/new-dates-2020-world-table-tennis-championships/|website=ITTF |date=7 April 2020 |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 ITTF-ATTU Asian Cup]] was scheduled to be held from 28 February to 1 March in [[Hainan]], [[China]], but was postponed until later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Postponement of 2020 Asian Cup |url=http://www.attu.org/en/news/1057 |website=ATTU |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFive events on the [[2020 ITTF World Tour]] have also been postponed, including the [[China Open (table tennis)|China Open]] and the [[Japan Open (table tennis)|Japan Open]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 ITTF World Tour Japan Open postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/03/10/2020-ittf-world-tour-japan-open-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hong Kong and China Opens postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/03/20/hong-kong-china-opens-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Four [[Table tennis at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|Olympic qualifying events]], scheduled to be held in April, were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=ITTF consider Tokyo 2020 Olympic qualification measures after events postponed |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1092033/ittf-tokyo-2020-qualification-plans |website=Inside The Games |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis==\nIn one of the first major U.S. sport cancellations of the pandemic, the [[2020 BNP Paribas Open]] [[tennis]] tournament in [[Indian Wells, California]] was postponed on 8 March 2020 as a precautionary measure, with organizers stating they planned to seek a new date.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rothenberg|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/sports/coronavirus-indian-wells-canceled.html|title=Indian Wells Tennis Tournament Canceled Because of Coronavirus Outbreak|date=2020-03-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|last2=Clarey|first2=Christopher|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/columnist/dan-wolken/2020/03/08/coronavirus-indian-wells-cancellation-potential-sports-turning-point/4997987002/|title=Opinion: Indian Wells cancellation could be turning point for sports and coronavirus|last=Wolken|first=Dan|website=USA Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On 12 March, [[List of mayors of Miami|Mayor of Miami]] [[Carlos A. Gim\u00e9nez]] ordered the cancellation of the [[Miami Open (tennis)|Miami Open]] pursuant to the state of emergency in [[Miami-Dade County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/tennis/story/_/id/28891183/miami-open-canceled-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Miami Open becomes latest top tourney canceled|date=2020-03-12|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, the [[Association of Tennis Professionals|ATP]] announced that in response to the aforementioned cancellations among others, they would suspend events for at least six weeks. The [[International Tennis Federation]] also suspended play through at least 20 April, and the [[Women's Tennis Association|WTA]] cancelled [[WTA Tour]] events through 12 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/tennis/story/_/id/28891268/atp-suspends-men-tennis-tournaments-six-weeks|title=ATP, ITF announce six-week shutdown over virus|date=2020-03-12|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> On 16 March, the WTA suspended play through May 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/tennis/story/_/id/28910506/wta-suspends-tour-2-due-coronavirus|title=WTA suspends tour until May 2 due to virus|date=2020-03-16|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the start of the [[2020 French Open]] was postponed from 24 May to 20 September, and the ATP and WTA jointly announced that their suspension of play had been extended through through 7 June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/tennis/story/_/id/28922126/tennis-tours-suspend-play-june-7-eliminating-clay-court-circuit|title=ATP, WTA suspend tour play until June 7|date=2020-03-18|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/sports/tennis/french-open-postponed.html |title=The French Open Is Postponed, to the Surprise of the Tours |last=Clarey |first=Christopher |newspaper=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On 1 April, [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] was cancelled for the first time since [[World War II]], while the ATP and WTA announced that their suspension will be extended through 13 July.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atptour.com/en/news/atp-wta-tours-announce-further-suspension-wimbledon|title=ATP & WTA Announce Further Suspension Of Tours|website=ATP Tour|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/tennis/52104196 |title=Wimbledon cancelled due to coronavirus \u2013 where does that leave tennis in 2020? |date=1 April 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=4 April 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Ultimate==\nOn March 24th, the World Flying Disc Federation announced to cancel or postpone all world championships over the next sixth months. This included the World Ultimate and Guts Championships (WUGC), World Junior Ultimate Championships (WJUC) and the World Masters Ultimate Championships (WMUC) due to the rapid spread of coronavirus.\n\nNorth America's national body for ultimate, USA Ultimate, also cancelled all scheduled club and college tournaments as well as the suspension of the semi-professional league, the AUDL, from commencing the 2020 season.\n\n==Volleyball==\nOn 13 March, the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball|International Volleyball Federation]] (FIVB) decided to postpone the Nations League for [[2020 FIVB Volleyball Men's Nations League|men]] (finals scheduled for [[Turin]], Italy) and [[2020 FIVB Volleyball Women's Nations League|women]] until after the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] caused by the outbreak of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fivb.com/en/about/news/fivb-announces-changes-to-events-calendar?id=90648 |title=FIVB announces changes to events calendar |date=13 March 2020 |website=FIVB|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Water polo==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2020 Women's Water Polo Olympic Qualification Tournament]] was scheduled to take place in [[Trieste]], [[Italy]], 8\u201315 March 2020. On 28 February 2020, [[FINA|International Swimming Federation]] (FINA) announced that the tournament would be postponed to 17\u201324 May due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fina.org/news/fina-announcement-fina-womens-water-polo-olympic-games-qualification-tournament |date=28 February 2020 |title=FINA ANNOUNCEMENT: FINA Women's Water Polo Olympic Games Qualification Tournament |publisher=[[FINA]] |website=fina.org |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, FINA announced that several international water polo tournaments would be postponed due to the coronavirus pandemic. The [[2020 Men's Water Polo Olympic Qualification Tournament]] due to take place in [[Rotterdam]], [[Netherlands]], 22\u201329 March, would be postponed to 31 May \u2013 7 June. The [[2020 FINA Men's Water Polo World League]] and [[2020 FINA Women's Water Polo World League]] would be postponed to September\u2013October 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fina.org/news/pr-16-first-meeting-fina-covid-19-taskforce |date=12 March 2020 |title=PR 16 \u2013 First meeting of FINA COVID-19 taskforce |publisher=[[FINA]] |website=fina.org |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n[[2020 Asian Water Polo Championship]], the Asian continental qualification for the [[Water polo at the 2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Olympic water polo tournament]], was scheduled to take place in [[Nur-Sultan]], [[Kazakhstan]], 12\u201316 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://astanatimes.com/2020/01/kazakh-capital-to-host-olympics-water-polo-asian-pre-qualification-tournament/ |first=Nurdana |last=Adylkhanova |date=31 January 2020 |title=Kazakh capital to host Olympics water polo Asian pre-qualification tournament |publisher=Astana Times |website=astanatimes.com |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In late January the event was cancelled as the Kazakh Government suspended all flights and visas from [[China]] due to concerns about the coronavirus outbreak in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/coronavirus-claims-first-tokyo-olympic-victim-2020-asian-water-polo-championships/ |first=Michael |last=Randazzo |date=13 February 2020 |title=Coronavirus Claims First Tokyo Olympic Victim: 2020 Asian Water Polo Championships |publisher=[[Swimming World]] |website=swimmingworldmagazine.com |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In mid-February [[Asia Swimming Federation]] decided to use the final ranking of the [[Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games|2018 Asian Games]] to allocate its continental quotas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://total-waterpolo.com/asian-federation-decides-kazakhstan-and-china-goes-to-tokyo/ |first=Ivan |last=Curcic |date=14 February 2020 |title=Asian Federation decides: Kazakhstan and China go to Tokyo |publisher=Total Waterpolo |website=total-waterpolo.com |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nOn 28 February 2020, [[LEN|European Swimming League]] (LEN) announced that the match of [[2019\u201320 LEN Champions League]] Day 10 between [[Ferencv\u00e1rosi TC (men's water polo)|Ferencv\u00e1ros]] (Hungary) and [[Pro Recco]] (Italy), and the match of [[2019\u201320 LEN Euro Cup]] semifinal between [[Egri VK]] (Hungary) and [[AN Brescia]] (Italy) would be postponed due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.len.eu/?p=16594 |date=28 February 2020 |title=Two matches postponed \u2013 Euro Cup & Champions League |publisher=[[LEN]] |website=len.eu |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2020, LEN announced that all eight matches of 2019\u201320 LEN Champions League Day 11, the second leg of the [[2019\u201320 LEN Euro League Women]] quarter-finals, and the 2020 men's U19 European Championships qualification tournaments would be postponed to later dates due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.len.eu/?p=16631 |date=11 March 2020 |title=LEN postpones upcoming water polo competitions |publisher=[[LEN]] |website=len.eu |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn 11 March 2020, the [[USA Water Polo]] (USAWP) announced that the 2020 ODP Girls National Water Polo Championship would be postponed, and the exhibition matches scheduled to be played on 19\u201321 March 2020 in [[California]] between [[United States men's national water polo team|United States]] and [[Spain men's national water polo team|Spain]] men's national water polo teams would be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usawaterpolo.org/news/2020/3/11/general-2020-odp-girls-national-championship-postponed-usa-mens-national-team-series-with-spain-canceled.aspx |date=11 March 2020 |title=2020 ODP Girls National Championship Postponed; USA Men's National Team Series With Spain Canceled |publisher=[[USA Water Polo]] |website=usawaterpolo.org |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, USAWP announced that the inaugural USA Water Polo Division III Women's National Championship scheduled for 8\u201310 May 2020 in [[Southern California]] would be rescheduled for May 2021; and week three of the 2020 National Water Polo League and the 2020 National League Championship/Fisher Cup would be canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usawaterpolo.org/news/2020/3/16/general-usa-water-polo-announces-the-cancellation-of-multiple-upcoming-events.aspx |date=16 March 2020 |title=USA Water Polo Announces The Cancellation Of Multiple Upcoming Events |publisher=[[USA Water Polo]] |website=usawaterpolo.org |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nOn 16 March 2020, the [[Australian Water Polo]] (WPA) announced that the 2020 [[Australian National Water Polo League]] would be terminated, the 2020 WPA National Championships scheduled to take place in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]] in May would be cancelled, and the 2020 Open Championships (Country and Masters) scheduled to take place in the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]] in May would be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.waterpoloaustralia.com.au/news/covid-19-virus-i-changes-to-national-calendar-/ |date=16 March 2020 |title=COVID-19 virus I Changes to National Calendar |publisher=[[Australian Water Polo]] |website=waterpoloaustralia.com.au |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in sports]]\n[[Category:Sports events cancelled due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:Sports events postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|sports]]\n", "name_user": "Natg 19", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUltimate Fighting Championship:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_games_and_sports"}
{"title_page": "Alan L. Hoffman", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name     = Alan L. Hoffman\n|image    = Alan L. Hoffman official photo.jpeg\n|office         = [[Office of the Vice President of the United States|Deputy Chief of Staff to the Vice President of the United States]]\n| term_start    = January 2009\n| term_end      = November 2012<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/alan-hoffman-1245608</ref>\n| president     = [[Barack Obama]]\n| vicepresident = [[Joe Biden]]\n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = [[Shailagh Murray|Shailagh J. Murray]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20191126234732/https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/GOVMAN-2014-10-06/xml/GOVMAN-2014-10-06-100.xml The United States Government Manual (October 2014), Executive Branch: The President - Office of the Vice President]</ref>\n|birth_name     = Alan Lawrence Hoffman\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1966|04|07}}\n|party          = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education      = [[Lafayette College]] {{small|(BA)}}<br>[[USC Gould School of Law|University of Southern California]] {{small|(MPA, JD)}}\n|spouse         = Lizzie Francis\n}}\n'''Alan Lawrence Hoffman'''<ref>http://members.calbar.ca.gov/fal/Licensee/Detail/158498</ref> (born April 7, 1966)<ref>{{cite book |last=Publishing Company |first=Monitor |date=2001 |title=Congressional Yellow Book: Who's Who in Congress, Including Committees and Key Staff |url= |location= |publisher=Monitor Publishing Company |page= |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> is an American lawyer, government official, and corporate executive who serves as Senior Vice President, Global Public Policy and Government Affairs at [[PepsiCo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=PepsiCo Names Alan Hoffman Senior Vice President, Global Public Policy and Government Affairs|url=http://www.pepsico.com/PressRelease/PepsiCo-Names-Alan-Hoffman-Senior-Vice-President-Global-Public-Policy-and-Govern11142012.html|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref>   Prior to joining PepsiCo, Hoffman served as Deputy [[Chief of Staff to the Vice President of the United States]] [[Joe Biden]] and [[Deputy Assistant to the President]]. While in the Vice President's office, Hoffman worked on a variety of issues including crime, drugs and protecting intellectual property, marking the third time Hoffman had worked for [[Joe Biden]]. Previously, Hoffman served as [[Chief of Staff]] to [[United States Senate|Senator]] Biden from 1998\u20132003 and from 2006-2008 while Biden was running for president.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/erin-medlicott/alan-hoffman-returns-to-w_b_154484.html |title=Erin Medlicott: Alan Hoffman Returns To Washington As VP-Elect Joe Biden's Deputy Chief Of Staff |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2011-05-25|accessdate=2011-06-02}}</ref>\n\n==Life and education==\nHoffman received his [[B.A.]] in [[American Civilization]] from [[Lafayette College]] in [[Easton, Pennsylvania]] and his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] and [[Master of Public Administration|M.P.A.]] from the [[USC Gould School of Law]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lafayette.edu/about/news/2009/09/10/alan-hoffman-%E2%80%9988-manages-daily-workings-of-vice-president-joe-biden%E2%80%99s-office/ |title=Alan Hoffman \u201988 Manages Daily Workings of Vice President Joe Biden\u2019s Office \u00b7 About \u00b7 Lafayette College |publisher=Lafayette.edu |date=2009-09-10 |accessdate=2011-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719230534/http://www.lafayette.edu/about/news/2009/09/10/alan-hoffman-%E2%80%9988-manages-daily-workings-of-vice-president-joe-biden%E2%80%99s-office/ |archive-date=2011-07-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://weblaw.usc.edu/news/assets/docs/USC_2009_LAW_MAGAZINEweb.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://alumni.usc.edu/profiles/alan_hoffman_class_of_91.html |title=Alan Hoffman Class of '91 &#124; USC Alumni Association |publisher=Alumni.usc.edu |accessdate=2011-06-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526025725/http://alumni.usc.edu/profiles/alan_hoffman_class_of_91.html |archivedate=26 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHoffman is married to Lizzie Francis and lives in [[Washington, D.C.]], with their dogs Brinkley and Franklin.\n\n==Career==\nHoffman is credited with helping Biden secure passage of numerous pieces of legislation including the criminal provisions of [[Sarbanes-Oxley]] and legislation closing the gap in sentencing between [[Crack cocaine|crack]] and powder [[cocaine]].<ref>http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CREC-2003-04-11/pdf/CREC-2003-04-11-pt2-PgS5325-4.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CREC-2010-08-05/pdf/CREC-2010-08-05-pt1-PgS6866-2.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after Biden withdrew from the [[2008 United States presidential election|presidential race]], Hoffman was the Senior Vice President for External Relations for the [[University of California]] system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/article/18232 |title=University of California - UC Newsroom &#124; Alan L. Hoffman appointed UC senior vice president for external relations |publisher=Universityofcalifornia.edu |accessdate=2011-06-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720093633/http://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/article/18232 |archivedate=2011-07-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/1514567631.html?FMT=FT&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+22%2C+2008&author=Jeffrey+H+Birnbaum&desc=Why+BlackBerry+When+You+Can+Take+the+Bus%3F |title=washingtonpost.com - search nation, world, technology and Washington area news archives |publisher=Secure.pqarchiver.com |date=2008-07-22 |accessdate=2011-06-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715111400/https://secure.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/1514567631.html?FMT=FT&FMTS=ABS%3AFT&date=Jul+22%2C+2008&author=Jeffrey+H+Birnbaum&desc=Why+BlackBerry+When+You+Can+Take+the+Bus%3F |archivedate=15 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nEarlier in his career, Hoffman was Vice President for External Relations at the [[RAND Corporation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.rand.org/news/press/2004/09/30.html |title=Alan Hoffman Joins RAND Corporation as Vice President of External Affairs &#124; RAND |publisher=M.rand.org |date=2004-09-30 |accessdate=2011-06-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234015/http://m.rand.org/news/press/2004/09/30.html |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref> Vice President at Timmons and Company,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A60781-2004Sep29_2.html |title=Snowmobiles? This Isn't Yellowstone! |publisher=washingtonpost.com |date= 2004-09-30|accessdate=2011-06-02}}</ref> Assistant United States Attorney in [[Philadelphia]], Special Counsel to the Assistant Attorney General at the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]], Special Counsel to the Assistant Secretary at the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]] and an attorney at the law firms Pepper, Hamilton and Scheetz.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Office of the Vice President of the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoffman, Alan L}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:PepsiCo people]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden]]\n[[Category:Lafayette College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:USC Gould School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:USC Sol Price School of Public Policy alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name     = Alan L. Hoffman\n|image    = Alan L. Hoffman official photo.jpeg\n|office         = [[Office of the Vice President of the United States|Deputy Chief of Staff to the Vice President of the United States]]\n| term_start    = January 2009\n| term_end      = November 2012<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/alan-hoffman-1245608</ref>\n| president     = [[Barack Obama]]\n| vicepresident = [[Joe Biden]]\n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = [[Shailagh Murray|Shailagh J. Murray]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20191126234732/https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/GOVMAN-2014-10-06/xml/GOVMAN-2014-10-06-100.xml The United States Government Manual (October 2014), Executive Branch: The President - Office of the Vice President]</ref>\n|birth_name     = Alan Lawrence Hoffman\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1966|04|07}}\n|party          = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education      = [[Lafayette College]] {{small|(BA)}}<br>[[USC Gould School of Law|University of Southern California]] {{small|(MPA, JD)}}\n|spouse         = Lizzie Francis\n}}\n'''Alan Lawrence Hoffman'''<ref>http://members.calbar.ca.gov/fal/Licensee/Detail/158498</ref> (born April 7, 1966)<ref>{{cite book |last=Publishing Company |first=Monitor |date=2001 |title=Congressional Yellow Book: Who's Who in Congress, Including Committees and Key Staff |url= |location= |publisher=Monitor Publishing Company |page= |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> is an American lawyer, government official, and corporate executive who serves as Senior Vice President, Global Public Policy and Government Affairs at [[PepsiCo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=PepsiCo Names Alan Hoffman Senior Vice President, Global Public Policy and Government Affairs|url=http://www.pepsico.com/PressRelease/PepsiCo-Names-Alan-Hoffman-Senior-Vice-President-Global-Public-Policy-and-Govern11142012.html|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref>   Prior to joining PepsiCo, Hoffman served as Deputy [[Chief of Staff to the Vice President of the United States]] [[Joe Biden]] and [[Deputy Assistant to the President]]. While in the Vice President's office, Hoffman worked on a variety of issues including crime, drugs and protecting intellectual property, marking the third time Hoffman had worked for [[Joe Biden]]. Previously, Hoffman served as [[Chief of Staff]] to [[United States Senate|Senator]] Biden from 1998\u20132003 and from 2006-2008 while Biden was running for President.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/erin-medlicott/alan-hoffman-returns-to-w_b_154484.html |title=Erin Medlicott: Alan Hoffman Returns To Washington As VP-Elect Joe Biden's Deputy Chief Of Staff |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2011-05-25|accessdate=2011-06-02}}</ref>\n\n==Life and education==\nHoffman received his [[B.A.]] in [[American Civilization]] from [[Lafayette College]] in [[Easton, Pennsylvania]] and his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] and [[Master of Public Administration|M.P.A.]] from the [[USC Gould School of Law]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lafayette.edu/about/news/2009/09/10/alan-hoffman-%E2%80%9988-manages-daily-workings-of-vice-president-joe-biden%E2%80%99s-office/ |title=Alan Hoffman \u201988 Manages Daily Workings of Vice President Joe Biden\u2019s Office \u00b7 About \u00b7 Lafayette College |publisher=Lafayette.edu |date=2009-09-10 |accessdate=2011-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719230534/http://www.lafayette.edu/about/news/2009/09/10/alan-hoffman-%E2%80%9988-manages-daily-workings-of-vice-president-joe-biden%E2%80%99s-office/ |archive-date=2011-07-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://weblaw.usc.edu/news/assets/docs/USC_2009_LAW_MAGAZINEweb.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://alumni.usc.edu/profiles/alan_hoffman_class_of_91.html |title=Alan Hoffman Class of '91 &#124; USC Alumni Association |publisher=Alumni.usc.edu |accessdate=2011-06-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526025725/http://alumni.usc.edu/profiles/alan_hoffman_class_of_91.html |archivedate=26 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHoffman is married to Lizzie Francis and lives in [[Washington, D.C.]], with their dogs Brinkley and Franklin.\n\n==Career==\nHoffman is credited with helping Biden secure passage of numerous pieces of legislation including the criminal provisions of [[Sarbanes-Oxley]] and legislation closing the gap in sentencing between [[Crack cocaine|crack]] and powder [[cocaine]].<ref>http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CREC-2003-04-11/pdf/CREC-2003-04-11-pt2-PgS5325-4.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CREC-2010-08-05/pdf/CREC-2010-08-05-pt1-PgS6866-2.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after Biden withdrew from the [[2008 United States presidential election|presidential race]], Hoffman was the Senior Vice President for External Relations for the [[University of California]] system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/article/18232 |title=University of California - UC Newsroom &#124; Alan L. Hoffman appointed UC senior vice president for external relations |publisher=Universityofcalifornia.edu |accessdate=2011-06-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720093633/http://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/article/18232 |archivedate=2011-07-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/1514567631.html?FMT=FT&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+22%2C+2008&author=Jeffrey+H+Birnbaum&desc=Why+BlackBerry+When+You+Can+Take+the+Bus%3F |title=washingtonpost.com - search nation, world, technology and Washington area news archives |publisher=Secure.pqarchiver.com |date=2008-07-22 |accessdate=2011-06-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715111400/https://secure.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/1514567631.html?FMT=FT&FMTS=ABS%3AFT&date=Jul+22%2C+2008&author=Jeffrey+H+Birnbaum&desc=Why+BlackBerry+When+You+Can+Take+the+Bus%3F |archivedate=15 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nEarlier in his career, Hoffman was Vice President for External Relations at the [[RAND Corporation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.rand.org/news/press/2004/09/30.html |title=Alan Hoffman Joins RAND Corporation as Vice President of External Affairs &#124; RAND |publisher=M.rand.org |date=2004-09-30 |accessdate=2011-06-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234015/http://m.rand.org/news/press/2004/09/30.html |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref> Vice President at Timmons and Company,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A60781-2004Sep29_2.html |title=Snowmobiles? This Isn't Yellowstone! |publisher=washingtonpost.com |date= 2004-09-30|accessdate=2011-06-02}}</ref> Assistant United States Attorney in [[Philadelphia]], Special Counsel to the Assistant Attorney General at the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]], Special Counsel to the Assistant Secretary at the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]] and an attorney at the law firms Pepper, Hamilton and Scheetz.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Office of the Vice President of the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoffman, Alan L}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:PepsiCo people]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden]]\n[[Category:Lafayette College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:USC Gould School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:USC Sol Price School of Public Policy alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: President \u2192 president", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_L._Hoffman"}
{"title_page": "Green Day", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[Greenery Day]], the Japanese holiday}}\n{{short description|American rock band}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name            = Green Day\n| image           = Green Day 2017 Germany.png\n| caption         = Green Day performing in January 2017; from left to right: [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]], [[Billie Joe Armstrong]], [[Tr\u00e9 Cool]], and [[Mike Dirnt]]\n| image_size      = 400\n| alias           = {{flatlist|\n* Sweet Children (1987\u20131989)\n* GD\n}}\n| landscape       = yes\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[East Bay]], California, U.S.<!-- DO ''not'' CHANGE WITHOUT A TALK PAGE DISCUSSION -->\n| genre           = {{flatlist|<!-- DO ''not'' CHANGE WITHOUT A TALK PAGE DISCUSSION -->\n* [[Punk rock]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* {{nowrap|[[alternative rock]]}}\n}}\n| years_active    = 1987\u2013present<!-- Do not change this; see WP:MOSNUM#Other date ranges -->\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n* [[Warner Records|Warner]]\n* [[Lookout Records|Lookout!]] \n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pinhead Gunpowder]]\n* [[The Network]]\n* [[Foxboro Hot Tubs]]\n* [[The Longshot (band)|The Longshot]]\n* [[The Coverups]]\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|greenday.com}}\n| current_members =\n* [[Billie Joe Armstrong]]\n* [[Mike Dirnt]]\n* [[Tr\u00e9 Cool]]\n| past_members    =\n* [[John Kiffmeyer]] \n* Sean Hughes\n* Raj Punjabi\n* [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]]\n}}\n\n'''Green Day''' is an American [[Rock music|rock]]<!-- Do not change; this is the genre settled on for the lead section after much discussion on the talk page. Other genre labels are discussed further down and are listed in the infobox --> band formed in the [[East Bay]] of [[California]] in 1987 by lead vocalist and guitarist [[Billie Joe Armstrong]] and bassist and backing vocalist [[Mike Dirnt]]. For much of the band's career, they have been a trio with drummer [[Tr\u00e9 Cool]], who replaced [[John Kiffmeyer]] in 1990 prior to the recording of the band's second studio album, ''[[Kerplunk (album)|Kerplunk]]'' (1991). Touring guitarist [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]] became a full-time member in 2012, but returned to his role as a touring member in 2016.\n\nGreen Day was originally part of the [[Punk rock#1979\u20131984: Schism and diversification|late 80s-early 90s punk scene]] at the DIY [[924 Gilman Street]] club in [[Berkeley, California]]. The band's early releases were with the independent record label [[Lookout! Records]]. In 1994, their major label debut ''[[Dookie]]'', released through [[Reprise Records]], became a breakout success and eventually shipped over 10 million copies in the U.S. Green Day is credited alongside fellow California punk bands [[NOFX]], [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]], [[Bad Religion]], [[the Offspring]], and [[Rancid (band)|Rancid]] with popularizing mainstream interest in punk rock in the U.S.\n\nThough the albums ''[[Insomniac (Green Day album)|Insomniac]]'' (1995), ''[[Nimrod (album)|Nimrod]]'' (1997), and ''[[Warning (Green Day album)|Warning]]'' (2000) did not match the success of ''Dookie'', they were still successful with the former two reaching triple platinum status while the latter achieved gold. Green Day's seventh album, a [[rock opera]] called ''[[American Idiot]]'' (2004), found popularity with a younger generation, selling six million copies in the U.S. Their next album, ''[[21st Century Breakdown]]'', was released in 2009 and achieved the band's best chart performance. It was followed by a trilogy of albums, ''[[\u00a1Uno!]]'', ''[[\u00a1Dos!]]'', and ''[[\u00a1Tr\u00e9!]]'', released in September, November, and December 2012 respectively. The trilogy did not perform as well as expected commercially in comparison to their previous albums largely due to lack of promotion and lead singer and guitarist [[Billie Joe Armstrong]] going into rehab. Their twelfth studio album, ''[[Revolution Radio]]'', was released in October 2016 and became their third to debut at No. 1 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. The band's thirteenth studio album, ''[[Father of All Motherfuckers]]'', was released on February 7, 2020.\n\nGreen Day has sold more than 75 million records worldwide, making them one of the [[List of best-selling music artists|best-selling music artists]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/10/09/rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-nominees-green-day-nine-inch-nails-lou-reed/16852249/|title=Green Day, Nine Inch Nails among Rock Hall nominees|work=[[USA Today]]|date=October 9, 2014|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The group has been nominated for 20 Grammy awards and has won five of them with [[Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Album]] for ''[[Dookie]]'', [[Best Rock Album]] for ''[[American Idiot]]'' and ''[[21st Century Breakdown]]'', [[Record of the Year]] for \"[[Boulevard of Broken Dreams (Green Day song)|Boulevard of Broken Dreams]]\", and [[Best Musical Show Album]] for ''[[American Idiot: The Original Broadway Cast Recording]]''.\n\nIn 2010, a [[American Idiot (musical)|stage adaptation of ''American Idiot'']] debuted on Broadway. The musical was nominated for three [[Tony Awards]]: [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]], [[Tony Award for Best Scenic Design|Best Scenic Design]], and [[Tony Award for Best Lighting Design|Best Lighting Design]], winning the latter two. The band was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 2015, their first year of eligibility. In 2018, members of Green Day, along with several friends, formed the side project [[The Coverups]] to perform cover songs.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Formation and Lookout! years (''39/Smooth'' and ''Kerplunk'', 1987\u20131993) ===\nIn 1987, friends Billie Joe Armstrong and Mike Dirnt, 15 years old at the time, formed a band under the name Sweet Children.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Green-Day|title=Green Day - History, Songs, Albums & Facts|last=Albert|first=Melissa|date=February 8, 2020|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|quote=In 1987 they and drummer Sean Hughes formed their first band, a punk outfit called Sweet Children.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/GreenDay/about|title=Green Day - Official Page|date=February 8, 2020|website=[[Facebook]]|publisher=Green Day|quote=Founded in 1987}}</ref><ref name=\"LLC1994\">{{cite journal|last=Weisbard|first=Eric|authorlink=Eric Weisbard|title=SPIN: Young, Loud, and Snotty|journal=Spin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8X17JjiXfYYC&pg=PA70|access-date=February 10, 2018|volume=10|date=September 1994|publisher=SPIN Media LLC; Camouflage Associates|location=United States|language=English|issn=0886-3032|page=70}}</ref> The group's first live performance took place on October 17, 1987, at Rod's Hickory Pit in [[Vallejo, California]].<ref name=Vhawk>{{cite web|title=Green Day|url=http://www.purevolume.com/Vhawk|publisher=Pure volume|access-date=June 13, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120124233318/http://www.purevolume.com/Vhawk|archive-date=January 24, 2012}}</ref> In 1988, Armstrong and Dirnt began working with former [[Isocracy (band)|Isocracy]] drummer [[John Kiffmeyer]], also known as \"Al Sobrante\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Small|first1=Doug|title=Omnibus Presents the Story of Green Day|url=https://archive.org/details/omnibuspresspres00smal|url-access=registration|date=2005|publisher=Omnibus Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/omnibuspresspres00smal/page/12 12]}}</ref> Armstrong cites the band [[Operation Ivy (band)|Operation Ivy]] (which featured [[Tim Armstrong]] and [[Matt Freeman]], who would later contact Armstrong to fill in as a possible second guitarist for their band [[Rancid (band)|Rancid]]) as a major influence, and a group that inspired him to form a band.<ref name=PunksNotDeadMovie>{{cite AV media |people =Susan Dynner (director) |date =July 27, 2007 |title =Punk's Not Dead |medium =Documentary Movie |language =English |url =http://www.punksnotdeadthemovie.com/ |access-date =February 10, 2018 |time =93 Minutes |location =United States |publisher =Vision Films |quote =\"Opartion Ivy was such a huge band. I was 15 years old when I got into that band, I just remember thinking 'This is the greatest band in the world'. |url-status =live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180211131232/http://www.punksnotdeadthemovie.com/ |archive-date =February 11, 2018 |df =mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Spitz>{{cite book|last=Spitz|first=Marc|authorlink=Marc Spitz|title=Nobody Likes You: Inside the Turbulent Life, Times, and Music of Green Day|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FSWZAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT41|date=November 7, 2006|publisher=Hachette Books|isbn=978-1-4013-8579-8|chapter=4: Op Ivy|quote=\"[Operation Ivy] became Billie Joe Armstrong's favorite band and biggest influence\"}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, [[Larry Livermore]], owner of [[Lookout! Records]], saw the band play an early show and signed the group to his label. In 1989, the band recorded its debut [[extended play]], ''[[1,000 Hours]]''. Before ''1,000 Hours'' was released, the group dropped the name Sweet Children; according to Livermore, this was done to avoid confusion with another local band [[Sweet Baby (band)|Sweet Baby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/25-worst-original-names-of-famous-bands-20150722/sweet-children-20150721|title=Sweet Children \u2013 25 Worst Original Names of Famous Bands|date=July 22, 2015|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=June 23, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620001326/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/25-worst-original-names-of-famous-bands-20150722/sweet-children-20150721|archive-date=June 20, 2016}}</ref> The band adopted the name Green Day, due to the members' fondness for [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.metropolis.co.jp/tokyomusicconcerts/concert/359/tokyomusicconcertsinc.htm |title=Music and Concerts: Green Day |publisher=Archive.metropolis.co.jp |access-date=September 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102214651/http://archive.metropolis.co.jp/tokyomusicconcerts/concert/359/tokyomusicconcertsinc.htm |archive-date=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode |url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kG-1ibZOJzk |title = Bill Maher and Green Day's Billy Joe Talk About Marijuana |access-date = May 30, 2015 |series = [[Real Time with Bill Maher]] |first = Bill |last = Maher |first2 = Billie Joe |last2 = Armstrong |network = HBO |date = April 9, 2010 |season = 8 |number = 179 |url-status = live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150217145028/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kG-1ibZOJzk |archive-date = February 17, 2015 |df = mdy-all}}</ref> Armstrong once admitted in 2001 that he considered it to be the worst band name in the world.<ref>{{cite web |last1=VH1 |title=Green Day: Behind the Music #155 |url=http://www.vh1.com/episodes/r1ctel/behind-the-music-green-day-behind-the-music-155-season-1-ep-155 |website=VH1 |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>  \n\nLookout! released Green Day's debut studio album, ''[[39/Smooth]]'' in early 1990. Green Day recorded two extended plays later that year, ''[[Slappy]]'' and ''[[Sweet Children (EP)|Sweet Children]]'', the latter of which included older songs that the band had recorded for the [[Minneapolis]] independent record label [[Skene! Records]].<ref name=\"Egerdahl2010\">{{cite book|first=Kjersti|last=Egerdahl|title=Green Day: A Musical Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UfMAtvcbex4C&pg=PA28|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-36597-3|pages=28\u2013}}</ref> In 1991, Lookout! Records re-released ''39/Smooth'' under the name ''1,039/Smoothed Out Slappy Hours'', and added the songs from the band's first two EPs, ''Slappy'', and ''1,000 Hours''. In late 1990, shortly after the band's first nationwide tour, Kiffmeyer left the East Bay area to attend [[Humboldt State University]] in [[Arcata, California]].<ref name=Vhawk /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Small|first1=Doug|title=Omnibus Presents the Story of Green Day|url=https://archive.org/details/omnibuspresspres00smal|url-access=registration|date=2005|publisher=Omnibus Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/omnibuspresspres00smal/page/17 17]}}</ref> [[The Lookouts]]' drummer [[Tr\u00e9 Cool]] began filling in as a temporary replacement and later Cool's position as Green Day's drummer became permanent, which Kiffmeyer \"graciously accepted\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Small|first1=Doug|title=Omnibus Presents the Story of Green Day|url=https://archive.org/details/omnibuspresspres00smal|url-access=registration|date=2005|publisher=Omnibus Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/omnibuspresspres00smal/page/19 19]|quote=graciously accepted}}</ref> The band went on tour for most of 1992 and 1993, and played a number of shows overseas in Europe. The band's second studio album ''[[Kerplunk (album)|Kerplunk]]'' sold 50,000 copies in the U.S.<ref>Thompson, Dave. \"Green Day.\" ''Alternative Rock''. San Francisco: Miller Freeman Books, 2000.</ref>\n\n=== Breakthrough success (''Dookie'' and ''Insomniac'', 1994\u20131996) ===\n''Kerplunk'''s underground success led to a number of major record labels being interested in signing Green Day, and the band eventually left Lookout! and signed to [[Reprise Records]] after attracting the attention of producer [[Rob Cavallo]]. The group was impressed by his work with fellow Californian band [[The Muffs]], and later remarked that Cavallo \"was the only person we could really talk to and connect with\".<ref name=\"vh1 behind the music\">{{cite episode|network=[[VH1]] |title=Green Day: Behind the Music|series=[[Behind the Music]] |episode=Green Day |year=2001}}</ref> Reflecting on the period, Armstrong told ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine in 1999, \"I couldn't go back to the punk scene, whether we were the biggest success in the world or the biggest failure ... The only thing I could do was get on my bike and go forward.\"<ref>Smith, RJ. \"Top 90 Albums of the 90s.\" ''SPIN''. August 1999.</ref> After signing with Reprise, the band went to work on recording its major label debut, ''[[Dookie]]''.\n{{Listen\n|filename = Basket Case1.ogg\n|title =\"Basket Case\"\n|description = Sample of \"Basket Case\", the seventh track and third single from ''Dookie'', which was about [[Billie Joe Armstrong|Armstrong]]'s panic attacks.\n}}\n\nRecorded in three weeks, and released in February 1994,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biography_story/1779:2213/1/Green_Day.htm |title=Green Day |publisher=Biography Channel |date=September 11, 2009 |access-date=September 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015021933/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biography_story/1779%3A2213/1/Green_Day.htm |archive-date=October 15, 2009 |df=}}</ref> ''Dookie'' became a commercial success, helped by extensive MTV airplay for the videos of the songs \"[[Longview (song)|Longview]]\", \"[[Basket Case (song)|Basket Case]]\", and \"[[When I Come Around]]\", all of which reached the number one position on the [[Modern Rock Tracks]] charts. The album went on to sell over 10 million copies in the US.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=0535F2FC-4B80-F5DD-14FD-27585998FEEA&searchterms=green%20day%20dookie&terminclude=&termexact= |title=Idiot Rules! |access-date=November 22, 2010 |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America|The Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA)]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622123613/http://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=0535F2FC-4B80-F5DD-14FD-27585998FEEA&searchterms=green%20day%20dookie&terminclude=&termexact= |archive-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref> At a performance on September 9, 1994 at [[Hatch Memorial Shell]] in Boston, mayhem broke out during the band's set (cut short to seven songs) and by the end of the rampage, 100 people were injured and 45 arrested.<ref>[[Fricke, David]] (December 16, 1999), \"Our Back Pages\". ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' (828/829):85</ref> The band also joined the lineups of both the [[Lollapalooza]] festival and [[Woodstock '94]], where the group started an infamous mud fight. During the concert, a security guard mistook bassist [[Mike Dirnt]] for a stage-invading fan and punched out some of his teeth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ram.org/music/woodstock/woodstock.html|title=Woodstock 1994 concert review|last=Samudrala|first=Ram|date=August 1994|access-date=December 19, 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128222654/http://ram.org/music/woodstock/woodstock.html|archive-date=November 28, 2010}}</ref> Viewed by millions by [[pay-per-view]] television, the Woodstock 1994 performance further aided Green Day's growing publicity and recognition.<ref name=\"vh1 behind the music\" /> In 1995, ''Dookie'' won the [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Album]] and the band was nominated for nine [[MTV Video Music Award]]s including Video of the Year.\n\nIn 1995, a new single for the ''[[Angus (film)|Angus]]'' soundtrack was released, entitled \"[[J.A.R.]]\". The single debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Modern Rock Tracks]] chart. The song was followed by the band's fourth studio album, ''[[Insomniac (Green Day album)|Insomniac]]'', which was released in the fall of 1995. ''Insomniac'' was a much darker and heavier response to the band's newfound popularity, compared to the more melodic ''Dookie''.<ref name=\"vh1 behind the music\" /> The album opened to a warm critical reception, earning 4 out of 5 stars from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', which said \"In punk, the good stuff actually unfolds and gains meaning as you listen without sacrificing any of its electric, haywire immediacy. And Green Day are as good as this stuff gets.\"<ref>Coleman, Mark. \"Insomniac.\" ''Rolling Stone''. November 1995.</ref> The singles released from ''Insomniac'' were \"[[Geek Stink Breath]]\", \"[[Stuck with Me]]\", \"[[Brain Stew/Jaded]]\", and \"[[Walking Contradiction]]\".\n\nThough the album did not approach the success of ''Dookie'', it sold three million copies in the United States.<ref name=\"Album Guide\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/green-day/albumguide|title=Green Day: Album Guide|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=January 8, 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123042756/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/green-day/albumguide|archive-date=January 23, 2011}}</ref> In addition, the album won the band award nominations for Favorite Artist, Favorite Hard Rock Artist, and Favorite Alternative Artist at the 1996 [[American Music Awards]], and the video for \"Walking Contradiction\" got the band a Grammy nomination for Best Video, Short Form, in addition to a Best Special Effects nomination at the MTV Video Music Awards. After that, the band abruptly cancelled a European tour, citing exhaustion.<ref name=\"snotty\">Di Perna, Alan. \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20091027102356/http://www.geocities.com/vintageinterviews/greenday.html Young, Loud, and Snotty].\" ''Guitar World''. August 1996.</ref>\n\n=== Middle years and decline in commercial success (''Nimrod'' and ''Warning'', 1997\u20132002) ===\nAfter a brief hiatus in 1996, Green Day began to work on a new album in 1997. From the outset, both the band and Cavallo agreed that the album had to be different from its previous albums.<ref>{{cite book|last=Spitz|first=Marc|authorlink=Marc Spitz|title=Nobody Likes You: Inside the Turbulent Life, Times, and Music of Green Day|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FSWZAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT41|date=November 7, 2006|publisher=Hachette Books|isbn=978-1-4013-8579-8|page=128}}</ref> The result was ''[[Nimrod (album)|Nimrod]]'', an experimental deviation from the band's standard pop-punk brand of music. The new album was released in October 1997. It provided a variety of music, from pop-punk, [[surf rock]], and [[ska]], to an acoustic ballad. ''Nimrod'' entered the charts at number 10. The success of \"[[Good Riddance (Time of Your Life)]]\" won the band an MTV Video Award for Best Alternative Video. The song was also used in the second \"clip show\" episode of ''[[Seinfeld]]'' and on two episodes of ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''.\n\nThe other singles released from ''Nimrod'' were \"[[Nice Guys Finish Last]]\", \"[[Hitchin' a Ride (Green Day song)|Hitchin' a Ride]]\" and \"[[Redundant (song)|Redundant]]\". The band made a guest appearance in an episode of ''[[King of the Hill]]'' entitled \"The Man Who Shot Cane Skretteberg\", which aired in 1997. In late 1997 and most of 1998, Green Day embarked on a tour in support of ''Nimrod''. In 1999, guitarist [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]] began supporting the band during concerts as rhythm guitarist.\n\nIn 2000, Green Day released its sixth studio album ''[[Warning (Green Day album)|Warning]]''. In support of the album, the band participated in the [[Warped Tour]] in 2000. In November 2000, the band performed for free on the steps on San Francisco's City Hall to protest the eviction of artists from the city in a show produced by [[Ian Brennan (music producer)|Ian Brennan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1429724/green-day-to-play-free-san-francisco-show/|title=Green Day To Play Free San Francisco Show|newspaper=MTV News|access-date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001194126/http://www.mtv.com/news/1429724/green-day-to-play-free-san-francisco-show/|archive-date=October 1, 2016}}</ref> The band also had an independent tour to support the album in 2001. Critics' reviews of the album were varied.<ref name=metacritic>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/warning/critic-reviews |title=Green Day: Warning (2000): Reviews |website=Metacritic |date=October 3, 2000 |access-date=September 6, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211033629/http://www.metacritic.com/music/warning/critic-reviews |archive-date=December 11, 2014}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] gave it 4.5/5 saying \"''Warning'' may not be an innovative record per se, but it's tremendously satisfying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r500748/review|pure_url=yes}}|title=Warning|website=AllMusic|access-date=July 10, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' was more critical, giving it 3/5, and saying \"''Warning''... invites the question: Who wants to listen to songs of faith, hope and social commentary from what used to be snot-core's biggest-selling band?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/warning-20001012|title=''Warning'' review|work=Rolling Stone|last=Kot|first=Greg|date=October 12, 2000|access-date=January 8, 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305223013/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/warning-20001012|archive-date=March 5, 2013}}</ref> Though it produced the hit \"[[Minority (Green Day song)|Minority]]\" and a smaller hit with \"[[Warning (Green Day song)|Warning]]\", some observers were coming to the conclusion that the band was losing relevance,<ref name=metacritic /> and a decline in popularity followed. While all of Green Day's previous albums had reached a status of at least triple platinum, ''Warning'' was only certified gold.<ref name=\"Timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-g/greenday_main.htm|title=Green Day Timeline|publisher=Rock on the Net|access-date=September 6, 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401193955/http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-g/greenday_main.htm|archive-date=April 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2001 California Music Awards, Green Day won all eight of the awards for which the group was nominated.<ref name=cal2001 /> The group won the awards for Outstanding Album (''Warning''), Outstanding Punk Rock/Ska Album (''Warning''), Outstanding Group, Outstanding Male Vocalist, Outstanding Bassist, Outstanding Drummer, Outstanding Songwriter, and Outstanding Artist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Green Day Dominates California Music Awards|url=http://idobi.com/news/2001/04/green-day-dominates-california-music-awards/|publisher=[[idobi Radio]]|access-date=June 20, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427042434/http://idobi.com/news/2001/04/green-day-dominates-california-music-awards/|archive-date=April 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe release of two compilation albums, ''[[International Superhits!]]'' and ''[[Shenanigans (album)|Shenanigans]]'', followed ''Warning''. ''International Superhits'' and its companion collection of music videos, ''[[International Supervideos!]]''. ''Shenanigans'' contained some of the band's b-sides, including \"Espionage\", which was featured in the film ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'' and was nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Instrumental Performance]].<ref name=\"cal2001\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2000-01-05/entertainment/17634952_1_sogno-andrea-bocelli-beautiful-stranger-madonna-unpretty-dallas-austin/2 |title=The Nominees for the Grammy Awards |date=January 5, 2000 |page=2 |access-date=June 20, 2012 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716044630/http://articles.sfgate.com/2000-01-05/entertainment/17634952_1_sogno-andrea-bocelli-beautiful-stranger-madonna-unpretty-dallas-austin/2 |archive-date=July 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2002, Green Day co-headlined the [[Pop Disaster Tour]] with [[Blink-182]], which was documented on the DVD ''Riding in Vans with Boys''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pop Disaster Tour|url=http://www.rockzone.com/concertreviews/blink-051102.shtml|work=Rockzone|access-date=June 20, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204174103/http://www.rockzone.com/concertreviews/blink-051102.shtml|archive-date=February 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== ''American Idiot'' and renewed success (2003\u20132006) ===\n[[File:Mike Dirnt and Tre Cool.jpg|thumb|left|Tr\u00e9 Cool (bottom left) and Mike Dirnt (right) performing on July 27, 2005.]]\n\nIn the summer of 2003, the band went into a studio to write and record new material for a new album, tentatively titled ''[[Cigarettes and Valentines]]''.<ref>Spitz, p. 152.</ref> After completing 20 tracks, the [[master recording]]s were stolen from the studio. Instead of re-recording the stolen tracks, the band decided to abandon the entire project and start over, considering the taken material to be unrepresentative of the band's best work.<ref name=\"Cigarettes\">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/08/31/watch-green-day-debut-cigarettes-and-valentines-and-olivia/|title=Watch: Green Day debut \"Cigarettes and Valentines\" and \"Olivia\"|last=Coplan|first=Chris|work=Consequence of Sound|date=August 31, 2010|access-date=January 8, 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100905035633/http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/08/31/watch-green-day-debut-cigarettes-and-valentines-and-olivia/|archive-date=September 5, 2010}}</ref> It was then revealed that a band called [[The Network]] was signed to Armstrong's record label [[Adeline Records]] with little fanfare and information.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/46067/green-day-unmasked|title=Green Day Unmasked?|date=October 16, 2003|website=Eonline.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2003-10-03-0310040002-story.html|title=Has Green Day gone incognito?|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> After the band, who concealed their identities with masks and costumes,<ref name=\"UNF\"/> released an album called ''[[Money Money 2020]]'', it was rumored that The Network was a Green Day side project, due to the similarities in the bands' sounds.<ref name=\"MTVNews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1510964/-green-day-their-own-worst-enemy.jhtml|title=Are Green Day Their Own Worst Enemy? Only Time\u2014Or Concerts\u2014Will Tell|last=Montgomery|first=James|date=October 5, 2005|publisher=MTV News|access-date=January 8, 2010}}</ref> However, these rumors were never addressed by the band or Adeline Records, except for a statement on the Adeline website discussing an ongoing dispute between the two bands.<ref name=\"MTVNews\" /> The bands \"feuded\" via press releases and statements from Armstrong.<ref name=\"UNF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/features/11_of_green_days_most_unforgettable_moments/|title=11 of Green Day's most unforgettable moments - Alternative Press|date=September 26, 2016|website=Altpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Boone|first1=Brian|title=I love rock 'n' roll (except when I hate it) : extremely important stuff about the songs and bands you love, hate, love to hate, and hate to love|date=2011|publisher=Perigee|location=New York|isbn=9781101507919|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CT_ViUaYTfwC |access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> Several journalists openly referred to the group as a Green Day side project,<ref name=\"GOFORM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldminemag.com/features/where-does-green-day-go-from-here|title=Where does a successful Green Day go from here?|date=May 4, 2011|website=Goldminemag.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Secret\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1479481/did-green-day-secretly-release-a-new-album-tuesday-only-the-snoo-knows/|title=Did Green Day Secretly Release A New Album Tuesday? Only The Snoo Knows|website=Mtv.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/features/the-many-sides-of-billie-joe-armstrong/|title=The Many Sides Of Billie Joe Armstrong \u2014 Kerrang!|website=Kerrang!}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2003/12/23/money-money-2020|title=Money Money 2020|first=Jesse|last=Lord|date=December 23, 2003|website=Ign.com}}</ref> although it was not confirmed as such until 2013.<ref name=\"IDENT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/qa-green-days-mike-dirnt-on-billie-joe-armstrongs-recovery-168010/|title=Q&A: Green Day's Mike Dirnt on Billie Joe Armstrong's Recovery|first=David|last=Fricke|date=March 1, 2013|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HaseAufCenterstage.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Green Day live in Germany during the ''American Idiot'' tour.]]\nGreen Day collaborated with [[Iggy Pop]] on two tracks for his album ''[[Skull Ring]]'' in November 2003. On February 1, 2004, a new song, a cover of \"[[I Fought the Law]]\" made its debut on a commercial for [[iTunes]] during [[NFL]] [[Super Bowl XXXVIII]]. ''[[American Idiot]]'' (2004), debuted at number one on the Billboard charts, the band's first album to reach number one, backed by the success of the album's first single, \"[[American Idiot (song)|American Idiot]]\". The album was labeled as a ''punk [[rock opera]]'' which follows the journey of the fictitious \"[[Jesus of Suburbia]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/eastbay/punk-rock-opera/Content?oid=1370982|title=Punk Rock Opera|last=Downs|first=David|work=East Bay Express|date=September 2, 2009}}</ref> The album depicts modern American life under the control of an idiot ruler who let people be misinformed by the media and a \"redneck agenda\". It gives different angles on an everyman, modern icons, and leaders.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title = GREEN DAY american idiots & the new punk explosion|last = Myers|first = Ben|publisher = The Disinformation Company Ltd.|year = 2006|isbn = 978-1-932857-32-0|location = New York}}</ref> Released two months before U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] was reelected, the album became protest art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ehis.ebscohost.com/eds/detail?sid=051541ef-fb2b-4cf8-8106-1faa8293a750%40sessionmgr4&vid=1&hid=4&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWRzLWxpdmUmc2NvcGU9c2l0ZQ%3d%3d#db=aph&AN=35740246.html|title=Green Day's 'American Idiot'|access-date=October 12, 2011|first=Lorraine|last=Ali|date=December 22, 2008|work=Newsweek}}</ref> ''American Idiot'' won the [[47th Grammy Awards|2005 Grammy]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]]. The band also won a total of seven out of eight awards for which the group was nominated, including the Viewer's Choice Award at the [[MTV Video Music Awards]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2005/|title=2005 Video Music Awards|publisher=MTV News|date=September 2, 2005|access-date=December 21, 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419023648/http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2005/|archive-date=April 19, 2012}}</ref> The album went on to sell 6 million copies in the US.<ref name=\"Timeline\" />\n\nIn 2005, ''American Idiot'' won a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]] and was nominated in six other categories including [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?year=2004 |title=2004 Grammy Award Winners |work=Grammy.com |accessdate=January 22, 2015 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211124314/http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?year=2004 |archivedate=February 11, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goweho.com/green-days-american-idiot-nominated-for-seven-grammy-awards/1002|title=Green Day's American Idiot Nominated for Seven Grammy Awards|last=|first=|date=December 13, 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326051513/https://www.goweho.com/green-days-american-idiot-nominated-for-seven-grammy-awards/1002|archive-date=2017-03-26|url-status = dead|work=GoWEHO|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> The album helped Green Day win seven of the eight awards it was nominated for at the 2005 [[MTV Video Music Awards]]; the \"Boulevard of Broken Dreams\" video won six of those awards. A year later, \"Boulevard of Broken Dreams\" won a [[48th Grammy Awards|Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&field_nominee_work_value=&year=2005&genre=All |title=2005 Grammy Award Winners |work=Grammy.com |accessdate=January 22, 2015 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110195125/http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&field_nominee_work_value=&year=2005&genre=All |archivedate=November 10, 2014 |df= }}</ref> In 2009, ''[[Kerrang!]]'' named ''American Idiot'' the best album of the decade,<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Kerrang!]] |date=August 5, 2009 |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |title=Kerrang! Top 50 albums of the 21st Century}}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' ranked it number 60 in a similar list,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/the-top-100-greatest-albums-of-the-decade/158049/page/5 |title=The Top 100 Greatest Albums of the Decade |work=[[NME]] |accessdate=December 10, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091120175203/http://www.nme.com/list/the-top-100-greatest-albums-of-the-decade/158049/page/5| archivedate= 20 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked it 22nd.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248017/100_best_albums_of_the_decade/27 |title=100 Best Albums of the Decade: #22-#21 |work=Rolling Stone |date=December 9, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091213004501/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248017/100_best_albums_of_the_decade/27| archivedate= 13 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' also listed \"Boulevard of Broken Dreams\" and \"American Idiot\" among the 100 best songs of the 2000s, at number 65 and 47 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248926/100_best_songs_of_the_decade/9 |title=100 Best Songs of the Decade: #68-65 |work=Rolling Stone |date=December 9, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091213004922/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248926/100_best_songs_of_the_decade/9| archivedate= 13 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248926/100_best_songs_of_the_decade/14 |title=100 Best Songs of the Decade: #48-45 |work=Rolling Stone |date=December 9, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091213004739/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248926/100_best_songs_of_the_decade/14| archivedate= 13 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref> In 2005, the album was ranked number 420 in ''Rock Hard'' magazine's book of ''The 500 Greatest Rock & Metal Albums of All Time''.<ref>{{cite book|last=[...]|first=Rock Hard (Hrsg.). [Red.: Michael Rensen. Mitarb.: G\u00f6tz K\u00fchnemund]|title=Best of Rock & Metal die 500 st\u00e4rksten Scheiben aller Zeiten|year=2005|publisher=Heel|location=K\u00f6nigswinter|isbn=3-89880-517-4|page=42}}</ref> In 2012, the album was ranked number 225 on ''Rolling Stone'''s list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/green-day-american-idiot-20120524 |title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time: Green Day, 'American Idiot' |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=2012-12-18 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105140215/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/green-day-american-idiot-20120524 |archivedate=2013-01-05 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Greenday1.jpg|thumb|left|Green Day performing in New Jersey in 2005]]\nThrough 2005, the band toured in support of the album with nearly 150 dates, which was the longest tour in the band's career, visiting Japan, Australia, South America and the United Kingdom. While touring for ''American Idiot'', the group filmed and recorded the two concerts at the [[Milton Keynes]] [[National Bowl]] in England, which was voted \"The Best Show On Earth\" in a ''[[Kerrang!]]'' Magazine Poll. These recordings were released as a live CD and DVD called ''[[Bullet in a Bible]]'' on November 15, 2005. This CD/DVD featured songs from ''American Idiot'' as well as songs from all its previous albums, except ''Kerplunk'' and ''1,039/Smoothed Out Slappy Hours''. The DVD featured behind-the-scenes footage of the band, and showed how the band prepared to put on the show. The final shows of its 2005 world tour were in Sydney and [[Melbourne]] in Australia, on December 14 and 17, respectively.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nOn August 1, 2005, Green Day announced that it had rescinded the master rights to its pre-''Dookie'' material from Lookout! Records, citing a continuing [[breach of contract]] regarding unpaid royalties, a complaint shared with other Lookout! bands.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.punknews.org/article/13338 |title=Lookout! downsizes, scales back plans for the future |publisher=Punknews.org |access-date=September 6, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526031604/http://www.punknews.org/article/13338 |archive-date=May 26, 2011}}</ref> On January 10, 2006, the band was awarded a [[People's Choice Award]] as favorite musical group or band.<ref>{{cite web|title=People's Choice Awards 2006|url=http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp?year=2006|publisher=People's Choice Awards|access-date=June 20, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722194402/http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp?year=2006|archive-date=July 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== ''21st Century Breakdown'' and ''American Idiot'''s stage adaptation (2007\u20132010) ===\n{{Listen\n|filename = Green Day - 21 Guns.ogg\n|title = \"21 Guns\"\n|description = Sample of \"21 Guns\", the second single from ''21st Century Breakdown''\n<!-- Commented out: |filename2 = Green Day - Last of the American Girls.ogg -->\n|title2=\"Last of the American Girls\"\n|description2 = Sample of \"Last of the American Girls\", the fifth and last single from ''21st Century Breakdown''\n}}\n\nGreen Day engaged in a number of other smaller projects in the time following the success of ''American Idiot''. The group released an album under the name [[Foxboro Hot Tubs]] entitled ''[[Stop Drop and Roll!!!]]'' In 2008, the Foxboro Hot Tubs went on a mini-tour to promote the record, hitting tiny Bay Area venues including the Stork Club in Oakland and Toot's Tavern in [[Crockett, California]].<ref>Crooks, Peter. [http://www.diablomag.com/Diablo-Magazine/July-2008/Green-Day-20/ \"Greenday 2.0\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829202623/http://www.diablomag.com/Diablo-Magazine/July-2008/Green-Day-20/ |date=August 29, 2008}} Diablo Magazine, July 2008.</ref>\n\n[[File:Green Day live.jpg|thumb|left|Green Day performing during a secret show at the Kesselhaus in Berlin on May 7, 2009.]]\nIn an interview with Carson Daly, [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]] lead singer [[Shirley Manson]] revealed that [[Butch Vig]] would be producing Green Day's forthcoming album.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=October 14, 2008|title=Green Day Are in the Studio With Butch Vig For New Album, Online Video Confirms|first=James|last=Montgomery|url=http://www.mtv.com./news/articles/1596973/20081014/green_day.jhtml|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081017113054/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1596973/20081014/green_day.jhtml|archive-date=October 17, 2008}}</ref> The span of nearly five years between ''American Idiot'' and ''21st Century Breakdown'' was the longest gap between studio albums in Green Day's career. The band had been working on new material since January 2006. By October 2007, Armstrong had 45 songs written, but the band showed no further signs of progress until October 2008, when two videos showing the band recording in the studio with producer Butch Vig were posted on YouTube.<ref>{{cite news|title=Green Day in studio with Nirvana producer|date=October 14, 2008|first=Jonathan|last=Cohen|agency=Reuters|url=http://ca.reuters.com./article/entertainmentNews/idCATRE49E04920081015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081018191932/http://ca.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idCATRE49E04920081015|archive-date=October 18, 2008}}</ref> The writing and recording process, spanning three years and four recording studios, was finally finished in April 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Green Day Reflects On '21st Century Breakdown' |url=http://75.125.194.26/gossips/music/green_day_reflects_on_21st_century_breakdown_/ |publisher=[[All Headline News]] |date=April 27, 2009 |access-date=May 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706002447/http://75.125.194.26/gossips/music/green_day_reflects_on_21st_century_breakdown_/ |archive-date=July 6, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n''[[21st Century Breakdown]]'', was released on May 15, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Green Day Announce New Album Title |publisher=Rocklouder |date=February 9, 2009 |url=http://www.rocklouder.co.uk/articles/6977/Green-Day-Announce-New-Album-Title.html |access-date=May 30, 2012|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090212130436/http://rocklouder.co.uk/articles/6977/Green-Day-Announce-New-Album-Title.html|archive-date=February 12, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idiomag.com/peek/72615/green_day|title=Green Day unveil new album release date|access-date=March 30, 2009|date=March 27, 2009|publisher=[[idiomag]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327140605/http://www.idiomag.com/peek/72615/green_day|archive-date=March 27, 2012}}</ref> The album received a mainly positive reception from critics, getting an average rating between 3 and 4 stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/green-day-21st-century-breakdown-reprise|title=Green Day, '21st Century Breakdown' (Reprise)|access-date=September 1, 2010|date=May 17, 2009|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524103340/http://www.spin.com/reviews/green-day-21st-century-breakdown-reprise|archive-date=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20276731,00.html?order=ASC&page=5|title=21st Century Breakdown|access-date=September 1, 2010|date=May 6, 2009|work=Entertainment Weekly|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522055326/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20276731,00.html?order=ASC&page=5|archive-date=May 22, 2012}}</ref> After the release, the album reached number one in fourteen countries, being certified gold or platinum in each. ''21st Century Breakdown'' achieved Green Day's best chart performance to date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/green-day/chart-history/billboard-200/song/612012 |title=21st Century Breakdown Chart History |website=Billboard.com |access-date=February 10, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404052625/https://www.billboard.com/music/green-day/chart-history/billboard-200/song/612012 |archive-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> The band started playing shows in California in April and early May. These were the group's first live shows in about three years. Green Day went on a world tour that started in North America in July 2009 and continuing around the world throughout the rest of 2009 and early 2010.<ref name=\"livedaily\">{{cite news|last=Madison |first=Tjames |title=Green Day taps big names as tour openers |url=http://www.livedaily.com/news/19183.html |publisher=[[LiveDaily]] |date=May 26, 2009 |access-date=June 1, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530070251/http://www.livedaily.com/news/19183.html |archive-date=May 30, 2009 |df= }}</ref> The album won the [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album]] at the [[52nd Grammy Awards]] on January 31, 2010. As of December 2010, ''21st Century Breakdown'' has sold 1,005,000 copies in the US<ref>{{cite news|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/71727/week-ending-dec-19-2010-michael-wouldnt-have-liked-this/;_ylt=Aj.H3JkWiMnvsI1nfdVCl7wPwiUv?page=2#comments |title=Week Ending Dec. 19, 2010: Michael Wouldn't Have Liked This|first=Paul |last=Grein |work=[[Yahoo! Music]] |date=Dec 22, 2010 |accessdate=February 3, 2011 |location= }}</ref> and more than 4 million worldwide.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[Wal-Mart]] refused to carry the album as it contains a [[Parental Advisory]] sticker and requested that Green Day release a censored edition. The band members did not wish to change any lyrics on the album and responded by stating, \"There's nothing dirty about our record... They want artists to censor their records in order to be carried in there. We just said no. We've never done it before. You feel like you're in 1953 or something.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsvine.com/_news/2009/05/21/2846595-green-day-lashes-out-at-wal-mart-policy |title=Green Day lashes out at Wal-Mart policy |date=May 21, 2009 |access-date=May 21, 2009 |publisher=Newsvine |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525094507/http://www.newsvine.com/_news/2009/05/21/2846595-green-day-lashes-out-at-wal-mart-policy |archive-date=May 25, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1611970/20090521/green_day.jhtml |title=You Won't Find Green Day's 21st Century Breakdown At Wal-Mart |date=May 21, 2009 |access-date=May 21, 2009 |publisher=MTV News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525083403/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1611970/20090521/green_day.jhtml |archive-date=May 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the band met with award-winning director [[Michael Mayer (director)|Michael Mayer]] and many cast and crew members of the [[Tony Award]]-winning musical ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'' to create a stage version of the album ''American Idiot''.<ref name=americanidiotmusii /><ref name=americanitiotcharaters /> ''[[American Idiot (musical)|American Idiot]]'' opened in the [[Berkeley Repertory Theatre]] during the end of 2009.<ref name=\"americanidiotmusii\">{{Citation |last = McElroy |first = Steven |title = Shakespeare, Singing and Solo Shows Galore |newspaper = The New York Times |date = September 10, 2009 |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/theater/13wtheaterlist.html?_r=1&ref=theater |url-status = live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150613085702/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/theater/13wtheaterlist.html?_r=1&ref=theater |archive-date = June 13, 2015 |df = mdy-all}}</ref> The show features an expanded story of the original album, with new characters such as Will, Extraordinary Girl, and Favorite Son.<ref name=\"americanitiotcharaters\">{{Citation |last = Ng |first = David |title = Berkeley Rep announces cast for Green Day's 'American Idiot' |newspaper = Los Angeles Times |date = August 3, 2009 |url = http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2009/08/berkeley-rep-announces-cast-for-green-days-american-idiot.html |url-status = live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090807150058/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2009/08/berkeley-rep-announces-cast-for-green-days-american-idiot.html |archive-date = August 7, 2009 |df = mdy-all}}</ref> On April 20, 2010, ''American Idiot'' opened on Broadway, and Green Day released the [[American Idiot: The Original Broadway Cast Recording|soundtrack]] to the musical, featuring a new song by Green Day entitled \"[[When It's Time]]\". In June 2010 [[iTunes]] released \"When It's Time\" as a single.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/when-its-time/id375645740?i=375645822&ign-mpt=uo%3D2 |title=When It's Time \u2013 Single by Green Day |publisher=iTunes Store |date=June 11, 2010 |access-date=March 14, 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108125922/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/when-its-time/id375645740?i=375645822&ign-mpt=uo%3D2 |archive-date=November 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Greenday2010.jpg|thumb|right|Green Day performing in New Jersey in 2010]]\nDuring the [[Spike Video Game Awards|Spike TV Video Game Awards 2009]], it was announced that Green Day was set to have its own ''Rock Band'' video game titled ''[[Green Day: Rock Band]]'', as a follow-up to the last band specific ''Rock Band'' game, ''[[The Beatles: Rock Band]]''. The game features the full albums of ''[[Dookie]]'', ''[[American Idiot]]'', and ''[[21st Century Breakdown]]'' as well as select songs from the rest of Green Day's discography.<ref name=\"hmxpresser\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockband.com/forums/showthread.php?p=3557574 |title=Green Day: Rock Band \u2013 Release date, pricing, export and preorder info! |last=HMXHenry |date=March 11, 2010 |access-date=March 11, 2010 |publisher=Rock Band Forums |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100314045748/http://www.rockband.com/forums/showthread.php?p=3557574 |archive-date=March 14, 2010 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"g4tv pax east\">{{cite web |url = http://g4tv.com/videos/45111/Green-Day-Rock-Band-Preview/ |title = Green Day Rock Band Preview |first = Abbie |last = Heppe |work = [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4TV]] |date = April 1, 2010 |access-date = April 2, 2010 |url-status = live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111212123446/http://www.g4tv.com/videos/45111/Green-Day-Rock-Band-Preview/ |archive-date = December 12, 2011 |df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the second leg of the [[21st Century Breakdown World Tour]] the band members stated that they were writing new material.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1630900/20100131/green_day.jhtml?rsspartner=rssYahooNewscrawler |title=Green Day : Green Day Say Grammy Win Came At The 'Sweetest Time' \u2013 Rhapsody Music Downloads |publisher=VH1 |access-date=August 22, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312055800/http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1630900/20100131/green_day.jhtml?rsspartner=rssYahooNewscrawler |archive-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Kerrang!]]'' magazine, Armstrong spoke about the possible new album: \"We did some demos in Berlin, some in Stockholm, some just outside of Glasgow and some in Amsterdam. We wanted get [the songs] down in some early form.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.kerrang.com/2010/03/green_day_new_album_exclusive.html |title=Kerrang! Green Day new album exclusive! |publisher=.kerrang.com |access-date=August 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322190329/http://www2.kerrang.com/2010/03/green_day_new_album_exclusive.html |archive-date=March 22, 2010 |df= }}</ref> The band members also stated that the group was recording a live album of the tour, featuring the previously unreleased song \"Cigarettes and Valentines\". In October 2010, Dirnt was interviewed by Radio W, mentioning that the group had completed the writing process of the ninth studio album. In the interview, Dirnt also mentioned that a new live album would \"most likely\" be released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nem-catacoa.com/2010/10/mike-dirnt-bajista-de-la-agrupacion-green-day-habla-en-exclusiva-con-w-radio/ |title=Mike Dirnt talks to Radio W about Green Day's upcoming South American tour (audio interview) |work=Nem Catacoa \u2013 Sonidos de la Tierra |publisher=Radio W |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101213134038/http://www.nem-catacoa.com/2010/10/mike-dirnt-bajista-de-la-agrupacion-green-day-habla-en-exclusiva-con-w-radio/ |archive-date=December 13, 2010 |df= }}</ref> The live CD/DVD and CD/Blu-ray entitled ''[[Awesome as Fuck]]'' was released on March 22, 2011.<ref name=\"Rutherford\">{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Rutherford |title=Green Day Confirms ''Awesome as F**k'' Live Album in New Trailer |date=January 10, 2011 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473709/green-day-confirms-awesome-as-fk-live-album-in-new-trailer |work=Billboard |access-date=January 13, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629045052/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473709/green-day-confirms-awesome-as-fk-live-album-in-new-trailer |archive-date=June 29, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"press release\">{{cite web|title=Green Day to Release Live Album \u2013 ''Awesome as Fuck'' \u2013 on March&nbsp;22nd, 2011, on Reprise Records |publisher=Green Day |url=http://www.greenday.com/article.php?id=2761 |access-date=January 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20110717035538/http://www.greenday.com/article.php?id=2761 |archive-date=July 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|\u00a1Uno!, \u00a1Dos!, and \u00a1Tr\u00e9! (2011\u2013present)}}''\u00a1Uno! \u00a1Dos! \u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' (2011\u20132014) ===\n[[File:Green day Live 5 june 2013 in Rome.JPG|thumb|right|Green Day performing in 2013]]\n\nDuring the end of 2011, the band played several secret shows (under the name [[Foxboro Hot Tubs]]) whose setlists consisted almost entirely of previously unheard songs. Green Day entered the studio and began recording new material in February 2012, later announcing a trilogy of albums titled ''\u00a1Uno!'', ''\u00a1Dos!'', and ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' which would be released in the fall of 2012.<ref name=\"Album Trio Press Release\">{{cite web|title=Green Day in the Studio Recording Three Albums \u2013 A Trilogy Entitled \u00a1Uno!, \u00a1Dos!, And \u00a1Tr\u00e9! Albums to be Released From September 2012 to January 2013 |url=http://greenday.com/node/7541 |date=April 11, 2012 |access-date=April 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721004314/http://greenday.com/node/7541 |archive-date=July 21, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1679342/green-day-new-music-studio.jhtml|title=Green Day Start Recording New Album|publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[MTV Networks]]|first=James|last=Montgomery|date=February 15, 2012|access-date=June 15, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203162346/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1679342/green-day-new-music-studio.jhtml|archive-date=December 3, 2013}}</ref> The trilogy marked longtime touring guitarist [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White's]] induction as the fourth member of the band.<ref name=\"Alan Di Perna\">{{cite magazine|url= http://gdaimages.s3.amazonaws.com/articles/guitarworld_110112_7.jpg|title= Green Day make the biggest move of their career|access-date= November 12, 2012|author= Alan Di Perna|date= November 12, 2012|magazine= Guitar World|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130819042911/http://gdaimages.s3.amazonaws.com/articles/guitarworld_110112_7.jpg|archive-date= August 19, 2013|df= mdy-all}}</ref> That summer Green Day played several festivals and promotional shows including the [[Rock en Seine]] festival in France, the Rock am See festival in Germany, and the [[Reading Festival]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|title=ROCK EN SEINE 2012 FRANCE |url=http://greenday.com/rock-en-seine-2012-france |access-date=May 31, 2012 |publisher=Green Day |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519213251/http://greenday.com/rock-en-seine-2012-france |archive-date=May 19, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Green Day to Headline Music Festival in Germany |url=http://greenday.com/node/6991/ |access-date=May 31, 2012 |publisher=Green Day |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522025050/http://www.greenday.com/node/6991 |archive-date=May 22, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:RiP2013 GreenDay Billie Joe Armstrong 0013.JPG|thumb|left|Armstrong performing with Green Day in 2013]]\n''[[\u00a1Uno!]]'', ''[[\u00a1Dos!]]'', and ''[[\u00a1Tr\u00e9!]]'' were released on September 21, November 9, and December 7, 2012, respectively and were met with generally positive reviews from critics, though fans were more lukewarm towards the albums. On January 22, 2013, the band announced that ''[[\u00a1Cuatro!]]'', a documentary about the making of ''\u00a1Uno!, \u00a1Dos!'' and ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'', would premiere on January 26 in Aspen, Colorado as part of the X Games FILM showcase, and would be released on DVD April 9, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Green Day's \u00a1Cuatro!|url=http://xgames.espn.go.com/scene/article/8868898/green-day-mike-dirnt-breaks-making-%C2%A1cuatro|publisher=ESPN|access-date=January 24, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126133036/http://xgames.espn.go.com/scene/article/8868898/green-day-mike-dirnt-breaks-making-%C2%A1cuatro|archive-date=January 26, 2013}}</ref> Another documentary was announced called ''Broadway Idiot'' which focuses on the creation on the [[American Idiot (musical)|American Idiot musical]] and Armstrong's run as playing the character of St. Jimmy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://broadwayidiot.com |title=Broadway Idiot is a documentary following Billie Joe Armstrong's journey from punk rock to Broadway |publisher=Broadway Idiot |access-date=April 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424063441/http://broadwayidiot.com/ |archive-date=April 24, 2013}}</ref> On March 10, 2013, Green Day began its [[99 Revolutions Tour]] to support the trilogy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greenday.com/news/green-days-armstrong-returns-authority-providence-ri-149946 |title=Green Day'S Armstrong Returns With Authority \u2013 Providence, Ri \u2013 Green Day Official News |publisher=Greenday.com |access-date=April 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425105046/http://www.greenday.com/news/green-days-armstrong-returns-authority-providence-ri-149946 |archive-date=April 25, 2013}}</ref> In June, Green Day broke [[Emirates Stadium]] attendance record with 60,000 tickets sold.<ref name=\"Emirates Stadium record\">{{cite web|last=Green Day Emirates Stadium|title=Green Day Emirates Stadium|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/82125/green-day-break-emirates-stadium-attendance-record|access-date=March 22, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322083258/http://www.gigwise.com/news/82125/green-day-break-emirates-stadium-attendance-record|archive-date=March 22, 2014}}</ref> The band played ''Dookie'' from start to finish on several dates on the tour's European leg, including during the [[Reading Festival]] 2013 headline show.<ref name=\"Green Day Reading\">{{cite web|title=Green Day Reading|url=http://www.nme.com/news/green-day/72222|work=NME|access-date=March 22, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023133755/http://www.nme.com/news/green-day/72222|archive-date=October 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''[[Demolicious]]'', a compilation album that contains alternate versions and demos of songs from ''\u00a1Uno!'', ''\u00a1Dos!'' and ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' recorded during the studio sessions of these albums, was released on April 19, 2014, for [[Record Store Day]]. It also contains a previously unreleased song called \"State of Shock\" and an acoustic version of \"Stay the Night\", from ''\u00a1Uno!''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Green Day's Demolicious|title=Green Day's Demolicious|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/green-day-to-issue-18-rarities-for-record-store-day-20140224|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=March 22, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302122659/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/green-day-to-issue-18-rarities-for-record-store-day-20140224|archive-date=March 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, ''Revolution Radio'', new greatest hits compilation (2015\u20132017) ===\n[[File:Green Day House OF Blues 2015 2.jpg|thumb|right|Green Day performing in [[Cleveland, Ohio]] in 2015]]\n\nGreen Day performed its first concert in a year on April 16, 2015. The group first played a set as Sweet Children with [[John Kiffmeyer]], followed by a set as Green Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/04/green-day-reunites-with-original-drummer-and-performs-as-sweet-children-watch/|title=Green Day reunites with original drummer and performs as Sweet Children \u2014 watch|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=April 19, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418184054/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/04/green-day-reunites-with-original-drummer-and-performs-as-sweet-children-watch/|archive-date=April 18, 2015}}</ref> On April 18, 2015, Green Day were inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame by [[Fall Out Boy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/read-fall-out-boys-loving-green-day-tribute-at-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-20150418|title=Read Fall Out Boy's Green Day Rock Hall of Fame Induction|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 19, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419100122/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/read-fall-out-boys-loving-green-day-tribute-at-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-20150418|archive-date=April 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2015, Rob Cavallo revealed Green Day were recording a twelfth studio album. Cavallo claimed to have heard \"five new songs that Billie has written and demoed\", and that the fans should be \"sure that when they do return, the music will be amazing\".<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.nme.com/news/green-day/84864|title = Green Day have written 'five fantastic new songs', says their producer|last = Morgan Britton|first = Luke|date = April 24, 2015|work = NME|access-date = April 27, 2015|url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150427010856/http://www.nme.com/news/green-day/84864|archive-date = April 27, 2015|df = mdy-all}}</ref> On December 24, 2015, Green Day released a Christmas song, \"[[Xmas Time of the Year]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carter|first1=Emily|title=Green Day Release New Song, Xmas Time of the Year|url=http://www.kerrang.com/39008/green-day-release-new-song-xmas-time-of-the-year/|website=Kerrang!|publisher=Kerrang|access-date=December 24, 2015|date=December 24, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225060710/http://www.kerrang.com/39008/green-day-release-new-song-xmas-time-of-the-year/|archive-date=December 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2016, Green Day released the first single, \"[[Bang Bang (Green Day song)|Bang Bang]]\",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ralph|first1=Caitlyn|title=Green Day announce new song, \"Bang Bang\"|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/green_days_new_album_is_reportedly_finished_announcement_coming_soon|website=AP|agency=Associated Press|access-date=August 1, 2016|date=August 1, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802150442/http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/green_days_new_album_is_reportedly_finished_announcement_coming_soon|archive-date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> from the group's album ''[[Revolution Radio]]'', which was released on October 7, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenday.com/revolutionradio |title=Revolution Radio &#124; New Album 10/7 |publisher=Green Day |date=June 30, 2016 |access-date=October 8, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008215817/http://www.greenday.com/revolutionradio |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Jason White returned to being a touring member, and the band confirmed that he would not appear on the album.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/billie-joe-armstrong-on-green-days-topical-new-lp-w433483|title=Billie Joe Armstrong on Green Day's Provocative New LP|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=August 11, 2016|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=October 8, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012140554/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/billie-joe-armstrong-on-green-days-topical-new-lp-w433483|archive-date=October 12, 2016}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2017}} The band went on [[Revolution Radio Tour|a world tour supporting the album]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leight|first1=Elias|title=Green Day Announce|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/green-day-announce-north-american-european-tour-dates-w438066|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=September 6, 2016|date=September 6, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906171156/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/green-day-announce-north-american-european-tour-dates-w438066|archive-date=September 6, 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, the band performed at the [[American Music Awards]] in Los Angeles and made a political statement about the then-recent US election of [[Donald Trump]] by chanting \"No Trump, No KKK, No Fascist USA\" during their rendition of \"Bang Bang\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2016/nov/21/green-day-protest-at-amas-no-trump-no-kkk-no-fascist-usa-video|title=Green Day protest at AMAs: 'No Trump, no KKK, no fascist USA' \u2013 video|last=|first=|date=November 21, 2016|work=|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=November 21, 2016|via=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121105017/https://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2016/nov/21/green-day-protest-at-amas-no-trump-no-kkk-no-fascist-usa-video|archive-date=November 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAaron Burgess at ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' observed, \"It's the first time in years Green Day haven't had all the answers. But as a statement on how it really feels to fight, it's the closest to the truth they've ever gotten. Gwilym Mumford of ''[[The Guardian]]'' stated \"[after their last few albums] the band have decided to get back to basics: ''Revolution Radio'' is their most focused work in years. Lead single Bang Bang sets the tone, with a caustic consideration of the fame-hungry psychosis of a mass shooter.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe band released their second greatest hits compilation, ''[[God's Favorite Band]]'', on November 17, 2017. It contains 20 of their hits, along with two new tracks: a new version of the ''Revolution Radio'' track \"Ordinary World\", featuring country singer [[Miranda Lambert]], and a previously unreleased song titled \"Back in the USA\".{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== ''Father of All Motherfuckers'' and continued activity (2018\u2013present) ===\nOn April 13, 2019, for [[Record Store Day]], the band released their [[Woodstock 1994 (Green Day album)|Woodstock 1994]] performance on vinyl for the first time. It contains all 9 songs they played live, as well as audio of the ensuing mudfight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://recordstoreday.com/SpecialRelease/10744|title=RSD '19 Special Release: Green Day - Woodstock 1994}}</ref>  \n\nOn September 10, 2019, the band announced the [[Hella Mega Tour]] with [[Fall Out Boy]] and [[Weezer]] as headliners alongside themselves, with [[The Interrupters (band)|The Interrupters]] as the opening act. They also released the single, \"[[Father of All... (song)|Father of All...]]\" off their thirteenth album, ''[[Father of All Motherfuckers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Greene|first1=Andy|title=Green Day, Weezer, Fall Out Boy Announce 2020 'Hella Mega' Stadium Tour|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/green-day-weezer-fall-out-boy-2020-hella-mega-tour-882156/|website=rollingstone.com|access-date=September 10, 2019|language=en|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 30, 2019, Green Day signed a two-year agreement with the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-green-day-two-year-partnership/c-309587012|title=NHL, Green Day announce two-year partnership|date=September 30, 2019|website=nhl.com|accessdate=September 30, 2019}}</ref> ''Father of All Motherfuckers'' was released on February 7, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/green-day-announce-new-single-and-confirm-father-of-all-tracklist/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114093003/https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/green-day-announce-new-single-and-confirm-father-of-all-tracklist/ |archive-date=January 14, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2020, Armstrong revealed that he had written six songs with the intention of recording new music with the band once the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] had passed.<ref>https://www.nme.com/news/music/billie-joe-armstrong-written-six-new-green-day-songs-during-lockdown-2641862?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=billie-joe-armstrong-written-six-new-green-day-songs-during-lockdown&amp</ref>\n\n== Musical style and influences ==\n[[File:Green Day King for a Day.jpg|thumb|left|Green Day performing \"King for a Day\", a [[ska]]-inspired song featuring saxophones and trumpets.]]\n\nGreen Day's sound is often compared to first wave [[punk rock]] bands such as the [[Ramones]], [[The Clash]], [[The Dickies]], and the [[Buzzcocks]].<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Stylistically, the group is characterized as punk rock,<ref name=\"Miami New Times\">{{cite news|first=Zac|last=Crain|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/music/green-day-family-values-6360499|title=Green Day Family Values|newspaper=Miami New Times|date=October 23, 1997|access-date=August 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"consequenceofsound\">{{cite magazine|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2016/10/green-days-top-20-songs/|title=Green Day's Top 20 Songs|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=October 2, 2016|access-date=August 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"m sacurrent\">{{cite web|url=https://m.sacurrent.com/sa-sound/archives/2017/09/11/green-day-destroys-san-antonio|title=Green Day Destroys San Antonio|last=Conde|first=Chris|access-date=February 18, 2018|publisher=Sacurrent|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002125911/https://m.sacurrent.com/sa-sound/archives/2017/09/11/green-day-destroys-san-antonio|archive-date=October 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2012/06/green-day-realize-they-are-not-really-99-percent/ |title=Green Day Realize They Are Not Really the 99 Percent |last=Maloney |first=Dan |date=June 20, 2012 |website=SPIN.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418032241/https://www.spin.com/2012/06/green-day-realize-they-are-not-really-99-percent/ |archive-date=April 18, 2015 |url-status=live |access-date=February 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Glenn|last=Gamboa|url=https://www.simplemost.com/billie-joe-armstrong-green-day-new-band/|title=Billie Joe Armstrong From Green Day Has A New Band|publisher=Simplemost|date=July 17, 2017|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219090355/https://www.simplemost.com/billie-joe-armstrong-green-day-new-band/|archive-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> {{nowrap|[[pop punk]],}}<ref name=\"Miami New Times\"/><ref name=\"consequenceofsound\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/sep/13/entertainment/ca-green-day13|title=Turning Green Day's 'American Idiot' into a rock opera|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=June 12, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150614204931/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/sep/13/entertainment/ca-green-day13|archive-date=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"AllmusicBio\">{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/artist/green-day-p69310/biography|title=Green Day \u2013 Biography|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen|access-date=July 20, 2011|website=AllMusic|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606113024/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/green-day-p69310/biography|archive-date=June 6, 2011}}</ref> [[alternative rock]],<ref name=\"m sacurrent\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=|editor1-last=Abbey|editor1-first=Cherie D.|title=Biography Today Vol. 11 No. 3|date=September 2002|publisher=Omnigraphics, Inc.|isbn=0-7808-0499-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/biographytodayvo0000unse_o8a5/page/17 17]|chapter=Aaron Carter 1987-|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/biographytodayvo0000unse_o8a5/page/17}}</ref> [[pop rock]],<ref name=\"consequenceofsound\"/> [[post-punk]],<ref name=\"histaltrock\">{{cite book |last1=Kallen |first1=Stuart A |title=The History of Alternative Rock |date=9 May 2019 |publisher=Greenhaven Publishing LLC |isbn=9781420509724 |page=97 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UVtmDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA97 |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> and {{nowrap|[[power pop]]}}.<ref name=\"Miami New Times\"/> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] described Green Day as \"[[punk revival]]ists who recharged the energy of speedy, catchy three-chord punk-pop songs.\"<ref name=\"AllmusicBio\"/> While Armstrong is the primary songwriter, he looks to the other band members for organizational help.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/entertainment/music/2009/07/03/10010606-sun.html|title=You think I'm funny?|access-date=July 3, 2009|first=Darryl|last=Sterdan|date=July 3, 2009|work=Toronto Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706091202/http://www.torontosun.com/entertainment/music/2009/07/03/10010606-sun.html|archive-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref> Billie Joe Armstrong has mentioned that some of his biggest influences are seminal alternative rock bands [[H\u00fcsker D\u00fc]] and [[The Replacements (band)|the Replacements]], and that their influence is particularly noted in the band's chord changes in songs.<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Green Day has covered H\u00fcsker D\u00fc's \"[[Don't Want to Know If You Are Lonely]]\" as a B-side to the \"Warning\" single, and the character \"Mr. Whirly\" in the group's song \"Misery\" is a reference to the Replacements song of the same name.<ref>Di Perna, Alan. \"Far From The Maddening Crowd\". ''Guitar World''. December 2000.</ref> Among other influences, Green Day have also cited [[the Kinks]], [[the Who]] and [[power pop]] pioneers [[Cheap Trick]].<ref name=\"RWAC\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/music/a34429/musicians-inspired-by-the-who/ |title=8 Massive Musicians Who Were Influenced By The Who |last=Drozynski |first=Kate |date=April 17, 2015 |website=Esquire.com |access-date=February 10, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809210108/http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/music/a34429/musicians-inspired-by-the-who/ |archive-date=August 9, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Spin Interview\">\"{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2009/05/green-day-we-love-who-and-cheap-trick/|title=Green Day: \"We Love the Who and Cheap Trick\"|last=Goodman|first=William|work=[[Spin Magazine]] Online|access-date=May 14, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515005910/https://www.spin.com/2009/05/green-day-we-love-who-and-cheap-trick/|archive-date=May 15, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> English rock musician [[Noel Gallagher]] of [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] complained about the band semi-jokingly, claiming that the band had ripped off his song \"[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]\" with its song \"[[Boulevard of Broken Dreams (Green Day song)|Boulevard of Broken Dreams]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/a40981/noel-gallagher-hits-out-at-green-day.html|title=Noel Gallagher hits out at Green Day|access-date=July 3, 2009|first=Matt|last=Houghton|date=December 21, 2006|work=Digital Spy|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010192701/http://www.digitalspy.com/music/a40981/noel-gallagher-hits-out-at-green-day.html|archive-date=October 10, 2009}}</ref> Green Day has cited Operation Ivy as a big influence.<ref name=\"PunksNotDeadMovie\" /><ref name=\"Spitz\" /> In August 1996, Billie Joe Armstrong told ''[[Guitar World]]'' he \"can remember a few different instances\" of when he first discovered punk rock: \"There were these two guys who introduced me to things like [[D.O.A. (band)|D.O.A.]] and the [[Dead Kennedys]]. Then, in the seventh grade, there was a girl at school who would bring in records like [[T.S.O.L.]] and say, 'Here, listen to this.'\"<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Armstrong said he thinks he \"really started getting into\" punk rock \"in 1987 with ''[[Turn It Around!]]'', a double seven-inch compilation record put out by [punk fanzine] ''[[Maximumrocknroll]]''.\"<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Armstrong cited ''Turn It Around!'' as an influence, calling it \"a pretty big record for\" him.<ref name=TenQuestions>{{cite web |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1997442,00.html |title=10 Questions for Billie Joe Armstrong |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=June 28, 2010 |access-date=October 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Green Day has been compared to the Buzzcocks, the Ramones and the Clash, Mike Dirnt said he had never heard the Buzzcocks when Green Day began.<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Dirnt said: \"First off, you can't sound like any of those bands. And secondly, those are probably the last ones in my record collection.\"<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Armstrong responded to Dirnt, saying: \"Mine too. Those are all bands I got into later.\"<ref name=\"snotty\" /> [[The Dickies]] is another band Green Day has been compared to.<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Dirnt said he \"never owned a Dickies album, although\" he \"did see\" the Dickies live \"around the time of\" ''Kerplunk!''. Dirnt said \"by that time, we'd played so many shows it really had no bearing.\"<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Armstrong referred to the Dickies as \"just another Ramones rip-off\".<ref name=\"snotty\" /> Although in August 1996, Armstrong said bands like the Ramones are bands he listened to later, in June 2010, Armstrong cited the Ramones as an influence. He also said his \"range of favorite songwriters goes anywhere from the [[Sex Pistols]] all the way to [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]].<ref name=TenQuestions/> During the ''[[American Idiot]]'' and ''[[21st Century Breakdown]]'' era of Green Day, the band was influenced by The Who, [[U2]], [[Motown]] albums, and musicals such as ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/green-day-and-the-palace-of-wisdom-20050224|title=Green Day and the Palace of Wisdom|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=October 16, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608015044/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/green-day-and-the-palace-of-wisdom-20050224|archive-date=June 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe band's 1992 album ''Kerplunk'' is one of the best selling independent albums of all time, selling over 4.5 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://loudwire.com/green-day-kerplunk-album-anniversary/ |title=26 Years Ago: Green Day Take a Step Toward Success With 'Kerplunk' |last=Childers |first=Chad |date=January 17, 2018 |access-date=February 10, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211131201/http://loudwire.com/green-day-kerplunk-album-anniversary/ |archive-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGreen Day is credited (alongside [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]], [[Bad Religion]], the [[The Offspring|Offspring]], and [[Rancid (band)|Rancid]]) with popularizing mainstream interest in punk rock in the United States.<ref>DeRogatis, Jim. ''Milk It!: Collected Musings on the Alternative Music Explosion of the 90s''. Cambridge: Da Capo, 2003. p. 357, {{ISBN|0-306-81271-1}}</ref><ref name=\"punk revival\">{{cite web |author=D'Angelo, Joe |year=2004 |title=How Green Day's Dookie Fertilize d A Punk-Rock Revival |publisher=MTV |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1491001/20040915/story.jhtml |access-date=July 26, 2006 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022232353/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1491001/green-days-dookie-pop-punk-fertilizer.jhtml |archive-date=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Punk Rock: An Oral History |url=https://archive.org/details/punkrockoralhist00robb |url-access=registration |last=Robb |first=John |publisher=PM Press, Ebury Press |isbn=978-1-60486-005-4 |quote=I saw Green Day, Rancid and the Offspring, taking punk to the mall rats and the stadiums with multi-million-selling albums. |page=[https://archive.org/details/punkrockoralhist00robb/page/537 537] |year=2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Luciano, Phil |title=Sublime to perform with new singer |date=July 14, 2011 |url=http://www.pjstar.com/entertainment/x1850043729/Sublime-to-perform-with-new-singer |newspaper=[[Journal Star (Peoria)|pjstar.com]] |access-date=July 19, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402235442/http://www.pjstar.com/entertainment/x1850043729/Sublime-to-perform-with-new-singer |archive-date=April 2, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Particularly the album ''[[Dookie]]'',<ref>{{cite web |author=Joe D'angelo |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1491001/how-green-days-dookie-fertilized-a-punk-rock-revival/ |title=How Green Day's Dookie Fertilized A Punk-Rock Revival |publisher=MTV.com |date=September 15, 2004 |access-date=June 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716054856/http://www.mtv.com/news/1491001/how-green-days-dookie-fertilized-a-punk-rock-revival/ |archive-date=July 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Melissa Bobbitt |url=http://90srock.about.com/od/Reviews/fl/The-Offsprings-Smash-Turns-20.htm |title=The Offspring's 'Smash' Turns 20 |publisher=[[About.com]] |date=April 8, 2014 |access-date=June 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712100116/http://90srock.about.com/od/Reviews/fl/The-Offsprings-Smash-Turns-20.htm |archive-date=July 12, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"punktomainstream\">{{cite news|author=Zac Crain |url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/1997-10-23/music/green-day-family-values/ |title=Green Day Family Values \u2013 Page 1 \u2013 Music \u2013 Miami |newspaper=Miami New Times |date=October 23, 1997 |access-date=September 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522215802/http://www.miaminewtimes.com/1997-10-23/music/green-day-family-values/ |archive-date=May 22, 2014 }}</ref> which was cited by [[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]] as the most important [[pop punk]] album of all time and named the best alternative album of 1994 by ''Rolling Stone''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2014/01/green-day-dookie-20-years |title=Green Day's 'Dookie' Turns 20: Musicians Revisit the Punk Classic \u2013 Features \u2013 Fuse |work=Fuse |access-date=February 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223080343/http://www.fuse.tv/2014/01/green-day-dookie-20-years |archive-date=February 23, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"rollingstonetop40\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/1994-the-40-best-records-from-mainstream-alternatives-greatest-year-20140417/green-day-dookie-19691231 |title=1994\u2013 The 40 Best Records From Mainstream Alternative's Greatest Year \u2013 Rolling Stone |date=April 17, 2014 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=May 23, 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419223450/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/1994-the-40-best-records-from-mainstream-alternatives-greatest-year-20140417/green-day-dookie-19691231 |archive-date=April 19, 2014}}</ref> It was also placed on the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]'s \"Definitive 200\" list of 200 classic albums.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.definitive200.com/200_list.php |title=The Definitive 200 |access-date=August 18, 2007 |publisher=Rock and Roll Hall of Fame|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070813004137/http://www.definitive200.com/200_list.php|archive-date =August 13, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Both ''Dookie'' and ''American Idiot'' appeared on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].<ref name=\"rs500\">{{cite magazine|url=http://archive.rollingstone.com/Desktop?s=2003121144#/20031211/83|title=The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|access-date=July 16, 2007|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=December 10, 2003|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120012459/http://archive.rollingstone.com/Desktop?s=2003121144#/20031211/83|archive-date=January 20, 2013}}{{Subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/green-day-american-idiot-20120524|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time|website=Rollinstone.com|access-date=November 17, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114172224/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/green-day-american-idiot-20120524|archive-date=November 14, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2011, they were voted best punk rock band of all time by Rolling Stone magazine.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/readers-poll-the-best-punk-rock-bands-of-all-time-15225/5-the-dead-kennedys-119199/ |title=Readers Poll: The Best Punk Rock Bands of All Time |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2011-08-02 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nGreen Day has sold more than 75 million records worldwide making them one of the highest selling artists of all time. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/10/09/rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-nominees-green-day-nine-inch-nails-lou-reed/16852249/|title=Green Day, Nine Inch Nails among Rock Hall nominees|work=[[USA Today]]|date=October 9, 2014|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The group has been nominated for 20 Grammy awards and has won five of them with [[Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Album]] for ''[[Dookie]]'', [[Best Rock Album]] for ''[[American Idiot]]'' and ''[[21st Century Breakdown]]'', [[Record of the Year]] for \"[[Boulevard of Broken Dreams (Green Day song)|Boulevard of Broken Dreams]]\", and [[Best Musical Show Album]] for ''[[American Idiot: The Original Broadway Cast Recording]]''.\n\nIn 2010, a [[American Idiot (musical)|stage adaptation of ''American Idiot'']] debuted on Broadway. The musical was nominated for three [[Tony Awards]]: <ref> [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best {{cite news|url=http://diffuser.fm/green-day-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-2015/|title=Green Day Join the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's Class of 2015|work=[[Diffuser.fm|Diffuser]] |date=April 18, 2015|first=Derrick|last=Rossignol |access-date=December 11, 2016 |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222102530/http://diffuser.fm/green-day-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-2015/|archive-date=February 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/495331/vh1-100-greatest-artists-of-all-time/franchises/list/ |title=VH1 100 Greatest Artists Of All Time |last=Stosuy |first=Brandon |date=September 3, 2010 |website=Sterogum |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412055609/https://www.stereogum.com/495331/vh1-100-greatest-artists-of-all-time/franchises/list/ |access-date=February 10, 2018 |archive-date=April 12, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The band was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in April 2015, their first year of eligibility.<ref name=\"RRHF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2015/04/green_day_takes_its_rightful_p.html|title=Green Day takes its rightful place in the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame|last=Smith|first=Troy|work=The Plain Dealer|date=April 18, 2015|access-date=April 19, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419040028/http://www.cleveland.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2015/04/green_day_takes_its_rightful_p.html|archive-date=April 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe band has been cited as an influence by wide variety of artists from different genres which includes [[Fall Out Boy]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Rolling Stone |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/read-fall-out-boys-loving-green-day-tribute-at-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-101167/ |title=Read Fall Out Boy's Green Day Rock Hall of Fame Induction |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2015-04-19 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Blink 182]], [[Weezer]], [[Slipknot (band)| Slipknot]], [[New Found Glory]], [[Lady Gaga]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lady-gaga-522-1311823 |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319090039/https://www.nme.com/news/music/lady-gaga-522-1311823 |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Kid Cudi]], [[Billie Eilish]], [[Avril Lavigne]], [[The Click Five]], [[My Chemical Romance]], [[Shakira]], etc.\n\n== Related projects ==\n{{Main|Green Day related projects}}\nSince 1991, members of the band have branched out past Green Day, starting other projects with various musicians. Notable projects related to Green Day include Billie Joe Armstrong's [[Pinhead Gunpowder]] with Jason White and [[The Longshot (band)|The Longshot]] with Jeff Matika, [[The Frustrators]] with Mike Dirnt, and [[The Network]], a collaboration between Green Day and members of the band [[Devo]] in which all members play under fake stage names.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1479481/10022003/green_day.jhtml |title=Did Green Day Secretly Release A New Album Tuesday? Only The Snoo Knows |publisher=VH1 |access-date=September 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312054559/http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1479481/10022003/green_day.jhtml |archive-date=March 12, 2010 |df= }}</ref> Green Day has also released an album titled ''[[Stop Drop and Roll!!!]]'' on May 20, 2008, under the name [[Foxboro Hot Tubs]], which the band uses to book secret shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1585150/20080410/green_day.jhtml |title='Green Day Confirm They Are Foxboro Hot Tubs', MTV News |publisher=MTV |date=April 10, 2008 |access-date=October 10, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315033524/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1585150/20080410/green_day.jhtml |archive-date=March 15, 2010}}</ref> In late December 2011, Armstrong formed a family band called The Boo which recorded a one off Christmas record for their friends and family making a few copies available in a local store.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/2877|title=Adrienne tweets about the new Armstrong family band \"The Boo\"|author=|date=|work=greendayauthority.com|access-date=November 13, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114083003/http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/2877/|archive-date=November 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/2883|title=A couple of tracks from \"The Boo\" up on YouTube|author=|date=|work=greendayauthority.com|access-date=November 13, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113911/http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/2883/|archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/thebooband/|title=the boo band|author=|date=|work=facebook.com|access-date=November 13, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404052624/https://www.facebook.com/thebooband/|archive-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/2881/|title=Pick up a copy of \"The Boo's\" album at 1\u20132\u20133\u20134 Go! Records|author=|date=|work=greendayauthority.com|access-date=November 13, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113175418/http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/2881/|archive-date=November 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006, Green Day collaborated with [[U2]] and producer [[Rick Rubin]] to record a cover of the song \"[[The Saints Are Coming]]\", originally recorded by [[The Skids]], with an accompanying video. The song was recorded to benefit [[Music Rising]], an organization to help raise money for musicians' instruments lost during [[Hurricane Katrina]], and to bring awareness on the eve of the one-year anniversary of the disaster.<ref>[http://musicrising.org/about/ About Music Rising] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331090201/http://musicrising.org/about/ |date=March 31, 2009}}. Retrieved May 6, 2007.</ref> In December 2006, Green Day and [[Natural Resources Defense Council|NRDC]] opened a web site in partnership to raise awareness on America's dependency on oil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrdc.org/media/pressreleases/061116a.asp|title=Green Day teams up with green group in campaign to 'move America beyond oil'|last=Hinerfeld|first=Daniel|date=November 17, 2006|publisher=[[Natural Resources Defense Council]]|access-date=December 19, 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927204004/http://www.nrdc.org/media/pressreleases/061116a.asp|archive-date=September 27, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendaynrdc.com/|title=Green Day + NRDC; the \"Move America Beyond Oil\" campaign and other environmental concerns|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113212544/http://www.greendaynrdc.com/|archive-date=January 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nGreen Day released a cover of the [[John Lennon]] song \"[[Working Class Hero]]\", which was featured on the album ''[[Instant Karma: The Amnesty International Campaign to Save Darfur]]''. The band performed the song on the season finale of ''[[American Idol]]''. The song was nominated for a [[50th Grammy Awards|Grammy Award in 2008]] but lost to [[The White Stripes]]' \"[[Icky Thump]]\". That summer, the band appeared in a cameo role in ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'', where the band performs [[The Simpsons Theme|the show's theme song]]; Green Day's version was released as a single on July 23, 2007.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Book|first1=Ryan|title=9 Great Cameos from Musicians on 'The Simpsons': Michael Jackson, The Rolling Stones, Weird Al and More|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/9121/20140822/9-great-cameos-musicians-simpsons-michael-jackson-rolling-stones-weird.htm|journal=Music Times|access-date=June 11, 2015|date=August 22, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222113641/http://www.musictimes.com/articles/9121/20140822/9-great-cameos-musicians-simpsons-michael-jackson-rolling-stones-weird.htm|archive-date=December 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Montgomery|first1=James|title='Simpsons Movie' Cast Discusses Green Day's Appearance In Film|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1559169/simpsons-movie-cast-discusses-green-days-appearance-in-film/|publisher=MTV|access-date=June 11, 2015|date=May 9, 2007|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612072907/http://www.mtv.com/news/1559169/simpsons-movie-cast-discusses-green-days-appearance-in-film/|archive-date=June 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Simpsons Theme (From \"the Simpsons Movie\") \u2013 Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/simpsons-theme-from-simpsons/id259702047|publisher=iTunes Store|access-date=June 11, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708065805/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/simpsons-theme-from-simpsons/id259702047|archive-date=July 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Conniff|first1=Tamara|title=Mmmmm, soundtrack: 'Simpsons' team effort|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/features/columns/music_reporter/e3i100bdf32d950877f04f3f3dce9e59d2a|work=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=dead|access-date=June 11, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701095344/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/features/columns/music_reporter/e3i100bdf32d950877f04f3f3dce9e59d2a|archive-date=July 1, 2007|date=May 24, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the band collaborated with theater director [[Michael Mayer (director)|Michael Mayer]] to adapt the group's [[rock opera]] ''American Idiot'' into a one-act stage [[American Idiot (musical)|musical]] that premiered at the [[Berkeley Rep]] on September 15, 2009. The show then moved to Broadway on April 20, 2010. The reviews of ''American Idiot: The Musical'' have been positive to mixed. Charles Isherwood of [[The New York Times]] wrote an enthusiastic review for the Broadway production. He called the show \"a pulsating portrait of wasted youth that invokes all the standard genre conventions ... only to transcend them through the power of its music and the artistry of its execution, the show is as invigorating and ultimately as moving as anything I\u2019ve seen on Broadway this season. Or maybe for a few seasons past.\" Jed Gottlieb of the [[Boston Herald]] enjoyed the premise of the show but found that \"the music and message suffer in a setting where the audience is politely, soberly seated\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bostonherald.com/entertainment/arts_culture/view.bg?articleid=1248227&position=0|title=Tale told by 'Idiot' lacks sound, fury|last=Gottlieb|first=Jay|work=[[Boston Herald]]|date=April 19, 2010|access-date=December 19, 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007042217/http://bostonherald.com/entertainment/arts_culture/view.bg?articleid=1248227&position=0|archive-date=October 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMichael Kuchiwara of the [[Associated Press]] found the show to be \"visually striking [and] musically adventurous\", but noted that \"the show has the barest wisp of a story and minimal character development\". Paul Kolnik in [[USA Today]] enjoyed the contradiction that Green Day's \"massively popular, starkly disenchanted album ... would be the feel-good musical of the season\". ''Time'' magazine's Richard Zoglin opined that the score \"is as pure a specimen of contemporary punk rock as Broadway has yet encountered, [yet] there's enough variety. ... Where the show fall short is as a fully developed narrative.\" He concluded that \"''American Idiot'', despite its earnest huffing and puffing, remains little more than an annotated rock concert. ... Still, [it] deserves at least two cheers \u2013 for its irresistible musical energy and for opening fresh vistas for that odd couple, rock and Broadway.\"<ref>Zoglin, Richard. \"Punks Take Broadway\", ''Time'' magazine, May 3, 2010, pp. 62\u201363</ref> Peter Travers from [[Rolling Stone]], in his review of ''American Idiot'', wrote \"Though ''American Idiot'' carries echoes of such rock musicals as ''[[Tommy (The Who album)|Tommy]]'', ''[[Hair (musical)|Hair]]'', ''[[Rent (musical)|Rent]]'' and ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'', it cuts its own path to the heart. You won\u2019t know what hit you. ''American Idiot'' knows no limits\u2014it's a global knockout.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/green-day-blast-broadway-with-american-idiot-20100423|last=Travis|first=Peter|title=Green Day Blast Broadway with American Idiot|work=Rolling Stone|date=April 23, 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613162546/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/green-day-blast-broadway-with-american-idiot-20100423|archive-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> The musical has been nominated for three [[Tony Awards]], including [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]] and [[Tony Award for Best Scenic Design|Best Scenic Design]]. It was also nominated for a number of [[Drama Desk Awards]] and [[Outer Critics Circle Awards]].\n\nIn October 2009, a Green Day art project was exhibited at StolenSpace Gallery in London. The exhibition showed artworks created for each of the songs on ''21st Century Breakdown'', was supported by the band, and led by the group's manager Pat Magnarella.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/6music/news/20091023_green_day.shtml|title=Green Day inspired art goes on display|access-date=October 24, 2009|first=Alex|last=Waez|date=October 23, 2006|publisher=BBC 6 Music News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028063117/http://www.bbc.co.uk/6music/news/20091023_green_day.shtml|archive-date=October 28, 2009}}</ref> He explained in an interview that \"[Artists are] basically like rock bands. Most are creating their art, but don't know how to promote it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.artdesigncafe.com/Pat-Magnarella-Green-Day-Broadway-Calls-Logan-Hicks-Charming-Baker-Art-Design-Publicity-1-4-2009|title= Pat Magnarella, Green Day manager: Why not a rock 'n' roll art world?|access-date= October 24, 2009|author= R.J. Preece|date= October 12, 2006|publisher= Art Design Publicity|url-status= live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20091015071553/http://www.artdesigncafe.com/Pat-Magnarella-Green-Day-Broadway-Calls-Logan-Hicks-Charming-Baker-Art-Design-Publicity-1-4-2009|archive-date= October 15, 2009|df= mdy-all}}</ref> For Billie Joe Armstrong, \"Many of the artists... show their work on the street, and we feel a strong connection to that type of creative expression.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/around-town/events/Green-Day-Turns-Punk-Rock-Into-Fine-Art.html|title=Green Day Turns Punk Rock Into Fine Art|access-date=October 24, 2009|first=Sajid|last=Farooq|date=October 23, 2006|publisher=NBC Bay Area|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027024123/http://www.nbcbayarea.com/around-town/events/Green-Day-Turns-Punk-Rock-Into-Fine-Art.html|archive-date=October 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2011, a film version of ''[[American Idiot (musical)|American Idiot]]'' was confirmed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kit |first=Borys |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/13/us-americanidiot-idUSTRE73C0E420110413 |title=American Idiot movie lands at Universal |agency=Reuters |date=April 13, 2011 |access-date=July 7, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416092251/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/13/us-americanidiot-idUSTRE73C0E420110413 |archive-date=April 16, 2011}}</ref> Michael Mayer, director of the Broadway musical, will be directing the film. It will be produced by Green Day, Pat Magnarella (Green Day's manager who also produced ''[[Bullet in a Bible]]'', ''[[Awesome as Fuck]]'', and ''[[Heart Like a Hand Grenade]]''), Playtone ([[Tom Hanks]] and [[Gary Goetzman]]) and [[Tom Hulce]].\n\nOn January 23, 2013, it was announced that a documentary showing Armstrong's journey from punk rock to Broadway was to be released.<ref>{{cite web|title=Broadway Idiot is a feature length documentary. We're currently fine tuning the edit.|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=332540920113728&set=a.332526693448484.83373.329318960435924&type=1|publisher=Broadway Idiot official Facebook|date=January 23, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129071854/https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=332540920113728&set=a.332526693448484.83373.329318960435924&type=1|archive-date=January 29, 2016}}</ref> Called ''Broadway Idiot'' and showing a lot of behind-the-scenes of the ''American Idiot'' musical production, the movie was directed by Doug Hamilton, veteran television journalist for [[CBS News]]' ''[[60 Minutes]]'' and [[PBS]] documentaries such as ''[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]'', ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]'' and ''[[American Masters]]''. A trailer was released on January 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=PUNK ROCK MEETS BROADWAY \u2013 BROADWAY IDIOT TRAILER|url=http://www.greenday.com/news/punk-rock-meets-broadway-broadway-idiot-trailer-129241|publisher=Green Day official site|date=January 31, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130204005421/http://www.greenday.com/news/punk-rock-meets-broadway-broadway-idiot-trailer-129241|archive-date=February 4, 2013|access-date=February 1, 2013}}</ref> The documentary premiered at the [[South by Southwest Film Festival]] on March 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=WORLD PREMIERE!|url=http://broadwayidiot.com/2013/01/31/world-premiere-sxsw-film-festival/|publisher=Broadway Idiot|website=BroadwayIdiot.com|date=January 31, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622151954/http://broadwayidiot.com/2013/01/31/world-premiere-sxsw-film-festival/|archive-date=June 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nGreen Day served as executive producers of ''[[Turn It Around: The Story of East Bay Punk]]'' (2017), an extensive documentary film about the San Francisco Bay area punk scene from the late 1970s to the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/turn-it-around-the-story-of-east-bay-punk-review-1202451514/ |title=Film Review: 'Turn It Around: The Story of East Bay Punk' |author=Harvey, Dennis |date=June 2, 2017 |publisher= |website=[[Variety.com]] |access-date=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nGreen Day has generated controversy over whether their musical style and major-label status constitutes \"true [[Punk rock|punk]]\".<ref name=\"softpedia2005\">{{cite web|url= http://news.softpedia.com/news/Green-Day-Still-A-Punk-Band-10426.shtml|title= Green Day Still A Punk Band|date= October 5, 2005|access-date=December 4, 2010|first=Mihaela|last=Stroia|publisher=Softpedia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728121625/http://news.softpedia.com/news/Green-Day-Still-A-Punk-Band-10426.shtml|archive-date=July 28, 2013}}</ref> In reaction to both the style of music and the background of the band, [[John Lydon]], former frontman of the 1970s punk band the [[Sex Pistols]] commented, \"So there we are fending off all that and it pisses me off that years later a wank outfit like Green Day hop in and nick all that and attach it to themselves. They didn't earn their wings to do that and if they were true punk they wouldn't look anything like they do.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news.asp?contentid=13310 |title=John Lydon Calls Green Day \"Plonk\" Not \"Punk\" |last=Melia |first=Daniel |access-date=September 11, 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211060301/http://www.gigwise.com/news.asp?contentid=13310 |archive-date=February 11, 2007}}</ref>\n\nArmstrong has discussed the group's status of being a punk band on a major record label, saying, \"Sometimes I think we've become totally redundant because we're this big band now; we've made a lot of money \u2013 we're not punk rock any more. But then I think about it and just say, 'You can take us out of a punk rock environment, but you can't take the punk rock out of us.'\"<ref name=\"softpedia2005\" />\n\nOn September 21, 2012, while Green Day was performing at the iHeartRadio music festival, Armstrong stopped while performing \"[[Basket Case (song)|Basket Case]]\", because he believed the group's time was being shortened, possibly in order to extend R&B artist [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]]'s performance. Angered, Armstrong began ranting while a screen in the rear of the audience was labeled \"1 Minutes Left\", saying \"You're gonna give me one fucking minute? You've gotta be fucking kidding me!\" He also told the crowd he \"was not [[Justin Bieber]]\" and labeled the festival as a \"joke\". When the screen went blank, Armstrong smashed his guitar, while bassist [[Mike Dirnt]] smashed his bass. Armstrong then gave [[the finger]], and declared that Green Day would be back before throwing his microphone down and walking off the stage.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g9zogQOmQVM/|title = Green Day Billie Joe freaks out at the I Heart Radio Music Festival and smashes guitar|access-date = Oct 16, 2013|publisher = YouTube}}</ref> Two days later, the band's representative apologized for the incident on the group's behalf stating that \"Green Day would like everyone to know that their set was not cut short by Clear Channel and to apologize to those they offended at the iHeartRadio Festival in Las Vegas\" also adding that Armstrong will be headed to [[Drug rehabilitation|rehab]], for abuse of alcohol and prescription pills.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/celebrities/index.ssf/2013/02/billie_joe_armstrong_rehab_1.html |title=Billie Joe Armstrong on pill-popping: Backpack sounded like 'giant baby's rattle' |work=NJ.com |date=February 28, 2013 |access-date=November 25, 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103224438/http://www.nj.com/entertainment/celebrities/index.ssf/2013/02/billie_joe_armstrong_rehab_1.html |archive-date=November 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/09/23/green-days-billie-joe-armstrong-heads-to-rehab/70000969/1#.Ul9-UySXKAJ|title = Green Day's Billie Joe Armstrong heads to rehab|date = Sep 23, 2012|access-date = Oct 16, 2013|website = USA today|url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140113110018/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/09/23/green-days-billie-joe-armstrong-heads-to-rehab/70000969/1#.Ul9-UySXKAJ|archive-date = January 13, 2014|df = mdy-all}}</ref> However, Dirnt would later say in an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' that he agreed with what Armstrong meant by his rant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/blogs/alternate-take/q-a-green-days-mike-dirnt-on-billie-joe-armstrongs-recovery-20130301|title=Q&A: Green Day's Mike Dirnt on Billie Joe Armstrong's Recovery|access-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005201955/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/blogs/alternate-take/q-a-green-days-mike-dirnt-on-billie-joe-armstrongs-recovery-20130301|archive-date=October 5, 2013}}</ref> The band would later make amends with the company and play an album release party for their 2016 release, ''Revolution Radio''. They also returned to the festival in 2019 supporting the album  \"Father of All Motherfuckers\".{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn July 7, 2017, about 20 minutes before Green Day headlined a Mad Cool festival in [[Madrid]], an acrobat fell about {{convert|30|m|ft|sp=us}} from a cage above the stage and died. Some fans were upset at the band and festival organizers for continuing the show, which was attended by about 35,000 people.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/acrobat-plunges-100ft-death-mad-10758333 \"Acrobat plunges 100ft to death at Mad Cool festival as 35,000 people watched on but headliners Green Day continued\", by Steve Robson, ''The Daily Mirror''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708004859/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/acrobat-plunges-100ft-death-mad-10758333 |date=July 8, 2017}}</ref> On their website, Armstrong said the band did not know about the accident before their set, and likely would not have played if they had.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/green-day-defends-performance-1.4196838|title='We are not heartless people': Green Day defends set after acrobat's death|website=Cbc.ca|access-date=October 16, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813013506/http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/green-day-defends-performance-1.4196838|archive-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Band members ==\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Billie Joe Armstrong]]&nbsp;\u2013 lead vocals, guitars, piano, harmonica (1987\u2013present)\n* [[Mike Dirnt]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass (1988\u2013present), backing vocals (1987\u2013present), guitars (1987\u20131988)\n* [[Tr\u00e9 Cool]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums, backing vocals (1990\u2013present)\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Raj Punjabi&nbsp;\u2013 drums, backing vocals (1987)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UfMAtvcbex4C&pg=PA7 |title=Green Day: A Musical Biography |first=Kjersti |last=Egerdahl |via=Google Books |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2010 |page=7 |access-date=January 5, 2016|isbn=9780313365973}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Lisa |last=Antao |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-minus-one-so-what-2072699 |title=Minus One. So what! |newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |date=March 29, 2015 |access-date=January 5, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209001401/http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-minus-one-so-what-2072699 |archive-date=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n* Sean Hughes&nbsp;\u2013 bass, backing vocals (1987\u20131988){{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n* [[John Kiffmeyer]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums, backing vocals (1987\u20131990; one-off guest appearance in 2015)<ref name=\"Kimpel2006\">{{cite book|last=Kimpel|first=Dan|title=How they made it: true stories of how music's biggest stars went from start to stardom!|url=https://archive.org/details/howtheymadeittru0000kimp|url-access=registration|access-date=July 31, 2010|date=May 1, 2006|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=978-0-634-07642-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/howtheymadeittru0000kimp/page/47 47]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/04/green-day-reunites-with-original-drummer-and-performs-as-sweet-children-watch/|title=Green Day reunites with original drummer and performs as Sweet Children \u2014 watch|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=April 19, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418184054/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/04/green-day-reunites-with-original-drummer-and-performs-as-sweet-children-watch/|archive-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n'''Current touring members'''\n* [[Jason Freese]]&nbsp;\u2013 piano, keyboards, saxophone, trombone, backing vocals (2004\u2013present)\n* [[Jason White (musician)|Jason White]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitars, backing vocals (1997\u20132012, 2016\u2013present; official member from 2012-2016)<ref name=\"instagram1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BqOeWe9Fl7D/ |title=Instagram |publisher=[[Instagram]] |date=November 15, 2018 |access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"instagram1\"/>\n* Kevin Preston&nbsp;\u2013 guitars (2019\u2013present)\n\n'''Former touring members'''\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Aaron Cometbus]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums, backing vocals (1990)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BA5brvIJFTg/ |title=Instagram |publisher=[[Instagram]] |date=January 23, 2016 |access-date=October 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404052624/https://www.instagram.com/p/BA5brvIJFTg/ |archive-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* Dave \"E.C.\" Henwood&nbsp;\u2013 drums, backing vocals (1990)<ref name=\"RWAC\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bbkSCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT46 |title=Green Day: Rebels With a Cause |first=Gillian G. |last=Gaar |via=Google Books |publisher=Music Sales Limited |page=46 |date=October 28, 2009 |access-date=January 5, 2016|isbn=9780857120595}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greendaycommunity.org/topic/97721-interview-with-temporary-drummer-dave-e-c-henwood/ |title=Interview With Temporary Drummer Dave E. C. Henwood |publisher=Green Day Community |date=December 17, 2014 |access-date=January 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229125305/http://www.greendaycommunity.org/topic/97721-interview-with-temporary-drummer-dave-e-c-henwood/ |archive-date=December 29, 2015 }}</ref>\n* Timmy Chunks&nbsp;\u2013 guitars, backing vocals (1997\u20131999)<ref>{{cite web|title=Timmy Chunks|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/timmy-chunks-mn0001429757|website=AllMusic|access-date=May 31, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125054706/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/timmy-chunks-mn0001429757|archive-date=January 25, 2016}}</ref>\n* Garth Schultz&nbsp;\u2013 trombone, [[trumpet]] (1997\u20131999)<ref>{{cite web|title=Garth Schultz |url=http://www.musicadvisor.biz/garth-schultz-complete-discography-2490.htm |publisher=Music Adviser |access-date=April 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409040045/http://www.musicadvisor.biz/garth-schultz-complete-discography-2490.htm |archive-date=April 9, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n* [[Gabrial McNair]]&nbsp;\u2013 trombone, saxophone (1999\u20132001)<ref>{{cite web|title=Gabrial McNair|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/gabrial-mcnair-mn0000777226|website=AllMusic|access-date=May 31, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121122094825/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/gabrial-mcnair-mn0000777226|archive-date=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n* Kurt Lohmiller&nbsp;\u2013 trumpet, percussion (1999\u20132004)<ref>{{cite web|title=Kurt Lohmiller|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/kurt-lohmiller-mn0001408238|website=AllMusic|access-date=May 31, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125043945/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/kurt-lohmiller-mn0001408238|archive-date=January 25, 2016}}</ref>\n* Mike Pelino&nbsp;\u2013 guitars, backing vocals (2004\u20132005)<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Pelino|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mike-pelino-mn0001900113|website=AllMusic|access-date=May 31, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125014357/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mike-pelino-mn0001900113|archive-date=January 25, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Ronnie Blake]]&nbsp;\u2013 trumpet, percussion (2004\u20132005)\n* Bobby Schneck&nbsp;\u2013 guitars, backing vocals (2004\u20132005)\n* Jeff Matika \u2013 guitars, backing vocals (2009\u20132019)\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Timeline ===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:805 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:110 bottom:80 top:0 right:15\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1987 till:{{#time:m/d/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:1\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:1987\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1988\n\nColors =\n id:vocals value:red    legend:Lead_vocals\n id:bvocals value:pink  legend:Backing_vocals\n id:guitar value:green  legend:Guitar\n id:keys   value:purple legend:Keyboards\n id:bass   value:blue   legend:Bass\n id:drums  value:orange legend:Drums\n id:lines  value:black  legend:Studio_album\n id:lines2 value:gray(0.65) legend:Live_album\n id:bars   value:gray(0.95)\n\nBackgroundColors = bars:bars\n\nLineData =\n color:line