tern Political Quarterly'' 34 (1981): 287\u2013300.\n* [https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=29158385 Sherman, Janann]. ''No Place for a Woman: A Life of Senator Margaret Chase Smith'' (2000).\n* Smith, Richard Norton. ''On His: Terms: A Life of Nelson Rockefeller'' (2014), a major scholarly biography.\n* Underwood, James F., and William J. Daniels. ''Governor Rockefeller in New York: The Apex of Pragmatic Liberalism in the United States'' (1982).\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.republicanmainstreet.org/ Republican Main Street Partnership] \u2013 Republican group interested in building a pragmatic center in the GOP\n* [http://www.progressiverepublicans.org/ Progressive Republicans]\n* [http://vftonline.org/XianAnarch/cause/bush/Nixon.html \"Liberals Get the Action, Conservatives Get the Rhetoric\"] \u2013 first chapter of ''Nixon: The Man Behind the Mask'' by Gary Allen\n\n{{Conservatism US footer}}\n{{Conservatism footer}}\n{{Leftism in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Centrism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Eponymous political ideologies]]\n[[Category:Nelson A. Rockefeller]]\n[[Category:Political party factions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political terminology of the United States]]\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States) terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political ideology within the US Republican Party}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Rockefeller Republicans\n| colorcode = {{Republican Party (United States)/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Thomas Dewey]]<br />[[Nelson Rockefeller]]\n| founded = 1930s\n| ideology = [[Liberal Conservatism]]{{refn|group=nb|\"In fact, moderate Republicanism was a separate political and ideological viewpoint that found adherents in all parts of the country, among members of all racial and ethnic groups, and along all points of the socioeconomic spectrum. It overlapped on some issues with liberals, on others with conservatives, and on still others with neither.\"{{sfn|Kabaservice|2012|p=xvii}}}}{{sfn|Libby|2013|p=77}}{{sfn|Stebenne|2006|p=38}}\n| position = [[Centrism|Center]] to [[Center-right politics|center-right]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n}}\n[[File:Nelson Rockefeller.jpg|thumb|[[Nelson Rockefeller]], after whom Rockefeller Republicans were named]]\n\nThe '''Rockefeller Republicans''', also called '''Moderate'''{{sfn|Stebenne|2006|p=38}} or '''Liberal Republicans''', were members of the [[History of the Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] (GOP) in the 1930s\u20131970s who held [[moderate]] to [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] views on domestic issues, similar to those of [[Nelson Rockefeller]], [[Governor of New York]] (1959\u20131973) and [[Vice President of the United States]] (1974\u20131977). Rockefeller Republicans were most common in the Northeast and the West Coast with their larger liberal constituencies while they were rare in the South and Midwest.<ref>Reiter (1981)</ref> They often saw themselves as champions of \"good government\", contrasting themselves to the often corrupt [[Political machine|machine politics]] of the Democratic Party, particularly in large cities.\n\nRockefeller Republicanism has been described as the last phase of the \"'''Eastern Establishment'''\" of the GOP which had been led by New York governor [[Thomas E. Dewey]]. The group's powerful role in the GOP came under heavy attack during the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1964|1964 primary campaign]] between Rockefeller and [[Barry Goldwater]]. At a discouraging point before the California primary, political operative [[Stuart Spencer (political consultant)|Stuart Spencer]] called on Rockefeller to \"summon that fabled nexus of money, influence, and condescension  known as the Eastern Establishment.\" Rockefeller replied, \"You are looking at it, buddy, I am all that is left\".{{sfn|Smith|2014|p=xxi}}\n\n[[Michael Lind]] contends that the ascendancy of the more [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] [[Fusionism|fusionist-wing]] of the Republican Party,{{sfn|Lind|1997|pp=53-54}} beginning in the 1960s with Goldwater and culminating in the [[Reagan Revolution]] in 1980, prevented the establishment of a [[Benjamin Disraeli|Disraelian]] [[one-nation conservatism]] in the United States.{{sfn|Lind|1997|pp=45-46}}{{sfn|Lind|1997|pp=55}} In its current usage, the term refers to \"[a] member of the Republican Party holding views likened to those of Nelson Rockefeller; a moderate or liberal Republican\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/rockefeller_republican|title=Rockefeller Republican {{!}} Definition of Rockefeller Republican in English by Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries {{!}} English|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref>\n\nThe phrase \"Rockefeller Republican\" has come to be used in a pejorative sense by [[Movement conservatism|modern conservatives]], who use it to deride those in the Republican Party that are perceived to have views which are too liberal, especially on major social issues.{{sfn|Coffey|2015|p=63}} The term was adopted mostly because of Nelson Rockefeller's vocal support of civil rights and lavish spending policies.{{sfn|Coffey|2015|p=63}} However, historian Justin P. Coffey has stated that Rockefeller's liberalism is a myth,{{sfn|Coffey|2015|p=64}} with former Vice President [[Spiro Agnew]] pointing out that the reality was quite different, stating that: \"A lot of people considered Rockefeller very liberal and very dovish on foreign policy, but he was not. He was harder than Nixon, and a lot more hawkish about the mission of America in the world\".{{sfn|Coffey|2015|p=64}}\n\n== Political positions ==\nIn domestic policy, Rockefeller Republicans were typically moderate to [[center-right]] economically,{{sfn|Libby|2013|p=77}} vehemently rejected [[American conservatism|conservatives]] like [[Barry Goldwater]], and held beliefs in social policies that were often [[Cultural liberalism|culturally liberal]]. They espoused government and private investments in [[environmentalism]], [[healthcare]], and [[higher education]] as necessities for a better society and economic growth in the tradition of Rockefeller. They were strong supporters of state colleges and universities, low tuition and large research budgets. They favored infrastructure improvements such as highway projects.\n\nIn general, Rockefeller Republicans opposed [[socialism]] and [[government ownership]], though they supported some regulation of business. They typically favored [[New Deal]] programs and a [[social safety net]] and sought to run these programs more efficiently than the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]].{{sfn|Baldi|2012|p=51}} They were strong supporters of [[big business]] and [[Wall Street]]. Many Rockefeller Republicans were major figures in business, such as auto executive [[George W. Romney]] and investment banker [[C. Douglas Dillon]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2019|reason=Need source for claims Romney and Dillon identified as Rockefeller Republicans}} In fiscal policy, they favored balanced budgets and were not averse to raising taxes in order to achieve them. Connecticut Senator [[Prescott Bush]] once called for Congress to \"raise the required revenues by approving whatever levels of taxation may be necessary\".{{sfn|Micklethwait|Woolridge|2005|page=29}} A critical element was their support for [[labor union]]s and especially the [[building trades]] appreciated the heavy spending on [[infrastructure]]. In turn, the unions gave these politicians enough support to overcome the [[anti-union]] rural element in the Republican Party. As the unions weakened after the 1970s, so too did the need for Republicans to cooperate with them. This transformation played into the hands of the more [[Timeline of modern American conservatism|conservative]] Republicans, who did not want to collaborate with labor unions in the first place and now no longer needed to do so to carry statewide elections.<ref>Rae. ''Decline and Fall of the Liberal Republicans: 1952 to the Present'' (1989)</ref>\n\nIn foreign policy, they tended to be [[Alexander Hamilton|Hamiltonian]], espousing [[internationalism (politics)|internationalist]] and [[Realism (international relations)|realist]] policies, supporting the [[United Nations]] and promoting American business interests abroad. Most wanted to use American power in cooperation with allies to fight against the spread of [[Soviet communism]] and help American business expand abroad. [[Richard Nixon]], a moderate [[political establishment|establishment]] Republican within the party's contemporary ideological framework, was influenced by this tradition.\n\n== History ==\n[[Thomas E. Dewey]], the [[Governor of New York]] from 1942 to 1954 and the Republican presidential nominee in 1944 and 1948, was the leader of the moderate-wing of the Republican Party in the 1940s and early 1950s, battling conservative Republicans from the Midwest led by Senator [[Robert A. Taft]] of Ohio, known as \"Mr. Republican\". With the help of Dewey, General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] defeated Taft for the 1952 presidential nomination and became the leader of the moderates. Eisenhower coined the phrase \"Modern Republicanism\" to describe his moderate vision of Republicanism. After Eisenhower, [[Nelson Rockefeller]], the Governor of New York, emerged as the leader of the moderate-wing of the Republican Party, running for President in 1960, 1964 and 1968. Rockefeller Republicans suffered a crushing defeat in 1964 when conservatives captured control of the Republican Party and nominated Senator [[Barry Goldwater]] of Arizona for President.\n\nOther prominent figures in the GOP's Rockefeller-wing included Connecticut Senator [[Prescott Bush]], Pennsylvania Governor [[Raymond P. Shafer]], Pennsylvania Senator [[Hugh Scott]], Illinois Senator [[Charles H. Percy]], Oregon Senator [[Mark Hatfield]], Maine Senator [[Margaret Chase Smith]], New York Senator [[Jacob Javits]], and Arkansas Governor [[Winthrop Rockefeller]], Nelson's younger brother (who was somewhat of an aberration in the [[Conservative Democrat|conservative, heavily Democratic]] South). Some also include President [[Richard Nixon]].<ref>[[Halberstam, David]] (1993). ''[[The Fifties (book)|The Fifties]]''. The Random House Publishing Group. New York. {{ISBN|0-449-90933-6}}. pp. 312\u2013315.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternet.org/newsandviews/article/641730/if_nixon_were_alive_today,_he_would_be_far_too_liberal_to_get_even_the_democratic_nomination|title=If Nixon Were Alive Today, He Would Be Far Too Liberal to Get Even the Democratic Nomination|author=|date=2011-07-29|website=Alternet.org|accessdate=2016-02-23}}</ref> Although Nixon ran against Rockefeller from the right in the 1968 primaries and was widely identified with the [[cultural right]] of the time, he adopted several Rockefeller Republican policies during his time as President, for instance setting up the [[Environmental Protection Agency]], supporting expanded welfare programs, imposing [[wage control|wage]] and [[price control]]s and in 1971 announcing he was a [[Keynesian economics|Keynesian]].{{sfn|Reeves|2002|p=295}} The men had previously reached the so-called [[Treaty of Fifth Avenue]] during the presidential primaries of 1960, whereby Nixon and Rockefeller agreed to support certain policies for inclusion in the 1960 Republican Party Platform.\n\nBarry Goldwater crusaded against the Rockefeller Republicans, beating Rockefeller narrowly in the California primary of 1964. That set the stage for a conservative resurgence, based in the South and West in opposition to the Northeast Rockefeller wing. However, the moderate contingent recaptured control of the party and nominated Richard Nixon in 1968. Easily reelected in 1972, after his resignation Nixon was replaced as President by the moderately conservative Republican [[Gerald Ford]]. After Vice President Rockefeller left the national stage in 1976, this faction of the party was more often called \"moderate Republicans\" or Nixonians in contrast to the conservatives who rallied to [[Ronald Reagan]]. Four years after nearly toppling the incumbent Ford in the 1976 presidential primaries, conservative [[Ronald Reagan]] won the party's presidential nomination at the [[1980 Republican National Convention]] and served two terms in the White House.\n\nBy 1988, the Republicans had chosen [[Prescott Bush]]'s son [[George H. W. Bush]] as its presidential candidate on a conservative platform. Bush's [[1988 Republican National Convention|national convention]] pledge to stave off new taxation were he elected president ([[Read my lips: no new taxes|\"Read my lips: no new taxes!\"]]) marked the candidate's full conversion to the conservative movement and perhaps the political death knell for Rockefeller Republicanism as a prevailing force within party politics.\n\nEthnic changes{{clarify|date=May 2017}} in the Northeast may have led to the demise of the Rockefeller Republican.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} Many Republican leaders associated with this title were [[White Anglo-Saxon Protestant]]s like [[Charles Mathias]] of [[Maryland]]. Liberal New York Republican Senator [[Jacob Javits]], who had an [[Americans for Democratic Action]] rating above 90% and an [[American Conservative Union]] rating below 10%, was Jewish. As time went on, the local Republican parties in the Northeast tended to nominate [[Catholic]] candidates who appealed to [[middle class]] social values-laden concerns, such as [[George Pataki]], [[Rudy Giuliani]], [[Al D'Amato]], [[Rick Lazio]], [[Tom Ridge]], [[Chris Christie]] and others, who in many cases represented the party's diversity more on the basis of religion and were often otherwise like their Protestant conservative counterparts.\n\nWith their power decreasing in the final decades of the 20th century, many moderate Republicans were replaced by conservative and moderate Democrats, such as those from the [[Blue Dog Coalition|Blue Dog]] or [[New Democrat Coalition|New Democrat]] coalitions. [[Michael Lind]] contends that by the mid-90s the liberalism of President [[Bill Clinton]] and the [[New Democrats]] were in many ways to the right of [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]], Rockefeller, and [[John Lindsay]], the Republican mayor of New York City in the late 1960s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Up From Conservatives|last=Lind|first=Michael|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=263}}</ref> In 2009, [[CNN]] published an analysis describing how liberal and moderate Republicans had declined by the start of the 21st century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/05/06/liberal.republicans/|title=Analysis: An autopsy of liberal Republicans|last=Silverleib|first=Alan|website=cnn.com|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> In 2010, [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]] was elected to the Senate to fill the seat once held by Democratic Senator Edward Kennedy. He was considered to be a moderate Republican in a similar mold as Susan Collins and Olympia Snowe of Maine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/35235106/ns/politics-capitol_hill/t/scott-brown-st-gop-senator-sworn/#.W0E3YbRmVBU|title=Scott Brown, 41st GOP senator, sworn in|date=2010-02-04|work=msnbc.com|access-date=2018-07-07}}</ref> However, by middle of the century's second decade, only Senator [[Susan Collins]] of Maine remained as a moderately liberal Republican representing the New England at the federal level.\n\n=== Challenged by the Tea Party ===\nIn 2010, several moderate Republicans lost their primaries or were challenged by the [[Tea Party movement]].  In [[2010 United States Senate elections|Alaska]], Senator [[Lisa Murkowski]], the ranking member of the [[Energy and Natural Resources Committee]], lost her GOP primary to conservative Tea Party challenger [[Joe Miller (Alaska politician)|Joe Miller]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/116703-sen-murkowski-concedes-defeat-to-tea-party-backed-miller|title=Sen. Lisa Murkowski concedes shock defeat in GOP Alaska primary|last=D'Aprile|first=Shane|date=2010-09-01|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> The Tea Party's campaign organization \"helped Miller portray the senator as too liberal for the state\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/how-alaskas-joe-miller-managed-stunning-upset-over-lisa-murkowski/|title=How Alaska's Joe Miller Managed Stunning Upset over Lisa Murkowski|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> Despite her primary defeat, Murkowski was reelected after waging a successful write-in campaign.\n\n[[Mike Castle]], a moderate former Governor and Representative of Delaware, lost his primary to conservative \"insurgent\" [[Christine O'Donnell]], who depicted Castle as being too liberal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/15/us/politics/15elect.html|title=G.O.P. Insurgents Win in Del. and N.Y.|last=Zeleny|first=Jeff|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref>\n\nSenator John McCain survived a primary in 2010, but his Tea Party opponent [[J. D. Hayworth]] accused him of being insufficiently conservative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/08/24/tuesday.primaries/index.html|title=McCain wins Senate primary in Arizona - CNN.com|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> A few years after in 2014, the [[Arizona Republican Party]] censured McCain \"for a record they called too 'liberal{{'\"}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/arizona-republicans-censure-john-mccain-for-being-too-liberal/|title=Arizona Republicans censure John McCain for being too \"liberal\"|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> An [[op-ed]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' made the assertion that Castle's loss marked the end of the party legacy of Nelson Rockefeller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/09/15/AR2010091502969.html|title=E.J. Dionne Jr. - Mike Castle's defeat -- and the end of moderate Republicanism|last=Jr|first=E. J. Dionne|date=2010-09-16|access-date=2018-07-08|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nIn upstate New York, GOP-nominated [[Dede Scozzafava]] was opposed by national conservatives within the Republican Party during her election bid for a congressional district: \"National PACs upset with Scozzafava's support of the federal stimulus, EFCA, same-sex marriage and abortion rights poured on money and attacks\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://observer.com/2009/11/the-collapse-of-dede-scozzafava-moderate-republican/|title=The Collapse of Dede Scozzafava, Moderate Republican|date=2009-11-01|work=Observer|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> She was pressured to drop out of the race,and when she did the [[Republican National Committee]] endorsed Tea Party-backed [[Doug Hoffman]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/01/nyregion/01upstate.html|title=Dede Scozzafava, Republican, Quits House Race in Upstate New York|last=Peters|first=Adam Nagourney and Jeremy W.|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Revival in the Northeast ===\n\"Liberal to moderate Northeastern Republicans were once as much a part of the political landscape as today's liberals from Massachusetts.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> According to the ''[[National Review]]'', \"At the state level, however, a kind of Rockefeller Republicanism seems to be rising once again in recent years\" in New England and the Northeast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/06/new-england-republicans-popular-conservative-roots/|title=Popular Republicans: The New England Enigma|date=2018-06-27|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, moderate Republicans were elected governor of Maryland ([[Larry Hogan]]) and Massachusetts ([[Charlie Baker]]). In 2017, New Hampshire ([[Chris Sununu]]) and Vermont ([[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]]) also elected moderates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/06/new-england-republicans-popular-conservative-roots/|title=Popular Republicans: The New England Enigma|date=2018-06-27|work=National Review|access-date=2018-07-07}}</ref> According to an analysis by [[FiveThirtyEight]] and polling by [[Morning Consult]], the quartet consistently rank among the most popular governors in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/how-every-senator-ranks-according-to-popularity-above-replacement-senator/|title=How Every Senator Ranks According To \u2018Popularity Above Replacement Senator\u2019|last=Rakich|first=Nathaniel|date=2019-05-08|website=FiveThirtyEight|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/magazine/2019/08/26/why-republican-governors-are-more-popular/amp/|title=Why Republican Governors Are More Popular {{!}} National Review|website=www.nationalreview.com|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In [[2018 Massachusetts gubernatorial election|2018]], Baker was re-elected by a 2:1 margin, receiving more votes than [[Elizabeth Warren]], who was also running for [[2018 United States Senate election in Massachusetts|re-election.]]\n\nMassachusetts Governor [[Charlie Baker]] \"is socially liberal [...]. He is pro-choice and has long supported gay marriage\". In Vermont, the voters elected [[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]] as Governor. Describing himself, Governor Scott stated: \"I am very much a fiscal conservative. But not unlike most Republicans in the Northeast, I'm probably more on the left of center from a social standpoint. [...] I am a pro\u2013choice Republican\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pressherald.com/2016/12/25/governors-lead-a-republican-renaissance-in-new-england/|title=Governors lead a Republican renaissance in New England|date=2016-12-25|work=Press Herald|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref> In 2017, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' described [[Larry Hogan]], another Republican governor in a deep-blue state, as \"a moderate Republican who is focused on jobs and the economy\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/why-marylands-popular-republican-governor-is-in-the-doghouse-with-maryland-conservatives/2017/08/26/d404fe2a-881e-11e7-a94f-3139abce39f5_story.html|title=Why Maryland's popular Republican governor is in the doghouse with Maryland conservatives|last=Wiggins|first=Ovetta|date=2017-08-26|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-11-21|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n== Modern usage ==\nThe term \"Rockefeller Republican\" is now somewhat archaic as Nelson Rockefeller died in 1979. ''[[The Atlantic]]'' has referred to the election of Northeastern Republicans as being similar to \"Rockefeller-style liberal Republicanism\", even though the label is not necessarily used by the candidates themselves.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/03/the-bluest-republican/384969/|title=The Bluest Republican|last=Ball|first=Molly|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref> The Rockefeller Republican label has sometimes been applied to modern politicians, such as [[Lincoln Chafee]] of [[Rhode Island]], who served as a Republican in the Senate, was elected that state's governor as an independent, and later became a Democrat and briefly sought [[2016 Democratic Party presidential primaries|that party's 2016 presidential nomination]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2006/0814/p01s02-uspo.html|title=Trouble for centrists: Is the Hill headed for a sharper split?|date=2006-08-14|website=CSMonitor.com|accessdate=2016-02-23}}</ref> Some more conservative members of the Republican Party use the label in a derisive manner, along with other labels such as [[Republican In Name Only|RINOs]], i.e. Republicans in Name Only,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/09/donald-trump-2016-rockefeller-republican-214260|title=Take It from a Rockefeller (Republican), We Can Revive the GOP|work=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref> The Establishment,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2010/09/17/rockefeller_republicans_107193.html|title=Rockefeller Republicans|last=Buchanan|first=Pat|access-date=2018-07-08|website=RealClearPolitics}}</ref> or \"Acela Republicans,\" a reference to the [[Acela Express]] running along the eastern seaboard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefederalist.com/2015/07/02/a-field-guide-to-acela-republicans/|title=A Field Guide To Acela Republicans|last=2016|date=2015-07-02|website=The Federalist|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Christine Todd Whitman]], former [[Governor of New Jersey]], referred to herself as a Rockefeller Republican in a speech on Governor Rockefeller at [[Dartmouth College]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beta.academicearth.org/lectures/nelson-rockefeller-still-influencing-people-christine-todd-whitman|title=Nelson Rockefeller: Still Influencing People, Christine Todd Whitman|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130223045123/http://beta.academicearth.org/lectures/nelson-rockefeller-still-influencing-people-christine-todd-whitman|archivedate=2013-02-23|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> [[Lloyd Blankfein]], Chairman and CEO of [[Goldman Sachs]], who is a registered Democrat, referred to himself as a \"Rockefeller Republican\" in a CNBC interview in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/47079531|title=First On Cnbc: Cnbc Transcript: Goldman Sachs Chairman & Ceo Lloyd Blankfein Speaks With Gary Kaminsky Today On Cnbc|date=2012-04-25|website=Cnbc.com|accessdate=2016-02-23}}</ref>  The retired four-star generals [[Colin Powell]] and [[David Petraeus]] have both described themselves as \"Rockefeller Republicans\".<ref>Steve Coll, [http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2008/09/08/080908fa_fact_coll \"The General's Dilemma: David Petraeus, the pressures of politics, and the road out of Iraq\"]. ''[[The New Yorker]]''. 8 September 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/10/19/obama-mccain-election-oped-cx_rs_1020salam.html|title=The Obama Generation|last=Salam|first=Reihan|date=October 20, 2008|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9031E5FCB111&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D|title=Powell's liberal stances hurt him, conservative says|date=November 9, 1995|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|via=Nl.newsbank.com|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref> Former Senator [[Olympia Snowe]] (R-Maine) and Senator [[Susan Collins]] (R-Maine) are also two notable moderately liberal Republicans from the Northeast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/05/06/liberal.republicans/|title=Analysis: An autopsy of liberal Republicans|last=Silverleib|first=Alan|website=cnn.com|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref> Former Senator [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]] (R-Massachusetts), who ran a Senate campaign in New Hampshire, also had a voting record described as more liberal than most Republicans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/scott-brown-is-liberal-republican/|title=Scott Brown is a Liberal Republican|last=Gelman|first=Andrew|date=2010-01-15|work=FiveThirtyEight|access-date=2018-06-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jan/22/nation/la-na-scott-brown22-2010jan22|title=Scott Brown gets a hero's welcome from Senate Republicans|last=Hook|first=Janet|date=2010-01-22|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-06-24|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\nSenator [[John McCain]] was often referred to as a moderate during his [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2000|2000]] and [[2008 United States presidential election|2008]] presidential campaigns by opponents and commentators alike. In the 2000 primary, Bush described the race as \"going to be a clear race between a more moderate-to-liberal candidate vs. a conservative candidate in the state of South Carolina\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/time/2000/02/07/conservative.html|title=How Conservative Is McCain? |date=February 7, 2000|website=cnn.com |last=Pooley |first=Eric |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727170443/http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/time/2000/02/07/conservative.html |archive-date=July 27, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> [[NPR]] covered the 2008 campaign reporting that \"some conservative Republicans say McCain's voting record shows him to be too moderate a GOP candidate\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=18664285|title=McCain Too Moderate, Some GOP Conservatives Say|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref> The [[BBC]] reported that that this reputation as being more centrist was \"for his relatively moderate views on [[civil union]]s, [[abortion]] and [[McCain-Kennedy|immigration reform]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-40666269|title=Senator John McCain: Who is the Republican elder statesman? |date=August 24, 2018 |work=BBC News|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> In 2004 and 2006, McCain was one of a few Republicans who voted against banning [[same-sex marriage]] at the federal level, arguing that the issue should be left to the states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/07/14/mccain.marriage/|title=McCain: Same-sex marriage ban is un-Republican |date=July 14, 2004|website=cnn.com|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> However, ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'', which tracks and scores Congressional votes, had found that McCain had shifted between being more moderate and more conservative based on its study.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/john-mccain-has-increasingly-been-a-thorn-in-trumps-side/|title=John McCain Has Increasingly Been A Thorn In Trump's Side|last1=Bacon Jr.|first1=Perry |last2=Enten |first2=Harry |date=July 20, 2017 |work=FiveThirtyEight |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the GOP nominated as their candidate for President [[Mitt Romney]] a Governor who had described himself as [[Centrism|moderate]] and [[Progressivism|progressive]] in 2002. Running for Governor of Massachusetts, he said of himself: \"I'm not a partisan Republican. [...] I'm someone who is moderate, and [...] my views are progressive\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/romney-in-2002-called-his-views-progressive/|title=Romney in 2002 called his views \"progressive\"|last=Condon |first=Stephanie |date=December 13, 2011 |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> In his 1994 Senate campaign, Romney distanced himself from Ronald Reagan, noting that he was an independent during the Reagan presidency.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2012/may/17/mitt-romney/mitt-romney-once-distanced-himself-ronald-reagan-n/|title=Mitt Romney once distanced himself from Ronald Reagan, but no longer|work=@politifact|last=Jacobson |first=Louis |date=May 17, 2012 |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> One of his 2012 primary opponents, Newt Gingrich, even referred to Romney as a \"Rockefeller Republican\" in order to draw a contrast between Romney's former self-description and his own.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesherald.com/article/JR/20111016/NEWS06/111019749 |title=Gingrich calls Romney 'Rockefeller Republican' |date=October 16, 2011 |access-date=March 30, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> However, in his own words during the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 campaign]] Romney described himself as a \"severely [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]\" Republican.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/romney-calls-himself-severely-conservative-republican-governor-katrina-trinko/|title=Romney Calls Himself a 'Severely Conservative Republican Governor' |last=Trinko |first=Katrina |date=February 10, 2012|work=National Review |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the 1988 Republican National Convention, [[Donald Trump]] was asked by [[Larry King]] on [[CNN]]: \"You might be classified as an Eastern Republican, Rockefeller Republican. Fair?\", to which Trump replied: \"I guess you can say that\". When Trump was considering to run against [[Andrew Cuomo]] for Governor of [[New York (state)|New York]], Trump was dubbed as a \"Conservative Rockefeller Republican\".<ref>{{cite news|work=Newsmax|url=https://www.newsmax.com/Politics/trump-governor-election-campaign/2013/12/26/id/543930/|title=Trump Dubbed 'Conservative Rockefeller' for New York Governor Bid|date=December 26, 2013|accessdate=September 26, 2016|first=Cathy|last=Burke}}</ref> During his [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]], Trump was described as both a modern-day Rockefeller Republican (by some conservative writers)<ref>{{cite web|work=[[National Review]]|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/424753/donald-trumps-empire-state-role-model-michael-barone|title=Donald Trump's Empire State Role Model|date=September 29, 2015 |last=Barone |first=Michael |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Trump, Christie and the Revival of GOP Moderates|work=[[The American Conservative]]|date=February 26, 2016 |last=McConnell |first=Scott |url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/trump-christie-and-the-revival-of-the-gop-moderates/ |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=[[Washington Examiner]]|title=Trump: Not Ryan, not Reagan, but maybe the new Nixon|date=May 12, 2016 |last=Antle, III |first=W. James |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/trump-not-ryan-not-reagan-but-maybe-the-new-nixon/article/2591108 |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> and as the heir to the Goldwaterite opposition to the Rockefeller Republicans.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|title=What Happened to Republicans Who Rejected Their Party's Nominee in 1964|url=http://time.com/4338450/republican-barry-goldwater-donald-trump-1964/|date=May 19, 2016 |last=Rothman |first=Lily |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|work=[[Politico]]|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/09/donald-trump-2016-rockefeller-republican-214260|title=Take It from a Rockefeller (Republican), We Can Revive the GOP|last=Spencer |first=Dave |date=September 19, 2016 |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=[[CNN]]|title=Is Donald Trump another Barry Goldwater?|date=March 2, 2016|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/03/01/opinions/trump-vs-goldwater-zelizer/index.html |last=Zeiter |first=Julian |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[Bill Weld]] announced that he would consider a challenge to President Trump for the Republican nomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/15/695100977/former-republican-gov-bill-weld-considers-a-primary-challenge-to-trump|title=Former Gov. Bill Weld Considers A Republican Primary Challenge To Trump|website=NPR.org|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref> Bill Weld has been described by ''[[The New York Times]]'', in both his gubernatorial and presidential campaigns, as a moderate Republican.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/15/us/politics/bill-weld-trump-2020.html|title=Bill Weld Will Challenge Trump for 2020 Republican Nomination|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=2019-02-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-16|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/04/us/1990-campaign-weld-hopes-personality-his-opponent-s-will-help-him-massachusetts.html|title=THE 1990 CAMPAIGN; Weld Hopes Personality (His Opponent's) Will Help Him in Massachusetts|last=Butterfield|first=Fox|date=1990-11-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-16|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He has been likened to Rockefeller.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/politics/national/features/5574/index1.html|title=Weld At Heart|date=January 14, 2002 |last=Goron |first=Meryl |website=NYMag.com|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.masslive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2016/02/chip_harrington_chooses_massachusetts_gop.html|title=Why I chose to switch from the Democratic Party to Massachusetts GOP (Guest Viewpoint)|last=Harrington|first=Chip|website=masslive.com|date=February 3, 2016 |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> Governor Weld is described as [[Fiscal conservatism|fiscally conservative]] and [[Liberalism in the United States|socially liberal.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/02/15/william-weld-challenge-donald-trump-gop-nomination-2020/2881686002/|title=Ex-Massachusetts Gov. William Weld to challenge Trump for Republican nomination in 2020 |last1=Ramer |first1=Holly |last2=Salsberg |first2=Bob |date=February 15, 2019 |website=USA TODAY|agency=Associated Press |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> After declaring his candidacy, Weld described himself \"the most pro-choice person\" running for President.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/748f66ac0b3445fea073aaf599618e4d|title=GOP's Weld says he's most pro-choice candidate in 2020 race|date=2019-05-19|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2019-05-18/gops-weld-says-hes-most-pro-choice-candidate-in-2020-race|title=GOP's Weld Says He's Most Pro-Choice Candidate in 2020 Race|last=|first=|date=May 18, 2019|website=U.S. News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Current officeholders==\n===U.S. Senators===\n* [[Susan Collins]], United States Senator from Maine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Sen. Susan Collins hopes moderates will return to the GOP {{!}} PBS NewsHour|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/sen-susan-collins-hopes-moderates-will-return-to-the-gop-1390511663/|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/02/10/514428845/the-power-center-how-a-moderate-wields-big-influence-in-a-polarized-senate|title=The Power Center: How A Moderate Wields Big Influence In A Polarized Senate|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Lisa Murkowski]], United States Senator from Alaska.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/us/politics/collins-murkowski-supreme-court-abortion.html|title=With Roe in the Balance, Two Republicans Hold High Court in Their Hands|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/alaska-sen-lisa-murkowski-declares-write-campaign-tea/story?id=11666831|title='Gloves Are Off': Murkowski Declares Write-In Bid|last=News|first=A. B. C.|date=2010-09-20|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2018-10-14}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. Governors===\n* [[Charlie Baker]], of [[Massachusetts]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/03/the-bluest-republican/384969/|title=The Bluest Republican|last=Ball|first=Molly|date=2015-02-16|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/06/new-england-republicans-popular-conservative-roots/|title=Popular Republicans: The New England Enigma {{!}} National Review|date=2018-06-27|work=National Review|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[Larry Hogan]], of [[Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Larry Hogan, Maryland Governor, Urges Republicans to Look Beyond \u2018Shrinking Base\u2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/23/us/politics/larry-hogan-trump-2020.html|last1=Burns|first1=Alexander|last2=Lerer|first2=Lisa|date=February 23, 2019|work=New York Times|access-date=February 23, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]], of [[Vermont]].<ref>{{cite article|last=Richards|first=Parker|title=The Last Liberal Republicans Hang On|journal=[[The Atlantic]]|publisher=[[Emerson Collective]]|date=November 3, 2018|access-date=January 3, 2019|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/11/republican-governors-new-england-defy-blue-wave/574726/}}</ref>\n*[[Chris Sununu]], of [[New Hampshire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/articles/outside-of-partisan-washington-d-c-governors-remain-popular-in-the-states/|title=Outside of D.C., Governors Remain Popular in the States \u2013 Sabato's Crystal Ball|last=Jacobson|first=Louis|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/04/blue-state-republican-governors-are-very-popular.html|title=The Most Popular Governors in America Are Republicans in Blue States|last=Kilgore|first=Ed|date=2019-04-25|website=Intelligencer|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/06/new-england-republicans-popular-conservative-roots/|title=Popular Republicans: The New England Enigma|date=2018-06-27|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Members of the U.S. House of Representatives===\n*[[Jeff Van Drew]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[New Jersey's 2nd congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Verma|first=Pranshu|last2=Tamari|first2=Jonothan|url=https://www.inquirer.com/news/jeff-van-drew-trump-switch-parties-democrat-republican-20191219.html|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Brian Fitzpatrick (American politician)|Brian Fitzpatrick]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Pennsylvania's 1st congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Pathe|first=Somone|url=https://www.rollcall.com/2019/02/27/republicans-from-moderate-districts-bucking-their-party-on-background-checks/|accessdate=February 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Chris Smith (New Jersey politician)|Chris Smith]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[New Jersey's 4th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parkinsion|first=John|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/pelosi-dems-vote-emergency-funding-children-border-detention/story?id=63930932|accessdate=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[John Katko]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[New York's 24th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Brufke |first=Juliegrace|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/437234-the-8-republicans-who-voted-against-trumps-anti-obamacare-push|accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Elise Stefanik]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[New York's 21st congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Harding|first=Robert|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/gop-rep-elise-stefanik-trump-withdrawing-from-paris-agreement-is/article_b31b0138-4727-11e7-a4e0-cf749933d314.html|accessdate=June 2, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Fred Upton]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Michigan's 6th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Wise|first=Lindsay|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-michigan-moderate-weighs-future-in-trumps-gop-11568039977|accessdate=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Will Hurd]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Texas's 23rd congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lambrecht|first=Bill|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/politics/texas/article/Will-Hurd-a-rare-moderate-in-Congress-scores-a-13432502.php|accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Jaime Herrera Beutler]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Washington's 3rd congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Groover|first=Hedi|url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2017/03/23/25038268/another-republican-against-trumpcare-washington-states-jaime-herrera-beutler|accessdate=March 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n*[[Peter T. King]], Member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[New York's 2nd congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cochrane|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/11/us/politics/peter-king-retire.html|accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Former officeholders===\n====Senators====\n* [[Edward Brooke]], former United States Senator from Massachusetts<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timescolonist.com/edward-brooke-liberal-republican-and-1st-black-popularly-elected-to-us-senate-dies-at-95-1.1703570|title=Edward Brooke, liberal Republican and 1st black popularly elected to US Senate, dies at 95|last=Wingfield|first=Sylvia|date=2015-01-03|work=Times Colonist|access-date=2018-12-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]], former United States Senator from Massachusetts<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politifact.com/new-hampshire/statements/2014/mar/27/scott-brown/scott-brown-says-he-was-most-bipartisan-senator/|title=Scott Brown says he was the most bipartisan senator|work=@politifact|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/scott-brown-is-liberal-republican/|title=Scott Brown is a Liberal Republican|last=Gelman|first=Andrew|date=2010-01-15|work=FiveThirtyEight|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* [[John Chafee]], former Governor of Rhode Island and United States Senator \n* [[Lincoln Chafee]], former United States Senator from Rhode Island<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2015/06/03/411327420/5-things-you-should-know-about-lincoln-chafee|title=5 Things You Should Know About Lincoln Chafee|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14228498/ns/politics/t/last-liberal-republicans/#.W8KikJNKiSM|title=The last of the liberal Republicans?|date=2006-08-07|work=msnbc.com|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en}}</ref> ''(Former Republican, Independent and Democrat)''\n* [[John Heinz]], former United States Senator from Pennsylvania\n* [[John Warner]], former Secretary of the Navy and United States Senator from Virginia\n* [[Jacob Javits]], former United States Senator from New York<ref>Taranto, Stacie (July 18, 2017) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/made-by-history/wp/2017/07/18/the-senate-health-care-battle-isnt-what-you-think/ \"The Senate health-care battle isn\u2019t what you think\"] ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref>\n* [[Mark Kirk]], former United States Senator from Illinois\n* [[Hugh Scott]], former United States Senator from Pennsylvania and Senate Majority Leader\n* [[Olympia Snowe]], former United States Senator from Maine<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/Olympia-Snowe-Shocks-Colleagues-With-Retirement-212715-1.html|title=Olympia Snowe Shocks Colleagues With Retirement|last=Livingston|first=Abby|date=2012-02-28|work=Roll Call|access-date=2018-10-14|last2=Shiner|first2=Meredith|language=en|last3=Livingston|first3=Abby|last4=Shiner|first4=Meredith}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Snowe: Not a lot of company as moderate Republican|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/video/snowe-not-a-lot-of-company-as-moderate-republican/|access-date=2018-10-14}}</ref>\n* [[Arlen Specter]], former United States Senator from Pennsylvania ''(Former Republican)''\n\n====Congressmen====\n*[[Charlie Dent]], former Congressman from Pennsylvania \n*[[Rodney Frelinghuysen]], former Congressman from New Jersey\n*[[John Lindsay]], former Congressman and Mayor of New York City\n*[[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]], former Congresswoman from Florida \n*[[Chris Shays]], former Congressman from Connecticut\n\n====Supreme Court Justices====\n* [[John Paul Stevens]], former [[Associate Justice]] of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]].\n* [[Anthony Kennedy]], former Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://time.com/5323863/justice-anthony-kennedy-retirement-time-cover/|title=How Anthony Kennedy's Swing Vote Made Him 'the Decider'|last=Reilly|first=Katie|date=2018-06-27|work=TIME|access-date=2019-06-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n====Governors====\n*[[Bruce Rauner]], former Governor of Illinois \n*[[Tom Ridge]], former Governor of Pennsylvania and Secretary of Homeland Security\n* [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], former Governor of California\n* [[Lowell Weicker]], former Governor of Connecticut<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/07/nyregion/1990-elections-connecticut-renegade-s-victory-man-lowell-palmer-weicker-jr.html|title='The 1990 Elections: Connecticut - Renegade's Victory Man in The News: Lowell Palmer Weicker Jr.; The Independence of a Maverick Republican'|last=Ravo|first=Nick|access-date=2018-12-19|language=en}}</ref> ''(Former Republican and A Connecticut Party member)''\n*[[Bill Weld|William Weld]], former Governor of Massachusetts<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/15/us/politics/bill-weld-trump-2020.html|title=Bill Weld Will Challenge Trump for 2020 Republican Nomination|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=2019-02-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/04/us/1990-campaign-weld-hopes-personality-his-opponent-s-will-help-him-massachusetts.html|title=THE 1990 CAMPAIGN; Weld Hopes Personality (His Opponent's) Will Help Him in Massachusetts|last=Butterfield|first=Fox|date=1990-11-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-16|last2=Times|first2=Special To the New York|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/15/695100977/former-republican-gov-bill-weld-considers-a-primary-challenge-to-trump|title=Former Gov. Bill Weld Considers A Republican Primary Challenge To Trump|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref>\n* [[Christine Todd Whitman]], former Governor of New Jersey<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/06/books/review/its-my-party-too-a-bigger-tent.html|title='It's My Party Too': A Bigger Tent|last=Miller|first=Matt|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Conservative Democrat]] ([[Blue Dogs]])\n* [[Factions in the Republican Party (United States)]]\n* [[Libertarian Democrat]]\n* [[The New York Young Republican Club]]\n* [[One-nation conservatism]]\n* [[Red Tory]]\n* [[Republican Main Street Partnership]]\n* [[Republican In Name Only]]\n* [[Ripon Society]]\n* [[Roosevelt Republican]]\n* [[South Park Republican|''South Park'' Republican]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite book|last=Baldi|first=Alipio|year=2012|title=On His Own Terms: A Life of Nelson Rockefeller|location=|publisher=WestBow Press|isbn=1-449-76213-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Coffey|first=Justin P.|year=2015|title=Spiro Agnew and the Rise of the Republican Right|location=|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=1-440-84142-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gritter|first=Matthew|year=2018|title=Presidents and the Safety Net: From Moderation to Backlash|location=|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=1-498-58357-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kabaservice|first=Geoffrey|year=2012|title=Rule and Ruin: The Downfall of Moderation and the destruction of the Republican Party, from Eisenhower to the Tea Party|location=|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-199-92113-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Libby|first=|year=2013|title=Purging the Republican Party: Tea Party Campaigns and Elections|location=|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=0-739-18764-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Lind|first=Michael|year=1997|title=Up from Conservatism|location=|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=0-684-83186-4|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/upfromconservati00mich}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Micklethwait|first1=John|last2=Woolridge|first2=Adrian|year=2005|title=The Right Nation: Why America is Different|location=|publisher=Penguin|isbn=0-141-01536-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Reeves|first=Richard|year=2002|title=President Nixon: Alone in the White House|url=https://archive.org/details/presidentnixon00rich|url-access=registration|location=|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=0-743-22719-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Smith|first=Richard Norton|year=2014|title=On His Own Terms: A Life of Nelson Rockefeller|location=|publisher=Random House|isbn=0-375-50580-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stebenne|first=David L.|year=2006|title=Modern Republican: Arthur Larson and the Eisenhower Years|location=|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-11232-X|ref=harv}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Burns, James MacGregor. ''The Deadlock of Democracy''. Englewood Cliffs, N.J.: 1967.\n* [https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=1528422 Joyner, Conrad]. ''The Republican Dilemma: Conservatism or Progressivism'' (1963).\n* [[Irving Kristol|Kristol, Irving]]. \"American Conservatism 1945\u20131995\". ''Public Interest'' 94 (Fall 1995): 80\u201391.\n* Perlstein, Rick. ''Before the Storm: Barry Goldwater and the Unmaking of the American Consensus'' (2001) [https://books.google.com/books?id=6jb9AgAAQBAJ text search], survey of GOP politics in 1960s.\n* [https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=91954887 Reinhard, David W.] ''The Republican Right since 1945'' (1983).\n* Rae, Nicol. ''Decline and Fall of the Liberal Republicans: 1952 to the Present''. 1989.\n* Reichley, A. James. ''Conservatives in an Age of Change: The Nixon and Ford Administrations.'' 1981.\n* Reiter, Howard. \"Intra-Party Cleavages in the United States Today\". ''Western Political Quarterly'' 34 (1981): 287\u2013300.\n* [https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=29158385 Sherman, Janann]. ''No Place for a Woman: A Life of Senator Margaret Chase Smith'' (2000).\n* Smith, Richard Norton. ''On His: Terms: A Life of Nelson Rockefeller'' (2014), a major scholarly biography.\n* Underwood, James F., and William J. Daniels. ''Governor Rockefeller in New York: The Apex of Pragmatic Liberalism in the United States'' (1982).\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.republicanmainstreet.org/ Republican Main Street Partnership] \u2013 Republican group interested in building a pragmatic center in the GOP\n* [http://www.progressiverepublicans.org/ Progressive Republicans]\n* [http://vftonline.org/XianAnarch/cause/bush/Nixon.html 